A0664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BIG12-TEXAS-OKLAS     03-07 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG12-TEXAS-OKLASTATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas makes it close but loses 59-57
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The floor at Kemper Arena appears to be flat and
level, but the way Texas and Oklahoma State went at it Saturday you
would think the surface was as slanted as one of the hills
bordering the Missouri River.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Longhorns were the ones contesting the
gravitational pull for the most part and, after a long afternoon of
uphill combat, they came up just shy of the crest by day's end.
</P>
<P>
   Despite holding Oklahoma State to 33-percent shooting and a
measly 18 points in the second half, Texas could not make the
game-winning plays it needed and lost 59-57 in a Big 12 tournament
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 5-seeded Cowboys (22-9) will face the Kansas Jayhawks,
69-58 winners over Kansas State, in the tournament final at 2 p.m.
today.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied only once, and Texas (19-12) had its only
lead at 23-22 midway through the first half. The Longhorns battled
to stay within an arm's length but never made the move it needed to
take control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an opportunity there for us coming out in the second
half when both teams came out a little bit sluggish, but we needed
to jump on them and we didn't,'' Texas sophomore center Chris Mihm
said. ``We let it slip right there, then we missed some
opportunities later as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost opportunities were costly for the Longhorns, who missed a
wide-open jumper, threw away a pass and missed a layup _ all in the
last 24 seconds _ to finally bring their tournament title dreams to
a close.
</P>
<P>
   The last was a potential game-tying burst up the floor by point
guard Ivan Wagner, but his layup never drew iron. Before Texas
could corral the offensive rebound and get up a follow attempt, the
buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well, and we missed out on a lot of chances to
win the game,'' forward Kris Clack said. ``But it says a lot about
what type of team we are to play terrible and only lose by two
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ``terrible'' in Texas' play came on the offensive
end as the Longhorns elected to launch 20 3-pointers, making only
four, against the zone-dominated Cowboys defense.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot Mihm and power forward Nnadubem ``Gabe'' Muoneke led
Texas with 17 and 16 points, respectively, but neither seemed to
get the ball as often as they are accustomed. Mihm was 5-for-9
shooting and Muoneke 5-for-7.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' shooters took turns misfiring from the outside. Clack,
who was severely hampered by a bruised tail bone, was 1-for-6 from
the 3-point arc, Ivan Wagner 1-for-5, William Clay 1-for-4 and
Chris McColpin 0-for-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to shoot those shots if teams are going to give them
to us,'' Texas coach Rick Barnes said, ``But we didn't do a good
job of attacking the gaps of the defense and getting the mid-range
shots. And we took some long shots early (in the possession) that
we don't want to take. Still, teams are gonna sag against our
inside game and we have to knock down some of those to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns fell behind by 11 points with just under nine
minutes remaining before the brawniest steer pulled his team up the
hill once more.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke scored five points, grabbed three rebounds and added a
steal in the next 3{ minutes to spark a 10-0 Texas run.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-7 junior scored on an offensive rebound and, after a
DeJuan Vazquez basket, dropped in two more points with a strong
move down low. Muoneke then made a nifty save under the basket of a
McColpin air ball that led to Clay's lone bucket from long range,
and hit a free throw to cut Oklahoma State's lead to 53-52 with
4:28 to play.
</P>
<P>
   But that was as close as Texas would get even though it had
several other chances.
</P>
<P>
   After Muoneke threw a beautiful no-look, behind-the-back pass to
Mihm for a dunk to pull Texas within 58-57, Clay got free on a
breakaway after a long rebound but lost the ball and traveled.
</P>
<P>
   A good defensive stand forced Oklahoma State's Adrian Peterson
to attempt a 25-foot bomb as the shot-clock buzzer went off. The
shot banged off the glass, but Mihm could not haul in the rebound,
losing it out of bounds with 57.7 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez got his hands on a pass to force a turnover, but on the
other end he couldn't get his 12-foot jumper from the left baseline
to fall with just more than 20 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Foul-plagued Desmond Mason, a 15.5-points-per-game scorer whom
Texas held in check with only four points, missed the front end of
a one-and-one, giving the Longhorns another opportunity to take the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was Wagner's turn to make a mistake, and he threw a
crosscourt skip pass intended for Vazquez that found press row
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, who had 13 of his game-high 18 points in the first
half, hit one of two free throws with 9.3 seconds to go, leading to
Wagner's final go at it.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke charged hard at the miss but couldn't get a grip on the
rebound for a flying put-back and ran out of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts to lose any game and we really wanted to win this
tournament, but it could turn out to be for the best as we can get
some rest and get geared up to play next week,'' Mihm said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas will not win the Big 12 tournament, but the Longhorns did
claim the regular-season title and felt coming into the tournament
that they would advance to the NCAA Tournament next week regardless
of the outcome here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident before we came here,'' Barnes said of his
team's postseason hopes. ``They're not going to keep the Big 12
champion out of the Tournament. I'm not worried at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes will find out today if his prognostication becomes
reality when the NCAA selection committee, which is sequestered at
a downtown hotel here, announces the 64-team field.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State believed it needed to win some games here to
advance to the NCAA Tournament, and it did that, knocking off
Baylor and exacting revenge on two teams _ Oklahoma and Texas _
that beat the Cowboys twice during the conference season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
