<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0677 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     03-07 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOYS OF MY YOUTH &LR;  By Jo Ann Beard. Back Bay/Little, Brown,
$13. These 12 essays about the author's largely uneventful
upbringing in the Midwest and her marriage and divorce are brought
to life by her comfortable voice and acerbic powers of observation.
``Beard remembers (or imagines) her childhood with an uncanny
lucidity that startles,'' Laura Miller wrote in The New York Times
Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WICKED WOMEN: STORIES &LR;  By Fay Weldon. Atlantic Monthly, $12.
With 21 novels and three short-story collections, the author has
perfected her ironic forays into the universe of the discarded wife
who is forced into heroic self-awareness. This time she also takes
aim at insecure househusbands, selfish adult children, therapists
and the culture's infatuation with New Age blather. ``She is a
Yahweh with a profound appreciation of irony,'' Deborah Mason wrote
in 1997. ``Weldon has become one of the most cunning moral
satirists of our time. In her rueful stories, justice is done _
whether we like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAUCASIA &LR;  By Danzy Senna. Riverhead, $12.95. This first novel
tracks the coming of age of the daughter of a white activist and a
black intellectual who struggles to find her identity in a harsh
and confusing world. ``Senna superbly illustrates the emotional
toll that politics and race take on one especially gutsy young
girl's development,'' Elizabeth Schmidt wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SERBS: HISTORY, MYTH AND THE DESTRUCTION OF YUGOSLAVIA &LR;  By
Tim Judah. Yale University, $16. A journalist argues that the Serbs
have been subjected to ``ethnic cleansing'' since medieval times,
making it the driving force behind their national consciousness,
and he links the recent atrocities committed by the Bosnian Serbs
to a collective madness prompted by a desire for revenge. In 1997
the reviewer Aleksa Djilas called this ``a lively and balanced
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Yale has also reissued  &UR; CROATIA: A NATION FORGED IN WAR &LR; , by
Marcus Tanner ($16), which focuses on a Balkan culture with a
bewildering web of influences and contradictions _ not to mention a
long tradition of close relations with Serbia. The book is
``written with vigor, full of absorbing stories and important
insights,'' Djilas wrote, also in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE KNIFE THROWER AND OTHER STORIES &LR;  By Steven Millhauser.
Vintage Contemporaries, $12. The dreamers, inventors, artists and
illusionists who populate these tales don't know when to stop. The
author reveals ``splendid flashes of absurdity and satire'' and a
``rich, sly sense of humor'' as he explores our complex response to
``the products and projections of our own minds,'' Patrick McGrath
wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAGNEY &LR;  By John McCabe. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $14.95. Cagney the man
was hardly the tough guy and ebullient showman he portrayed on
screen: He was a retiring sort with surprisingly refined tastes,
the former ghostwriter of his autobiography maintains. This
``revealing biography'' exceeds ``the half-dozen previous books on
the actor at illuminating the private Cagney,'' David Hajdu wrote
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Another iconic entertainer is profiled in  &UR; MAN ON THE FLYING
TRAPEZE: THE LIFE AND TIMES OF W.C. FIELDS &LR; , by Simon Louvish
(Norton, $18), which recalls the actor's early vaudevillian career
as a world-class pantomime juggler and does its best to sift
through the ``acres of flamboyant flim-flam'' that obscured his
past. ``Besides proffering anecdotes, Louvish does a heroic job of
filling in Fields' life,'' Katharine Whittemore wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ALL-TRUE TRAVELS AND ADVENTURES OF LIDIE NEWTON &LR;  By Jane
Smiley. Fawcett/Ballantine, $12.95. The spunky 20-year-old narrator
blossoms into a committed abolitionist when she and her husband
journey to the Kansas Territory in the 1850s and are forced to cope
with hardscrabble prairie life and nasty pro-slavers. Until it
lapses into a ``feminist revenge fantasy,'' the novel is
``consistently entertaining, filled with action and ideas,'' Thomas
Mallon wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EDITH WHARTON MURDERS &LR;  By Lev Raphael. St. Martin's,
$11.95. The moderator of a conference of hostile Wharton scholars
at a Michigan university turns reluctant sleuth when a celebrated
author turns up dead. The result is a ``maliciously funny campus
mystery'' that satirizes ``the intellectual jealousies and
political rivalries ... in academic communities,'' Marilyn Stasio
wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRASSAI: LETTERS TO MY PARENTS &LR;  Translated by Peter Laki and
Barna Kantor. University of Chicago, $16. The Hungarian-born
photographer Brassai (1899-1984) recounts in exuberant fashion his
efforts to support himself as an aspiring young artist in Berlin
and Paris. In 1997 Christine Schwartz Hartley called this a
``delightful volume'' that is ``rich in anecdotes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIGHT OF MANY DREAMS &LR;  By Gail Tsukiyama. St. Martin's Griffin,
$12.95. This novel centers on two sisters from Hong Kong growing up
during and after World War II and the family rituals that bind
them. Last year the reviewer Bill Kent admired the ``evocative
scenes of a wonderfully unexotic, warmheartedly domestic Hong
Kong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
