<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRANKLIN-SEMIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURY FORCES AGASSI TO GIVE UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Youth may have been served Saturday in the
semifinals of the Franklin Templeton Tennis Classic at the Canadian
Pacific Scottsdale Princess.
</P>
<P>
   But third-seeded Andre Agassi certainly wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Tied, 3-3, with 21-year-old Jan-Michael Gambill in the first
set, Agassi reached for a backhand shot and strained a hamstring in
his right leg. He tried to continue playing. It was evident that
Agassi was in pain and not moving well. He hurt it again when
reaching to return a shot. He fell behind, 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   Then to the disappointment of the crowd, Agassi was forced to
resign, sending Gambill into today's 1 p.m. final against
18-year-old Australian Lleyton Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt beat fellow countryman Mark Woodforde in straight sets,
6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt is the youngest player on the ATP Tour. Woodforde, at 33,
was the oldest player in this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill, of Colbert, Wash., upset the world's top player, Pete
Sampras, in the second round. Hewitt did the same to second-seeded
Patrick Rafter. Hewitt has won one ATP Tour tournament, and this
will be his second final. Gambill never has played in an ATP final.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Angelo Mattalino, a Scottsdale orthopedic surgeon, treated
Agassi after the match and said the hamstring strain ``appears at
this time to be mild.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattalino said Agassi will be given anti-swelling and
anti-inflammatory medications, electrical stimulation and ice.
</P>
<P>
   He said Agassi will be treated again this morning, then decide
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a hamstring injury,'' Agassi said. ``It was a
sharp pain, and I knew something was wrong. I walked it off at
first, but when I tried to play again and kind of stepped over on a
pass shot, I felt it again. It's rather stiff and painful now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I tried to go on, something worse could happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi said in 48 hours he should know whether he can play at
this week's ATP Tour event at Indian Wells, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to have something good happen,'' Agassi said. ``I was
playing well. I thought it could be a 4-2 (6-4, 6-2) match. ``If I
had gone on I wouldn't have been worth a damn anyhow.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill said he never hoped to get to his first final like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to play him,'' he said. ``He's my hero and
always has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hollow feeling (winning like this). I was hitting the
ball good. It was a well-played match.'' Gambill said his serve has
improved considerably since he arrived in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practiced it this morning, and I'm getting in a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing Hewitt, whom he has never played, will be a different
kind of match, Gambill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have a huge serve,'' Gambill said. ``But I'm going
to run and run and run. He doesn't miss very many balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt and Woodforde are from the same city in Australia,
Adelaide. Woodforde is better know as a doubles player. He and his
partner have won five Wimbledon titles.
</P>
<P>
   This was their second meeting. Hewitt has won both.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can wave the singles flag over Adelaide,'' Woodforde said,
``and I can fly the doubles banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite winning only four games, Woodforde said he didn't think
it was a whipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically made a lot of errors,'' he said. ``I had to go for
it. The other day I was attacking pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sort of surprised. He doesn't hit the ball hard at all.
It comes across softly. But he moves so quickly. I didn't move fast
enough to respond. I had no rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great set of legs. He's fast. He's very classy at
that point. The next step is that he has to strengthen up a little
bit.'' Hewitt has been compared to American Michael Chang, a
counterpuncher on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He relies entirely on an opponent's errors,'' Woodforde said.
``He baits you. That's what makes him good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt agreed that the match was better than the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy out there,'' he said. ``Really, it was pretty
tough. I kept him guessing. I lofted a lot of balls.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Gimelstob of Miami and Richey Reneberg of Atlanta
advanced to the doubles final and will meet Mark Knowles of the
Bahamas and Australian Sandon Stolle.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are playing together for the first time in this
tournament. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
