<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRANKLIN-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWINS' DOUBLES LOSS DISAPPOINTS CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - All good things must come to an end, and
they did Saturday afternoon for the doubles team of  &UR; Bob and  &UR; Mike
Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old identical twins were the darlings of this
tournament. It's hard to tell them apart except on the court. Bob
is left-handed, while Mike hits from the right.
</P>
<P>
   When they were junior players, they frequented the Fiesta Bowl
Tournament. They went to college at Stanford for two years, and
they won the NCAA title last season.
</P>
<P>
   They joined the Association of Tennis Professionals Tour last
summer and made the semifinals once before playing in the Franklin
Templeton Tennis Classic here. Again, they reached the semifinals.
Familiar with them because of their play in the West, the tennis
crowd was quick to hop on their bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   They were disappointed Saturday when  &UR; Mark Knowles of the
Bahamas and
 &UR; Sandon Stolle of Australia beat them in straight sets, 6-2, 7-6
(8-6).
</P>
<P>
   The Bryans led, 6-5, in the tiebreaker before dropping the
match. &QL; 
They'll meet again &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Woodforde, the oldest player in the tournament at 33, will get
a chance for revenge again this week after losing to 18-year-old
 &UR; Lleyton
 &UR; Hewitt, the youngest player, in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   They'll meet in the first round of the ATP Tour event at Indian
Wells, Calif., just outside Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   The following week, the players will move to Key Biscayne, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Both are Mercedes Super 9 tournaments and usually draw the top
30 players in the world because of the purses. The Franklin
Templeton is a warm-up for the next two tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The purse for this tournament is $350,000 plus incentive money
that makes the total about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Wells has a $2.45 million purse and Key Biscayne $2.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Woodforde and Hewitt both live in Adelaide, Australia. But they
had met only once before, in January 1998 in Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who was 16 at the time, beat Woodforde, 4-6, 7-6 (7-1),
in the second round and ultimately won his only tournament on the
tour.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first semifinal in tour history when two players
from Adelaide met in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   After winning in the quarterfinals Friday, Woodforde was out to
even things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we played it was a bit of an upset,''he said,
``and I would like to get a bit of revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 0013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
