<HEADER>
A0681 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMA     03-07 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY DUCKS ARE PECKING AT COYOTES' HEELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reality has reached up and smacked the Coyotes square in the
face like an errant high stick. It has cut them badly.
</P>
<P>
   If they manage to lose tonight to the expansion Nashville
Predators, and if Anaheim can find a way to beat Detroit, the
Mighty Ducks will be just one point behind Phoenix in the battle
for the fourth playoff seed in the Western Conference and the
all-important home-ice advantage in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim did it to the Coyotes two years ago, wrestling away the
No. 4 seed in the final week of the regular season and then
dispatching the Coyotes in the opening round in the deciding
seventh game in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Can it happen again, only sooner this time?
</P>
<P>
   ``How many points? Anything's possible,'' Anaheim right wing
 &UR; Teemu
 &UR; Selanne said. ``I don't see any reason why we couldn't do it. But
we haven't even been thinking of catching them because it's been
(such a) hard battle with the teams fighting for playoff spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Ducks were seven points behind the Coyotes last
week, Selanne wasn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nothing,'' he said. ``One good week, it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's here already. The Mighty Ducks have gone 12-3-0 in their
past 15 games, climbing four games above .500 for the first time in
franchise history. The Coyotes have gone 5-10-0 in their past 15
and can forget about catching Dallas for first in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   But Anaheim is taking nothing for granted. The Coyotes might be
looking over their shoulders, but Anaheim is doing its best to keep
looking straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't start focusing on what's behind us or really worry
about what's ahead of us,'' Coach  &UR; Craig Hartsburg said. ``But if
we just keep playing and focusing on the next game, we'll have a
chance to compete with Phoenix for that spot. But right now, our
only focus has to continue to be on ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's fellow All-Star linemate, left wing  &UR; Paul Kariya,
couldn't agree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a long ways away from the end of the season,'' he said.
``Just because we've beaten some teams that are underneath us
doesn't mean we're anything special. We still have a lot of work to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim is 3-0-1 against the Coyotes this season. The teams will
meet twice more, including Saturday at America West Arena in what
figures to be a preview of the playoffs. The fourth seed plays the
fifth, and it's almost a foregone conclusion that they will meet in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't bode well for the Coyotes either that the two-referee
system will be used in the postseason. Obstruction penalties will
be called for every hook, hold and stick infraction. And Anaheim
just happens to have the best power-play unit in the NHL, with a
league-high 66 man-advantage goals. The Coyotes? Despite scoring
two during their 7-2 loss to Detroit on Friday, they rank at the
bottom of the league, tied for last with just 32.
</P>
<P>
   What's it all mean? Anaheim in seven, that's what. &QL; 
Trade winds
</P>
<P>
   Next week, we'll try to give you a rundown on all the possible
moves that are shaping up before the March 23rd NHL trading
deadline. Here's just a sampling of what could be on the horizon:
</P>
<P>
   After re-signing  &UR; Trevor Kidd, Carolina is shopping goalie
 &UR; Artus Irbe, perhaps to Edmonton in a multi-player deal. New Jersey
also may want to deal with the Oilers, possibly sending  &UR; Sheldon
Souray and  &UR; Sergei
 &UR; Brylin and a second-round pick for  &UR; Boris Mironov and  &UR; Dean
McAmmond.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, Philadelphia, Dallas and even the Coyotes might be
interested in Rangers physical defenseman  &UR; Ulf Samuelsson. Chicago
wants to trade for a mobile defenseman and a proven goal scorer and
is willing to give up just about anything _ short of  &UR; Tony Amonte.
The Flyers are willing to move recently acquired  &UR; Andrei Kovalenko,
and Carolina's  &UR; Martin Gelinas, a former 35-goal scorer, could also
be on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Other rumors making the circuit include the Oilers willing to
part with veteran backup goalie  &UR; Mikhail Shtalenkov (to Phoenix?)
for a draft pick or a minor-league prospect; Buffalo moving  &UR; Wayne
Primeau in addition to always-on-the-block  &UR; Matthew Barnaby, Derek
Plante and  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Wilson; and the Devils perhaps parting with center  &UR; Jason Arnott to
anyone for the right price. &QL; 
Fuhr not charmed
</P>
<P>
   Repeated injuries to  &UR; Grant Fuhr have just about left the future
Hall of Famer forgotten in St. Louis, where the Blues are now on
their fifth goalie after former Vezina Trophy winner  &UR; Jim Carey was
acquired last week from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr is supposed to be back well before the playoffs, assuming
St. Louis gets there, but there are whispers that the Blues might
squeeze him out of the mix now. Would anybody be interested?
Perhaps even the Coyotes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 36, I'm broken down, and I'm expensive,'' Fuhr said.
``Where do I go?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe nowhere, noted his agent,  &UR; Jay Fee, referring to the
plethora of goalies the Blues have stockpiled for various reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're collecting them like charms on a bracelet,'' Fee
said. &QL; 
Robinson safe
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continued woes of the Los Angeles Kings, who are
hanging onto the final playoff spot in the West, Coach  &UR; Larry
Robinson's job appears set. Team President  &UR; Tim Leiweke guaranteed
it during a rather animated chat with reporters recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys have a death watch,'' he said. ``We don't. We're very
patient. Our coaches are going to finish the year. Our players know
their damn careers are on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's contract, though, expires at the end of this season. &QL; 
Road rage
</P>
<P>
   It took the Edmonton Oilers 17 hours to get to Denver last week
for a game against the Avalanche. Their problems started with fog
in the early morning in the Edmonton area, which scrubbed their
flight the day before the game.
</P>
<P>
   So they chartered a bus to take them to nearby Calgary for the
flight out. That worked fine, until the bus broke down on the way.
By the time a new bus picked them up and got them to Calgary, they
had to wait an additional five hours in the airport for their
flight.
</P>
<P>
   At 1 a.m., the Oilers finally made it, which made them all a
little giddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing missing,'' rookie  &UR; Tom Potti said, ``was a
flaming plane crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Ron Low said, ``With good shoes, I likely could have
walked there faster.''
</P>
<P>
   But the best line of the day might have been delivered by
play-by-play voice  &UR; Rod Phillips, who quipped: ``We knew about this
trip to Denver since August when the schedule first came out, and
 &UR; Theo
 &UR; Fleury beat us to Colorado with three hours' notice after he was
traded.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at &QL; 
bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
