<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS, SPURS COACHES FIND JOBS IN PERIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The season is just more than a quarter over, the Lakers already
have fired  &UR; Del Harris, and two more coaches are on shaky ground.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets and the San Antonio Spurs have been the
league's biggest busts, and coaches  &UR; John Calipari of the Nets and
 &UR; Gregg
 &UR; Popovich of the Spurs are feeling the heat.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, the Spurs have begun to show some life and went
into Saturday night's game against the Clippers at the .500 mark.
It should be noted that the Spurs started last season 10-10 before
going 52-10 the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Popovich is being questioned for making second-year
center  &UR; Tim
 &UR; Duncan his first offensive option this season.  &UR; David Robinson, the
club's centerpiece for so long, often has appeared lost. There has
been speculation that Robinson's back isn't completely healthy. His
psyche probably hurts even more.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich's strategy hasn't worked. The Spurs, despite the return
of forward  &UR; Sean Elliott and the additions of  &UR; Mario Elie and
 &UR; Steve Kerr in the off-season, have had a difficult time scoring
points.  &UR; Peter Holt, the chief owner of the club, has pledged
support _ so far.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich also is the club's general manager, which complicates
matters. He might be wise to make a move himself rather than risk
losing both jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The man believed to be the likely candidate to replace Popovich
in such a scenario is  &UR; Doc Rivers, who lives in the Alamo City and
works as an analyst for Turner Sports.
</P>
<P>
   He has an out clause in his broadcasting contract that is
supposed to apply only after the season, but it's unlikely that
Turner, a coaching springboard these days, would stand in the way
of Rivers going to the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The struggles of the Spurs are a mystery, but nothing compared
to what is happening at New Jersey. With a nucleus that includes
 &UR; Jayson Williams, Keith Van Horn and  &UR; Kerry
 &UR; Kittles, the Nets were regarded as one of the up-and-coming clubs.
The team signed Williams to the maximum allowable contract
extension in the off-season, and it appeared the team was ready to
replace the Knicks as the best team in the Gotham area.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they've stumbled. Williams is playing with a torn thumb
ligament that makes it difficult for him to grab rebounds, which is
his strength. He isn't producing any offense. Point guard  &UR; Sam
Cassell has been out with an injury and is rumored to be on his way
to Milwaukee for  &UR; Terrell Brandon. The trading deadline is four
days away.
</P>
<P>
   There are reports that the players already have begun to tune
Calipari out. It's unlikely the Nets will fire Calipari, but he has
an option clause that would allow him to escape the remainder of
his contract this summer. He might be tempted to use it. &QL; 
It adds up &QL; 
Is  &UR; George Shinn about to unload the Charlotte Hornets?  &UR; Robert
L. &UR; Johnson, chief executive officer of Black Entertainment
Television, whose company has a value of $1.2 billion, has
expressed interest in purchasing the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely intrigued,'' Johnson told the ``Charlotte
Observer.'' ``But it has to be up for sale. And I don't know if
it's up for sale (in reality) or up for sale to price it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has approached investment bankers to determine whether
they've been contacted by Shinn looking for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Shinn has fueled the speculation by moving his legal residence
to Florida, where he has owned a home for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has no state income tax. North Carolina's state tax is
7.75 percent. Now, if Shinn were about to make a $100 million
windfall from, say, selling an NBA basketball team, it would figure
that he wouldn't want to shell out $7.75 million to North
Carolina. &QL; 
Taking a dive &QL; 
Dallas Mavericks Coach  &UR; Don Nelson has always been a
non-conformist. He drew the league's ire by essentially forfeiting
a game to Utah. He pulled all his starters once the Jazz had a
double-digit first-quarter lead. Utah won, 80-65.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't even present a challenge,'' Jazz forward  &UR; Bryon
Russell said. ``I don't even know what tactic Don Nelson was using.
I guess he gave up already.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what he did. Nelson's logic was that, with the
game scheduled between Denver and Sacramento, it was in his best
interest to try to win two of the three. The Mavericks had defeated
Denver and ended up beating Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never coached a game like that, but I've never been in a
season like this, either,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, the NBA office contacted Nelson, but there was no
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Fans pay to see teams give their best effort, at least until the
game is out of reach. A double-digit lead in the first quarter is
common. Resting the starters in the fourth quarter would have been
fine. Giving up in the first quarter is stealing from the paying
public. &QL; 
Not so fast &QL; 
Maybe those predictions of Chicago suffering forever in lottery
land were premature.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Bulls are as bad as expected. But apparently they've
gotten a boss.  &UR; Jerry Krause may hold the title of operations
chief, but it's beginning to sound as if agent  &UR; David Falk is
holding some strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I represent, among others, three very talented players who
could become free agents this summer,'' Falk said recently ``They
are
 &UR; Stephon Marbury (Timberwolves point guard),  &UR; Kerry Kittles (Nets
shooting guard) and  &UR; Vitaly Potapenko (Cavaliers center). I also
have good relations with (Bulls owner)  &UR; Jerry Reinsdorf and with
Jerry Krause. I like working with them, and we've always worked
some good deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves, Nets and Cavaliers have until March 13 to sign
those players to contract extensions, which might be all Falk is
attempting to leverage. But he may also try to broker all three
into Chicago. Falk argues that under the new collective bargaining
agreement, players will ask for an early termination option clause
in their contracts after five years. Thus, there isn't a big
advantage in re-signing with the club the player is with,
particularly if it's a small-market team.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsements and other off-the-court earnings are maximized in a
major market, such as Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to get three or four quality young players to come
to the Bulls at the same time,'' said Falk, sounding a lot more
like GM than agent. ``Forget the names of the players. But I would
love to bring three or four guys to the Bulls at the same time.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob Young can be
reached at 602-444-8271 or at bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
