<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-PAIRINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO ARE BEST BETS TO LOSE TO DUKE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here's one way to look at today's highly anticipated,
greatly awaited announcement of the teams, seedings and brackets
for the NCAA basketball tournament:
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't really matter.
</P>
<P>
   Why should it? No one is going to beat Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils, who went unbeaten during the Atlantic Coast
Conference regular season and will wrap up the ACC Tournament when
they beat North Carolina by 30 today, are everybody's choice to win
the last national championship before that Y2K thing wreaks such
havoc with the computer rankings that next year's champ will be
Quinnipiac.
</P>
<P>
   Even Monica Lewinsky and Ken Starr agree (or would if they were
asked, probably): Duke is No. 1, and everyone else is way, way
outside college basketball's beltway. So who cares what Digger,
Dick and Billy, not to mention Spanky, Alfalfa and Buckwheat, have
to say about the rest of the field, about who gets in and who
doesn't, about the seedings and the sites?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, we all do. That's why we love what has become known as
``Selection Sunday.'' It's why teams have been giving their all
during what we call ``Championship Week,'' and why ``the Big
Dance,'' and ``on the bubble'' have become what are known as
``obnoxious cliches'' that we keep using because there really
aren't any other words in the English language that quite sum it
all up.
</P>
<P>
   So let's start by figuring out the No. 1 seeds, knowing full
well that at least one No. 1 seed has made the Final Four every
year since 1979, but only twice have three No. 1 seeds made it and
never all four. In other words, it's good, but not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   There is Duke, of course, and Connecticut, which destroyed St.
John's to win the Big East Tournament championship Saturday night.
Michigan State has to play the hottest team on the planet, hotter
even than Duke, today in the Big Ten Tournament final. That team,
of course, is Illinois, which has racked up upset after upset.
Until today. The Fighting Illini will fight but lose, and the
Spartans will win and be a No. 1 seed. Should the unheard of happen
and Illinois wins, it doesn't matter who the No. 1 seeds are
because the entire NCAA Tournament will be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   One big question regarding the final No. 1 seed _ Stanford or
Auburn? _ apparently was resolved late Saturday night when Stanford
lost at Oregon State. Sorry, folks, but no way the Cardinal should
be a top seed. Losing to the Beavers isn't quite the same as Auburn
losing to Kentucky in the Southeastern Conference Tournament
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Stanford had won, Auburn still deserved it. Why? Think
back to Feb. 6, which technically is less than a month ago because
February has just 28 days (except in a leap year, which this is
not. Nor will next year be, because that Y2K thing will mess up all
the calendars). It was then that Connecticut hopped a plane, flew
3,000 miles to play at Stanford, learned that its best player,
Richard Hamilton, was in too much pain to play and then beat the
Cardinal, 70-59. That was telling.
</P>
<P>
   Or try this: Imagine Auburn and Stanford playing on a neutral
site. Can't you just picture the Auburn players flying past
Stanford's as if they were glued to the floor? Auburn is faster,
quicker, more athletic and ultimately better. Which doesn't mean
the tournament selection committee will see it that way, but it
should.
</P>
<P>
   Now, where will the No. 1 seeds play? The conventional wisdom is
that Duke is headed to the East regional, where it can play its
first- and second-round games in Charlotte, N.C., which is located
three 7-Elevens from its campus. This seems right, because it
sounds so much like something the NCAA would do.
</P>
<P>
   Adhering to geography, that would logically place Auburn in the
South, Michigan State in the Midwest and . . . Connecticut in the
West. OK, look, don't tell Rand McNally.
</P>
<P>
   There were several upsets in the conference tournaments _ North
Carolina over Maryland, North Carolina-Charlotte over Cincinnati,
Illinois over everybody _ that make the rest of the top-seeded
teams a scramble. It will be interesting to see how much weight the
committee places on tournament losses. It also would be interesting
to see the room service bill after nine guys stay cooped up in a
hotel suite for several days.
</P>
<P>
   And what of UCLA, which lost big at Arizona on Saturday and
might have lost its best player, point guard Baron Davis, for the
first two games with an injured toe? Even with the loss, the Bruins
were no worse than a No. 4 seed. Without Davis, or with a wobbly
Davis, they might drop.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of the Pac-10, when Oregon lost to Stanford on
Thursday, the Ducks lost out on the tournament. California did the
same _ or should have _ by losing to Oregon on Saturday. But you
never know. The Pac-10 is popular, and Cal might get in. If not,
it's Stanford, Arizona, UCLA and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Cal's players and coaches will be engaged in a group
sweat-a-thon awaiting today's announcement. But the Golden Bears
will have company. Purdue and Minnesota, who were supposed to give
the Big Ten seven tournament teams, have lately played like they
couldn't beat Quinnipiac.
</P>
<P>
   Will the mighty ACC only get three teams in? Even though only
three teams really, really deserve it, it's unlikely. North
Carolina State or Wake Forest _ but please, not both _ probably
gets a bid.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma and Nebraska, not long ago considered shoo-ins for the
tournament, are in danger of becoming shoo-outs. Rutgers' prospects
are sinking into the New Jersey swamps. DePaul and
Alabama-Birmingham, Southwest Missouri State and Evansville,
Mississippi State and Mississippi and Toledo probably didn't sleep
well Saturday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
