<HEADER>
A0691 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-KINGS-AZR &LR;      03-07 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-KINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS GET BOOED AND DESERVE IT  
 FALL FLAT ON FACES IN LOSS TO KINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - That wasn't ``Gooooogs'' you heard emanating from
America West Arena on Saturday night. It wasn't ``Luuuuuuuc,''
either.
</P>
<P>
   Those were boos, baby.
</P>
<P>
   They came as loud and lusty as Suns fans have given it to the
home team since their abysmal 0-13 start in 1996-97. And the Suns
earned every bit of it.
</P>
<P>
   They backed up the most complete game they have played all
season in Seattle on Thursday night with their most complete
disaster in a 111-99 loss to the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings hadn't won in Phoenix in 24 tries before breaking
through earlier this season. Led by Jason Williams, the rookie
point guard with brass and flash, the Kings led by 23 in the first
half and coasted to their second win in a row at America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we like this arena now,'' Kings center Vlade Divac
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Suns who don't seem to like it. They fell to 4-5 on
their own floor .
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a damn shame,'' forward George McCloud said. ``In this
league, you've got to play hard every night, and you've got to
protect your home court. We didn't play smart, we jacked up bad
shots, and we played soft.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty fair assessment. And Coach Danny Ainge said the
booing was fair, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to show up here for our home fans,'' Ainge said.
``They were booing us, and they should be. If I had paid to see
that game, I would have been very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   While beating the Kings hasn't been a problem for the Suns in
the recent past, it was an important game for the Suns this time.
With the earlier victory in Phoenix and only one more meeting
between the clubs during this lockout-shortened season, Sacramento
already has captured the head-to-head tiebreaker for playoff
position.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (8-9) figure to be one of the teams the Suns (9-8) are
battling with for one of the final Western Conference postseason
berths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was,'' Sacramento Coach Rick Adelman
said. ``The first half was probably as well as we've played. We
shot it well, we passed it well. We were so active that we got them
back on their heels.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Suns were a step behind in transition
defense, giving layups, dunks, three-point shots, whatever the
Kings wanted in the first half. It wasn't even that the Suns
fumbled along on the offensive end.
</P>
<P>
   But they couldn't even inbound the ball on a couple of occasions
without throwing it away and finished with a season-high 21
turnovers that led to 20 Sacramento points. The Kings turned it
over 22 times themselves, but they came into the game leading the
league in turnovers with their up-tempo, freewheeling style.
</P>
<P>
   During one miserable second-quarter stretch, the Suns managed to
get only one shot off in six possessions, and missed that one. A
smattering of boos sprinkled the crowd during a timeout with 9:13
to go in the second period after the Kings started on a 7-2 run.
</P>
<P>
   The hoots got a little more intense after Jon Barry stole an
inbound pass from Danny Manning and hit a three-point shot. And
they really let the Suns have it when Barry, now made to look like
an All-Star, hit yet another three with 6:47 to go that gave the
Kings a 23-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the margin remained at halftime, with the Kings
leading, 66-43.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, the Suns raised their defensive effort,
Tom Gugliotta got going offensively, and they got back into the
game by forcing seven Sacramento turnovers, which the Suns
converted for eight points. The result was a 29-point Phoenix
quarter. A 9-2 finish cut the Kings' lead to 14.
</P>
<P>
   With Jason Kidd playing full out on his way to 21 points, 11
assists, nine rebounds and five steals, the Suns kept the run going
early in the fourth quarter, trimming it to 10 with 10:09 to play
on Clifford Robinson's short jump hook.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Suns cut the Kings lead to eight points on a
couple of occasions, but they expended too much to get back into it
and never came any closer.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said it wasn't just the defense, the passing or the
sloppiness with the ball that were to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's an attitude,'' Ainge said. ``It's effort. We can
have any kind of defense we want, if we play it like we did tonight
with no urgency, no pride, we have nights like this. It's not the
first time it's happened to us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
