<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0692 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-LEWIS-HOLYFIELD-A     03-07 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-HOLYFIELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD MAKES HEARTY CLAIM  
 VOWS KO IN 3RD ROUND VS. LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's a quiet man in a very loud place. If it weren't for the
punches he throws and takes, it would be easy to say he doesn't
belong at all.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something else about Evander Holyfield. The
self-proclaimed humble warrior has strung together more surprises
than nearly anybody still active in a conflicted business built on
schlock and shock.
</P>
<P>
   The fighter with a couple of upsets over Mike Tyson at the price
of his ears is noted for his courage. He's said to have a great
heart. That's a cliche, but a diagnosed coronary problem a few
years ago was not. He's a religious man who fathered two children
with a woman other than his wife, Janice.
</P>
<P>
   Humble, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing simple about him or, perhaps, any other
great fighter. Survival isn't always simple. It's often about
throwing the unseen punch or acting in a fashion contrary to what
is assumed or expected.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is at it again.
</P>
<P>
   In stark contrast to his reputation for humility, he said in a
conference call last week that he would knock out Lennox Lewis in
the third round next Saturday at New York's Madison Square Garden
in a bout that will unify the heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not predicting,'' said the preacher-turned-prophet, who
repeated the promise Friday night on the ``Tonight Show with Jay
Leno.'' ``I am telling you and everyone: I am knocking him out in
the third round.''
</P>
<P>
   From a fighter not known to boast, it was matter-of-fact. There
were no flourishes, but it still had the confident ring that used
to come with pronouncements from Muhammad Ali, who will be in the
Valley this week for a benefit on behalf of the Parkinson's
Research Center that stands in his name at the Barrow Neurological
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   From Lewis' perspective, it was a sign of panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fail to see the realism in that,'' Lewis said last week,
also in a conference call. ``Evander Holyfield has never knocked
anybody out in three rounds. Me being his toughest opponent out
there, I still fail to see the realism in that kind of comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's interesting that he is making predictions for the
first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his corner is surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of came as a shock to me,'' Holyfield trainer Don
Turner said in still another conference call. ``But I took it a
step further and asked him: `What are the other two rounds for?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure when he said something like that, Lennox Lewis
changed gears.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Holyfield and Lewis have been verbally sparring in an
attempt to gain a psychological edge before the best heavyweight
clash at Madison Square Garden since Joe Frazier's stirring
decision over Ali on March 8, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has been charging Holyfield with hypocrisy for fathering
children out of wedlock while being very public about his religious
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only speaking from reality,'' said Lewis, the World Boxing
Council champion and the underdog in his attempt to take the World
Boxing Association and International Boxing Federation titles from
Holyfield. ``I'm only saying what people think. If I say that I
don't drink, yet I go out and drink, then I am a hypocrite. Simple
as that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just stating the obvious. For him to get upset makes me
believe that the truth hurts. That's actually happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's not clear at all. Holyfield has possessed an
almost eerie sense of calm in the moments before his last few
fights. As Tyson raged and glared in the long walk from the
dressing room to the ring, Holyfield smiled and cast his eyes
skyward. It was almost as if he knew he couldn't lose.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of people who believe Holyfield will fall this
time. At 6-foot-2 and a projected 215 pounds, he's had difficulty
against bigger heavyweights. Riddick Bowe and George Foreman are
two examples. At 6-foot-5 and a projected 250, Lewis is big, very
big.
</P>
<P>
   But there are doubts about whether Lewis has more than imposing
size and a powerful punch. His courage _ his willingness to fight _
has been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``How dare they question my heart,'' said Lewis, who was knocked
out by Oliver McCall and has never faced Tyson, Bowe or even
Foreman. ``Holyfield doesn't have the monopoly on hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to. One heart _ Holyfield's own _ has been more
than enough for an ever-surprising fighter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
