<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0693 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-GOALIES-A     03-07 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-GOALIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOAL DISORIENTED  
 KHABIBULIN'S INJURY LEAVES COYOTES IN JAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As quandaries go, the one the Coyotes face with their
goaltending situation is a beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Nikolai Khabibulin is bothered by a tender groin and any
decision on whether to start him tonight against Nashville will be
made by exercising overwhelming caution. Indications are he will
play because emergency backup Scott Langkow was returned to Utah of
the International Hockey League on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With the Coyotes having lost nine of their past 10 games, and
Anaheim breathing down their neck just three points behind in the
race for the Western Conference's No. 4 seed _ including home-ice
advantage in the first round of the playoffs _ an understandable
urge is to rush Khabibulin back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Niki is our man. We can't afford to rush him back before he's
ready,'' Keith Tkachuk said. ``We don't want to go into the
playoffs with him hurting, or without him. That would be too
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Backup goalie Jimmy Waite was sensational while starting the
season with a 6-0-2 record. But he has not won a game since Dec. 9,
when he bested Montreal, 4-2, and has gone 0-5-2 since.
</P>
<P>
   The team sent him to Springfield of the American Hockey League
for six games to work on his sagging confidence. His return Friday
night was greeted by disaster as he allowed Detroit four goals on
10 shots and was pulled in the second period for Langkow, who was
summoned from Utah Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of their goals were pretty good ones,'' Waite said.
``One came on a good deflection and on another one they skated in
two-on-one and put it by me. I don't think anyone would have
stopped those goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it definitely wasn't the kind of night I hoped for. It's
been tough on me and tough on the team. I was sent to Springfield
and I was feeling good down there. I didn't give up any bad goals
and it was good to play in a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Langkow is basically untested at the NHL level, which makes him
a reluctant choice for play down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on,'' said Langkow, who started the
season at Las Vegas of the IHL before moving to Utah when the
Coyotes terminated their agreement with Las Vegas. ``If I get a
chance to play, great. If not, I'll be ready if I do get some
action. I can't worry about things I can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   But unless Waite steps up, Khabibulin's work load, which saw him
work 22 of 25 games while acquiring his injury, is not going to be
eased. His tender groin will be overly exposed entering the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Is a trade a possibility? League sources say Edmonton is
shopping backup Mikhail Shtalenko, who is 12-16-3 this season with
a 2.61 goals-against average. However, Coyotes General Manager
Bobby Smith said it is difficult to trade for goalies right now.
</P>
<P>
   Each NHL team must expose a goalie in the upcoming expansion
draft. After Jan. 4, to be exposed a goalie must have played 15
games (a minimum of 31 minutes constitutes a game) this season, or
25 in the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say if the Islanders traded Tommy Salo. It would mean they
would have to then acquire a goalie who has played in 15 NHL games,
or expose Felix Potvin to expansion,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   If Shtalenko were dealt, the Oilers would face the same dilemma
with No. 1 goalie Bob Essensa, leaving them without a top goalie.
</P>
<P>
   So it's hoped Waite regains his early season form _ quickly. And
he'll have to do it with a defense missing Gerald Diduck (broken
foot) and Jyrki Lumme (shoulder) for most of the final six weeks of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy had a tough night against Detroit,'' Coach Jim
Schoenfeld said. ``I don't want to throw this whole thing on him
because it's not right to do. He was probably the only person who
felt worse than I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll be able to rally around him the next time
he's in net. Goaltending can give a team a big boost, or take the
life out of it, like it did Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky added, ``We are allowing too many
scoring chances. Sooner or later, any goalie is going to give up
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Khabibulin, he said his groin was sore after Saturday's
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too bad, but it's in the same spot as last year,''
said Khabibulin, who didn't know if he'll be able to play tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
