<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0694 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ASU-USC-AZR &LR;      03-07 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-USC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER CLOSE LOSS ENDS ASU'S SEASON  
 EVANS QUESTIONS HIS PLAYERS' WILL TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Arizona State's basketball past was honored
Saturday, after which the present came to an abrupt halt.
</P>
<P>
   On a day the court was named for former Coach Ned Wulk, the Sun
Devils needed to beat Southern California in the last game of the
year to earn consideration for the NIT and prolong their first
season under new Coach Rob Evans.
</P>
<P>
   To pull that off, ASU had to reverse an annoying trend of
getting crunched during crunch time. It needed to find a resolve
and inner strength lacking during many second halves this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Devils again failed at that and lost, 84-73, to an
athletic but otherwise nondescript USC team in front of 7,308 at
Ned Wulk Court. ASU's seventh defeat in eight games left it with a
14-16 record, 6-12 in the Pac-10, which was better than only
Washington State. There will be no postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   The loss also left Evans relieved the season is over, which
seemed unthinkable considering his competitive drive and spirit.
But therein lies the problem; such drive and spirit probably
exceeded the team's as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's hard to coach when you feel you want it more
than the guys out there,'' he said. ``But those are traits that are
learned. . . .I can't make them want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans certainly tried, however, using heretofore unseen
combinations of players and taking a technical foul to try to
ignite a spark. And it temporarily worked. With walk-on Brad Nahra
and former walk-on Ron DuBois on the floor, and Evans getting T'ed
up right in front of a courtside Booker Turner, the Pac-10
coordinator of officials, the Sun Devils turned a 52-42 deficit
with 11:36 to go into a 55-54 lead over the next four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Evans was concerned he had to resort to the equivalent of
CPR to restore a heartbeat to his club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing everything we could on the sidelines to get them
moving,'' he said. ``They weren't moving very well on the offensive
end. I took every timeout I could to get them to move. And then I
just decided to see if I could fire them up a little bit, by making
some changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought in a couple of guys and I was hoping, like I told
them in the huddle when I got the technical, to make it a them
against us type thing. But it says a little about your situation
when you have two walk-ons that come in, and those are the guys
that get you going. That's difficult for me to understand. I
understand it, but it's difficult to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   And the problem with artificial stimulation is that it's just
that, artificial, and usually doesn't last. So neither did ASU's
lead. On the next USC possession, Eddie House fouled Elias Ayuso on
a three-point attempt. Ayuso made all three foul shots to put the
Trojans up, 57-55. Then, after ASU guard Alton Mason lost the ball,
Adam Spanich was left open to hit a three-point basket, and USC
(15-12, 7-11) led by five.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils twice got to within one, but could not force the
stop they needed. USC, which shot 65.2 percent in the second half
and 60.8 percent for the game, kept making baskets and free throws.
</P>
<P>
   In his final game, ASU senior forward Bobby Lazor had 30 points
and 11 rebounds. His fellow senior, forward Mike Batiste, had 17
points. But the 6-foot-8 Batiste had just two rebounds, three fewer
than House, a 6-1 guard. This also was the last game for DuBois,
who got to start.
</P>
<P>
   House, a junior who leads the Sun Devils in scoring, made just 2
of 8 shots and had five points, a season-low. He suffered a
slightly sprained ankle in the second half, but didn't use that as
a reason. Actually, he had no reason for his play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said, letting out a big sigh. ``I'm just
ready to go home to my family, to tell you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   House, Batiste and Lazor all made the 10-player All Pac-10 team,
and no other team had three players on it. One left off was Ayuso,
a senior guard who made 9 of 13 shots for 25 points. That tied a
career-high set last year, also against the Sun Devils.
</P>
<P>
   USC sophomore forward Brian Scalabrine made 9 of 10 shots and
scored 21 points, two days after he was scoreless against Arizona.
Evans said keeping the ball away from Scalabrine and double-teaming
when he did get it was stressed in practice, but failed to
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a nice basketball player, but you get out and attack him,
battle him, he's not the most versatile, agile player,'' Evans
said. ``But you don't get to him, he's a very skilled player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
