r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-A     03-07 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL LIKELY TO FOLLOW WOM ACK IN LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ It is a virtual certainty that  &UR; Tony Womack will be the
Diamondbacks' leadoff hitter most of the season. But who will draw
the No. 2 assignment of moving him along and setting the table for
the heavy hitters _  &UR; Steve Finley, Travis Lee and  &UR; Matt Williams?
</P>
<P>
   The man most likely to be in that spot is veteran  &UR; Jay Bell, who
also is moving from shortstop to second base.
</P>
<P>
   Bell has four hits in his first eight at-bats while hitting
second this spring, including two in Saturday's 11-6 victory over
the Chicago White Sox at Tucson Electric Park. It was Arizona's
second straight win after dropping its opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of different scenarios, depending on
match-ups and so forth, but Jay seems to be a good fit there,''
Manager  &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter said. ``He knows how to handle the bat, usually takes a
lot of pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell began the 1998 season in the No. 2 spot but struggled a bit
and spent most of the second half in the No. 6 spot. He hit at No.
6 57 times, No. 2 47 times, No. 3 30 times and No. 5 16 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable hitting there,'' Bell said. ``I can work the
hit-and-run pretty well, I can bunt the ball, and I walk a lot (81
times last season). I like to drive in runs, but scoring them is
equally important. I'm hoping I can have the best of both worlds,
setting the guys up and maybe driving Tony in if he doubles or gets
on and steals second.'' &QL; 
Kim update &QL; 
General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr. returned to Phoenix late Friday
night and was at Saturday's game after a long trip to South Korea
to set up the move of right-hander  &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim to the
Diamondbacks. The 20-year-old signed Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola visited the U.S. Consulate to get assistance with
paperwork. Once that is completed, Kim will be able to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Kim will join the 40-man roster, Garagiola said, ``When
he arrives, we will watch him and assess where he is, his pitching
shape, and then make a determination on his assignment.'' &QL; 
Short stops &QL; 
The team sent right-handed pitchers  &UR; Brad Penny and  &UR; John Patterson
and left-hander  &UR; Nick Bierbrodt to its minor league camp for
reassignment. Minor league pitchers and catchers will work out
today for the first time. Three more players are expected to be
reassigned today and three more Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander  &UR; Randy Johnson is scheduled to make his first
official Cactus League start today against the Chicago White Sox at
Tucson Electric Park. He pitched two innings against the University
of Arizona on Wednesday and struck out four of the six batters he
faced. There is a chance of showers today, and Showalter said that
if the game is canceled, Johnson likely will throw in simulated
game conditions in one of the covered batting cages. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
