<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE WOMEN EARN NCAA BID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Perhaps when one thinks of big-time Division I
athletics, one doesn't think of Cal State Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when an athlete gets recruited by a Division I
institution that promises big-time exposure and a chance to play in
the NCAA Tournament, Northridge doesn't come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this group of 11 women's basketball players bought into the
dream first presented by Michael Abraham and furthered by Frozena
Jerro: That Northridge can be a school in the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   And it is, by virtue of its 79-65 victory Saturday over Portland
State in the Big Sky Conference tournament final at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone came from big, winning teams,'' guard LaShaunda
Fowler said. ``All of us had the skills.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all fighters,'' post player Neda Milic said. ``We don't
give up.''
</P>
<P>
   From a drug trafficking arrest to two coaching changes to a slow
start, Northridge has seen the lows. Now, it's one of 64 teams in
the penthouse after achieving what many thought was unachievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 11 people on a team that is strong,'' tournament MVP
Edniesha Curry said. ``We've been a family, from preseason to now.
If someone's in trouble, you know you can lean left or right, and
someone's going to be on your back.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA bracket will be announced today on ESPN at 2:15 p.m.
Sources close to Northridge believe the Matadors (21-7) will be
seeded 16th in the West and travel to Colorado State, the expected
top seed in the West Region, for a first-round matchup Thursday or
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the men's tournament, the first two rounds of the women's
tournament are at on-campus sites.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the Matadors' custom, they started slowly before
exploding in the second half Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, also keeping with custom, led the charge, scoring five
points in 19 seconds and 10 points in 3:27 to key a 15-4 Northridge
run that turned a 33-31 lead into a 48-35 advantage with 13:44 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's semifinal victory over Northern Arizona, she scored
17 points in 5:07.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let the game come to me,'' Curry said. ``If I score 20
points in two minutes or 20 points the whole game, it doesn't
matter. I feel the energy from (teammates' defense). That helps me
excel in the offensive end.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry finished with a game-high 23 points. Lynda Amari also made
the all-tournament team with a 14-point, nine-rebound effort. Milic
came off the bench to score 13 points and guard Tina Greer had 10
points.
</P>
<P>
   Portland State (18-10) got 15 points from sophomore forward
Robbie Nix, the conference's Sixth Man Award winner, and 13 points
from guard Monique Zampera. Nix and forward Carrie Hawes (8 points,
8 rebounds) made all-tournament.
</P>
<P>
   PSU coach Jenny Yopp said Northridge's defense played a role
down the stretch. The Vikings were within striking distance,
trailing 67-62, with 3:57 to play, only to be outscored 12-0 in the
next 3:53. The team finished shooting 38.8 percent from the field,
compared to 46.2 percent for Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit goes to Northridge's defense,'' Yopp said. ``They kept
the heat on defensively. The pressure they put on our guards took
us out of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Big Dance awaits. Jerro has been to the NCAAs, as a
player on the 1992 Arizona State team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great when you lay it on the line and you get what you
want,'' she said. ``When you get into the NCAA Tournament, it's one
of the greatest experiences for a college athlete. I'm glad the
girls can experience it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
