<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR SEASON TO START IS THE HARDEST PART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By POALA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - April 5.  &UR; Randy Johnson. Kevin Brown. Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Are we there yet?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Russ Davis' error-prone ways last season (34 in 141 games)
prompted fans to offer the Seattle third baseman some possible
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   One came up with the idea that Davis should play without a, er,
protective cup, suggesting that the sheer terror of such an injury
would help him react.
</P>
<P>
   Position battle of the week: Keep an eye on how things shake out
in center field for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   When  &UR; Ellis Burks re-signed with the team, he insisted on a move
from center to right. That leaves a battle for center among  &UR; Marvin
Benard, who batted .322 as a leadoff hitter last season, veteran
 &UR; Stan Javier and rookie  &UR; Armando Rios.
</P>
<P>
   Only three players on the White Sox spring training roster have
reached their 30th birthdays: designated hitter  &UR; Frank
 &UR; Thomas, pitcher  &UR; Jaime Navarro and pitcher  &UR; Darren Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs' fifth starting spot remains open, with left-hander
 &UR; Terry Mulholland and free-agent acquisition  &UR; Scott Sanders among
the front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle outfielder  &UR; Butch Huskey is petitioning Major League
Baseball for the right to wear 42, the number his idol,  &UR; Jackie
 &UR; Robinson, wore while breaking baseball's color barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey always wore 42 but has 36 in camp because Robinson's
number was retired last season. He has 42 on the back of his
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects worth keeping an eye on:
</P>
<P>
   Angels right-hander  &UR; Ramon Ortiz, whose 94 mph fastball belies
his 6-foot, 165-pound frame, and White Sox pitcher  &UR; Kip Wells, a
6-3, 195-pound right-hander who struck out five of the eight
hitters he faced in a recent intrasquad game.
</P>
<P>
   We're predicting a big year from Cubs outfielder  &UR; Henry
 &UR; Rodriguez, who was slowed by a severe ankle sprain late last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez will be the first left fielder to start consecutive
opening days for the Cubs since  &UR; Brian Dayett 1986 and '87.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor making the Cactus League rounds: The White Sox will send
Navarro to San Diego for closer  &UR; Randy Myers.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to see Colorado's  &UR; Larry Walker, the Most Valuable
Player in 1997 and the National League batting champion in '98,
secure a long-term, big-money deal. Watch for another huge season.
</P>
<P>
   Don't assume pitcher  &UR; Jim Abbott is a gimme when he steps to the
plate this season.
</P>
<P>
   Although Abbott, who was born without a right hand, will be
asked to bunt on occasion, he is more than capable of swinging the
bat and looks better at the plate than some pitchers who were
shellshocked by the offensive requirements of interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott flew out to center in his first spring at-bat Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fire sale in the off-season, let's not forget who
the Padres have at the heart of their order:  &UR; Tony Gwynn,
 &UR; Greg Vaughn and  &UR; Wally Joyner. Add closer  &UR; Trevor Hoffman, and the
team is clearly still competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Only four active players have been with the same teams longer
than the underappreciated and unassuming  &UR; Edgar Martinez, who has
played 12 with Seattle: Baltimore's  &UR; Cal Ripken (18 years), Gwynn
(17), Cincinnati's  &UR; Barry Larkin (13) and Anaheim's  &UR; Chuck Finley
(13).
</P>
<P>
   Words of wisdom:
</P>
<P>
   Chicago White Sox General Manager  &UR; Ron Schueler, on Navarro
missing his first day of camp: ``Maybe he had a visa problem
getting out of Wisconsin where he lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs first baseman  &UR; Mark Grace: ``We're not an old team. Well,
(40-year-old infielder Gary) Gaetti is old.''
</P>
<P>
   This and that:
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a young Cactus League pitcher facing this Seattle order:
 &UR; Alex
 &UR; Rodriguez, Ken Griffey Jr., Martinez,  &UR; David Segui and  &UR; Jay Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs Manager  &UR; Jim Riggleman has set 200 as the maximum number of
innings he'd like to see  &UR; Kerry Wood throw in 1999. Wood was
bothered by elbow problems late last season. &QL; 
Paola Boivin can be reached at 602-444-8956 or at
Paola.Boivin(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
