<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL MISSES CHANCE TO TAKE TOBACCO STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent legislation against the tobacco industry brought one
significant change in major league baseball clubhouses everywhere.
Tobacco companies will no longer be allowed to send free samples of
their products (mostly smokeless tobacco) to players.
</P>
<P>
   With all the information we have on the dangers of using chewing
tobacco, you would think Major League Baseball officials would have
taken an equally strong stance. But a recent memo sent by
Commissioner Bud Selig fell way short of what it could have done.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the memo signed by Selig, reads ``This office strongly
recommends that you not permit your clubhouse attendant to purchase
products for players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Strongly recommends?'' Ooooohhh! Strong stuff there. Selig and
baseball could have taken a cutting edge stance, yet failed.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the Diamondbacks, who have the strongest
anti-tobacco campaign of the 30 clubs, went one step further and
issued their own memo, signed by General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola
Jr., that includes termination for any clubhouse employee who
purchases tobacco for players.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have even gone so far as to offer nicotine
patches and/or whatever type of help is necessary for players
wanting to quit. Doctors from the National Spit Tobacco Education
Program (NSTEP) performed oral examinations on 141 willing players
who use tobacco last spring and found an astonishingly-high 83 with
tobacco-related lesions in their mouths. For 15 of them, diagnostic
biopsies were recommended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask them to think about their wife or girlfriend or
children,'' said  &UR; Joe Garagiola, chairman of NSTEP who has seen
several close friends die due to oral cancer. ``Smokeless does not
mean harmless. It's like taking it intravenously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the players all the time that it's not a failure if
they fall off the wagon. It's part of the quitting process. If they
fall off, try again. I'm not here to tell them to quit; just make
the right choice. All I want them to know is, `Here's what can
happen to you.' It's a decision they all make on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying players should eliminate the use of tobacco all
together (although that would not be such a bad idea). However, if
they want to use tobacco, players are more than free to bring their
own into the clubhouse. Asking a clubhouse attendant to buy it is
inappropriate and unfair to the employee.
</P>
<P>
   On this note, the Diamondbacks deserve credit for taking a
strong proactive stance. Baseball should be watching and doing the
same. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
Last year's Cleveland Indians became the seventh club in major
league history to lead their division/league every single day from
opening day to the final game. Name the other six? &QL; 
Pudge, oh Pudge &QL; 
As if Texas catcher  &UR; Ivan Rodriguez hadn't already dug himself a
bit of a hole when he missed the first eight days of workouts _
without ever having called the Rangers to alert them to his
situation _ the perennial All-Star now says the club is paying him
to play and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a leader,'' said Rodriguez, who will
start the second year of a five-year $42 million deal this season.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers Manager  &UR; Johnny Oates, who must play the diplomat in
this scenario, tried to put as positive a spin as he could on the
situation with Rodriguez, who is upset that the Rangers are
disappointed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a multi-Gold Glove winner, you're looked up to,''
Oates said. ``You don't have any choice about that. In two years,
we're probably not going to remember that Pudge showed up late this
year. We're just disappointed in it.'' &QL; 
Someone who knows &QL; 
Several Los Angeles players were joking about a friendly bet made
last year that still had not been paid off when  &UR; Pete Rose Jr., who
is in the Dodgers camp as a non-roster invitee, approached the
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys better be careful,'' said Rose, holding back a smirk,
``you can get in trouble for that betting stuff.'' &QL; 
Was Hank Cy considered? &QL; 
 &UR; Tom and  &UR; Donna Candiotti had a son last October, naming him  &UR; Casey
 &UR; Koufax Candiotti. The Oakland Athletics pitcher, who grew up in
California a big fan of  &UR; Sandy Koufax and  &UR; Don Drysdale, eventually
got to know Koufax during his days with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   After the birth, the Candiottis sent Koufax, a Hall of Famer, a
letter to inform him of the baby's name. Koufax responded with a
note of his own that read: ``I hope he hits like Casey and pitches
like me.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Starting chronologically, the 1923 New York Giants, the '27 New
York Yankees, the '55 Brooklyn Dodgers, the '84 Detroit Tigers, the
'90 Cincinnati Reds and the 1997 Baltimore Orioles. Of those, the
'27 Yankees, the '55 Dodgers, the '84 Tigers and the '90 Reds went
on to win the World Series. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Talk about filling a guy's shoes: Pitcher &UR; David Wells, who
reluctantly accepted his trade from the Yankees to Toronto last
month, is literally wearing the uniform pants of the pitcher he was
traded for,  &UR; Roger Clemens. ``They fit,'' Wells said of the pants.
``He's got big legs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; And now, a special sneak preview?: The Montreal Expos, who are
perilously close to playing their final season in Montreal, will
play two exhibition games at Washington's RFK Stadium on April 2-3.
Officials from the D.C. area and northern Virginia plan to battle
over the right to purchase the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Dave Goltz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; One ringing endorsement: Florida pitcher  &UR; A.J.
 &UR; Burnett, considered one of the Marlins top prospects, caused quite
a stir when he arrived at camp bearing a pair of pierced nipples.
Florida minor leaguers are prohibited from wearing facial hair or
earrings. Nipple rings, however, are not covered. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
One of new Atlanta hitting coach  &UR; Don Baylor's primary goals for
the 1999 season is to make  &UR; Chipper Jones a more imposing
right-handed hitter. Of Jones' 108 career home runs, only 12 have
been hit from the right side. ``Opposing managers want to flip him
around to the other side,'' said Baylor, who served as Colorado's
manager the past six years. ``We just want to make them think.''
</P>
<P>
   Seriously worried that the Toronto Blue Jays may be looking for
another spring training home, the town of Dunedin, Fla., is
searching for ways to keep the Blue Jays in the area. One direction
Toronto is looking at is sharing a spring home with Los Angeles in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Manager  &UR; Gene Lamont is thinking of hitting catcher
 &UR; Jason Kendall in the leadoff spot, a place rarely seen by
catchers. But Kendall, who has a career .393 on-base percentage, is
no ordinary catcher. He set the NL record for stolen bases by a
catcher with 26 last season. The big league record is 36 by  &UR; John
 &UR; Wathan in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Manager  &UR; Davey Johnson received a box last week that
contained his 1997 ``The Sporting News'' manager of the year award
for the job he did in directing Baltimore to the playoffs. It
appears the magazine had no forwarding address for Johnson last
season. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Atlanta special assistant  &UR; Bill Lajoie has been spotted at several
of Cincinnati's workouts in recent days. The Braves are apparently
interested in one of the following: First baseman  &UR; Hal &UR; Morris,
pinch hitter  &UR; Mark Sweeney or outfielder  &UR; Jon Nunnally.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Manager  &UR; Jack McKeon appears to have tipped his hand
as to what kind of club he plans to field this season and running
will be a big part of it. In two intrasquad games last week, the
Reds attempted 10 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   It now seems official that Heisman Trophy winner
 &UR; Ricky Williams will not participate in Texas' spring training camp.
Williams' baseball contract was purchased from Montreal by the
Rangers in December for $100,000. In addition, Williams is said to
be about 20 pounds heavier than when his college football career
ended in early January.
</P>
<P>
   Boston first baseman  &UR; Reggie Jefferson is suffering from severe
back pains and has actually floated the idea that his career may be
over. One name the Red Sox may be looking at is Kansas City's  &UR; Jeff
King. Boston's current alternatives would be  &UR; Bob Hamelin or  &UR; Midre
Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Boston, the Red Sox and  &UR; Carlton Fisk may be
reunited once again. Nearly 19 years after he became a free agent
through a technicality, Fisk and the club are talking about having
him return in some capacity. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
