<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YES, THIS RIVALRY GETS PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS for writethru to reflect Connecticut victory.)  (fb) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Calhoun stood in a corridor of Madison Square Garden
Saturday night, holding court after his Connecticut team's 82-63
victory over St. John's for the Big East championship.
</P>
<P>
   This was the matchup, but not the result, that the Big East
wanted to culminate its 20th anniversary season. In January, St.
John's came within a breath of upsetting UConn on this very court,
fueling speculation that the championship game would be a classic
and the dawn of a new conference rivalry. Instead the Huskies burst
St. John's bubble with a sustained ferocity that seemed to surprise
even Calhoun. From the opening player introductions, when UConn
fans transformed the Garden into Gampel Pavilion South, Connecticut
stripped St. John's of any notion it could win this game. The
victory was more dominating, by octaves, than the 19-point margin
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energy,'' Calhoun said. ``We talked to the kids a great deal
about playing with a great deal of passion this time of year
because if, in fact, someone is good enough to beat you, make sure
they beat you; don't lose the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in four years, Connecticut was the Big East
champion. The Huskies joined Georgetown as the only teams to win
back-to-back Big East tournament championships and became the only
team to win regular season and tournament championships twice in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, UConn was an afterthought in the league. Now
it is virtually in a league of its own. And until further notice,
the Garden belongs to the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it mean?'' Calhoun asked. ``It means an awful lot of
good players come to Connecticut.'' He nodded in the direction of
Scott Burrell, the Nets forward who played for Calhoun. ``I've been
blessed with having some tremendous players play for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As Connecticut sails off to try to win an elusive national
championship, the Big East is left still trying to rekindle the
sort of rivalries that used to be its backbone.
</P>
<P>
   When Big East Commissioner Mike Tranghese kicked off Big East
Tournament week he acknowledged Pearl Washington, the former
Syracuse star. Then Tranghese recalled the Big East championship
game in 1984 between Syracuse and Georgetown, a game still
remembered as one of the fiercest championship games in Big East
history with Michael Graham decking Syracuse's Andre Hawkins, the
game going into overtime and Jim Boeheim storming off the podium,
knocking over a folding chair as he left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really had to be there,'' Tranghese said. Like many fans
of the era, the commissioner longed for that time when the Big East
was legendary.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalries were forged not by teams or institutions but by
personalities. John Thompson and Rick Pitino going at it, with
Thompson calling Pitino a ``young punk'' and Pitino shouting:
``Grow up, John.'' Or Lou Carnesecca calling Rollie Massimino a
``Hollywood Hotdog'' a year after Massimino led Villanova to the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The personalities faded and the thrill was gone as well. But
there was a resurgence of bad blood and angst over the last week.
The tension was back, largely because St. John's was back. At least
before Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In January UConn overcame a 12-point deficit and handed St.
John's a 78-74 defeat at Madison Square Garden. After that loss,
Jarvis said: ``We can play with them _ and we can beat them. And
they know it. The day will come, I hope sooner than later. We will
beat them. In our house. Madison Square Garden. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing friendly about this rivalry. The tension
between the coaches has deep roots. Calhoun, 56, and Jarvis, 53,
first met as players: Jarvis at Northeastern, Calhoun at American
International. In 1972, Calhoun was hired to coach Northeastern,
effectively passing over Jarvis, who had been an assistant at
Northeastern since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis left after a season and took a job as assistant coach at
Harvard then got his first head coaching job in 1985 when he became
head coach at Boston University. Saturday night's championship game
marked the eighth time Calhoun and Jarvis have met. Calhoun leads
the series 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between the two grew out of Calhoun's one loss _ an
80-71 defeat in December 1986 in a game at B.U. It was Calhoun's
fifth game at UConn.
</P>
<P>
   The team bus was involved in an accident beforehand and UConn
wanted to postpone the game. B.U. told the Huskies they would have
to forfeit if they didn't show. Calhoun said Jarvis did not give
his team enough time to warm up and vowed never to play B.U. again.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship took another turn last year when Jarvis and
Calhoun were honored at the America East Conference 20th
anniversary banquet. Jarvis spoke first, offering insights and
comments about his accomplishments. When Calhoun stepped up to
podium that was close to a wall, he said he was surprised there was
enough room to accommodate Jarvis and his ego. Will the Big East
ever recapture its glow of the 1980s? If Calhoun's relationship
with Jarvis is any indication, the answer is a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese put his finger on it earlier this week. What makes the
Big East so tantalizing is the mix and clash of personalities. It's
never business, it's personal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
