</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE HAS SENSE OF URGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ROGER PHILLIPS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ As far as Luc Robitaille is concerned, the
finals have arrived, and those of his teammates not ready to
contribute in this premature pursuit of Lord Stanley's Cup would be
well-advised to take a seat at the end of the nearest bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, unfortunately, we don't have time to wait for guys
that are struggling,'' Robitaille said before Saturday night's game
at the Forum against the Calgary Flames. ``We've got to go with the
guys that are just saying, `Screw it, I'm going to do whatever it
takes to win.' If you're in the Stanley Cup finals and you had a
guy struggling a little bit, you can't just keep giving him ice
time to get him out of his slump. You've got to go with whoever is
hot or whoever is working hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our Stanley Cup finals right now for this season.
That's what everybody has to understand. It goes from the players,
the trainers, equipment manager, the coach, everybody. This is our
playoffs, this next week. It's not time to do anything outside the
ice. It's time to get ready. These are the most important games of
our season.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille said the time has come for the coaching staff to
become undemocratic in the distribution of ice time. He insisted
that he hasn't given up hope, even though a playoff berth is
starting to look remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, it's frustrating right now,'' he said. ``But I'm a
positive guy. I still believe. ... There's no excuse, guys that are
tired, whatever. It's time to play the guys that want to win, and
even guys that aren't playing as much, it's time for guys to pick
it up a notch. There's no excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   A grand reward (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Last month, after he played in his 1,000th NHL game, Kings
defenseman Garry Galley's wife decorated their home with 1,000
roses.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, when Ray Ferraro returned home from Dallas after
playing in his 1,000th game, his wife, Tracey, led him into the
garage. Awaiting him was a red 1965 Mustang convertible in mint
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome,'' Ferraro said. ``I just always liked it. I
always thought it looked sharp. I'd been hoping to find one, one
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got home and the kids were sitting in it. I took it for a
spin (Friday). I can hardly wait to drive it home this summer (to
British Columbia).''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was looking forward to getting under the hood and
tinkering with his new car, Ferraro said, ``If I take a wrench
anywhere, I'm worried that it will fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Entering play Saturday, the Flames were 1-1 since trading Theo
Fleury to Colorado for winger Rene Corbet, defenseman Wade Belak, a
draft choice and future considerations. Belak is playing in the
American Hockey League. ... General Manager Dave Taylor, who has
been scouting in Europe, is scheduled to return to Los Angeles
today. Coach Larry Robinson is scheduled to return Monday from
Ontario, where he attended the funeral of his mother, Isobel, who
died this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
