<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0709 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAIN-ACTIVIST-LADN     03-07 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAIN-ACTIVIST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVIST SLAIN IN COLOMBIA UPHELD BELIEFS TO END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA WEISS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For Terence Freitas, ``Save the Rain Forest'' was
much more than a slogan; it was his life's work, and it eventually
led him to his death.
</P>
<P>
   The man from the North Hollywood community of Los Angeles,
described by friends as a dedicated activist, was found slain with
two companions Thursday in Venezuela, a week after they had been
kidnapped in the Colombian rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lived the life that he wanted to live,'' said Freitas'
mother, Julie, of North Hollywood. ``I'm grateful that his life was
so full of passion and that . ... he did what he believed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Freitas and his two friends had traveled to the rain forest at
the invitation of the U'wa, a group of indigenous people whose
land, about 200 miles from Bogota, has been targeted for oil
exploration by Los Angeles-based Occidental Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   A rancher found Freitas' body, along with those of his
companions Ingrid Washinawatok of New York and Lahe'ena'e Gay of
Hawaii, in his cow pasture in Venezuela, just across the border
from Colombia. The three travelers were members of the Hawaii-based
Pacific Cultural Conservancy International.
</P>
<P>
   The victims had been shot with 9 mm weapons, the women four
times each in the face and chest, and Freitas six times, according
to Venezuelan police. No group has claimed responsibility for the
killings, but Washington has blamed them on the 15,000-member
leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC.
</P>
<P>
   Freitas graduated from the University of California at Santa
Cruz with a degree in biology and worked in various environmental
law projects after college. In May 1997, he had just started
working with the Santa Monica-based Amazon Watch when the U'wa's
elected leader, Roberto Cobaria, came to speak to the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry was very moved by their struggle,'' said Atossa Soltani,
the director of Amazon Watch. Three weeks later, the U'wa had an
assembly in Colombia, and Freitas traveled there. ``He came back
inspired and committed. He was incredibly bright, and in a very
quick time, he became an expert. No one outside Colombia has done
more to support the U'wa's struggle,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   He had an immense love for nature, she said, and would become
animated when he showed slides he took of frogs and other forest
creatures while visiting U'wa territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U'wa are of such strong spirit,'' Soltani said. ``They
believe that oil is the blood of Mother Earth and that they were
put on the earth to defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Freitas mirrored that passion in his work, putting in long hours
for little or no money and financing his own trips to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Before his trip, he was in the process of moving to New York to
become the director of the U'wa Defense Working Group, an umbrella
group of nine environmental and human rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said Freitas knew of the dangers of traveling to
Colombia, where violence perpetrated by leftist guerrillas,
right-wing paramilitary groups and drug traffickers is common.
</P>
<P>
   Melina Selverston, director of the Coalition for Amazonian
Peoples and their Environment, a Washington, D.C., advocacy group,
said Freitas had received death threats on his telephone answering
machine. She said they came from the right-wing paramilitary groups
that operate in the Arauca area of Colombia where the Americans
were abducted.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement released by the U'wa Defense Working
Group, Freitas was forced to sign a statement by the Colombian
military that absolved them of any responsibility for his safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very confused and don't understand the motives behind
the killings. We have been in touch with the State Department,
pressing our interest in finding the truth. We want to see that
Terry's death was not in vain,'' Soltani said. ``We're very proud
of him. He was a warrior and a brother. This only strengthens our
resolve to carry on his work.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
