<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS WASTE OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ From the out-of-town scoreboards at both
ends of the Forum, the news almost screamed down at the Kings. San
Jose had lost to Chicago. Edmonton had lost to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This was the opportunity the Kings were looking for, the chance
to gain ground in the race for a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Kings, they either didn't see the
scoreboard, didn't hear its scream or, most likely, simply weren't
equipped to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a Calgary Flames team in a similar position in the
standings, a Calgary team that had traded star forward Theoren
Fleury six days earlier, a tired Calgary team that had played the
night before in Vancouver, the Kings couldn't help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They lost 4-1 before a disgruntled Forum crowd of 14,451, and
with 18 games left, the Kings (23-36-5) remained seven points
behind the Sharks and nine behind the Oilers in the race for one of
the bottom playoff spots in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are 0-2 on a seven-game home stand that was supposed
to be their salvation but is turning into their final downfall. The
Flames (23-30-10), adjusting to life without Fleury, moved within
two points of the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rob Blake's third-period lapse of judgment added one
more page to his team's miserable season.
</P>
<P>
   With the Kings shorthanded and trailing by two goals with 16:10
left, Blake took a high stick to the jaw from Calgary center Clarke
Wilm.
</P>
<P>
   If Blake had simply stayed down, Wilm would have been penalized,
and the Kings eventually would have gone on the power play.
Instead, the Kings' captain arose, skated to Wilm, and began
throwing punches.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Mick McGeough assessed Wilm high-sticking and fighting
penalties, and gave Blake two minutes for instigating, five for
fighting and an automatic 10-minute misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   So the Kings remained shorthanded and Jarome Iginla's power-play
goal gave the Flames an insurmountable 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings played physically at the start Saturday, but in
typical fashion, one mistake knocked them out of the game mentally,
if not on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   It started with a Kings scoring chance, a blast from the slot by
Ian Laperriere three minutes into the game. Calgary goalie Fred
Brathwaite made the save, and on a clearing attempt by the Flames,
Kings defenseman Sean O'Donnell misplayed the puck at the blue
line.
</P>
<P>
   Valeri Bure burst past O'Donnell on a breakaway. O'Donnell
hooked Bure, but not enough to bring him down or keep him from
shooting or keep him from slipping the puck past goalie Stephane
Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and wanted to have a good start,'' Kings center
Ray Ferraro said. ``The first two shifts, we got some momentum, and
the puck jumps over O'Donnell's stick and Bure scores on a
breakaway. We're down, 1-0, and we didn't seem to get it going
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings could have gotten a lift when they killed a
four-minute shorthanded situation after Russ Courtnall high-sticked
Calgary's Todd Simpson at 9:31. Instead, five seconds after
Courtnall stepped out of the penalty box, the Flames' Cory Stillman
made it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bodger put the Kings on the scoreboard in the final minute
of the second period with his first goal of the season, but
Iginla's power-play goal quelled comeback hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games, we have been saying for a month, are way too
important not to have,'' Ferraro said. ``We have to find a way to
get back into this pretty quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
