<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS MISS OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ROGER PHILLIPS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ From the out-of-town scoreboards at both
ends of the Forum, the news almost screamed down at the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose had lost to Chicago. Edmonton had lost to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This was the opportunity the Kings had awaited, the chance to
gain ground in the race for a playoff berth. Unfortunately for the
Kings, they either didn't see the scoreboard, didn't hear its
scream or, most likely, simply aren't equipped to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings may remember Saturday night for an undisciplined
third-period outburst by their captain, Rob Blake. They won't
remember it as the night they resuscitated their fading season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seize the moment,'' assistant coach Jay Leach said, ``and I
think initially they tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, the Kings failed against a Calgary Flames
team that had traded star forward Theo Fleury six days earlier and
played in Vancouver the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Before a disgruntled Forum crowd of 14,451, the Kings lost, 4-1,
and with 18 games left, they remained seven points behind the
Sharks and nine behind the Oilers in the race for one of the bottom
playoff spots in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (23-36-5) are 0-2 on a seven-game home stand that was
supposed to be their salvation but is turning into their final
downfall. The Flames (23-30-10) moved to within two points of the
Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's third-period lapse of judgment added one more gloomy
chapter to his team's miserable season.
</P>
<P>
   With the Kings shorthanded and trailing by two goals with 16:10
left, Blake took a high stick to the jaw from Calgary rookie Clarke
Wilm. Blake arose and skated to Wilm, and a fight ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Mick McGeough assessed Wilm high-sticking and fighting
penalties, and gave Blake two minutes for instigating, five for
fighting and an automatic 10-minute misconduct. Blake disputed the
instigator call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we squared off,'' he said. ``He dropped his gloves
the same time I did. I think it was a pretty (expletive) call by
the ref. ... The kid sticks me on a faceoff. Then he dropped his
gloves the same time I did. If you look at my history, I have one
fight a year. It's not like I'm looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was indisputable, however, that if Blake had simply stayed
down, the 22-year-old Wilm would have been penalized, and the Kings
eventually would have gone on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit down,'' Blake said. ``We're far enough
out of the playoff hunt that you're not going to sit there and take
that stuff. I'm not going to take that. I'm not going to sit there
and take that from a kid, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed on the fact that his reaction cost the Kings an
eventual power play, Blake said, ``Would you like me to take (the
stick to the jaw)? If you'd like me to, then I'll take it. It was
my fault that we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake then stalked off.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Blake had shown a lack of discipline on the ice, Leach
responded, ``I would say so.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Blake's play hardly was the reason the Kings lost,
though their chances of rallying would have been better if he'd
been on the ice for the final 16:10 instead of in the dressing
room.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings remained shorthanded after the incident, and Jarome
Iginla's goal on the power play just after the Blake incident gave
the Flames an insurmountable 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The game had been lost much earlier, when Valeri Bure and Cory
Stillman scored in the first period and Denis Gauthier scored late
in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bodger's first goal of the season, in the final minute of
the second period, gave the Kings hope, but Iginla's power-play
goal snuffed it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games, we have been saying for a month, are way too
important not to have,'' center Ray Ferraro said. ``We have to find
a way to get back into this pretty quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
