<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'ED-FLEX' BILL BECOMES A SCHOOL POLICY BATTLEGROUND
 &HT;    730&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Inside the cramped but friendly office of Garrison
Elementary hangs a photo of President Clinton reading ``The
Tortoise and the Hare'' to students at the District of Columbia
public school, where test scores have long been low.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years since that presidential visit, Garrison's
administrators, like the tortoise in the fable, have plugged away
at securing federal education grants. It's part of what Principal
P. Dianne Worthy calls a ``mission'' to catch up to better-funded
schools in reading and math skills.
</P>
<P>
   The federal assistance has paid for teaching aides, workshops
for teachers, and Saturday remedial reading classes for students.
</P>
<P>
   But applying for the grants consumes a vast amount of time, and
requires an entire school district office to monitor tight
restrictions on how the money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   Now Republicans in Congress are trying to compete with Clinton
and the Democrats by offering remedies for the nation's education
problems that would cut out some of that red tape.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate leadership has scheduled a test vote Monday on the
Educational Flexibility Partnership Act, which would provide
broader flexibility to states and school districts in six major
programs, including the $8 billion Title I supplements for
low-income students. The House is scheduled to vote Wednesday on a
similar ``Ed-Flex'' measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support this bill,'' Clinton said in his Saturday radio
address. But at the same time, the president turned up the heat on
Republicans to fully fund the Democrats' goal of hiring 100,000 new
teachers over the next six years to cut class sizes in the first
three grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have the first big test,'' Clinton said, ``of whether
the Congress is serious about giving our children the education
they need and deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Some doubt whether either party's proposed federal solutions
will restore the luster to America's school system, whose students
rank near the bottom of the industrial world in international
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the public attention to federal aid, it accounts for
only about 6 percent of all funding for elementary and secondary
education. Most funding comes from localities and states.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it is uncertain whether school officials, if loosed
from some of the chains of regulation, will make much better use of
the federal money. The Department of Education has already
experimented with the ``Ed-Flex'' idea, allowing a dozen states to
seek waivers from some federal rules that govern education aid, but
results have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   A study released last fall by the General Accounting Office, the
investigating arm of Congress, reported that some states found the
program ``useful for creating a climate that encourages
innovation,'' but others said the program still had too many
restrictions and was ``of limited value.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the states, Texas made the greatest use of the new
flexible rule, with Ohio, Massachusetts, Maryland and Kansas making
modest use of the program. Others requested few if any waivers from
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate proposal would extend that experimental program to
all 50 states. However, for some education reformers, that is not
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The existing Ed-Flex idea doesn't go very far at all in terms
of empowering states to use the federal money for their own
purposes,'' said Chester E. Finn Jr., a former education official
in the Reagan administration, at a briefing sponsored last month by
the Thomas B. Fordham Foundation. ``It does not, for example, allow
them to redirect money from one purpose to another purpose. It just
simplifies the regulations within a program.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the federal government should give each state
``five years of freedom'' with its federal education money and then
insist on proven academic results at the end of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, on the other hand, are expressing concern that the
states might stint on low-income students if the federal government
no longer sets the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP bill ``turns over 35 years of important history,
legislation that has really worked well for children,'' said Sen.
Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone said he was concerned that the pilot program did not
measure how the redirection of Title I funds affected poor and
disadvantaged students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have they used this ``Ed-Flex'' to improve the opportunity for
poor
</P>
<P>
   children?'' he asked. ``We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, led by Sen. Ted Kennedy of Massachusetts, are trying
to tack the Clinton teacher plan onto the Republican education
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration points to a wide range of studies
showing that smaller classes lead to higher student achievement and
fewer discipline problems. Vice President Al Gore, in his travels,
reminds each state of how many new teachers it would be entitled to
under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's seize the moment to make a commitment to our children's
education and America's future,'' Gore said last week in a
campaign-style stop at a New York school.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans last fall went along with funding for
hiring about 30,000 new teachers for the fall of 1999, the program
has encountered a growing teacher shortage in many big areas.
</P>
<P>
   California, under a state mandate to reduce class size, has
hired teachers who lack proper credentials and recruited teachers
from Mexico. New York City, desperate for qualified math and
science teachers, recruited two dozen Austrians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of lowering class size is very attractive and a way
to get news,'' said Paul T. Hill, co-author of the book ``Fixing
Urban Education.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are some places where that's not appropriate for
that,'' he said, adding that in regions with a shortage of
qualified teachers, the danger could be hiring less desirable
teachers who will then have tenure in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
