A0803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN08-COX     03-07 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Managed care meets its match
 &HT;    (EDs: The following editorial is from Monday's Atlanta Journal.)
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia will soon be the second state in the nation to
impose liability on HMOs. In Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes, the highly
paid health insurance lobbyists have met their match. Barnes' three
reform bills _ doctor choice, HMO liability and the creation of an
insurance consumer office _ appear headed for legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   The latest of the governor's savvy moves was to fire off a
letter to a local radio station when an outfit named ``Georgians
for Affordable Health Care'' started running opposition ads. Barnes
pointed out the organization hadn't filed as a lobbying group and
hadn't registered as a business with the secretary of state. The
ads were pulled _ and haven't reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, apparently funded by managed care companies, listed an
interesting telephone number for citizens to call _ the same as
that of insurance giant CIGNA Healthcare. But it's doubtful that
top officers at CIGNA or any other health care megacorporation
relate to ``affordable'' anything. CIGNA CEO Wilson Taylor's 1997
salary was $12.5 million, $1 million more than the previous year,
despite industry losses. Plus almost $10 million in stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor isn't even the highest paid of the for-profit HMO
executives. Oxford Health Plans Inc., which has suffered serious
financial setbacks, paid former CEO Stephen Wiggins $30.7 million.
The stock option champ, though, is United Healthcare CEO William
McGuire, with $61.2 million. Families USA, a nonprofit organization
that researches health care issues, compiled the data on salaries
and stock options from Securities and Exchange Commission filings.
The Crystal Report, which regularly surveys executives'
compensation, found that managed care executives make two to three
times more than CEOs in 31 comparable industries. No wonder the
general public is disgusted with warnings that premiums must rise
for companies to make a go of it if reforms become law.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the governor's success with the liability bill, which
allows consumers to sue managed care companies (after third-party
reviews), is its prohibition against punitive damages. The
legislation bars ``pain and suffering'' claims that often produce
exorbitant jury awards. No question that's a reason the managed
care industry has been willing to work with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Barnes has pulled the rug out from under insurance
lobbyists, the head-shaking about increased health care premiums
continues. But there's no real data to support those claims _ and
plenty to indicate increases will be minimal. Four independent
firms, including the Kaiser Family Foundation, estimated the cost
of reforms more extreme than the modest ones before the Georgia
Legislature at less than $2 per month per person.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is one of 17 states clamping down on managed care
abuses. State regulation is just the first step in assuring
for-profit companies give proper weight to patient concerns about
quality. The next is national reform to guarantee state-enacted
patients' rights apply to the approximately 60 percent of Georgia
workers (40 percent to 60 percent of workers nationally) whose
employers' benefit plans are self-insured. Federal law exempts them
from state regulation _ though that's being challenged in Texas,
the only other state with an HMO liability law.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that managed care reform knows no party bounds.
Georgia Rep. Charlie Norwood, a conservative Republican, is in the
forefront of HMO reforms in Washington. There's nothing wrong with
making a profit, but patient needs deserve more clout. Fortunately,
politicians are responding to the people's outcry.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
