A0804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN08-COX     03-07 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In this court, dad and son bond as they fight for rebounds
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I've always wanted a bald spot.
</P>
<P>
   The thought came to me at an unusual time, as my 11-year-old
gained an H-O advantage against me in a game of HORSE.
</P>
<P>
   This year I proudly noticed the bald spot. No, not the vacancy
atop my skull. I did not invite that. What I greeted was the
wearing out of the grass just a few feet beyond the driveway, a
long jumper from our basketball hoop.
</P>
<P>
   I know I should fret about the grass that bit the dust there.
It's unsightly by certain standards. In Yard of the Month scoring,
we foul out.
</P>
<P>
   But by my recollection, this is the way a yard is supposed to
look _ not a sea of dirt, mind you, just a bald spot.
</P>
<P>
   Driveway basketball courts are like snowflakes, unique and
apart. Each has its hazards and wrinkles _ an angular crack here,
an overhang there.
</P>
<P>
   Our court is suitably odd. The goal is to the side of the
slightly sloping, one-car driveway. To stay on the concrete, play
must be tight to the goal or way off on either wing. But play
migrates outward, and the grass is gone past the concrete, roughly
out to where the top of the key would be.
</P>
<P>
   The bald spot of my youth was different, a pie slice out from
where the lip of the porch met our driveway. The basket was _ still
is _ over the garage. The porch is elevated three inches above the
driveway. Only inches away from the basket, it's amazing that lip
didn't break half a dozen ankles in all the sweaty games we played,
brothers, neighbors, Dad and I.
</P>
<P>
   Dad and I had a particular spot, behind a crack past the gutter
drain, from which we would have long contests. Shoot till you hit.
Shoot till you miss.
</P>
<P>
   You want bonding? It comes in all forms. One is the bounce pass.
Then there's the chest pass. You and your old man can even bond
when he's giving you the hip and trying to take you down with a
scoop shot, one-on-one. Nice try, old man.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of this bonding is without a word, only the cadence of the
ball, a satisfying slap against a surface you know well. I love
that sound on my own driveway.
</P>
<P>
   This year our youngest son really discovered basketball,
bringing a smile to my face and, simultaneously, causing me to
hitch up my britches. Each new game, HORSE, one-on-one, or
two-on-two with Rob's big brother and a friend, picks up topspin.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the narrowness of our driveway, one of our home-court
factors is the tree overhanging it, an Arizona ash. I have it
trimmed so in cold months it plays no factor. But when it buds and
the limbs get heavy with green, it decides it must play, too.
</P>
<P>
   In these early weeks of green, if you launch one from a certain
angle you'll get it swatted by the tree. A collision between ball
and branches sends foliar casings fluttering down like sleet, and
with them the smell of spring.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, as headlights from our van supplemented a
porchlight so we could keep shooting, Robert noticed the tree shed
after one such rejected shot. He started lofting the basketball up
into the boughs, singing, ``Let it snow, let it snow.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day Jeff, one of the boys' friends, hit a shot from
behind the tree, actually through the cross-hairs where its torso
splits into biceps. I might place a plaque there.
</P>
<P>
   You want to remember stuff like this, because bald spots, games
of HORSE and childhood don't last forever. At my boyhood home
there's grass where once there was dirt near the basket. Dad's lawn
is unblemished now. It looks good. I know he'd rather have it worn.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball comes out, though, when we visit. I know it will
this summer when the hotshot grandson shows up and wants to show
off.
</P>
<P>
   If we hang around the house long enough there's certain to be
some wear there. The old spot will feel like family again.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
