   CHINA-POLICE (Zhanlong) _ The widespread abuses of China's local
police and the efforts to curb them. By Elizabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIANS (Pristina) _ Life among Kosovo's ethnic
Albanians. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKES (Beijing) _ China reacts angrily to reports of
nuclear espionage. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-KHMERROUGE (Undated) _ More on the capture of the last
Khmer Rouge outlaw, Ta Mok. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Yeltsin warns Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov about ``complacency'' and threatens to fire his team. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI-IRAQ (Riyadh) _ Defense Secretary William Cohen on Sunday
offered Saudi Arabia new weapons and military training to help
shore up its defenses against any threat from the Baghdad
government. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-CUTBACKS (Washington) _ The world's seafaring nations
have promised to make the first far-reaching cuts in the size of
their fishing fleets. By John H. Cushman.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-WHALES (Laguna San Ignacio) _ The bay here and its
surrounding salt flats have become the center of a noisy clash
between environmentalists and the Mitsubishi Corp., which hopes to
build a huge salt plant in partnership with the Mexican government.
By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ One of Mexico's leading
opposition parties elects a new head. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
