   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   LOST-PLAYS (New York) _ Most writers have a long apprenticeship
and years of struggle before they break through, and even the most
accomplished have early plays that have not been produced. In many
cases the authors simply forget their apprentice work. Currently
theater goers have an opportunity to see lost plays by two diverse
writers, ``Not About Nightingales,'' by Tennessee Williams, and
``The Hothouse,'' by Harold Pinter. Each followed a different path
to production. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (New York) _ Visionaries, hopefuls, hucksters and
self-described geeks mingled over the weekend at the first New York
Music and Internet Expo. While Web pages flickered on monitors and
cellular phones beeped, musicians and computer entrepreneurs
swapped business cards and ideas about how the Internet could
revolutionize the music business. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   EVENSONG-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The title of Gail Godwin's rich
new novel, ``Evensong,'' refers, according to its epigraph, to ``a
worship service said or sung at the onset of evening to mark the
close of day and to compose the mind and renew the spirit for the
coming day.'' As you read ``Evensong,'' however, you find its title
taking on an ironic edge. For its story is not about the close of a
day but rather about the end of the old millennium and the coming
of the new. Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews.
</P>
<P>
   BAND-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Band in Berlin'' is not so
much a play as a kind of docu-cabaret. Through slide projections,
re-enactments of newsreel clips and the jukebox-style performances
of a stream of Teutonic folk songs and American pop standards, the
show recounts the rise and fall of the Comedian Harmonists, the
renowned German singing group forced by the Nazis to disband
because three of its members were Jewish. Peter Marks reviews.
</P>
<P>
   SUE-MILLER-INTERVIEW (Undated) _ In her fiction, from her first
novel, ``The Good Mother,'' to her latest, ``While I Was Gone,''
Sue Miller is the doyenne of domesticity. Probing beneath the
surface of marriages, she uncovers the disharmony as well as an
individual's urge to find an alternative life. During a recent
interview she acknowledged that the search for another self was a
continuous theme in her work. She characterized it as ``the
difference between the self we present to people and the self we
feel ourselves to be,'' leading to the eternal question ``how much
we can truly know another person.'' By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STRANGE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Here's a new television series
with a mission statement. In the pilot episode of ``Strange World''
the central character, Dr. Paul Turner, works up a righteous head
of steam and declares: ``Why are people more afraid of aliens from
outer space than they are of the monsters we're creating ourselves?
From genetically engineered animals, viruses . . . .'' Ron
Wertheimer reviews.
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK-OBIT (Undated) _ Stanley Kubrick, the director of
``2001: A Space Odyssey'' and ``A Clockwork Orange'' died Sunday at
his home in England. He was 70. (Will move in category ``a'')
</P>
