   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PHONES (Undated) _ As it halts decades of investing in
the traditional gear that makes up most of the global telephone
system _ AT&AMP;T is starting to retool its network around a new
generation of technologies inspired by the Internet. For consumers,
this evolution could lead to lower prices. And in the future, as
the new technologies expand from the core of the network to homes
and businesses, consumers could also benefit from new sorts of
features and services. A news analysis by Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-TRIAL (Washington) _ At the heart of the government's
antitrust case that goes on trial against Intel Corp. on Tuesday is
a meeting nearly five-and-a-half years ago at the industry's annual
Comdex convention in Las Vegas. There, in November 1993, the
chairman of the giant chipmaker cut a fateful deal with his
counterpart at a small but leading maker of highly specialized
computer workstations, Intergraph Corp. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-TV-DEREGULATE (Washington) _ Cable television, one of the
last industries to have its prices controlled by the government, is
about to become almost completely deregulated. But while the
prospect of competition was supposed to drive prices down, the
opposite has happened. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   BUYING-ELECTRONICS (Undated) _ Buoyed by strong holiday sales of
large screen television sets, video cassette recorders and Sony
PlayStation video games, and signs pointing to strong first-quarter
sales, the makers and sellers of consumer electronics products are
predicting that 1999 could be the industry's best year ever. Rather
than scaring off consumers, they are counting on a dazzling _
skeptics might say dizzying _ array of new and enhanced products to
stimulate sales. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV-INTERACTIVE (Washington) _ Results of a recent study by the
Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association, the industry's main
trade group, showed that consumers are at least as interested in
using digital television sets for interactive services as for
watching high-definition programming. By Joel Brinkley. (With
BUYING-ELECTRONICS)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-MONITORS (Undated) _ Corporations have long paid
so-called clipping services to monitor their appearances in the
conventional news media. But several companies have taken the
practice online and a step further. This new generation of monitors
goes beyond news publishers and instead trolls for rumor and
innuendo in the Net's virtual back alleys _ in thousands of chat
rooms and discussion forums where, some say, unchecked scuttlebutt
can damage corporate reputations and stock prices. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-DROPOUTS (Undated) _ Internet shoppers may be at the
vanguard of a retail revolution, but as with anyone on the front
lines, they are a jittery bunch. Those who shop on the Internet
abandon one-half to two-thirds of the purchases they begin,
industry executives and analysts say. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
