<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE: INTERNET RETAILERS WORK TO TURN SHOPPERS INTO BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Internet shoppers may be at the vanguard of a retail
revolution, but as with anyone on the front lines, they are a
jittery bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Those who shop on the Internet abandon one-half to two-thirds of
the purchases they begin, industry executives and analysts say. One
way that sites can measure the dropouts is through ``shopping
cart'' technology, which, as the name suggests, allows users to
gather items at a site for a one-stop checkout.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that online shoppers often start filling a cart,
but then leave the site without buying anything.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of such almost-sales, e-commerce sites have begun looking
at the problem and are feverishly devising methods to convert these
browsers into buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there widespread concern in the industry about this?'' said
Arno Harris, vice president for marketing at 911gifts.com, whose
site has seen 45 percent of its potential transactions abandoned
before checkout. ``I think there is.'' Of those who bail out,
Harris said, 30 percent drop off at the first page of the billing
process. ``We're still in the early phase of e-commerce adoption,
so a lot of people just get into the process and panic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives cite various reasons why customers bail out.
</P>
<P>
   First, some consumers are just trying out the online shopping
experience, without intending to make a purchase. Others abandon
the process when confronted with often-hefty shipping and handling
charges at the end of the transaction, or with registration forms
that ask for personal information, like a home address, e-mail
address or phone number. Finally, a significant _ but diminishing _
number of users remain unsure about giving out their credit card
information online.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Hyde, vice president of online sales for REI.com, an
outdoor goods retailer, conjectures that many Internet users are
simply playing with sites that have e-commerce capabilities, just
as people try out anything new before seriously considering
spending money on it. ``I put stuff in the cart all the time and
then leave, don't you?'' Hyde said. ``I did it three times on
Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Cassar, an e-commerce analyst for Jupiter
Communications, a New York-based research firm, said a big problem
was shipping and handling costs, which many sites do not disclose
until late in the buying process. ``It's sticker shock,'' Cassar
said. ``A lot of people just aren't willing to pay what is
essentially a 30 to 40 percent markup.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassar and other analysts said that security was less of an
issue than it was last year, when many in the industry were
predicting that such fears would slow the growth of e-commerce. To
date, there have been few actual reported instances of online
credit card fraud. And many consumers have chosen to shop online at
sites operated by established companies, perhaps further reducing
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   More Internet retailers are also designing their Web sites to
convey the image of a secure store, with an abundance of credit
card logos and other seals of approval adorning many companies'
home pages. Though some shoppers still balk at using their credit
cards online, Cassar said that many more were put off by
registration forms.
</P>
<P>
   William Bryant, chairman of Qpass, a company that has developed
a billing system for e-commerce sites, understands consumer
resistance to registering. ``Imagine going to a 7-Eleven to buy a
can of Coke, and having to fill out a registration form that asks
you about marital status,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect registration forms to disappear any time soon.
Internet companies love them, because they help retailers refine
their marketing efforts and aim advertisements on the site more
precisely (and thus charge more to advertisers). Even so, online
merchants are exploring ways to make registering less of a
hindrance, such as systems that would let users register one time
for multiple Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Excite, for example, lets users type in their credit card
information once and then shop at a number of merchants within the
network.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Halliday, vice president for Excite's commerce division,
said the system not only eliminated registration redundancies, but
also gave shoppers fewer opportunities to abandon a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly important, he said, because the Internet
has been a medium for impulse spending. ``You have to make a
consumer's purchase decision as slippery a slope as possible,''
referring to the speed with which sites should finalize sales.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, of 911Gifts.com, said that his company recently started
a similar system and that he expected it to reduce the number of
lost purchases at his site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that people have pretty much figured out the economics of
getting customers to their sites, the focus is on conversion,'' he
said, noting that e-commerce sites typically convert less than 2
percent of their visitors into customers. ``This is a really
critical way merchants can improve economics without spending a lot
more money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most aggressive approach to the problem is
represented by Cybershop, an online department store that actually
pursues shoppers who abandon large purchases. Jeffrey Tauber,
Cybershop's chief executive, says that even when a shopper fills
and flees, the company can still ``capture a pretty good level of
information'' about who the consumer was. ``And if it's a nice-size
order, we'll call or e-mail them and try to close the sale,''
Tauber said.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of the customers the company pursues ultimately
complete the sale, Tauber said.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the best antidote for shopping jitters is, simply, more
practice. Industry executives and analysts predict that if the
Internet's flagship merchants continue to provide positive shopping
experiences, fewer customers will hesitate about making a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if the industry is going to get past its
abandonment issues, companies will have to allay customers'
concerns. The e-merchants, meanwhile, will also have to stock up on
the one commodity rarely found in cyberspace: patience.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Monday, the E-Commerce Report will appear on alternate
Mondays in Business Day, and every Monday in the Technology section
of The New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/tech.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
