<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HDTV-INTERACTIVE-800(     03-07 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV-INTERACTIVE-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-DEFINITION TELEVISION INDUSTRY STILL ON THE DEFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When several hundred executives from the consumer
electronics industry gathered here for a conference on digital
television last week, the leaders of their trade group greeted them
with a rude surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Results of a recent study by the Consumer Electronics
Manufacturers Association, the industry's main trade group, showed
that consumers are at least as interested in using digital
television sets for interactive services as for watching
high-definition programming.
</P>
<P>
   In simplest form, interactive services might include the ability
for a viewer to watch a television commercial and then click the
remote control to download more information about the product being
advertised.
</P>
<P>
   But because the new HDTV sets already on the market do not offer
even such rudimentary interactive services, the trade group's
tentative finding raised new questions about how rapidly consumers
might embrace HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that only about 20,000 of the HDTV sets, which
cost between $3,000 and $12,000, have been sold since the new
television came on the market last August.
</P>
<P>
   The television industry has bet the farm on HDTV, hoping that
vivid pictures and crystal-clear sound will, over time, prompt
Americans to trade in 250 million conventional sets for new,
high-definition models. Some manufacturers are even paying
television networks to broadcast HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the survey set off skeptical grumbling among the
manufacturers and retailers at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know what questions they asked to get that
result,'' groused one senior executive for a major manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the survey showed that the consumers were enthusiastic
about both HDTV and interactivity. ``People want a high-quality
picture and data at the same time, and they want us to figure out
how to do it,'' Todd Thibodeaux, a vice president with the
manufacturers' association, said in his presentation of the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   And as it turned out, the report was based on the reactions of
only about 70 people in focus groups assembled by the association a
few weeks ago. Nonetheless, the tentative findings set off a day of
questions and defensive explanations about the industry's strategy
as the manufacturers introduce the most important new product they
have offered in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the promise'' of interactivity ``and then there's the
physical logistics,'' said Bruce Babcock, a vice president with
Thomson Consumer Electronics, &UR;  &LR; the nation's largest seller of
televisions. ``We're waiting for standards. First a standards
document has to be proposed and commented on and approved. And then
we can build to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus groups were shown high-definition broadcasts as well
as ``data-streaming and multicasting capabilities,'' an association
document explains. The multicasting demonstration _ in which
several lower resolution shows were offered in place of one
high-definition program _ seemed to garner the least interest among
viewers. But they were quite enthusiastic about interactivity.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was simply an advertisement for a BMW that
ended with an on-screen prompt telling viewers that they could
print out more information about the car by pressing a button on
the remote control. The printer was attached to the digital set.
</P>
<P>
   That simple form of interactivity can be accomplished easily
with the nation's existing digital-television standard. But none of
the digital televisions on sale today, or announced for the coming
year, are equipped to handle even this.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with more ambitious interactivity is the lack of
standards. At the same time, most manufacturers had enough trouble
last year simply producing a high-definition set that worked in
time for the launch of the product last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a second-generation feature,'' Babcock said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, HDTV sets are barely selling. Of the estimated
20,000 that have been sold so far, most seem to be high-definition
monitors, lacking the digital tuner needed to pick up the
programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that the public is embracing high-definition is not
true,'' Noah Herschman, a vice president of the Tweeter Home
Entertainment Group, &UR;  &LR; a chain of stores in New England, told the
conference. ``Out of 60 stores, we have sold 200 HD-ready sets _
and only nine digital receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Myer, president of Myer-Emco, &UR;  &LR; a chain of audio-video stores
in the Washington area, where five digital stations are now
broadcasting, said, ``We've sold 10 tuner boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   One huge hurdle is the price. Even for those willing to pay
$3,000 or more, there is only the tiniest amount of high-definition
programming _ generally only three or four hours a week from the
television networks and none from cable. Satellite television
services have promised to offer it but not before late summer or
fall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, HBO began broadcasting one channel of
high-definition programming, beginning with the movie ``U.S.
Marshals.'' But the show had no viewers because within the cable
industry, only HBO's owner, Time Warner, has offered to carry it on
its cable franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Luftman, a spokesman for Time Warner cable, said engineers
had scrambled to complete the necessary technical upgrades by
Friday so that Time Warner could make the high-definition service
available to any customers in New York City who requested it. So
far, however, Time Warner has not received a single request.
</P>
<P>
   ABC &UR;  &LR; continues to broadcast several hours of high-definition
programming a week. But NBC &UR;  &LR; has broadcast none and has announced
no plans to do so before the network begins airing ``The Tonight
Show'' in high definition later this spring.
</P>
<P>
   CBS &UR;  &LR; aired several football games in high definition, the last
in early January. And last week the network announced that the news
show ``48 Hours'' would be broadcast in high definition beginning
at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Not satisfied with that, several television manufacturers are
negotiating with CBS and other networks to underwrite more
high-definition broadcasts, principally movies, beginning in the
fall, network and industry executives said. The manufacturers would
pay the cost of converting a movie to high definition _ between
$15,000 and $50,000 an hour, depending on the format.
</P>
<P>
   A Sony &UR;  &LR; executive pointed out that Sony has already put more
than $1 million into CBS' football broadcasts, primarily in
subsidized goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   But even with additional programming, the manufacturers face
another stumbling block. They acknowledge that many retailers are
making little effort to sell the HDTVs they have on their sales
floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be a technological leader,'' Herschman said.
``But we still have to sell television sets every day because if we
stop selling TVs, we stop selling everything else too _ home
theater systems, speakers. So we walk a fine line between telling
people that digital television is coming _ but we don't know when _
so buy an analog set today.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 1628EST &QL; 
