<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-MONITORS-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY TROLLS FOR SCUTTLEBUTT ON THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By   MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James Alexander is the bearer of bad news for
hundreds of corporations. And now, Alexander's clients can take
heart that he intends to bring them more negative tidings more
quickly than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, 30, and his brother, Charles Lukaszewski, 32, are
co-founders and operators of Ewatch, a company that scours the
Internet on behalf of corporate clients who want to know what the
rest of the world is saying behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chairman is a pedophile; the chairman is arrested; the
chairman has checked into a hospital under an assumed name,''
Alexander said, rattling off recent examples of false rumors from
the dark corners of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations have long paid so-called clipping services to
monitor their appearances in the conventional news media. But
Ewatch and its several competitors have taken the practice online
and a step further.
</P>
<P>
   This new generation of monitors goes beyond news publishers and
instead trolls for rumor and innuendo in the Net's virtual back
alleys _ in thousands of chat rooms and discussion forums where,
Ewatch executives say, unchecked scuttlebutt can damage corporate
reputations and stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   These brothers grim _ Lukaszewski a programmer by training and
Alexander a former television producer _ started Ewatch in 1994
from their home offices in Minneapolis and New York, respectively.
With help from friends and family, they spent days searching the
Internet for venom spewed against corporations, trying to convince
potential clients of the need for online rumor detection and
control.
</P>
<P>
   But bad news for corporate America meant good public relations
for Ewatch. After O.J. Simpson's acquittal on murder charges in
October 1995, for example, a false rumor _ first reported on the
tabloid television show ``Hard Copy,'' and then spread on the
Internet _ said that Mrs. Field's Cookies had underwritten a party
for the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sales dipped, Alexander said, and Ewatch was hired
to help Mrs. Fields find online discussion groups where the rumor
had appeared, and then post corrective messages. Cookie sales soon
returned to normal levels, Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, as cyberspace has grown, so have Ewatch's methods.
As its client list expanded, the company scrapped manual monitoring
for automated ``spiders'' _ search tools that scour chat groups for
key-word phrases.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this month, Ewatch began a more fundamental
overhaul, upgrading its software and server computers to quadruple
the speed at which they scan and process information. The company
also replaced its home-brewed search engine with search software
from Excalibur Technology, which will be coupled with a new Oracle
data base management system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is experiencing uncontrollable growth, and we
have to be prepared for it,'' said Alexander, who also said that
the upgrade would cost $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, Ewatch combs through more than 250,000 postings from
the sprawling online discussion forum known as Usenet. It also
monitors thousands of other postings from the financial chat rooms
on leading Web sites, including Yahoo and Motley Fool, while also
scanning discussion areas on the leading proprietary online
services like America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the challenge of keeping apace of Internet growth,
Ewatch has another concern: competition.
</P>
<P>
   Among the handful of competitors offering monitoring services
are Cybercheck, a Denver company that says it can search for key
words in 150,000 online sources, and Cyveillance, an Alexandria,
Va., company that scans the bit stream for rumors, trademark
infringements and e-commerce developments that might affect its
corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   But Louis M. Thompson, president and chief executive of the
National Investor Relations Institute, a trade group based in
Vienna, Va., said that among Internet monitoring companies, Ewatch
``seems to be the big one on the block.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewatch serves about 130 clients full time, including US West,
H.J. Heinz, Owens Corning and Northwest Airlines. It is no longer
independent, having been acquired by Wavephore Inc., a publicly
held data broadcasting company based in Phoenix. But it is still
operated by the brothers, with Alexander overseeing marketing from
New York and Lukaszewski operating the technology side from
Minneapolis, where the brothers were raised.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said that corporations had come to realize that the
same attributes that make the Internet a valuable commercial medium
_ such as the ability to quickly and cheaply spread information to
the masses _ can be a liability, too. That is especially true as
the rising popularity of online stock trading has placed a
fast-twitch premium on corporate information, often with little
regard to its accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as more companies come to recognize the perils of the
electronic grapevine, Ewatch and other monitoring agents are
finding that their real competitors are often their would-be
clients. Many companies use in-house resources to monitor the
Internet, or ask their public relations firms to do the work.
</P>
<P>
   Even if companies acknowledge that Ewatch may have superior
surveillance capabilities, they may not always be convinced that
the $13,000-a-year service is worth the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Take Itex Corp., a small, publicly held financial record-keeping
company in Portland, Ore., which has filed a lawsuit against
several people whom Itex accuses of making defamatory remarks
against the company in a Yahoo chat room.
</P>
<P>
   Since the company filed its suit, the burden of trolling the
Internet for corporate gossip is being borne by the company's
assistant general counsel, Stephen C. Pearson. He said the small
public company _ which was recently delisted from the Nasdaq stock
market after the Securities and Exchange Commission said Itex had
failed to submit its annual report on time _ could not afford the
likes of Ewatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at Ewatch in particular and did a brief analysis of
their systems,'' Pearson said. ``We came to the conclusion that it
was pretty expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Ewatch's better capitalized bigger clients say the
service has proved valuable, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a loose and free exchange of information on the
Internet,'' said Tom Pinto, spokesman for the giant pension system
TIAA-CREF, which manages more than $250 billion in assets.
``Anything that is inaccurate or harmful, we want to know
immediately about it and respond.''
</P>
<P>
   One day last October, for example, a visitor to a Compuserve
discussion room wrote that a TIAA-CREF pension fund called Global
Equities held 25 percent of its assets in Asia. In fact, the fund
held only 5 percent of its assets in the region, and it was a
potentially devastating error, coming amid the Asian economic
crisis. Had the rumor spread, Pinto recalled, it might have caused
investors to flee the $6 billion pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, an Ewatch report landed on Pinto's desk. Two days
later, the TIAA-CREF manager of media relations sent e-mail to the
mediator of the chat group, who posted a correction.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of thousands of messages posted daily to tens of
thousands of Internet message boards, it might seem humanly
impossible to patrol even a fraction of cyberspace. But Ewatch
relies on its search spiders and computers to do most of the
culling, before handing off to the half-dozen people Ewatch employs
to do the final winnowing before passing along the information to
clients.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the searches have periodically turned up some
juicy material. Take the episode, for instance, when a group of
restive shareholders plotted online to disrupt an annual corporate
meeting _ even agreeing to the clothes they would wear so they
could identify one another.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Ewatch clients are not necessarily looking for bad
tidings, but simply any news or discussions that might be relevant
to the company. Owens Corning, based in Toledo, Ohio, instructs
Ewatch to search not just for its name, but also for the words
``fiberglass,'' ``insulation'' and ``asphalt,'' Jim Worden, an
Owens Corning spokesman, said. Such searches, he said, help the
company stay abreast of consumer sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Ewatch will be offered for an extra fee to subscribers of
Wavephore's primary product, Newscast, which gives corporations
tailored news feeds from thousands of sources like Dow Jones,
Reuters and PR Newswire. And Ewatch subscribers, in turn, will be
given access to Newscast Lite, a significantly slimmed-down version
of Newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Alexander said he would like to create a service
that would help a company analyze the combined impact of Internet
rumors, media coverage and the client's own public relations
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Although he acknowledged that plenty of details still need to be
worked out, he envisions the day when a client could type in a
natural-language query like ``Why are sales lagging in Minnesota?''
and receive reports about marketing, media and mendacity that might
help explain the problem.
</P>
<P>
   And on the assumption that no news is not necessarily good news,
the company plans eventually to monitor not only for gossip and
innuendo, but for the absence of chatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a company that's spent $100 million on a launch
campaign and no one's talking about you _ why is that?'' Alexander
said. ``If there's nothing about you online, isn't that valuable
information to know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
