<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ HAS NEW CHALLENGER FOR GOLD GLOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez faces his
first Gold Glove challenge this year. Charles Johnson has come to
the American League.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles traded for Johnson this winter after he
spent the past four seasons with the Los Angeles Dodgers and the
Florida Marlins. He was the National League's Gold Glove winner at
catcher all four years.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has been the American League winner in each of his
seven full seasons. Only Hall of Famer Johnny Bench, with 10 Gold
Glove awards, has won more among catchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both outstanding players,'' Boston manager Jimy
Williams said. ``To be voted by your peers that many times, it's
something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, a lifetime .295 hitter, is easily the better
offensive player. He has also been an All-Star the past seven
seasons. Johnson, a career .234 hitter, has never made an All-Star
team.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gold Glove, voted on by league managers and coaches, is
only about defense, and Rodriguez faces a formidable challenge this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about that,'' Rodriguez said. ``Goals ...
that's for the end of the year. I'm going to do my job, he's going
to do his job. I just play hard to make this team make the playoffs
and the World Series, that's the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I say to him is good luck, I hope he stays
injury free and hope he has a good season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Glove offers an interesting contrast because, as
Rangers pitcher Rick Helling said, ``They're both similar, but they
are both different.''
</P>
<P>
   The similarity is in ability. The difference is style.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is big and strong. Rodriguez is short and quick. Both
have fabulous throwing arms, still the most important asset for any
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   But the similarities end there.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball people who have watched them both say Rodriguez is
better at throwing out runners and getting to balls hit in front of
the plate. Johnson is given the edge when it comes to fewer passed
balls and blocking wild pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Former Marlins reliever Robb Nen, commenting on Johnson's
ability to block pitches in the dirt, said throwing to Johnson ``is
like throwing to a brick wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Witt, a former Ranger and Marlin who, like Nen and
Helling, has thrown to both Rodriguez and Johnson, said, ``Charles,
as far as blocking balls, he's the best. He gets mad if the ball
gets by him. He can't stand it. No matter what you throw, he feels
he shouldn't let it get by.''
</P>
<P>
   A major-league scout said, ``Johnson is fundamentally sound. He
always goes to his knees and blocks the ball properly. Pudge has
great quickness but sometimes he reaches for balls rather than
blocking them. He gets lazy and balls get away that shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's tremendous concentration was evident in 1997, when he
went the entire season with no errors and only one passed ball. He
holds the major-league record with 172 consecutive errorless games.
Rodriguez's best is 61 consecutive errorless games.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four years, Johnson has allowed only 18 passed
balls and committed 17 errors. Rodriguez, in the same span, has
allowed 31 passed balls and committed 31 errors. But Rodriguez has
also played in 104 more games _ 578 to 474 _ than Johnson during
that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a lot of pride in my defense, but I'm not going to get
caught up in the Gold Glove thing,'' Johnson said. ``As a player,
you want to win it, no doubt. But you want to be judged fairly and
hope they take into consideration everything _ errors, passed
balls, wild pitches, runners caught stealing, everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you're judged across the board, if his numbers are
better than mine, he deserves it. If my numbers are better than
his, I hope I'm deserving.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has been more successful than Rodriguez at throwing out
basestealers in recent years. He has led the major leagues in
throwing out basestealers the past four seasons, nailing 49.3
percent, compared to Johnson's 43.3 percent during the same
stretch. Runners tried stealing 53 more times against Johnson even
though he played 104 less games than Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better pick your spots with both of them if you're going
to go because they've got a good chance of throwing you out,'' said
Red Sox center fielder Darren Lewis, a former National Leaguer with
215 career steals. ``You look at both those guys on defense, it
doesn't get any better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has another advantage over Johnson as a thrower and
that's his ability to pick off base runners. His aggressiveness
leads to more errors, but he has also picked off 27 baserunners the
past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just freezes runners,'' Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild
said. ``You sit there and say before the game, he's going to throw
through, he's going to throw to first, he's going to throw to
second, he's going to throw to third. Be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you can see, when he gets set to throw and it's so quick,
the runner freezes. Then his arm is so strong, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Physical statistics do not alone determine a catcher's defensive
worth. Calling games and handling pitchers also comes into play.
Houston Astros pitchers, for instance, give Brad Ausmus much of the
credit for their recent success.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is considered adept at calling a game. Rodriguez is
considered to be improving, although it's long been considered an
area where he needs the most work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely gotten better,'' Witt said. ``A lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, however, said, ``To me it doesn't matter. I pretty much
call my own gme. If I don't like what they put down, I just shake
them off.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to who is the best overall catcher, Helling makes
the best point. ``I'd take either one of them. There's no question
they're the two best catchers in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But only one can win the Gold Glove this year.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
