<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS GM DIDN'T PANIC AFTER WINTER REBUFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ After a winter of being rejected,
spurned, stood-up and cold-shouldered, Doug Melvin could have:
</P>
<P>
   (a) Dropped a note to Dear Abby. (Signed, Desperate Doug in
Arlington).
</P>
<P>
   (b) Taken the cheesy route by shedding a tear on The Jerry
Springer Show.
</P>
<P>
   (c) Written a country song.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Melvin did the manly thing. He refused to take ``no''
for an insult, even as that Randy Johnson-Roger Clemens-Todd
Stottlemyre echo pounded his eardrums.
</P>
<P>
   By regrouping, what Melvin eventually ended up with is the best
overall Rangers' team in history _ if you don't count the pitching
rotation. Yeah, just that.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin: ``I don't mind matching our everyday lineup against
anybody's, based on offensive production, offensive balance,
defensive skill and defensive balance up the middle. Plus, there's
enough of a speed factor. It's only my opinion, but we've got a
chance to be real good.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, of course, is a so-so rotation surviving behind run
support and defense. It might work. It would work much better if
Randy or Roger were included, or maybe even Todd. But that's
yesterday's heartbreak. Baseball life moves on.
</P>
<P>
   And for those of us who claim the Rangers flunked their No. 1
off-season priority _ corraling a rotation ace _ manager Johnny
Oates has this message:
</P>
<P>
   Get a baseball grip.
</P>
<P>
   Oates waived his Miranda rights the other day, and also
volunteered to be strapped to a polygraph. His version of the
truth, even without legal counsel being present, is he never asked
Melvin or owner Tom Hicks to make Johnson or Clemens the top winter
priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortstop,'' said Oates. ``I requested they make sure we were
strong at shortstop. As strong as we were once Royce Clayton joined
us \Rin late July '98).\S
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, as it turned out, didn't say ``no.'' He re-enlisted in
Arlington. And then a pleasant surprise for Oates was when Rafael
Palmeiro refused to take from the Rangers any other answer except
``yes.'' Rafael wanted to come back, and made it happen. What also
happened was an instant offensive and defensive upgrade at first
base, plus the perfect No. 5 hitter behind Juan Gonzalez, a
seldom-mentioned area where the Rangers were lacking.
</P>
<P>
   An ailing knee has limited Palmeiro thus far, and as a
precaution, Rafael returned to Texas yesterday for a medical check.
When healthy, however, this is a premier hitter and glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally,'' said Oates, ``I think we had a great winter. You
can talk all you want about the pitcher we didn't get, but Randy
Johnson made a family decision \Rto sign with Arizona and live at
home in Phoenix\S, and Roger Clemens simply wanted to pitch for the
Yankees. I can't hold that against him.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the Rangers certainly wanted to re-sign Stottlemyre,
they had a financial ceiling on him. ``What'd he get in Arizona?''
asked Oates, knowing the answer was $8 million a season. ``Well,
that was a heck of a lot more than we were gonna pay. There are
exceptions like Rafael and Pudge \RRodriguez\S and Randy
\RJohnson\S. But mainly these guys don't care where they live.
Waive a few extra million in their face, and they will live on the
moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates found last season he couldn't live without an established
shortstop. ``Put Randy Johnson or Roger Clemens on our team last
season and we don't win the division without Royce Clayton,'' he
said. ``We wouldn't have caught enough balls. Look at everybody
that wins in our league _ they have a tremendous shortstop. You can
have an ace, but you still won't win without a shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton hadn't been in Arlington three weeks when it was already
safe to declare him the best defensive shortstop in franchise
history. That is not necessarily a compliment, considering the
misadventures of past job holders. But actually, Clayton may be
twice as good as the Rangers have ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Stottlemyre, Clayton was also liking what he was seeing
during his two-plus months with the Rangers. ``Other teams were
calling \Rover the winter\S,'' he said, ``but I kept telling my
parents, where was I going to find a better place to live, a better
ballpark, or a better chance to be on a winner. These people,
starting with the owner, want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the emphasis, and rightfully so, has been on pitchers the
Rangers couldn't land over the winter. But what they did get in
Clayton and Palmeiro was much more than consolation prizes. They
are both key ingredients to success.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Doug Melvin, if he had so desired, could have written in
that country song this winter:
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit me below the belt, darlin', but I was wearing my
Wranglers higher than you thought.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
