<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ'S DEAL COULD BE EXTENDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers are expected to discuss a
long-term contract extension for outfielder Juan Gonzalez when club
president Tom Schieffer arrives in camp later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's agent, Jim Bronner, also is expected to be in Port
Charlotte at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll sit down and talk about it then,'' Rangers general
manager Doug Melvin said. ``We'll be able to tell after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has two years left on the seven-year, $45.45 million
contract he signed before the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to play baseball,'' Gonzalez said. ``My contract is
up to my agent, Mr. Schieffer and Doug.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got an idea of how much it will take to keep
Gonzalez when the Rockies signed Larry Walker to a six-year, $75
million contract last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``His signing is somewhere in there,'' Melvin said. ``Mo Vaughn
is right there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn signed a six-year, $80 million contract with the Angels
in the off-season, making him the highest-paid position player in
baseball. The highest-paid player is Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown,
who signed a seven-year, $105 million contract.
SIMMS OUT
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Mike Simms has a torn Achilles tendon and is
expected to be sidelined three to four weeks. Simms injured his
foot running last week.
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league pitcher Corey Lee also is out indefinitely after
cutting his left index finger with a knife when he was slicing a
bagel.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers good news concerns pitcher John Wetteland, who is
sidelined with an ankle injury. He threw 20 minutes in the bullpen
yesterday and is expected to pitch batting practice tomorrow.
Pirates 15, Rangers 6
</P>
<P>
   Rangers pitchers gave up 18 hits and walked seven against the
Pirates at Charlotte County Stadium yesterday, throwing 182
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's way too many pitches,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said. ``We need to throw more strikes, get ahead of hitters, let
them hit it and see if we can catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the plate: First baseman Lee Stevens went 2-for-3 yesterday
with three runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound: Aaron Sele breezed through the first inning, but
couldn't get out of the second, allowing six runs on six hits and a
walk. Oates said Sele was throwing mainly fastballs in the second
inning. Mike Morgan took over and threw 21/3 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the field: Second baseman Mark McLemore and shortstop Royce
Clayton failed to turn an inning-ending double play with the bases
loaded in the fifth. Instead they got just one, and the Pirates
ended up with four runs off pitcher Mike Munoz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
