<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULL-RIDING-ST.-LOUIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST TOPS FIRST-ROUND FIELD AT ST. LOUIS SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ For the past year, Terry Don West has patiently
waited for a match against the bucking bull Gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, West's wishes were fulfilled in a big way as the
former world champion won the first round of the St. Louis Open
with a score of 91.5 at the Kiel Center.
</P>
<P>
   West topped the spinning bull at the Professional Bull Riders
Bud Light Cup Series' 10th stop of the 1999 season. The two-day
show is scheduled to conclude this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the tour is scheduled to stop in Fort Worth for the
Tuff Hedeman Championship Challenge, scheduled Friday through March
14, at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis this weekend, West, a Henryetta, Okla., resident,
said he was elated to learn that he would face Gusto, which is
owned H.D. Page of Ardmore, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen him before and I had wanted to draw him, and
tonight was my night,'' West said. ``He was a hard bucker, but I
got in time with him and he felt good to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time world champion Jim Sharp, who returned this weekend
after being sidelined for 10 months with a dislocated shoulder,
finished second in the round with a 90.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got on a couple of practice bulls last week, and my shoulder
felt good,'' Sharp said. ``I needed to practice because when you
come to one of these shows, you'll get a good bucker.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp topped Magic Carpet Ride, owned by Jerry Nelson. ``After
laying off, I feel really healthy,'' Sharp said.
MURRAY'S ABSENCE
</P>
<P>
   Though seven-time world all-around champion Ty Murray will not
qualify for tonight's Houston Livestock Show Rodeo final round, the
Stephenville cowboy could win Houston's $25,000 prize, which is
presented to the two-week rodeo's all-around winner. Murray could
win the all-around title on the basis of strong finishes in
preliminary rounds during the Professional Rodeo Cowboys
Association show.
</P>
<P>
   Murray is scheduled to compete in this afternoon's PBR show in
St. Louis. Last night, Murray, who leads the 1999 cup series race,
finished sixth in the first round with an 85.5.
MORAES' ABSENCE
</P>
<P>
   Adriano Moraes, the PBR's 1994 Bud Light Cup Series champion,
said he will decline to compete on the 1999 tour. Moraes, who lives
near Sao Paulo, Brazil, said he plans to spend most of his time at
his home tending to his year-old son, working on his ranch and
doing church work.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Moraes was sidelined for about six months after
breaking his leg at the PBR show in Fort Worth. He has recently
recovered from being sidelined for about three months; Moraes
suffered a broken clavicle at the November PBR World championships
in Las Vegas.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
