A0894 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-UTAH-REACTION-TEX     03-07 1812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-UTAH-REACTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC MESS SHAKES UTAH'S PRIDE, MAYBE ITS FAITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Sanctuaried by high walls and serenaded by the
11,000 pipes of the Mormon Tabernacle organ, Temple Square has long
been a tranquil retreat in this decidedly godly city.
</P>
<P>
   But even here, on the home grounds of the Church of Jesus Christ
of Latter-day Saints, there are signs.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of intruders, like the massive road work taking place
beyond the north gate. Sounds of jackhammers, crumbling what was
old to make way for the new.
</P>
<P>
   The 2002 Winter Olympics is lapping at Temple Square's saintly
heels.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Utah, Mike Leavitt, is a Mormon. The new head of
the Salt Lake Olympic Organizing Committee, Mitt Romney, is a
Mormon. The former head of the bid committee, Tom Welch, is a
Mormon.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 70 percent of Utah's 2 million residents are
Mormons, which is not presented here to imply anything about the
denomination or about Olympic corruption, but rather to give an
idea of the communion of souls that make up this valley of the
Wasatch Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city grows, and people move here each year from places
like California,'' said Catherine Collins, a mother of five and
lifelong resident. ``But I'd like to think that we've stayed a
simple and honest people. We have a high sense of right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, yes, I worry about the damage that the Olympic mess has
done to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In a state where image matters, Utahns' pride has been shaken as
well as maybe even their faith. Welch was a former church bishop.
He resigned in 1997 after spousal abuse charges were filed, and he
was the ground-zero target of accusations rendered in a February
300-page ethics report.
</P>
<P>
   Utahns bear each day's news, wondering what will be next. They
wince. They wait. They want to move on.
UNDER INVESTIGATION
</P>
<P>
   Last week in New York, a special commission of the U.S. Olympic
Committee blamed the USOC itself for not exercising more stringent
oversight of the Salt Lake bid committee. Chaired by former senator
George J. Mitchell, the USOC panel also called on President Clinton
to declare the International Olympic Committee a ``public
international organization,'' a designation that would make bribing
its officials a crime punishable under the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   The next in a series of reports from five separate probes into
Salt Lake-related improper spending and unethical conduct will come
when the IOC convenes March 17 in Lausanne, Switzerland.
Twenty-four IOC members have either already resigned or are under
suspicion and could eventually be recommended for expulsion at that
special session.
</P>
<P>
   Still to be released are the findings of an investigation by the
Utah state attorney general's office and a probe by the FBI and
U.S. Justice Department. The latter, which is expected to be
released late this month, could lead to criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   The report that the Salt Lake Organizing Committee (SLOC) Board
of Ethics presented is 2 1/2 inches thick. It details a pattern of
excessive gift-giving and favor-rendering to members of the IOC and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   Among the charges: Jean-Claude Ganga of the Congo Republic
soaked the Salt Lake committee for gifts estimated at $250,000,
including plastic surgery for his wife and shopping sprees at
Wal-Mart. Other charges border on potentially criminal. General
Zein El Abdin Mohamed Abdel Gadir, IOC member from Sudan, once
faxed the bid committee requesting that $1,000 per month be sent to
``Zema Gadir,'' the general's supposed daughter. The general, as it
turned out, has no daughter named Zema. The name is a pseudonym for
Gadir himself. He simply put the first letters of all his names
together.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the SLOC report charged that 24 IOC members or their
associates received, either directly or indirectly, an estimated
$1.2 million in cash, scholarships, free trips, medical care and
sundry improper inducements from the Utah bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in last week's USOC findings, however, there was no
smoking gun in the SLOC report. Nothing to link a direct payment
with an explicit promise of a vote. Rather, according to attorney
David Jordan, the evidence shows that, ``There was an explicit goal
of establishing long-term, vote-influencing relationships with IOC
members.''
</P>
<P>
   The SLOC board even cited a date _ June 15, 1991, the day that
Salt Lake City, bidding for the 1998 Olympic Winter Games, lost on
the final ballot to Nagano, Japan, by four votes.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering for the vote in Birmingham, England, the Salt Lake
contingent distributed ``goodie bags'' to IOC members of Utah
souvenirs and home-grown products. Among the token gifts were
disposable cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The Nagano committee gave the IOC voters Sony camcorders. It
hosted lavish parties.
</P>
<P>
   As the report later read, ``The exposure to Nagano's well-oiled
bid machine and to the excessive demands of certain IOC members
would prove to be a watershed event that shaped the approach of Mr.
Welch and Mr. \RDave\S Johnson to the campaign for the 2002
Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning from England, Welch and Johnson, the bid
committee's former vice president, met with board trustees and
civic leaders to analyze what went wrong. They decided to press
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   There would be more fund-raising. Staff was increased. There was
a successful push to the Utah legislature to approve infrastructure
projects and build facilities that would be used should Salt Lake
City get the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   With the increased commitment came added pressure for Welch and
Johnson. This time, they had to deliver the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the excesses that followed filled the 300 pages of last
month's report. The U.S. Justice Department report, however, could
have far more serious repercussions. FBI investigators, for one
thing, have been able to use their power of subpoena to examine
bank records and interview individuals not available to the SLOC,
USOC and IOC panels. Four separate prosecutors and 15 FBI agents
have been assigned to the federal government's Salt Lake City
probe.
</P>
<P>
   For Utahns, however, the damage already is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to look at the newspapers,'' said Mary
Stringham, a bank clerk from Bountiful, Utah. ``To me, it's no
longer the Olympics the way I always thought they were. It's greed.
It's people I don't even want to be associated with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, some of those people are . . . us.''
`WHAT'S WRONG IS WRONG'
</P>
<P>
   In Crossroads Plaza, the downtown shopping mall directly across
the street from Temple Square, sales of Olympic souvenirs have not
slowed, store managers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not allowed to talk about that,'' said a young store
clerk, a student at nearby University of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being an honest person,'' said a shopper who would only
give her name as ``Lea.'' ``What's happened here, as far as I'm
concerned, isn't any better than the Clinton thing. What's wrong is
wrong. What's right is right.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial fears here were that in the wake of the scandal, the
Games would be taken from Salt Lake City and moved elsewhere. IOC
president Juan Antonio Samaranch was quick to assure that that
would never happen.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch himself remains under a veritable public relations
siege. Editorial writers around the globe have called for his
resignation. Corporations, including advertising's 5,000-pound
gorilla _ Coca-Cola _ said two weeks ago that are re-evaluating
their investment in the Olympics. One of the Salt Lake sponsors, US
West, temporarily withheld a $5 million payment in January until it
felt that steps were being taken toward reform.
</P>
<P>
   And just last week, the USOC turned a chilly shoulder when asked
whether it would endorse the notion of Samaranch continuing after
the IOC special session next week.
</P>
<P>
   The new head of SLOC, Romney, has been summoned home from
Massachusetts to mend some of those corporate and diplomatic
fences. Romney said last week that he sees ``no alarm'' in raising
the private funds to meet the Games' $1.45 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   His attitude has re-energized the local community, some say.
</P>
<P>
   A survey whose results were published last week in the ``Salt
Lake Tribune'' says that two-thirds of Utah residents still believe
that the area can host a scandal-free and successful 2002 Olympics.
The same survey also said that 75 percent of those polled want
former trustees of the bid committee who are still on the SLOC
board to publicly acknowledge some responsibility for the
misconduct and/or resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mormons are proud of being moral people and abiding by the
commandments,'' said Darien Fry, a computer consultant from Salt
Lake City. ``So all this has been a deep jolt to what we believe in
and what we feel we stand for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embarrassed? Yes, I would say so. But recovering? I would say
that we are recovering, too.''
SCANDAL THERAPY
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days before the scandal broke last December, the LDS
church had publicly endorsed the idea of the Olympics coming to
Utah. Church spokesmen have avoided most comment on the ensuing
troubles, other than to describe the bribes and payments as ``a
terrible lapse in moral judgment'' and to remind reporters sternly
that these are not the ``Mormon Olympics.'' One LDS spokesman
likened the queries to calling the Vatican every time there was
news of a Mafia slaying.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs of Olympic-scandal therapy in the works. A
stone's throw from SLOC headquarters and from Temple Square, a
local photofinishing company owner decided to put a wry twist on
the Olympic scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Green of Creative Color hosted ``Schmooze Day,'' and
invited downtown business people to come in and be wined and dined
like a true IOC committee member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bribery,'' Green concluded, tongue in cheek, ``is an effective
tool in attracting business.''
</P>
<P>
   While a piano player tickled the keyboard with free ``Olympic
songs'' like ``Love With A Proper Stranger'' and ``Something to
Remember You By'', customers were schmoozed with free manicures,
massages and shoe shines. A suitcase filled with Monopoly money
added to the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can read only so much without saying enough already,''
said Wendy Ripley, the company's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   As Ripley noted, the Salt Lake City Games are still three years
away. That is ample time, she said, for images to be repaired and
for wounded souls to heal.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, Utahns hope _ and maybe pray _ the
investigations will be over and the winter athletes will finally
take over the newspapers and the television reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep reminding myself,'' Stringham said, ``that this is all
about the athletes. But it's hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, when this is all over, what we'll remember are them
and the medals they won. I pray for that. I really do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
