<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR TO GET A BIG-NAME BASKETBALL COACH? DREAM ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ This space is normally reserved for ``another
view.'' And that perhaps is entirely appropriate for today's
subject.
</P>
<P>
   It will be some time before a lot of people have any other view
of Baylor athletic director Tom Stanton and university president
Robert Sloan other than that of the pair of them bolting from
Kemper Arena on Thursday while their basketball team was still
playing on the court below.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation offered by another Baylor staff member was that
they had a plane to catch. OK, I'll accept that. So let's just say
the two of them _ especially Stanton _ were guilty of nothing more
than short-sighted and abysmally bad judgment and exhibited a total
lack of public relations awareness. Which is nothing new at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Where should they have been? Well, for my money they should have
either taken a later flight or delayed departure until the next day
to have been present in the postgame dressing room _ where other
Big 12 administrators frequently appear in similar situations.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they had not given now former coach Harry Miller the
time of day, they should have been there to console and _ yeah _
congratulate a basketball team that could have but did not go
belly-up on Miller and the university a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there on Thursday were the Bears, overmatched again but
playing to the last minute. The temptation is to imagine that as a
courageous Kish Lewis was tearing across the Kemper floor in quest
of a loose ball during the last minute of a 26-point loss, that his
university's administration was in a rental car squealing out of
the parking lot for the airport.
</P>
<P>
   This is a way to treat a team, a coach they've repeatedly
referred to as one with a great deal of character and integrity?
Those qualities _ on that day at least _ were lacking at the top.
</P>
<P>
   What does that have to do with the next coach? Maybe nothing. Or
maybe it becomes yet another reason for some qualified candidate to
doubt the wisdom of interest in a job that could be a ticket to
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has some illusions of grandeur. I keep hearing that we'll
all be surprised at the quality of the man who is chosen to succeed
Miller. But all I can think of is the number of coaches I talked to
last spring who were not interested in the Texas A&AMP;M job _ a
position with more available resources and at least the appearance
of a greater chance for success _ though the Aggies got a gem in
Melvin Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   You've possibly heard some of the names already being tossed
around. Names like deposed Iowa coach Tom Davis. Or Tulsa's Bill
Self. Southwest Missouri's Steve Alford. Former Michigan coach
Steve Fisher? Get real.
</P>
<P>
   Would Davis, at 60, want to tackle the chore of building a
program with little foundation and any modicum of success
realistically inside of three seasons?
</P>
<P>
   Self has a good young team and plays in a new arena where he
gets good support and makes good money. He has told friends he's
not interested in Baylor. The long-range speculation is that Self
has eyes on succeeding former boss Eddie Sutton someday at Oklahoma
State.
</P>
<P>
   Alford reportedly has worn out his welcome in some circles at
Southwest Missouri and may be interested in succeeding Davis at
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Baylor and its deep-pocket program backer indeed have a
prized candidate. I hope so. But realistically, this search may
turn to another tier. One that might include promising young guys
like Dickey Nutt at Arkansas State or Barry Hinson at Oral Roberts.
Or, a guy like Oklahoma State assistant Paul Graham _ a sharp guy
with Sutton-Dave Bliss bloodlines who won't have to introduce
himself to Texas high school coaches. Graham has proven he can
recruit the state, where he was formerly a state championship high
school coach at Dallas Kimball.
</P>
<P>
   Will Baylor pay a basketball coach more than the guessed
$400,000 ceiling for new football coach Kevin Steele? Good
question. If their purported big name is a big name, they'll have
to.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
