<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' NOWITZKI STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ From a rookie of the year candidate to
project of the year. That's where the Mavericks stand with Dirk
Nowitzki.
</P>
<P>
   The German native has struggled so much in his first NBA season
that Mavericks coach Don Nelson has reluctantly reduced Nowitzki's
playing time. Instead of showcasing Nowitzki as a starter and
watching him get torched on the defensive end, the Mavericks have
instead decided to spoon-feed minutes to the 7-foot forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll pick his spots for him,'' Nelson said. ``We'll take a
step back, breathe, take a look, do some practices and see how he
goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely in over his head right now, but he's got to
work his way out of it. I read where he's tired, but it's just so
different for him. It's a bigger step than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   But not a bigger step than what Nowitzki thought.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Nowitzki repeatedly said he didn't think he was
ready to play pro basketball at the NBA level. Nelson nevertheless
convinced him to make the jump. He even had Mavericks owner Ross
Perot Jr. travel to Germany to meet Nowitzki's parents.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like Nowitzki was a prophet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inevitable for a rookie to go through periods for
which they don't quite have a feel for the situation,'' guard Steve
Nash said. ``He's only 20, so he's a young rookie and he's been a
long way away from the NBA before this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another stumbling block that'll make him a better
player once he overcomes it, and he'll overcome it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki has averaged only seven points and 3.8 rebounds in 18.8
minutes per game. From the field, he's making only 33.9 percent of
his shots.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, while playing for DJK Wurzburg, Nowitzki averaged
28.3 points, 9.9 rebounds and made 56.1 percent of his shots. .561
percent.]
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought my shot would be going so badly,'' Nowitzki
said. ``But I'm trying to stay cool and keep my head up.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to beef up his body so he can handle the constant
bumping and pounding from opponents, Nowitzki has gone on a
weight-training program and gained 10 pounds in the past three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made improvements,'' Nelson said. ``But he's just
swamped with a little of everything. Physicality is probably a big
part of \Rhis struggles\S, but he hasn't made his outside shot and
we know he's just a fantastic shooter. It's just a learning
process.''
</P>
<P>
   For every poor game Nowitzki has, Mavericks fans scan the box
scores and continue to remind management that they passed up a
known quantity in Kansas forward Paul Pierce, drafted one spot
later by the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like Paul Pierce,'' Nelson said. ``But I think in the long
run, we like our guy \RNowitzki\S better.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
