<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHEME-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY OPERA ' S SEASON BEGINS WITH `BOHEME'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although the spring offerings of the New York City
Opera will feature some much-anticipated productions of less-known
works, including Strauss' ``Intermezzo'' and a Ravel double bill of
``L'Heure Espagnole'' and ``L'Enfant et les Sortileges,'' the
season officially began on Friday night with the most familiar of
all operas, Puccini's ``Boheme.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the City Opera has worked hard, and by most
measures successfully, to distinguish itself from its Lincoln
Center neighbor. Obviously this is easier to do when the company
presents unusual repertory, like Handel's ``Partenope'' and
Carlisle Floyd's ``Of Mice and Men,'' that the Metropolitan Opera
would not be interested in.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night's performance was a reminder of why the City
Opera has something to offer when it comes to the staples. The
company may not be able to cast ``Don Giovanni'' or ``Tosca'' with
world-class voices, but when things go right, it presents young,
ardent singers who plausibly resemble the characters they are
portraying in intimate, freshly rethought productions.
</P>
<P>
   A lot is right about the company's production of ``La Boheme,''
gracefully directed with a eye for telling detail by the former
soprano Graziella Sciutti. The designer John Conklin is credited
with having revised the spare, colorful sets that Michael Anania
created for this 1995 production.
</P>
<P>
   Now the sets are even more spare. For example, the bohemians'
garret in Act I is suggested by a wall-less platform with a chair
here, a table there, and the requisite battered old sofa that Mimi
will come to die on in the last act. But behind them, on a lovely
painted backdrop, is the expanse of Paris in the twilight.
</P>
<P>
   The cast was youthful and appealing. As Mimi, Pamela Armstrong
sang with plaintive tone and unmannered phrasing, though her lyric
soprano voice was not consistently secure. But there was much
beauty in her singing, and her poignant death scene was affectingly
done.
</P>
<P>
   A New York-born tenor, Emmanuel di Villarosa, made his company
debut as Rodolfo. He has a sweet lyric tenor voice and good musical
instincts. His sound is not large, though this is a characteristic,
not a shortcoming. He may not feel the same way, however, for here
and there he pushed his voice to fill out Rodolfo's arching
climactic phrases, and when he did, his sound turned shaky.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest ovation of the night went to the lanky baritone John
Hancock, who, as Marcello, gave the most accomplished performance.
Indira Mahajan brought her bright soprano voice and vitality to the
role of Musetta, but in overdoing Musetta's bundle-of-trouble
willfulness, she let her voice turn shrill at times. Peter Volpe, a
robust bass also making his debut, was a solid Colline; the
baritone James Bobick was an amiable Schaunard.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Mosteller, the conductor, was trying to be sensitive to
the needs of his young singers. But they might have been better off
had he kept the music moving more strictly. The performance was
sometimes languid. The ensemble between the orchestra and singers
was not always together, though this should improve as the run
continues in the spring season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
