<SLUG> BC-PARIS-IMAGINED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REALITY OF PARIS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn.)   By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Paris always has loomed large in the American
imagination: Thomas Jefferson, Henry James, Ernest Hemingway and
James Baldwin all fell under its spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Americans, when they die, go to Paris,'' wrote Thomas
Appleton, Longfellow's brother-in-law. Oscar Wilde said he had it
all wrong: ``When bad Americans die, they go to Paris,'' Wilde
said.
</P>
<P>
   Myth and countermyth have all illuminated and obscured the
historical reality of the city through the centuries, says Patrice
Higonnet, a French-born Harvard professor who has devoted a lecture
series to the subject this year at the College de France.
</P>
<P>
   This prestigious institution has been constructing and
deconstructing myths since 1530, and this year one of its vast
renovated lecture halls, next to the Sorbonne, has been filling
Thursday afternoons with Parisians who come to hear Higonnet
explain how the idea of Paris has changed over the years, not only
in the French but also in the American mind.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway and his friends in the ``lost generation'' were truly
lost in Paris, he says. They did not speak French and were not
interested in the art or culture of the French people around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Hemingway and most of his friends, Paris was one long
binge, all the more enjoyable because it wasn't very expensive,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans may go to Europe to be Americanized, as Ralph Waldo
Emerson put it more than a century ago. But Higonnet, whose father
was French and his mother French and Hungarian, often comes to
Paris to renew his French roots. He was born here 60 years ago but
has taught at Harvard since getting his doctorate there in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The College de France invites some of the finest students of
Europe to do research and then share their findings in lectures and
seminars that are open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, the audience here is retired people who have an
interest in culture,'' Higonnet said, ``but there are also
students, and colleagues who are professors. You can't say stupid
things, but it's impossible to satisfy everybody in the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what this specialist in 18th-century French history has
to say sounds almost new. Think of the Louvre, for example, as the
royal palace of French kings and he will remind you that Louis XIV,
the greatest of them all, could not tolerate Paris and did not
consider it the French capital at all. For the Sun King, that was
the vast palace he built in Versailles, from which he ventured
forth to Paris only 24 times in 44 years. He did not spend the
night in the city if he could help it.
</P>
<P>
   Think of Paris as Notre Dame, and his lectures remind you that
the Enlightenment considered Medieval Paris filthy and barbaric,
and the Cathedral a monstrosity. Desecrated by the Revolution,
Notre Dame de Paris nearly fell to ruins before Victor Hugo took up
its cause and helped to save it in the late 19th century _ as the
centerpiece of a new myth, ``le vieux Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   That myth took root only after the Second Empire Prefect Baron
Georges Eugene Haussmann pierced wide boulevards through the
Quartier Latin and other crowded, ancient neighborhoods to create
the Paris that so many people so love today.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Baudelaire complained to Victor Hugo in 1859 that
Baron Haussmann had ruined the city. ``Paris-New York,'' Baudelaire
called the transformed capital, while Haussmann defensively
riposted that the people who professed admiration for ``old Paris''
knew it only from books.
</P>
<P>
   Other prefects also have their uses, and one, named Poubelle,
even gave his name to the public trash cans that the city began
putting out in the 19th century to try to keep the city clean.
</P>
<P>
   Haussmann's intent actually was to counter another powerful
myth, that of Paris as caldron of revolution.
</P>
<P>
   It was easier for the police to clear crowds from Haussmann's
wide boulevards than from the narrow, twisting and cobbled streets
whose cobblestones were used by Parisians in revolt to build
barricades in 1848.
</P>
<P>
   Students did tear the cobblestones out of the Boulevard
St.-Germain in 1968, Higonnet reported, so the authorities replaced
them with a tarred surface that is difficult to turn into
projectiles. The ``pave'' or cobblestone has a powerful mythology
all its own in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Higonnet's Harvard connection started with his father, Rene A.
Higonnet, who came to the United States in 1920s on a Harvard
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fell in love with America, which at the time had no
national police force, no military draft, and hardly any income
taxes,'' his son said with a laugh. Later, Rene Higonnet and a
partner invented the photocomposition process, which replaced
Linotypes at newspapers. In 1968 he returned to Europe, and he
ended his days in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Higonnet's wife, Margaret, professor of comparative literature
at the University of Connecticut, is American and enjoying the
academic year with her husband in a house on the
Mont-Ste.-Genevieve a cobblestone's throw from where Rene Descartes
once lived.
</P>
<P>
   Higonnet's latest book, ``Goodness Beyond Virtue,'' is about the
Jacobin movement during the Revolution, and after his last lecture
April 15, he said, he planned to write another book about the
Revolution. But, shattering the myth that all the French are
natural-born chefs, he said, ``I'm going to cooking school as soon
as this is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
