<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAT-TV-MEDIA-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDATED MAPS AT HEART OF SATELLITE TV DISPUTE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., Colo., Fla., Maine, Mont., N.Y., Penn.,
Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basketball fans in Denver know that to see local television
broadcasts of Nuggets games, they had better stay home. A signal
from a network affiliate in the city cannot be picked up in Vail,
100 miles away, even though special maps used by regulators to
predict a television signal's reach say it should.
</P>
<P>
   The signal-coverage maps unaccountably view the world as flat,
failing to account for the 14,000-foot Rocky Mountains, among other
obstructions. Designed in the 1950s to prevent signal interference,
the maps are at the center of a legal battle between broadcasters
and the satellite television industry that resulted in 750,000
viewers nationwide losing programming from CBS and Fox last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The cutoff in programming followed a ruling last year by a
federal judge who said that Prime Time 24, a contractor of DirecTV,
the nation's largest satellite television provider, had violated
federal law by illegally delivering network signals to homes in
areas where coverage maps indicate that customers can receive
programming from local stations. Satellite transmission of network
signals is allowed only in areas where local signals are poor.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Lenore Nesbitt of U.S. District Court in Miami, had
set a deadline of Feb. 28 for the satellite transmissions to stop.
On Feb. 26, some DirecTV subscribers who pay extra for network
programs but live in ineligible areas started seeing a static
screen with a brief explanation about the court order. By April 30,
1.5 million more viewers may be cut off.
</P>
<P>
   The court order resulted from a suit brought by CBS Corp. and
Fox Entertainment Group Inc., which contended that the satellite
transmissions were illegal and were taking away advertising revenue
and ratings from their local affiliates by providing network shows
from distant cities.
</P>
<P>
   The cutoff in programming is something of a setback for DirecTV,
which is a unit of Hughes Electronics, a subsidiary of General
Motors Corp. By offering as many as 100 channels, including the
History Channel and HBO, as well as prime-time programming from
eight network affiliates around the nation, DirecTV, and the other
leading satellite television company, the Echostar Communications
Corp., have together attracted 8.5 million subscribers. (Echostar,
which operates Dishnetwork, with two million subscribers, also
transmits network signals; the networks have a suit pending against
the provider.)
</P>
<P>
   Many of these subscribers live behind mountains or tall
buildings, or in rural areas without cable television, and are
willing to pay as much as $50 a month for a large menu of channels
delivered by satellite to $200 pizza-size home receivers. In 10
mostly rural states, like Montana, Maine and Texas, more than 20
percent of television households use satellite dishes, according to
Bruce Leichtman, an analyst with the Yankee Group, a market
research firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Most satellite subscribers, however, are in urban areas. Even
where cable is available, they choose satellite to receive
out-of-town sports broadcasts, to watch David Letterman three hours
early, or to get programming from their old hometown.
</P>
<P>
   During the court dispute in Miami, maps were introduced to show
that a majority of Prime Time 24 subscribers in Los Angeles, New
York, San Francisco, Dallas and Philadelphia live in the forbidden
zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``These folks don't get an acceptable network picture,'' said
Patrick Morrisey, a Washington lawyer for Prime Time 24. ``There
are buildings, planes. The network maps don't tell the true
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Satellite transmission of network programming is clearly a
profitable business. Under the Satellite Home Viewers Act of 1994,
satellite companies can broadcast a network's programming to
unserved households at a cost of 27 cents a subscriber. For a
package of eight network signals, which cost the satellite
companies $2.16 a subscriber, Echostar charged $7.99 and DirecTV
charged $6.67.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Satellite subscribers, meanwhile, are not taking the cutoff in
silence. ``We've been inundated with 3,000 letters and postcards in
the last month,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is the
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, which oversees the
satellite television industry.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation introduced by McCain would allow satellite
subscribers to continue to receive network signals for six months
while the Federal Communications Commission figures out whether
local affiliates are being harmed. It would also permit satellite
broadcasters, for the first time, to carry local signals in local
markets.
</P>
<P>
   A separate bill approved last month by the Senate Judiciary
Committee would enable satellite television companies to get the
copyright licenses they need to transmit local broadcasts, as cable
operators do. And on Thursday, the House Commerce Committee's
telecommunications subcommittee approved legislation calling for a
180-day moratorium on the cutoff order.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasters oppose the proposed measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress should not be in the business of rewarding industries
that willfully and repeatedly violate the law,'' Andrew S. Fisher,
an executive vice president at Cox Broadcasting, said in a recent
Senate hearing. He added that most affected subscribers could get
network reception with a properly installed antenna.
</P>
<P>
   Still, securities analysts expect some sort of revisions to the
satellite broadcasting laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one battle in a long war,'' said Thomas W. Watts, a
satellite analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``It's difficult to
understand what is gained by cutting off 700,000 subscribers for
something that probably will be allowed in six months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
