<HEADER>
A0915 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-REPUBS-2TAKES-     03-07 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-REPUBS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN POWER SHIFTS FROM HOUSE TO SENATE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: R.I., Ind., Ky., Okla., Texas, Idaho)   (ms) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After four years in which House Republicans
dominated Congress, bringing their party its legislative energy as
well as its public-relations disasters and the impeachment drive,
power has shifted on Capitol Hill. In the 106th Congress, Trent
Lott and his Senate majority have become the ascendant Republican
presence.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of change are everywhere. When the congressional
leadership met with President Clinton recently, the new speaker, J.
Dennis Hastert, said little _ Lott talked far more, participants in
the meeting said. Outside on the White House driveway, the pair
fell into the same pattern in front of reporters. Lott, more
polished and more practiced, even jumped in and answered questions
directed to the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In the first congressional recess after the Senate impeachment
trial, there was Lott at a high-profile town meeting in Detroit
promoting tax cuts. With House Republicans little prepared to
conduct a post-impeachment policy offensive, Senate Republicans
gave them the recess packages that they had prepared for their own
members, instructing them on the issues to highlight and explaining
how to talk about them.
</P>
<P>
   And last week it was the Senate that prevailed in budget talks
among Republican leaders. The group agreed to a budget framework
that embraced the Senate Republican position on Social Security and
strategy to counter the Democratic assault on the potent retirement
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans attribute the shift, in part, to Lott's skillful
handling of the Senate impeachment trial, which senators from both
parties say increased his stature. At the same time, the House
Republicans have been weakened by the November elections and the
self-immolation of Newt Gingrich, and then Robert L. Livingston,
the first person selected to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   With the House Republican majority down to only six members
(five, at the moment, with the retirement of Livingston), Hastert's
deputies concede they barely have control over the House, let alone
the leeway to lead in crafting new themes.
</P>
<P>
   Thrown into the job when Livingston resigned in December,
Hastert, an Illinois Republican, is still trying to sort out how to
govern under such difficult circumstances and how to hold his once
raucous, now shaken flock together.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he is trying to rein in the impulsive Republican
firebrands and keep them from taking public stands that make it
more difficult to pull together legislative compromises.
Republicans say he recently told them not to commit themselves
completely to any specific tax cut, in order to give the House and
Senate more flexibility in deciding which proposal they will
ultimately back.
</P>
<P>
   And where once Gingrich was such an overpowering presence that
no other leader could emerge, Hastert, a former high school
teacher, is the rambunctious Georgian's polar opposite. He is most
comfortable outside the limelight and wants to avoid any showy
missteps, his advisers and colleagues say. His public appearances
tend to be risk-free. Last week, he read Dr. Seuss to school
children, welcomed the Boy Scouts to the Capitol and talked about
making ``the future better for all of our nation's children'' in
the weekly Republican radio address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his style is more low-profile and behind the scenes,''
said Sen. Tim Hutchinson, an Arkansas Republican who formerly
served in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the natural flow of things places Trent in more
of a spokesman's role than Denny even desires to have,'' Hutchinson
said. ``It's not what Denny wants for himself and he doesn't see
this as a primary goal and that moves the center of gravity to
Trent Lott. And until we have a presidential nominee come to the
fore, Trent will be the primary spokesman for the party.''
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics could change once again, as Hastert gains
experience. House Republicans are hoping he will turn out to be a
more effective leader than Gingrich, who was a font of ideas but
also of controversy. But for now, congressional Republicans have an
enormous amount riding on how well their senators and Lott, an
order-obsessed Mississippi conservative with a pragmatic streak,
can lead them. House Republicans have lost seats for two elections
in a row and the impeachment proceedings left the party at new lows
in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, moreover, believe strongly that the policy terrain
has shifted since the Republicans took control of the House and now
tilts in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '94 it was abortion, guns and welfare and we were on the
defensive,'' said Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy, the Rhode Island
Democrat and Kennedy scion who has taken over the House Democrats'
election effort. Now, he said, ``it's Social Security, Medicare and
education. Those are Democratic issues and we are on the offensive
_ and they are on the defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans fear that if they do not come up with a
compelling agenda this year and soften their avenging image, even a
charismatic presidential candidate will not be able to help them
hold their House majority in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to run as a team with whoever gets the nomination,''
said Rep. David M. McIntosh, R-Ind. ``I'd hate to see a situation
where we elect a President and not a Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the chairman of the Republican National
Committee, has warned the congressional leaders that they have to
end the disarray that left them without a platform to run on in
1998, and trying instead to ride to victory on Clinton's scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody understands that we need a unity agenda,''
said Clifford D. May, director of communications for the Republican
National Committee. ``There needs to be a message from Congress, a
reason for governors to support Republicans in Washington and for
our candidates not to run against Washington,'' he said, expressing
the hope that Republican presidential candidates will not want to
distance themselves from the Republican Congress.  &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Lott took the first step toward giving Republicans a new
definition by holding the impeachment trial to five weeks and
working closely with his Democratic counterpart, Sen. Tom Daschle
of South Dakota, to preserve civility in the Senate. He did so,
even though it irked conservative groups who are his natural
allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That strengthened him with the American people as a whole,''
said Hutchinson, ``but if you look at the core constituencies of
the GOP, they are not happy with how the process went in the
Senate. They do not feel the House managers got a fair shake and
they lay that at Lott's doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Still Hutchinson added, ``He'll never face a bigger challenge
than he did on impeachment. He walked his way through a
minefield.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott and his leadership team also prepared Senate Republicans
for a fast start with legislation, aware that the party had to
blunt the effects of impeachment as soon as the trial ended. ``He
was ready to go right after the trial,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell,
a Kentucky Republican.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the first week back from the recess that followed the
impeachment trial, the Senate approved a pay raise for the military
_ part of a Republican effort to strike a Reaganesque posture on
defense. Last week, the Senate debated legislation to give states
more flexibility in spending federal education money.
</P>
<P>
   The House, by contrast, has been wiling away its time by passing
uncontroversial measures like a nonbinding proclamation that
Congress should strengthen Social Security and a measure giving
leeway to Amish parents to employ their teen-agers in family
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Lott and Hastert took a large step toward ameliorating
last year's disarray when they and their budget committee chairmen
agreed on a budget framework. But not everyone is sure Lott will be
able to sustain his quick start and his influence. Some Senate
Republicans privately criticize him for being indecisive and too
watchful of potential conservative rivals such as his
second-in-command, Don Nickles of Oklahoma, or of the strong-willed
Phil Gramm of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also could soon become as bogged down as the House.
Fifty-five senators make up the Republican majority but that is not
enough to break the filibusters that the opposition can mount on
any issue. The education bill on the Senate floor, to the dismay of
some Republicans, has already become a vehicle for an amendment war
and a fierce partisan battle over education priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lott and Hastert, despite last week's agreement on budget
principles, still face the daunting task of assembling the votes
for the components of a budget plan that will require them to make
deep reductions in domestic programs. They may very well find the
spending bills are too lean to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Some House Republicans who believe they have taken too much of
the blame for their party's failures say that keeping warring
conservatives and moderates united is a taxing, no-win task. ``They
are going to have a headache every day between now and Election
Day,'' said one influential House Republican aide of the Senate
Republicans. ``Because it isn't easy and if they really get into
this role, they will be responsible, with no one else in the party
to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republicans say they are prepared to play a more
aggressive role, when needed, to help their House counterparts.
``We may be asked to take some of the tough votes first and work
things through to help with the momentum in the House,'' said Sen.
Larry E. Craig, an Idaho Republican in the Senate leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said: ``Clearly there's an understanding on the
Senate side that the House is in a precarious position, that they
are not in a strong position to move forward aggressively. That
does create a kind of vacuum that you will find senators ready to
step up to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
