<SLUG> BC-SUE-MILLER-INTERVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUE MILLER DISCOVERS A TROVE OF DOMESTICITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Mass., Ill. )  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her fiction, from her first novel, ``The Good Mother,'' to
her latest, ``While I Was Gone,'' Sue Miller is the doyenne of
domesticity. Probing beneath the surface of marriages, she uncovers
the disharmony as well as an individual's urge to find an
alternative life.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Becker, the protagonist of the new novel, a veterinarian
happily married to a minister and the mother of three grown
daughters, is content in her present until a man from her past
suddenly reappears. She is forced to come to terms with her
previous life and with a personal trauma, the unsolved murder of
her best friend, a woman of great magnetism who influenced others
through ``a sort of phototropism.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of her short stories, ``Travel,'' Ms. Miller says about a
character, ``She wasn't who she thought she was.'' During a recent
interview she acknowledged that the search for another self was a
continuous theme in her work. She characterized it as ``the
difference between the self we present to people and the self we
feel ourselves to be,'' leading to the eternal question of ``how
much we can truly know another person.''
</P>
<P>
   During her own life Ms. Miller has gone through substantial
changes. Now 55, she came rather late to her career. She was 43, a
wife and mother, when she published her first novel.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Chicago (as Susan Nichols), the daughter of a
university professor, she was by her own description an
overachiever but one without direction or intention. At 16 she went
to Radcliffe College and married soon after graduation. While her
husband was in medical school at Yale University and with a child
to support, she worked at a variety of jobs. She taught high school
and did psychological testing of Yale students and also of rats.
(She liked the rats better, she said.) Although she had written
poetry and stories, a literary career seemed only a distant
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   When she was a teen-ager her parents had rented a basement room
in their house to Robert Coover, then a graduate student in
philosophy and history at the University of Chicago. In 1966 while
working as a cocktail waitress in West Haven, Conn., Ms. Miller
read an enthusiastic review for Coover's first novel, ``The Origin
of the Brunists,'' and realized the artist who had lived among
them.
</P>
<P>
   As she said, ``It was encouraging to me to see that someone who
seemed as unlikely as I did to myself could write a book that was
so well received and was so wonderful.'' Coover's metafiction is,
she realized, oceans away from her own naturalistic writing, but
that does not lessen her admiration. ``It's a very brave kind of
writing,'' she said. ``I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   After discarding an early novel, she turned to short stories,
which she began selling to literary quarterlies. When the Atlantic
Monthly accepted one, an editor recommended that she use her full
name, Susan Miller, because ``at a certain point we all have to
grow up.'' She refused: ``I don't mind growing up, but I mind being
told that I ought to. I'm Sue Miller.'' She remained Sue Miller
after she divorced her husband, who is now a psychiatrist. The
divorce, she said, was central to her ``in terms of claiming my own
life, and that allowed me to grow up.'' Fourteen years ago she
married Douglas Bauer, also a novelist; they live in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Winning a grant from the Bunting Institute, a research center
for women at Radcliffe, she was able to have an office and to
devote a year to writing full time. Before then, she said, ``I had
always worked at the dining room table and then cleared it off when
it was time to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, that year her son chose to go to boarding
school: ``I thought he was too young to begin his life away from
home, and I was sad about that. A lot of my sorrow entered `The
Good Mother.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Published by Dell in 1986, this novel about a custody battle
after a divorce, was a phenomenal success, both artistically and
commercially. It remains her signature work. That was followed by
four other novels and a collection of stories. ``The Good Mother''
was the first of her works to be filmed (with Diane Keaton and Liam
Neeson); the most recent, in 1997, was an adaptation of her story
``Inventing the Abbotts.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had not seen any of the movies. ``Everything I've
written I see in a very precise way and I hear in my inner ear,''
she said. ``I know that no matter how carefully people try, it
wouldn't be possible to reproduce what I have in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she wrote what she did, she replied: ``By default!
It's my default mode. Henry James said we all have our donnee, our
gift. We're confined by it and privileged with it.'' Defending her
particular area, she deferred again to James: ``He said why should
you write about war, why not parturition?'' Parturition is one of
her many subjects, along with sibling and spousal rivalry and the
quest for redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally she is criticized for limiting herself to a
domestic world. ``They say that less to men,'' she said. ``In a way
Raymond Carver was always doing marriages and families, and Updike
certainly, with a few exceptions.'' Along with Anne Tyler, Alice
Munro, Carol Shields and other contemporary woman writers she has
found this a rich territory for characters in conflict, with others
and with themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always thinking that I'm the main character in my
books,'' she said, ``but each one has been different and sometimes
they've been men.'' Then she admitted that half of her fiction
``centers on some episode or event in my life,'' one definite
exception being ``Inventing the Abbotts,'' which deals with two
brothers, one of whom has sequential affairs with three sisters.
The original of that story was told to her by a former boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Becker in ``While I Was Gone'' (Alfred A. Knopf) is, and is
not, Sue Miller. The facts diverge: unlike her character, the
author never lived in a communal house in Cambridge, Mass., during
the 1960s, but she had friends in the counterculture. Character
traits overlap. In the book Jo and her housemates play a game of
labeling one another with adjectives. Jo is described as
``reserved, sexy, curious, fragile, blue and opaque.'' The
adjectives, especially the first three, apply equally to Ms.
Miller, although, she said, she disguises her natural reserve by
pushing herself to be outgoing.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the book is the murder and the mystery that
endures as Jo moves into another life. The inspiration for that
aspect came partly from the trial of Katherine Ann Power, a 1960s
political activist who was involved in a robbery and the killing of
a policeman in Boston. Escaping punishment, she led a secret life
until she came out of hiding to accept her responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, another side to the story. ``You don't
change anything by changing your life dramatically,'' she said.
``There's the sense that you haul it all along with you. You're
accountable finally for your life. I think that's been a kind of
preoccupation in my fiction. In my work, people pay for things.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
