<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-POLITICS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS RIP PAGE FROM GOP CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Fla., N.C., La.)  (Editors: This is Southern Exposure, a Southeast-oriented weekly
political column from the Washington Bureau of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.) 
(lb) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN  
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Enthusiastic members of Congress gather outside the
Capitol for a pep rally and proudly pledge fealty to their party's
specific legislative agenda. A few months later they grab control
of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans pulled off that feat in 1994 with their famous
``Contract with America.'' Now Democrats hope they can do the same
with last Wednesday's party unity rally, which looked suspiciously
like the kickoff to the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some would probably classify it as that,'' conceded Rep. Allen
Boyd, a moderate Florida Democrat on hand for the event featuring
President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and Democratic
congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that Republicans are on the ropes from the impeachment
fight, Democrats are pressing their advantage, presenting
themselves as solidly behind a ``families first'' platform that
would protect Social Security and Medicare, reduce the national
debt and bolster education and health care. They even called on
Republicans to join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Democrats want to prove, since this impeachment
trial is over, that we can work across party lines and get
something done for the American people, things they really care
about,'' said Sen. Mary Landrieu, D-La.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans staged their own small tax-cut rally and dismissed
the Democratic proposals as more tired Washington ideas. But they
are on the defensive, feuding among themselves over their own
approach to the main issues.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have not always been so cohesive. Early in the Clinton
administration, Southern moderates and conservatives complained
that the White House was veering too far left to appease the
liberal wing of the party. Some bolted to the GOP. Later, liberal
Democrats claimed that Clinton was selling them out on issues such
as welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Now Democrats claim to be one big happy family, though several
Southerners, citing scheduling conflicts, declined to attend the
rally.
</P>
<P>
   Good Neighbor Howard
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Coble follows that Southern tradition of being a
good neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   So it stands to reason that when presidential hopeful Elizabeth
Dole, a Tar Heel native, came calling to ask the senior North
Carolina Republican for his support, Coble quickly said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she wants me to go somewhere for her, I'll be glad to do
it,'' Coble said.
</P>
<P>
   Coble had previously spoken excitedly of Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's likely candidacy, but said he would endorse Bush only if Ms.
Dole declined to run.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Coble expressed surprise that so many North Carolina
state legislators had already publicly endorsed Bush, saying he
thought ``state pride alone'' would have encouraged them to rally
behind Ms. Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Until new district lines were drawn recently, Coble's district
included Ms. Dole's hometown of Salisbury. ``She's my neighbor down
the road,'' Coble said. ``And she's fully qualified and
competent.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatherhood I
</P>
<P>
   As one of the House impeachment managers, Florida GOP Rep.
Charles Canady has not had many nice things to say about President
Clinton over the past few months. But he has finally found
something to compliment the president on _ his stance on infant car
seats.
</P>
<P>
   As a brand-new dad, Canady admits to his share of struggles with
the carriers. Like many parents, he has found that the varied seat
styles are not always compatible with car restraints, leaving one
uncertain if the chair is properly installed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed a solution _ a standard three-point
attachment system in new cars and trucks by next year _ and Canady
has seen the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with what the president's doing about safety seats,''
said Canady.
</P>
<P>
   Now about that job search for Monica Lewinsky ....
</P>
<P>
   Fatherhood II
</P>
<P>
   The television event of the week was Ms. Lewinsky's interview,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Not for Rep. Mike McIntyre, D-N.C., co-chairman of the
congressional Task Force on Fatherhood Promotion. He's upset with
the way television networks portray dear old dad.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new report, only 15 of the 102 shows on network
television feature a father as a regular character. And only four
of those shows portray Pop in a favorable light.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre, who has two school-aged sons of his own, said that at
a time when millions of American children lack a father in their
home, television needs to do a better job of depicting fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television cannot be expected to solve this national problem,
but I challenge those at the networks to think about their
permeating influence on whether children in our nation see fathers
as positive role models,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin work in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This story was
distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
