<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0937 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-GLOBAL-TWOTAKES-K     03-07 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-GLOBAL-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNPREPARED NATIONS POSE Y2K THREAT IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Two-thirds of businesses in some developing
countries will be hit by major computer failures after Jan. 1,
according to one study.
</P>
<P>
   Even some traditionally strong European countries will see one
in three of their businesses affected by Year 2000 computer
problems, says the GartnerGroup, a Stamford, Conn., technology
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Experts predict some countries also will experience power
failures, water-service shutdowns and civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Those who study the Year 2000 problem overseas say they believe
many countries outside the United States did not take the problem
seriously until 1997, or even later. There is some concern that
some still have not.
</P>
<P>
   France and Germany, in particular, have been low-key, said
Martha Bennett, a London-based vice president with the Giga
Information Group, a Cambridge, Mass., research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``German officials are saying, `All this Y2K stuff is all
American hype,''' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Europe has been distracted by the euro monetary
conversion, which required extensive computer reprogramming.
</P>
<P>
   With 299 days remaining before the new year, Y2K already has
caused problems overseas.
</P>
<P>
   At John Radcliffe Hospital in Oxford, England, a Year 2000
computer test knocked out most of the hospital's emergency phone
lines for a weekend last November. Had there been a major
emergency, people would have died, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Many more failures are likely, say authors of a Jan. 26 report
from the World Bank, the financial offshoot of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing problems of incorrect projections in loan
payments, lost patient records, and prematurely canceled orders for
supplies, such as food, oil, machine parts and microcomputer
chips,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank officials will not identify where the problems have
occurred, for fear of undermining efforts to fix Year 2000 problems
and eroding confidence among global trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   In January an international group of banks, securities firms and
insurers even decided not to release a report rating the computer
readiness of the world's trading nations. The Global 2000
Coordinating Group was concerned that the ratings would cause a
``flight of capital'' from low-rated nations and make the Y2K
problem even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Although international discussions focus on industrialized
countries, the developing countries, many of which rely on U.S.
hand-me-down technology, are not immune from Y2K problems. Even the
poorest have computerized essential services such as banking,
telecommunications, power, manufacturing, health care and
government services.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of January, a World Bank survey found that of 139
developing countries, only 15 percent were taking steps to fix
their Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   It's what experts don't know that causes them the most concern.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who studies Year 2000 issues for Giga, said she saw
three countries with a Y2K information black hole _ Japan, France
and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is rated low for its Y2K efforts not necessarily because
its efforts are lagging _ although some say that is the case _ but
because no information is forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're told by Japan to `take it on trust; we'll be OK,' ''
Bennett said. ``And it would be a huge cultural affront to the
Japanese for the world to turn around and say, `Look, we don't
believe you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Japanese officials say they have the Year 2000
problem in hand.
</P>
<P>
   But they are threatening to suspend financial agencies after a
government survey found that half of the nation's top 19 banks had
completed updates to only a quarter of their computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Russia have been more forthcoming, but the news has
not been good.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have warned that everything from the country's rail
system to its nuclear reactors is at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``To guarantee that we will be ready is impossible,'' said
Alexander Krupnov, director of the agency coordinating government
Y2K efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts are particularly worried about Russia's large
nuclear arsenal and nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Last month U.S. and Russian military experts agreed to work
together to tackle the Y2K problem, and they plan to meet again
this month. The cash-strapped Russians estimate that solving the
country's Y2K problem could cost up to $3 billion. They have asked
for help from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The story is not much different in China, which is flooded with
bootleg software. Y2K updates probably are not possible.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of China's businesses surveyed by the government
did not know how to find the computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have ordered Chinese airline executives to
take a flight Jan. 1, an added incentive to make sure the country's
airline industry takes the problem seriously.
MORE...MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 1840EST &QL; 
