<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0941 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-GLOBAL-2ndTAKE-KA     03-07 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-GLOBAL-2ndTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.: country's airline industry takes the problem
seriously.)
</P>
<P>
   Experts also are concerned about the Arab states of the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things break down, then the action taken is usually
spur-of-the-moment, unorganized and takes time,'' said Mohammed
Mrayati, an adviser for the United Nations Economic and Social
Commission for Western Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Airports, Egypt's Suez Canal and electric networks could take a
hit, U.N. officials said. Highly computerized oil refineries and
water desalination plants are a big concern, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they should stop,'' Mrayati said, ``then millions of people
would have no power and no water to drink.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chicago Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa returned to the Dominican
Republic last year, much of the island nation had been without
power three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations outside the United States could be in for a
similar experience after Jan. 1, said Matt Hotle, a GartnerGroup
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But he sees no reason for panic. With the exception of Western
European countries, many parts of the world are accustomed to
occasional service failures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've dealt with this before, and they'll deal with it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequences of unpreparedness in any one country can
rapidly spill over to other parts of the world,'' said Ahmad Kamal
of Pakistan, who organized a Dec. 11 meeting of 120 national Y2K
coordinators at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist for Deutsche Bank Securities in
New York, believes the Year 2000 problem will lead to a global
recession that will last through much of the year.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that individual countries can get through
occasional catastrophes, he said, the world has never faced a
problem like Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put a lot of these disruptions in the bottle at the
same time, you're going to shatter the glass,'' Yardeni said.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem is forcing companies to rethink how they do
business overseas.
</P>
<P>
   For the International Division of Hallmark Cards, addressing the
problem means dealing with hundreds of suppliers in a dozen or more
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hallmark is fortunate. Our major international operations are
in countries where there is the least risk,'' said Kim Westerfield,
coordinator of Hallmark's Year 2000 effort overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to take the stance of understanding what the
infrastructure risk is and focus on things within our control.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other Kansas City area companies, most of which are
small and medium-size firms, are taking similar measures.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon Industries in Blue Springs is working with customers
around the globe to update Harmon-manufactured railroad equipment
that otherwise might malfunction after Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Diamant Boart Inc. of Lenexa, a subsidiary of a Belgium
corporation, is stocking up on diamond saw parts and other critical
components to make sure it can continue assembling saws in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni said the problem for many U.S. companies could be traced
to how American manufacturers did business.
</P>
<P>
   Most American companies rely on ``just in time'' manufacturing,
in which factories receive vital components as they are needed for
assembly. Most of the labor-intensive parts are manufactured
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those parts don't get made in time, there would be some
very significant employment reductions,'' Yardeni said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer industry is especially vulnerable, Scott McNealy,
chief executive of computer maker Sun Microsystems, told a global
Y2K gathering in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Asia is way, way behind,'' he said. ``It might be
difficult to buy computer hardware in the first half of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The Automotive Industry Action Group, a nonprofit coalition, is
helping Ford, General Motors, Daimler-Chrysler, Toyota and Volvo
keep international supply lines open.
</P>
<P>
   There are few parts on an automobile assembly line that are not
crucial, said Fred Craig, Year 2000 program manager for the group.
If a foreign supplier shuts down, it could have a ripple effect
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   An industry SWAT team of sorts is prepared to help suppliers
that are falling behind in Y2K repair efforts, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting a few hiccups. But we're not expecting to see
a lot of major disasters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some global companies, such as Kansas City engineering firm
Black &AMP; Veatch, are hesitant to discuss the worldwide implications
of the Year 2000 problem for fear of ``compromising the
confidentiality of our foreign customers,'' spokesman John Allen
said.
</P>
<P>
   International pharmaceuticals maker Hoechst Marion Roussel took
a similar approach. Spokesman Charles Rouse of the company's North
American branch in Kansas City said only that the company was aware
of the Year 2000 problem and was making ``continued progress''
toward fixing the bug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
