<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, March 8. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POLICE (Zhanlong) _ A look at the widespread abuses of
China's local police and the efforts to curb them. By Elizabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-ANTIBIOTICS (Undated) _ Faced with mounting evidence that
the routine use of antibiotics in livestock may diminish the drugs'
power to cure infections in people, the Food and Drug
Administration has begun a major revision of its guidelines for
approving new antibiotics for animals and for monitoring the
effects of old ones.
</P>
<P>
   COASTGUARD-HAITIANS (Miami) _ The Coast Guard has called off a
search for Haitians who were on board two boats that capsized off
Florida. As many as 40 people are presumed dead; three were
rescued. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-KUBRICK (Undated) _ Stanley Kubrick, the director of
``2001: A Space Odyssey'' and ``A Clockwork Orange'' died Sunday at
his home in England. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-REPUBS (Washington) _ After four years in which House
Republicans dominated Congress, bringing their party its
legislative energy as well as its public relations disasters and
the impeachment drive, there has been a power shift on Capitol
Hill. In the 106th Congress, Trent Lott and his Senate majority
have become the ascendant Republican presence. By Alison Mitchel.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-TV-DEREGULATE (Washington) _ Cable television, one of the
last industries to have its prices controlled by the government, is
about to become almost completely deregulated. But while the
prospect of competition was supposed to drive prices down, the
opposite has happened. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKES (Beijing) _ China reacts angrily to reports of
nuclear espionage. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUTURE-FORECASTS-2NDT     03-07 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-FORECASTS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.: greatest institutions of science and
learning.'' He concluded:)
</P>
<P>
   -- C, X and Q would be dropped from the English alphabet by
1999. ``They will be abandoned because unnecessary. Spelling by
sound will have been adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   -- A gymnasium in every school. This good guess offsets Watkins'
bad guess: ``A man or woman unable to walk ten miles at a stretch
will be regarded as a weakling.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Pneumatic tubes would deliver packages and groceries to
homes.
</P>
<P>
   -- The 2000 federal census would record between 350 to 500
million Americans. This estimate was too high, as about 270 million
people live in the United States today.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The trip from suburban home to office will require a few
minutes only. A penny will pay the fare.''
</P>
<P>
   A hit-and-miss thing, prognostication. Watkins did manage some
hits by predicting snowmobiles (``automobile sleighs in the
winter''), live video broadcasts (``American audiences in their
theaters will view upon huge curtains before them the coronations
of kings in Europ'') and direct dialing ``by an automatic signal
... without the intervention of a `hello girl.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cars would replace horse-drawn buggies in the 20th century, the
oracles agreed. One, however, ventured so far as to predict that
the absence of slow-moving horses would mean pristine roads and no
more traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   Planes would turn the sky ``almost black'' with criss-crossing
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Telephones would allow Americans to converse not only with
people in other countries, but also with ``inhabitants of Mars and
many other worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy would be tapped from the wind, sun rays and ocean waves.
</P>
<P>
   Political corruption, gone. Industrial monopolies, banished.
Labor strife, eliminated by collective bargaining for all.
</P>
<P>
   So now with our modern conveniences and push-button technology,
why do so many people foresee gloom in the next century?
</P>
<P>
   According to historian Moran, three things happened to dim a
once-bright future: the atomic bomb, the Holocaust and the
environmental movement.
</P>
<P>
   These events _ hardly on anyone's intellectual radar in 1900 _
``made people question whether technological progress equated with
moral progress.'' Progress made life easier, perhaps; it also could
destroy life.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago the upbeat Clark offered but one warning about
life ``at the portal of the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   He thought progress might weaken individual morality. Wealth and
whiz-bang gadgets at home might spur the ``sore temptations'' of
materialism, isolation and loss of community, Clark wrote. ``In
this direction the strongest effort is needed. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You have work before you, children of the twenty-first
century; but my hope is that the area of greatest danger has been
passed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 1844EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
