<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER GENERATION FROM RUFUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people hold that no dog or cat should be allowed to breed,
because there already are too many of them in the world.
</P>
<P>
   I respect that view, even if I don't share it.
</P>
<P>
   My own opinion is that what there are too many of is us, and if
the planet is to be saved, it's people who need to be prevented
from breeding.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there'll be the devil to pay for confessing it, but the
Brittany bird dog, Bear, will be siring a litter any day now. We're
waiting, Bear and I, for the phone call that will alert him to his
duty.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie is the female's name. Her owner is a friend, and we've
hunted the two of them together several times.
</P>
<P>
   They're both liver and white, and so alike you'd almost think
them brother and sister. We've sometimes momentarily mistaken one
for the other as they bounded through the weeds and high grass.
</P>
<P>
   Bear's a bit on the short and sturdy side. Maggie's more svelte,
and stands perhaps a half-inch taller at the shoulder. She'll put a
little more leg in the pups they make together.
</P>
<P>
   And what's certain is they'll be good dogs _ fine companions in
the house, hard and capable workers in the field. With dogs, as
with anything else alive, bloodlines count for much. Not
everything, but a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Bear's grandsire was Winchester Repeater Seeley, and his
granddam was Rosanna, both of hunting stock, both with good names
behind them. Out of a litter by those two came Rufus, who was my
partner for nearly 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his life, Rufus, whose coat was white and
orange, was paired with a small liver and white female, Holly. And
the get of those two was a litter of 10, five orange, five liver.
We kept one of each.
</P>
<P>
   Bear is Holly's Bear, because he favors his mother. Pete, being
orange, is Rufus Repeater. At not quite 6 months of age, on their
first morning afield, those two honored the first point they saw
their father make _ froze in place behind him as steady as seasoned
hunters.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, they were pointing quail independently, honoring
one another's points, finding and fetching the downed birds. A
couple of years later, the first time we were out together with
Maggie, she was hardly older than they'd been then, but already as
precocious.
</P>
<P>
   I'd meant to keep only one out of those last Rufus pups. We
ended up with two. There almost was a third, another liver one. My
wife had even named him already _ Cyrus, a kingly moniker for the
runt of the litter.
</P>
<P>
   Three seemed an awful lot of pups, though. So we hesitated. Then
some other man fancied him, and the chance was lost.
</P>
<P>
   The other day the question came up of what I'd do with the pup
out of this prospective new litter, the customary compensation for
the sire's service. My compensation, that is. Bear's reward will be
immediate.
</P>
<P>
   There were several friends, I told my wife, who might be glad to
have a pup from Rufus stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``But won't you be keeping him?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well ...''
</P>
<P>
   I'd wanted to, of course. But I'd considered it the remotest of
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a Cyrus after all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So it's settled.
</P>
<P>
   For the man who follows bird dogs, it's important to be careful
about their pedigrees.
</P>
<P>
   It's even more important to marry well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
