<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0948 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-VOTE-2ndTAKE-KAN     03-07 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-VOTE-2ndTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.: statistics that say pulling a gun increases
the likelihood of suffering an injury.)
</P>
<P>
   The Koch Crime Institute of Topeka, a nonpartisan organization
that studies crime and juvenile justice, concluded in a January
study that much of the data are ``subjective and based on anecdotal
information, opinions and speculation that make seemingly
compelling arguments for each side of this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Janice Jaworsky, the Koch Institute's director of research, said
advocates and opponents of concealed weapons sometimes used the
same data to support different conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, opponents of Proposition B are attacking details of
the proposal that they say would make it particularly lax. They
warn that it would allow permit-holders to carry guns into bars,
Little League games and even into Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants would have to complete training but would not have to
demonstrate that they knew how to handle a firearm. Even people who
are legally blind or too weak to safely lift a gun could get a
permit, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also would allow people to obtain permits even
after convictions for serious misdemeanors, such as sexual
misconduct or receiving stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   Boone County Sheriff Ted Boehm, president of the Missouri
Sheriffs' Association, said he opposed Proposition B because people
who committed crimes that could require a year in jail should not
carry guns.
</P>
<P>
   Gun advocates argue that Proposition B includes enough
safeguards to protect the public. Applicants would have to submit
fingerprints and authorize a review of their juvenile and medical
records. Property owners could post signs prohibiting guns in their
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriffs could refuse to issue a concealed-carry permit to
drunks, drug abusers or the mentally ill. Applicants could be
denied if they had threatened or attacked anyone in the preceding
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that the background checks are inadequate to
prevent dangerous people from carrying guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no foolproof system,'' said Robert Gartner, the
Missouri Highway Patrol's director of criminal records. ``The movie
version of Big Brother, where with one entry you can check
everything in a computer, is not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding juvenile and mental-health records sounds good _ if
you can find them,'' he said. ``What if the applicant doesn't
truthfully tell the sheriff where he grew up? Or what if a person
wasn't committed to an institution?''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also warn that inadequate training will lead to
accidental shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to know mechanically how to load a gun, aim and
pull the trigger,'' said Liberty Police Chief Arthur Chevalier.
``But the judgmental decisions on when to shoot and when not to,
they don't require enough training.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some supporters acknowledge that additional training should
be required when permits come up for renewal.
</P>
<P>
   But they scoff at the idea that permits would be issued to
criminals or lunatics. They point out that citizens could challenge
a person's permit by filing a complaint with the court.
</P>
<P>
   Experience in other states indicates that fears of inadvertent
shootings and criminals' getting permits are overblown.
</P>
<P>
   The Koch Crime Institute found that fewer than 1 percent of
permit holders nationwide lost their permits because they had
committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Withers, associate director of the Firearms Injury
Center at the Medical College of Wisconsin, said his organization
concluded that laws allowing concealed weapons did not put
additional guns on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hypothesis is that many people carry illegally until the
law changes,'' Withers said. ``People who are motivated by fear to
carry a gun aren't deterred by laws that prohibit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cases of shootings over minor altercations have been ruled
self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, for example, a Texas man was charged with murder
for shooting another motorist after a traffic accident. The grand
jury refused to indict him, because he shot after the other man
began punching him in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Accidental shootings do happen. In November 1997 two women in an
Indianapolis restaurant were shot when a gun fell out of a man's
pocket as he bent over to help a waitress pick up a broken
necklace.
</P>
<P>
   A bullet went through one woman's hand as she applied lip balm
and then entered the other woman's arm.
</P>
<P>
   But cases like that have proved to be highly unusual.
</P>
<P>
   While more states were adopting concealed-carry laws, the number
of accidental shooting deaths dropped from 1,416 in 1990 to 1,134
in 1996, the latest figures available.
</P>
<P>
   A search of national newspapers and court filings failed to turn
up a case of bystanders' having been shot by people legally
carrying concealed weapons. Even Handgun Control could not come up
with any.
</P>
<P>
   In a few cases, however, bystanders were shot by robbers
returning fire after victims pulled concealed weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
