<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-VOTE-TWOTAKES-KA     03-07 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-VOTE-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS IN MISSOURI HEAR LOTS OF RHETORIC IN DEBATE OVER CONCEALED
WEAPONS ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- The public appears to have a growing
infatuation with the idea of carrying hidden handguns.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 12 years, the number of states allowing concealed
weapons has more than tripled. When Missouri voters go to the polls
next month, they will decide whether their state will follow the
trend.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot measure has divided law enforcement groups, civil
libertarians and even gun advocates. And it has sparked sometimes
angry debate over what happens when the government lets the public
carry guns.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional rhetoric has obscured two major trends:
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what many gun advocates say, legal concealed weapons
appear to have a negligible effect on violent crime, most studies
have shown.
</P>
<P>
   And contrary to what gun-control proponents say, concealed
firearms have not led to more accidental shootings, vigilante
actions or cases of road rage ending in gunplay.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to the people on either side of the campaign to
legalize concealed weapons in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Steve McGhee, president of the gun-advocacy group Missourians
for Personal Safety, said he is convinced that concealed weapons
reduce crime because criminals don't know who might shoot back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right-to-carry puts a question mark in their minds,'' McGhee
said. ``They can't assume their next victim is helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun opponents, including Kansas City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, said
concealed weapons put everyone at greater risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``While a gun may provide a psychological sense of security, it
actually makes people more vulnerable,'' Cleaver said. ``When you
bring out a weapon, it increases the chances that you will be
killed by a weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   While the two sides share little common ground, they agree that
the leading adversaries in the national gun-rights debate _ the
National Rifle Association and Handgun Control Inc. _ have a lot
riding on the April 6 vote in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The election will mark the first time a state's voters will have
decided whether to allow concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The winning side will walk away with political momentum in the
fight over gun control. And the vote could pave the way for ballot
initiatives or legislative efforts in states where politicians have
balked at authorizing concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   While Handgun Control has achieved modest victories in Congress,
the NRA has won a series of votes in the nation's statehouses.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s eight states allowed residents to obtain
permits to carry concealed guns without demonstrating a need. One
other _ Vermont _ allows concealed weapons without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the NRA, state legislatures started authorizing
concealed weapons. The issue gained credibility when Florida
approved hidden guns in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Today 30 states have laws similar to the Missouri proposal,
according to the National Conference of State Legislatures. The
District of Columbia and 13 states tightly control who gets
permits. Only seven states _ including Missouri and Kansas _ still
ban concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Legislature passed a right-to-carry bill two years
ago, but Gov. Bill Graves vetoed it. A new effort this year has
been endorsed by a House committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gun advocates in the Missouri General Assembly tried
unsuccessfully for years to get a law allowing concealed weapons.
Unable to overcome the opposition of Gov. Mel Carnahan, lawmakers
last year approved a measure that bypassed the governor and set up
a statewide vote.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal _ Proposition B _ would allow people to apply for
three-year permits to carry concealed weapons. Applicants would
have to be 21, be Missouri residents and undergo a criminal
background check. They also would have to have 12 hours of firearms
training.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is shaping up as a classic urban vs. rural issue.
Both sides agree that rural parts of the state, where hunting and
shooting are a part of the culture, appear to be supporting
concealed weapons. Opposition is expected to be strongest in Kansas
City and St. Louis, where guns are often associated with a culture
of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Urban opposition is one of the biggest ironies in a debate
fraught with irony.
</P>
<P>
   Self-defense is the reason most often cited to justify concealed
weapons. Yet urban residents, who are more likely to be crime
victims, are less enthusiastic about legally carrying guns.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in states that allow concealed guns, elderly people
tend to obtain permits even though they make up the group least
often victimized by violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   The interest in concealed weapons is driven by the public's
gut-wrenching fear of violent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``An armed society,'' former NRA President Tom Washington once
said, ``is a polite society.''
</P>
<P>
   But do concealed weapons really reduce crime?
</P>
<P>
   Each side cites a slew of statistics and academic studies to
support its position. Gun advocates point to declining crime rates
in states, such as Florida, that have legalized concealed weapons.
Opponents point to violent-crime rates that have dropped even
faster in California, New York and other states that prohibit or
strictly control concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Gun advocates point to studies that say crime victims who pull a
gun are far less likely to be injured than victims who don't have a
gun. Opponents point to statistics that say pulling a gun increases
the likelihood of suffering an injury.
MORE...MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
