u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-RACE-ART-2T     03-07 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-RACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERSITY LOWEST AMONG 10 LARGEST POLICE DEPARTMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ariz., Mich., Ill., Texas, Calif., Pa.)   NEW YORK RACIAL (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By JODI WILGOREN AND MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a decade of record expansion, New York City's
police force remains among the least racially diverse of the
nation's 10 largest police departments, with the lack of black and
Hispanic representation most pronounced in the higher ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The department does not come close to reflecting the diversity
of the city it serves: whites are 67.4 percent of the force, but
only 43.4 percent of the population. Among the 10 largest cities,
the only two with a higher percentage of white officers are San
Diego and Phoenix, where a far greater percentage of residents are
white.
</P>
<P>
   And the disparity is even worse among the brass. Of the 449
captains, 94 percent are white. Among the 237 inspectors and chiefs
who run the force, only nine are black and 10 Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   In the month since four white officers killed Amadou Diallo, an
unarmed West African immigrant, in a barrage of 41 bullets,
politicians and protesters have stepped up their calls for more
minority representation on the force and better treatment of black
and Hispanic officers already on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir recently announced the
largest-ever recruitment drive focused on city residents as an
effort to diversify the department. But coming at the end of a
decade in which the force swelled by more than 25 percent, the new
drive cannot have much impact: Even if all of the approximately
1,200 recruits the city plans to hire in July were members of
minorities, the force would still be 65 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have done this a long time ago,'' said Samuel
Walker, a criminal justice professor at the University of Nebraska
who has studied affirmative action in police departments. ``It is
25 years late. Where have they been?''
</P>
<P>
   Some black and Hispanic officers, as well as experts on
affirmative action and policing, said that during the Giuliani
administration, the department lost prominent minority chiefs and
watered down the commitment to diversity seen during the eight
years when New York had black police commissioners, Benjamin Ward
and Lee P. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people feel like the commitment is not there that
once was,'' said Dr. Elsie Scott, who was New York's deputy
commissioner for training from 1990 to 1994, and now is an
executive in the Washington Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Lee Brown and Ben Ward were there,'' Dr. Scott said,
``they constantly looked at numbers and looked at assignments:
Where did we have blacks assigned? Are they in positions where they
could move up? How many blacks are being put into the detective
list? How many blacks are going to the FBI academy?'' Dr. Scott,
who is also coordinator of education and training for the National
Organization of Black Law Enforcement Executives, added, ``I'm not
sure anybody is doing that now to make sure there is an equal
playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cities with more diverse departments, including Los
Angeles, were forced to hire and promote specific numbers of black
and Hispanic officers through court orders. In New York City,
applicants from racial and ethnic minorities successfully
challenged the department's hiring and promotional exams in the
early 1980s, but the resulting quota system was much narrower and
shorter-lived than those in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, police officials say that while they would like the force
to better reflect the community, they run the police department as
a strict meritocracy, and they say the falling crime rate validates
that philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Officers, sergeants, lieutenants and captains are chosen from
the candidates with the highest scores on multiple-choice tests.
The police commissioner can tap any captain for the top 236 posts
in the department, and Safir said recently that he does not take
race or city residency into account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to select the most talented people,'' he said. So
the department's efforts to attract more minorities have boiled
down to this: it pitches the advantages of the job, and hopes
people sign up. But the visits to churches, job fairs at city
colleges and leafleting at subway stations have produced recruit
classes only marginally more diverse than the department as a
whole. Of the 4,706 officers hired in the four police academy
classes since April 1997, 65 percent were white, 11 percent black
and 20 percent Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to encourage diversity as much as possible,'' said
Michael A. Markman, chief of personnel, in an interview last week.
``It's an open, competitive examination _ everyone can see it's
fair. Whether everybody takes advantage of it is something else.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
