<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-RACE-2NDTAK     03-07 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-RACE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: something else.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once in the department, minority recruits contend they have a
harder time rising through ranks. Departmental records show that
black and Hispanic officers have not done as well as whites on
promotional exams. On the most recent exams to become a sergeant,
lieutenant and captain, whites passed at more than twice the rate
of their black counterparts, while Hispanic officers fared
somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the discrepancy, Markman said he had no explanation
for why any one group would perform better than another. He pointed
out that a diverse group of officers writes each exam and that the
questions are based on readily available materials and are not
``tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to fool people,'' he said. ``The test
measures what's in the book here. We're not looking at any esoteric
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Minority officers say the figures on hiring and promotion signal
deeper, more complicated problems within the department.
</P>
<P>
   They maintain that black and Hispanic officers are disciplined
more frequently than their white counterparts in the trial room on
the fourth floor of police headquarters, and say that resulting
blemishes on their records can delay or prevent their promotion
even if they pass the exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're under-represented on the job,'' said one black officer
who passed a promotional exam and is waiting to see if he will be
selected, ``but over-represented on the fourth floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Others complain that their best path to a detective's shield is
to work in dangerous, undercover narcotics assignments while their
white counterparts get more prestigious roles as investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do a close examination of the various prestigious
units in the police department, you will see that there is an
unwritten rule that African-Americans are kept out,'' said Lieut.
Eric Adams of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who Care, a fraternal
organization of black officers.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said he planned to address such concerns by turning other
units into paths to promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents like the Diallo shooting, the 1997 police assault on
Abner Louima and the 1994 choking death of Anthony Baez, minority
officers say, only heighten the perception that New York has a
police department run by whites hostile to minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have failed in recruitment, in trying to make the
department look appealing to different groups,'' Adams said. The
lack of diversity in the upper ranks, meanwhile, means that there
are few role models to show recruits and young officers the range
of opportunity available in the department, and that minority
perspectives are absent from policy-making discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Scott recalled an executive staff meeting while she was a
deputy commissioner in New York where there was a discussion of
whether to allow 13-year-olds to stand in lineups without parental
permission. ``Being a black person, to me, this was a red flag: I
wouldn't want my child to be brought in for a lineup _ there have
been a lot of mistaken identities,'' she said. ``Whites in the room
had never thought about it. They were used to receiving equal
justice. You grow up as a black person in the United States, you're
used to unequal justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to integrate New York's police force span more than a
century. The city's first black officer, Wiley G. Overton, joined
the Brooklyn Police Department in 1891, before the consolidation of
the city, said Roger L. Abel, a retired detective and former leader
of the Guardians, a black officer's group. Officer Overton left
after a year because of an unwelcome reception from his colleagues,
said Abel, who is writing a history of black police officers in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Hispanic officers first came in numbers after World
War II. In the fiscal crisis of 1975, many blacks were laid off,
and sued the department, Abel said. In 1979, when a class of 415
new recruits included only 45 minorities, there was another
lawsuit. That ended in a court decree outlining hiring quotas for
black and Hispanic applicants, which the Koch administration
reluctantly accepted, but the system waned after a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in the last 10 years, we're going backwards,'' Abel
said. ``In every aspect _ recruitment, retention, promotions, the
whole gamut. It's just reversing itself. The leaps and bounds that
we should have taken have not materialized.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest influx of minorities came in 1995, when the
transit and housing police, smaller agencies long seen as friendly
to minorities, were merged into the New York Police Department.
More than 2,500 black and Hispanic officers joined the rolls, and
the department went from being 72 percent white to 69 percent
white.
</P>
<P>
   As the city has grown more heavily Hispanic, the department has
attracted Hispanic officers more quickly than blacks. In 1992, the
department was 11.4 percent black and 13.6 percent Hispanic; now,
it is 13.4 percent black and 17.4 percent Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity between the percentage of police officers who are
black and the percentage of residents who are black is wider in New
York than in any of the nation's 10 largest cities, according to an
analysis by The New York Times. New York is 25.6 percent black,
according to 1990 census figures, the latest available, but
African-Americans make up on 13.4 percent of the department.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are better represented on the force. New York ranks
fifth among the 10 cities: The city is 23.7 percent Hispanic, the
department 17.4 percent. The only departments with a larger
over-representation of whites than New York are Detroit, where the
population is just 20.7 percent white and white officers are 35.4
percent of the department, and Chicago, which is 38.2 percent white
and where white officers are 61.9 percent of the department.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities are also better represented in the upper echelons of
other departments than New York. In Los Angeles, 26 percent of
those ranked captain and higher are black, Hispanic or
Asian-American, compared to 7 percent in New York. In Philadelphia,
23 percent of sergeants are black, compared to 8.3 percent in New
York. Whites are 70 percent of the lieutenants in San Diego, 80
percent in Houston and 87.5 percent in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the issue is that there are not people who are prepared to
take these positions, it begs the question of development,'' said
Bob Stewart, executive director of the National Organization of
Black Law Enforcement Executives. ``What's happening throughout the
ranks of the department, that the department is not preparing
people? I can't believe it's because people don't want those
positions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
