<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0954 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-POLICE-ART-890(     03-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POLICE-ART-890(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ABUSE IN CHINA IS COMING INTO THE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZHANLONG, China _ Villagers here say they were not entirely
surprised when on the night of Aug. 7, 1997, public security
officers piled four farmers deemed troublemakers into a van, drove
them to an isolated rice field in front of a copse of trees and
riddled them with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were quickly cremated, and the policemen probably
assumed that the case was closed. After all, local residents say,
police harassment and even summary executions have for years been
an occasional fact of life in this rural town in the southeastern
province of Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
   And villagers say they dare not complain, knowing that policemen
receive praise from above, and at times even $1,200 bonuses, for
such swift ``justice.''
</P>
<P>
   But China is changing, and in this case the four dead men's
cause did not disappear. Their relatives, all barely literate
farmers, waged a yearlong campaign for redress.
</P>
<P>
   A high-powered Beijing lawyer agreed to represent the families,
pro bono, in a lawsuit against the police. And a reporter from
China's increasingly vigorous press helped expose a harrowing tale
of police brutality that local officials had kept under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``As ordinary Chinese we felt we had the legal right to have
this case heard,'' said Zheng Canming, the younger brother of one
of the dead men.
</P>
<P>
   Later in March, seven police officers are due to stand trial on
murder charges, in a case that casts a rare spotlight on widespread
abuses by China's local police _ as well as the fledgling efforts
to control them.
</P>
<P>
   Such abuses, from torture to ``extrajudicial killings,'' have
been attacked recently in human-rights reports and implicitly
criticized by top Beijing officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case shows a problem of law enforcement across the
country,'' said Gu Xianping, the lawyer. ``It is typical: The
farmers are victims and don't get protection from the law. We are
gradually improving our legal system, but I'm very concerned about
why the police thought they could get away with this.''
</P>
<P>
   China's state-owned law journals and newspapers now often
publish hair-raising exposes of torture and other forms of police
brutality, although such stories rarely seep into the mainstream
press. But experts say it is significant that such a delicate
subject is raised publicly at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese officials are clearly getting more serious about
police and security abuses,'' said Scot Tanner, a professor at
Western Michigan University. ``They know it is a very serious
problem.'' Tanner has done extensive research on Chinese law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the government's legal publishing house came out
with a new series of books about legal abuses, with titles
including ``The Crime of Confession Obtained by Torture'' and ``The
Crime of Illegal Detention.''
</P>
<P>
   The books estimated that hundreds, if not thousands, of Chinese
were illegally detained each year and that 250 people were tortured
to death in police custody in 1993 and 1994. It was the first time
such figures had been publicly released and was an extraordinary
admission, even though experts said the true numbers were certainly
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Although Westerners tend to focus on more abstract rights like
freedom of speech, Chinese officials know that arbitrary harassment
and punishment by local public security officials are far more
gripping issues for ordinary people in this country and threaten to
undermine the government's authority.
</P>
<P>
   So, to help control abuses in its far-flung law-enforcement
system, the central government has recently allowed and even
encouraged press coverage of abuses and lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But there remains great ambivalence about the new openness,
Tanner said. On one hand it deters wayward police officers, but on
the other it fuels criticism by Western human-rights groups. And
the desire to provide more even-handed justice does not extend to
those who threaten communist rule, like democracy activists, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are moving to a two-track legal system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 miles from Beijing, on the freewheeling southern
coast of Guangdong province, Zhanlong and its neighboring villages
exude lawlessness. In these once-poor rice-growing towns, many
villagers have become prosperous in the last five years by
reselling fabric, cigarettes and liquor smuggled from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In an area where family-planning regulations allow at most two
children, many families have four or five. Drugs and prostitution
are growing problems. The narrow roads lined by pressed-clay and
tile homes are filled with a strange jumble of ancient tractors,
motorcycles and contraband Mercedes Benzes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlessness also reigns at the local Public Security Bureau,
villagers said, where officers are quick to fine, confiscate,
detain _ and sometimes physically punish _ with little provocation.
Taxi drivers from the nearby cities of Shantou and Shenzhen refuse
to enter places like Puning, the county seat that encompasses
Zhanlong, where they say the police stop taxis and hold licenses or
even cars if they feel the driver has no business in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is afraid of the police here _ everyone,'' said a
farmer-turned-cloth-salesman who gave his surname as Chen. ``We all
know of the killings. These kinds of incidents have happened a lot
here before. The police like to deal on the spot with people they
consider hoodlums.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like most people in Zhanlong, the four men who were killed that
night in August 1997 were legally registered as farmers but in
reality made most of their money in small business _ though none
was very successful at it. All were between 20 and 35, had
grade-school education and were married with children. One, Zheng
Canyan, who was either 29 or 30 (his family is unsure when he was
born), had five children aged 6 months to 9 years when he died.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the killings, the local government-owned
television station broadcast the official version of the night's
events: Four ``vicious thugs with guns'' had threatened a villager,
looted his home, and were shot dead after they escaped from
officers who had arrested them.
</P>
<P>
   But from the start, the men's relatives felt something was
amiss.
</P>
<P>
   Zheng Canming said he became suspicious the moment he nervously
went to the police station to report that his brother Zheng Canyan,
a homebody, had not returned to his house. The police sent him to
fetch his brother's photo. When he returned, they confirmed that
his brother had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock, crying and wailing,'' said Zheng, who agreed
to speak about the killings, but would not talk generally about the
police. ``He was one of the most simple, honest men in the village.
The police who had shot him couldn't even identify him, since he
didn't have a record.''
</P>
<P>
   A shaken Zheng immediately went to the county morgue, in Puning,
where he persuaded someone to let him see the body, which was about
to be cremated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for a cloth to clean him, since he was covered with
bullet holes and blood,'' he recalled. ``I spent some time there
trying to close the eyes _ one wouldn't go down. And I noticed all
the bullets had entered from the front, and I thought: `That's
strange. Why would it be this way if he was fleeing?'''
</P>
<P>
   The families ultimately pieced together a different story, which
was supported by an intensive investigation by the state-owned
Legal Daily, and later by provincial law-enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the killings, one of the four farmers, Chen
Guanfeng, had gone to another villager's house to demand money that
he said he was owed. The two argued, and the villager, who was
related to a former Zhanlong police chief, went to the Public
Security Bureau claiming that Chen had tried to extort money from
him at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   A deputy police chief immediately sent six officers to Chen's
small paper factory and arrested him as well as three other men,
all casual acquaintances who were there drinking tea. Witnesses
said the men had been led into a van with their hands bound with
belts and strips of cloth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spoke to a local farmer who lived near the field, who said
that night he heard sounds like firecrackers, then crying and then
more firecrackers and then more crying,'' Zheng said. ``How could
four men with their hands tied escape from six policemen with
guns?''
</P>
<P>
   Days after the killings, 200 friends and relatives descended on
the Puning prosecutor's office demanding an investigation, Zheng
said. Two weeks later, when that investigation concluded that the
police had acted lawfully, indignant families fanned out to
Guangzhou, the provincial capital, and to Beijing to present their
findings to officials.
</P>
<P>
   Later they contacted a reporter at Legal Daily and decided to
retain a lawyer as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always believed that the party and the government would
abide by the Chinese people,'' said Zheng. ``But at that point I'd
already spent a lot of time and money on fruitless visits to
Beijing. And life was so hard for my sister-in-law with five
children to feed. I felt we needed a top-class lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   He found Gu Xianping, who has a reputation as one of the best
lawyers in China and was originally from a rural area.
</P>
<P>
   Gu credits the families' persistence with turning their tragedy
into a test case. ``In the last 10 years there have been campaigns
to raise legal consciousness among ordinary Chinese, and so the
families came convinced that China was a country with the rule of
law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that a yearlong investigation by Legal Daily ``broke
the case'' and pushed the Guangdong authorities to conduct their
own inquiry. On Sept. 10, 1998 _ more than a year after the
killings _ two deputy police chiefs and five policemen were
arrested. The Guangdong prosecutor's office concluded that one
deputy chief had ordered the killings while most of the officers
had taken part reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   The case, however extreme, clearly reflects systemic problems.
</P>
<P>
   In February, China Consumer Journal reported the case of Wang
Chonggao, a model worker and head of a local electricity-supply
bureau in Hubei province, who died after 29 hours of continuous
interrogation and extensive torture that included beatings around
the ears, painful handcuffing and more. The local prosecutor's
office had suspected him of embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine Chinese Lawyer recently reported on Zhao Yi, a
young engineer, who suffered brain injuries and a ruptured eardrum
after she endured four hours of beatings at the hands of police
interrogators in Liaoning province who suspected her of theft.
Although the police concluded that she was innocent, she sued. A
number of reporters attended the trial, but wrote that there had
been efforts in court to intimidate them.
</P>
<P>
   The Zhanlong trial, originally scheduled for early February, has
been ``postponed'' because of intense public interest, said Gu, who
is now fielding interview requests from the mainstream press.
``Before this, cases like this wouldn't have been reported,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seeking the $12,000 that each family could
receive under the state compensation law, Gu has filed a civil suit
demanding further damages for the victims' families. Zheng's widow
now supports her five children by selling sundries like toilet
paper and pens out of her mother-in-law's house, her brother-in-law
said, and is buoyed by the prospect of justice and money.
</P>
<P>
   But other villagers remain skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a court case, but I don't expect them to be
punished,'' said the cloth salesman, Chen. ``The police they are
bigwigs. We are not. It is hard for me to take the trial
seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
