<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, March 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A broad flow of moist air from the Gulf of Mexico into the
eastern Plains and Mississippi Valley will precede low pressure
emerging from the Rocky Mountain states. Snow will be widespread in
the central and northern Plains as the moist air is forced to rise
over the colder air covering the region. While most of the snow
will be light in the northern parts of the Plains and the
Mississippi Valley, a band of heavy snow is expected near a jet
stream disturbance as it moves from eastern Nebraska early Monday
across Iowa into northern Illinois and Indiana Monday night. The
snow will change to sleet and rain over northern Missouri and
central Illinois. The snow and rain will move into the Ohio and
Tennessee Valleys overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt in the increasingly moist air
over the lower Mississippi Valley. Shifting winds between the
surface and 10,000 feet will impart rotation to some of the
thunderstorm raising the risk of tornadoes later Monday from
eastern Oklahoma to southern Mississippi and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawling high pressure will promote abundant sunshine and
rather chilly conditions in most of the East Coast states. Gusty
winds from the north will persist over New England as low pressure
stalls south of Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, patchy clouds and snow showers will occur along
west-facing slopes in the central Rockies. Otherwise, partly to
mostly sunny skies will prevail in much of the interior. Meanwhile,
a cold front will reach the Northwest Coast accompanied by rain and
mountain snow.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Signals From Snow
</P>
<P>
   Despite a series of storms that have left parts of the interior
Northeast a blanket of white, there are subtle signals in the snow
that spring is on the way. With the strengthening March sun, solar
energy received at the ground is steadily increasing. While the
snow reflects much of the sunlight, dark trees and roads do not. As
trees absorb the light, they warm and give off more infrared
radiation. Since snow absorbs infrared energy, it melts around
trees, forming depressions. Also, snow falling during the day has
difficulty sticking to roads, which are exposed to more of the
sun's energy, even through thick clouds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
