<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      03-07 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATED OVER STRAINED IMF NEGOTIATIONS, YELTSIN WARNS HIS PRIME
MINISTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris N. Yeltsin has delivered a stern
warning to Prime Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov, accusing him of
being too ``complacent'' about the nation's economic course and
threatening yet another government shakeup.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's unusual public riposte was expressed through a senior
aide, Oleg Sysuyev, the president's deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   It represents Yeltsin's sharpest critique of the Primakov team
and reflects mounting frustration over the country's stalemated
talks with the International Monetary Fund over the country's
appeal for additional credits.
</P>
<P>
   There were no signs that Primakov was about to be replaced, but
the same could not be said of the prime minister's aides.
</P>
<P>
   The comments underscored the tensions that have developed in the
relations between the two leaders, already strained by Primakov's
efforts to position himself as a potential successor to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of Russia's political developments, this one took
place on television _ specifically, during a late Saturday night
interview on the ORT television channel, which is partly owned by
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the usual bromides about the president and the prime
minister working together in harmony, Sysuyev expressed Yeltsin's
anxiety over Primakov's failure to come to terms with the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is very worried about the future of the
negotiations with the International Monetary Fund,'' Sysuyev said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yevgeny Maximovich should be advised to be more critical of
the performance of the government,'' Sysuyev added, using the prime
minister's first name and patronymic. ``Such a complacent position
can make the prime minister and ourselves miss something of key
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov enjoys a ``very big reserve of confidence on the part
of the population,'' Sysuyev said pointedly. ``But this does not
mean that this confidence is endless.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there has been growing criticism over how the
Primakov government has handled the talks with the IMF. Much of the
negative talk has centered on Primakov's top economic aide, the
Communist first deputy prime minister, Yuri D. Maslyukov.
</P>
<P>
   The cash-strapped government is obliged to repay $4.5 billion in
IMF loans this year, and the Kremlin has been anxious to avoid a
humiliating default.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is of supreme political importance for Yeltsin, who
has cast the fund's seal of approval as a sign his nation is still
on a reform course.
</P>
<P>
   But as Primakov prepares for a critical trip to Washington later
this month, the quest for new aid from the fund appears to be as
elusive as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has yet to produce an economic plan to pull the nation
out of its slump. He has managed to win parliamentary approval of a
budget for 1999. But the fund has complained that the budget is
based on unrealistic assumptions about the government's ability to
collect tax revenue and to limit spending.
</P>
<P>
   Maslyukov, critics say, has compounded the problem by engaging
in a public duel with the fund. After Michel Camdessus, the fund's
managing director, warned last week that the fund would stick to
its tough stance, Maslyukov complained that the fund was being
``indecent'' by trying to pressure Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there have been increasing demands that Primakov
fire Maslyukov. Boris Fyodorov, a pro-capitalist former economic
aide, has lambasted the Primakov economic team as ``incompetent.''
Even former Prime Minister Viktor S. Chernomyrdin has criticized
Maslyukov for creating conflict with the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we make threats when we need loans?'' Chernomyrdin
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's move last week to oust the tycoon Boris A. Berezovsky
from his post as executive secretary of the Commonwealth of
Independent States, a group of former Soviet republics, kindled
speculation that a broader shake-up might be under way.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, however, has been loath to discharge Maslyukov. The
Communist-led Parliament approved Primakov's nomination as prime
minister in September but insisted in return that his government
team include leading Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Maslyukov flew on Friday to Sochi, where Primakov is on a
working vacation, in an apparent effort to save his job. Yevgeny K.
Svanidze, the host of the Zerkalo news interview program on the
government RTR channel, said that Primakov had reconfirmed his
support for Maslyukov.
</P>
<P>
   ``The position of the prime minister _ not to replace even the
most odious figures in the Cabinet _ has a clear political
explanation: the Red majority in the parliament,'' Svanidze said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is not likely to correspond to the president's point of
view, which was explicitly expressed by Sysuyev. Even now, we can
talk about a quite serious government crisis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
