<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COASTGUARD-HAITIANS-A     03-07 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COASTGUARD-HAITIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 SURVIVE AND 40 DIE IN SINKING OF 2 HAITIAN BOATS NEAR FLORIDA
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)   (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The three Haitian men who rescuers found in cold, rough
seas are apparently the only survivors of two boats that sank this
weekend off the South Florida coast, leaving as many as 40 dead in
what may be the worst smuggling disaster in this state's history.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Coast Guard, which had found only the three survivors
and four bodies in its sweep of the open ocean from Cape Canaveral
to Palm Beach, called off its search Sunday as hope faded of
finding anyone still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty are presumed dead,'' said Art Bullock, a U.S. Border
Patrol officer in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The two boats, with most of their human cargo, vanished about 30
miles east of Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found no debris, no vessels,'' Jeff Hall, petty
officer with the Coast Guard in Miami. Even if survivors had
something to cling onto, it was unlikely they could have survived,
Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water temperature was 70 to 72 degrees,'' he said. ``We
factored in the water temperature to gauge their chances of
survival.''
</P>
<P>
   In a state that has seen bodies and makeshift rafts wash up on
its beaches for as long as most people here can remember, this sea
disaster is almost certainly the most costly, in lives, in the
seemingly never-ending crossings from Haiti and Cuba, rescuers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest disappearance of a boatload of refugees that
I've heard of,'' in Florida waters, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The Haitians, trying to escape the latest rounds of violence and
persecution and a endless poverty, were apparently making their
crossing with the help of a for-profit smuggling ring,
law-enforcement officials said, after speaking with the three
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The two vessels, a 17-foot boat and a 20-foot boat, were
believed to have cast off from the western end of Grand Bahama, and
headed straight for Palm Beach, a usual smuggling route, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, such boats carry about nine people at most, Hall said.
These boats had at least twice that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday morning, sometime just after midnight, one of the
boats began to sink, and the second boat came alongside to help.
But as the terrified passengers crossed over on the second boat,
it, too, began to sink, one of the survivors told rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   At about 2 a.m. Saturday, about 30 miles off Palm Beach, crewmen
aboard the passing freighter Tomas Faith heard screams in the
water, and radioed the Coast Guard. The sinking might have gone
unreported, if crewmen aboard the Tomas Faith had not heard people
screaming. As it turned out, only a few people, dead or alive, were
found on the surface as dawn broke.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter found the first survivor, weakly trying to stay
afloat as he grasped a propane tank, at about at about 5 a.m., and
two others were found clinging to a barrel at about 8 a.m. All
three survivors, one man in his late 30s, one in his early 40s and
another in his 20s, were treated for hypothermia, and questioned by
the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Although rescuers used helicopters, planes and seagoing boats to
search an area of 2,600 square miles, they found only four bodies.
</P>
<P>
   They found no life jackets, either on the survivors, on the
bodies, or floating on the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Bahamas, smugglers tell them it's easy to get here,''
said Samedi Florvil, who works with the Haitian Refugee Center in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Haitians here in Miami said, those who can afford the
costs _some pay hundreds of dollars, or more, a small fortune in
that poor country _ are loaded onto unsafe boats, and risk their
lives in crossings in the dead of night.
</P>
<P>
   It is happening, immigration officials said, more and more, in
both Haiti and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The sinking of the two vessels on Saturday follows a December
incident, in which a larger vessel sank in high seas just off
Elliott Key, about 20 miles south of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe that 14 Cubans perished, although only
nine bodies were recovered and the rest are believed to have been
lost at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the nine survivors were charged with smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   As conditions in those Haiti and Cuba worsen, the number of
rafters and smuggled people is expected to rise. In 1998, the Coast
Guard intercepted 1,025 Cubans and 1,206 Haitians as they tried to
enter the country, said Petty Officer Hall. In 1997, only 406
Cubans and 587 Haitians were intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, 112 Cubans and 258 Haitians have been
intercepted at sea, said Petty Officer Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami's Little Haiti, where many of the Haitian refugees have
settled after fleeing a history of dictators and chaos, the news of
the disaster saddened many people, but surprised no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are hurting, day after day after day,'' said
Gerard Joseph, a radio commentator, of deteriorating economic and
political conditions in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   All three survivors will eventually be taken to Krome Detention
Center in Miami, and could be deported back to Haiti.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 1939EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
