<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPIONAGE ASSERTIONS UNFOUNDED, CHINA SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China said Sunday that accusations that its spies had
stolen nuclear weapons designs from the United States were
``unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan gave the first official response
to accusations of nuclear espionage Sunday at a previously
scheduled news conference. The assertions, circulating within the
U.S. government, were reported in The New York Times on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. security officials, the report said, believe that in the
1980s Chinese spies learned the U.S. design of an advanced, small
nuclear warhead, used for hitting multiple targets with a single
rocket. U.S. officials believe that the spying effort, centered on
national weapons laboratories, has continued, it said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Tang said, ``I think the report by The New York Times
was irresponsible and unfounded.'' The espionage assertions, Tang
noted, followed other recent accusations that China has gained
military technologies through commercial satellite transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always some people trying to obstruct normal trade
relations between the United States and China, including the export
of high-technology items,'' he said. ``This will not be beneficial
to the interests of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In his news conference, held during the annual session of the
national Parliament, Tang also said any effort to condemn China's
human rights record at a U.N. meeting this month would fail, and he
repeated China's vehement opposition to research by the United
States and Japan on anti-missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those problems, Tang said, he is hopeful that the
planned visit to Washington in April by Prime Minister Zhu Rongji
will aid progress toward a Chinese-American ``constructive
strategic partnership.'' It has become clear to both sides, he
said, that ``friendly and cooperative relations serve the interests
of our two countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is under strong pressure from
Congress to sponsor a resolution censuring China at an annual U.N.
human rights meeting in Geneva this month.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have described past efforts to condemn
China in the Geneva meetings as futile and counterproductive, and
last year the United States did not offer a resolution. But
recently, after China gave harsh sentences to several democracy
advocates, the Senate voted 99-0 to urge the White House to again
sponsor a condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   Should that occur, Tang said Sunday, ``I think the outcome will
not be different than in the previous seven times.'' Tang said he
told Secretary of State Madeleine Albright during her visit earlier
this week that ``On the question of human rights there will be no
way out if you replace dialogue with confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tang asserted that research on missile defenses for U.S. allies
in Asia reflected Cold War thinking and would destabilize the
region. China is particularly alarmed by discussion of including
Taiwan, which it considers a part of China, in a missile-defense
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Tang warned of an unspecified ``strong reaction'' to any U.S.
extension of missile defenses to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would amount to an encroachment on China's sovereignty
and territorial integrity, and also be an obstruction to the great
cause of peaceful reunification of the motherland,'' Tang said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
