<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH UNVEILS DIVERSE COMMITTEE TO EXPLORE HIS CANDIDACY
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a grand pageant of political might, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas rolled out the 10 members of his
presidential exploratory committee Sunday, an ethnically and
ideologically diverse tableau of some of the Republican Party's
biggest names and most promising stars.
</P>
<P>
   The carefully choreographed juggernaut was intended to convey a
sense of inevitability about Bush's presidential quest, a move that
could help him lock up crucial financial and political support in
the next few months. With each speaker offering a crisp testimonial
explaining why the governor was destined for the White House, the
accolades sounded as if they were for a beloved leader who was
about to be handed his gold watch _ not a man who had never been
elected to any office until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The assemblage, which Bush introduced as ``the best of the
Republican Party,'' included George P. Shultz, secretary of state
under President Ronald Reagan; Rep. Henry Bonilla of Texas, the
first Mexican-American Republican elected to the House; Condoleeza
Rice, the provost of Stanford University who was a national
security official for President George Bush; Rep. J.C. Watts Jr. of
Oklahoma, a conservative who is the only black Republican in
Congress, and Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Washington, who, unlike
Governor Bush, supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   For added heft, Bush's advisers distributed a list of elected
officials backing the governor, including 72 House members and six
senators.
</P>
<P>
   The outpouring was all the more striking because Bush has yet to
stake out public stands on pressing matters that his rivals are
already debating. Questioned by reporters at the event about issues
ranging from whether he favored a tax cut to what he would do in
Kosovo to the economic crisis in Asia, Bush offered the same
answer: that he would not articulate his positions until he
formally declared his candidacy, which would be in June, after the
state Legislature adjourns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't have specific remedies or specific suggestions until I
start moving around the country,'' Bush, in a common refrain, said
when asked about Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Haley Barbour, a former Republican Party chairman who is one of
the heavyweights in the party, said no candidate _ not even Reagan
in 1980, or Richard M. Nixon in 1968, after toiling for years in
Republican politics _ had assembled such an early powerhouse of
support when they sought the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can ever remember there being such a
widespread interest in a candidacy that hasn't even been decided or
announced yet,'' said Barbour, a member of the Bush steering
committee.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is not expected to formally declare his candidacy
until June, he is dominating the polls. This announcement of his
committee to raise money drew such attention, even in the foreign
press, that it had to be held in a large ballroom at the convention
center here. As Bush and his wife, Laura, sat on a stage lined with
Texas and American flags, members of his committee, one by one,
spoke emphatically about his prospects.
</P>
<P>
   But the scene offstage was perhaps as significant. As many as
three dozen financial and political advisers flew to Austin to
lunch with Bush and offer counsel. Among them were three of the
party's most successful fund-raisers, Wayne L. Berman, Heinz C.
Prechter and Mel Sembler. Sembler is supposed to be uncommitted
because he is finance chairman of the Republican National
Committee. He insisted, with a smile, that he has not signed on
yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
