<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARJACKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS 49,000 CARJACKINGS ANNUALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There are an estimated 49,000 carjackings a year, a far
higher figure than criminologists had believed, the Justice
Department reported Sunday in the first comprehensive study of the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of the carjackings involved the use of a gun, and in
16 percent of the cases a victim was injured, according to the
report, by the Bureau of Justice Statistics, a branch of the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the large number of carjackings, only an estimated
average of 27 people were killed each year in the 1990s in
carjackings. About 58 percent of the carjackers were black,
according to their victims, while 19 percent were white, the report
said. There are no data on the race of the others, because such
percentages are based on victim data, not arrest data.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate, of an average of 48,787 carjackings annually from
1992 to 1996, amounts to 10 percent of the average of 500,000
reported robberies a year, said Alfred Blumstein, a professor of
criminology at Carnegie Mellon University.
</P>
<P>
   Since only about half of all robberies are reported to the
police, there are actually about 1 million robberies a year, and
carjackings would thus account for 5 percent of all robberies,
Blumstein said. But even this percentage, he added, ``suggests that
carjackings are a more serious problem than most people, including
me, anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   The professor noted that the most common place for robberies,
outside the home, is convenience stores, the site for 5.7 percent
of robberies each year, about equal to the proportion of
carjackings. The next-most-frequent location is gas stations, the
site for 2.4 percent of robberies.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the rise in the number of carjackings, Blumstein
said, is that in recent years automobile manufacturers have made
major improvements in ``hardening the ignition of cars, making them
less easy to hot-wire and steal.'' As a result, more thieves have
had to get the key from the owner of the car to steal it, he said.
``This is an unintended consequence of a successful form of crime
control,'' making cars harder to steal, the professor said.
</P>
<P>
   Automobile theft reached a peak of 1.66 million stolen vehicles
in 1991 and has fallen since then, dropping to 1.35 million stolen
vehicles in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Carjackings first came to national attention with the surge of
crack cocaine and semiautomatic handguns in the 1980s. Another
reason for the increase in recent years, Blumstein said, is that
drug dealers did not want to risk being caught in their own cars,
which could be seized by the police if drugs were found in them. So
drug dealers began hijacking occupied cars.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate of the number of carjackings was derived from the
National Crime Victimization Survey, a nationally representative
sample of households that are questioned by the Census Bureau. The
survey is one of two national databases on crime, the other being
the Uniform Crime Report, which is maintained by the FBI and is
based on arrests reported by police agencies around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The survey does not ask about homicides, so the estimate of an
average of 27 people murdered a year in carjackings is from the FBI
statistics. The estimate that 58 percent of carjackers were black
is virtually identical with the proportion of offenders in all
robberies who are black, 57 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
