<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUYING-ELECTRONICS-AR     03-07 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYING-ELECTRONICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONICS INDUSTRY HOPES CONSUMERS WILL EMBRACE NEW HIGH-END
PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By   SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Scott walked up to a display of digital cameras inside the
Wiz consumer electronics store in Carle Place, N.Y., last Thursday
evening with a single purpose: purchasing a gift for his wife's
50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Scott peered inside the gleaming display case, a slightly
perplexed look on his face, trying to decide which of the more than
a dozen models of digital cameras he would buy. He quickly accepted
help when a salesman, David Levine, questioned him whom the camera
was for and how it would be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a little direction, I wouldn't know the first thing;
I'm a total impulse shopper,'' Scott conceded after paying $800 for
a Sony Mavica model, which stores photos on a 3.5-inch computer
floppy disk, instead of one of the models using an even smaller,
oblong-shaped memory card. ``After looking at all the bells and
whistles,'' he said, newly confident, ``I opted for the best one.''
</P>
<P>
   But the flush of victory was short-lived. Scott is already
dreading his next planned consumer electronics foray: stalking the
large-screen TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overwhelming,'' he said, anticipating the task of hacking
through the features-and-options jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he seemed more concerned about choosing which one to buy
than the likelihood that he will pay $1,500 or more, once he
decides.
</P>
<P>
   And Scott hardly seems to be a unique consumer. Buoyed by strong
holiday sales of large-screen television sets, videocassette
recorders and Sony Playstation video games, and signs pointing to
strong first-quarter sales, the makers and sellers of consumer
electronics products are predicting that 1999 could be the
industry's best year ever. Rather than scaring off consumers, they
are counting on a dazzling _ skeptics might say dizzying _ array of
new and enhanced products to stimulate sales.
</P>
<P>
   The new products include digital television sets with 60-inch
screens and promises of sharper pictures, better sound and new
features like embedded program guides. Add an outdoor surveillance
camera and a set-top box, and a TV can let a person see who's
knocking at the front door without ever leaving the Barcalounger.
And enhanced versions of other electronic products, like
wireless-messaging Palm Pilots and recordable compact disk players,
are expected to keep shoppers pouring out cash to stay on the crest
of the digital product improvement wave.
</P>
<P>
   After declining in 1991, sales of consumer electronics have
since been growing at an average of 3 percent to 5 percent a year,
according to the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association,
the industry's main trade group. And this year, the association
expects sales to reach almost $80 billion _ an increase of more
than 6 percent and up from a record $75 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   In discretionary-spending terms, Americans now shell out more on
consumer electronics each year than on furniture, jewelry,
household appliances or sporting goods. The rise in sales is
attributed in part to what the trend watcher Faith Popcorn has
called the ``cocooning'' and ``burrowing'' stay-at-home habits of
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Whether consumers come through to meet the industry's optimistic
forecast, of course, depends on where householders draw the line.
It's one thing to pay $350 to $500 for a 27-inch television set for
the children's room to keep up with the burrowing Joneses.
</P>
<P>
   But with high-definition television programs still scarce on the
airwaves, are consumers really ready to hand over $800 to $1,500
for a set-top box that will translate digital signals into enhanced
pictures on their conventional TV's _ or pay up to $12,000 for a
completely new HDTV set?
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' said Terry Webb, a mother of two in Virginia Beach,
Va. ``I know someone who bought a video disk player, and they paid
a lot of money for it. I wouldn't buy any new product in the first
year that it's out. It's too expensive and you want to make certain
they've gotten all the kinks out first.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers like Mrs. Webb could prove the industry's toughest
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we see, consumers haven't figured out why they need
to own any of this stuff,'' said Nick Donatiello, president and
chief executive of Odyssey, a San Francisco-based market research
firm. And for retailers and manufacturers alike, ringing up high
volumes of sales will be the key to profitability because of the
tight profit margins on all but the biggest-ticket products.
</P>
<P>
   Donatiello said that so far interest in some of the other newer
products, like digital video disk players for watching movies, had
been limited. Still, industry executives are excited because sales
of DVD players, introduced in 1997, topped one million units last
year, rising to that level quicker than sales of the industry's
last entirely new product _ audio compact disk players, which were
introduced in the early 80s.
</P>
<P>
   The availability of movies on DVD is growing, with retailers
like Best Buy, Borders and Blockbuster now carrying many of the
2,800 titles available. And while Hollywood is moving quicker to
make new releases available in the DVD format when they come out on
videocassette, copy-protection issues are keeping some studios from
offering some of the hottest titles on disk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, the digital video disk player is going to represent a
sea change in the way consumers watch television at home,''
Donatiello said. ``But not this year, and not next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even industry leaders acknowledge that the newest, high-priced
products may be a tough sell. One reason is that while
manufacturers are pushing HDTV, there are few broadcast programs
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first two to three years, it's going to be the early
adopters who are going to be customers'' for HDTV, David Arland, a
spokesman for Thomson Consumer Electronics, the nation's
top-selling television set maker, acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry officials bring a World's Fair optimism to the
issue, reasoning that curiosity about the newfangled could help
stimulate sales of the older-fangled products.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going into retail outlets to see what the
excitement is about,'' said Jeff Joseph, a spokesman for the
Consumer Electronics Manufacturing Association. ``They are not
walking out with a new digital television. but they may walk out
with a new VCR or a television.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 1998's strong sales were fueled by purchases of items
like large-screen conventional television sets, videocassette
recorders and video games _ and in many cases, as the second or
third TV set, VCR or game console in the household.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the number of American households owning three or
more television sets reached 49 percent, according to Odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   The typical supply-and-demand curves for new types of consumer
electronics products would indicate that sales volume will pick up
as prices decline. And past patterns indicate that as prices fall,
the products themselves will become more functional.
</P>
<P>
   Digital video disk players, for example, had a price tag of
about $1,000 when they first reached the market in 1997. Since
then, prices on some models have dropped below $300, even with
several video disk movies thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   And these days, $100 can fetch a VCR with many more features
than the models costing more than $1,000 when the machines first
came on the market in the late 70s. Even the compact disk player
continues to evolve; this year's portable models offer improvements
in the anti-skip features that are popular with joggers and
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Recent history also factors into the industry's current
optimism. Repeatedly in the last 20 years, new types of consumer
electronics have caught on much faster than analysts expected. When
compact disk players were introduced in 1983, for instance, many
market forecasts called for a player to be found in only one in 10
homes within a decade. At this point, 54 percent of households own
them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And in 1984, when the nascent cellular telephone industry was
lobbying for radio airwave space, advocates said that by 1995 more
than 900,000 people would own the devices. ``They were off by about
17 million,'' remarked Richard F. Doherty, director of research at
the Envisioneering Group, a market research firm in Seaford, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Video games are the fastest-growing category of consumer
electronics, with sales rising 22 percent, to $6.3 billion last
year. And these, too, are on the verge of a major product overhaul
_ even if the first of the new devices, the Dreamcast from Sega, is
not expected to reach the market until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The current generation of game machines use chips that process
information in 64-bit chunks. But the Sega Dreamcast, which is
already available in Japan, will have a 128-bit chip and give
players access to the Internet for group play on line _ a
capability that has so far been limited to PC games.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Sony announced plans for release early next year of a
128-bit version of its Playstation, which may also play CDs and DVD
movies. Nintendo's 128-bit upgrade is not expected before 2001.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the consumer electronics bazaar may be offering
bewildering new wonders. And consumers may be forced to become
familiar with computer terms like convergence and networking,
whether they want to or not.
</P>
<P>
   Working with chip makers like Intel and computer companies like
Sun Microsystems, consumer electronics makers including Sony,
Toshiba, Thomson, Sharp, Panasonic and Philips are developing
consumer products that could be joined in home networks.
</P>
<P>
   And new alliances between such companies as Bell Atlantic and
IBM are paving the way for home appliances like microwaves and
heating systems to link with computers, VCR' and home security
systems for remote access via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But not to worry, Scott _ probably not this year. Such
consumer-electronics convergence is ``a trend that's just taking
shape,'' said Jim Hirschberg, director of Intelect ASW, a market
research firm. ``Unless you're Bill Gates,'' he said, ``it's a
little bit down the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
