<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CAMPAIGN AGAINST IRAQ, U.S. OFFERS SAUDI ARABIA NEW MISSILES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia _ As Iraq accused the United States of
resorting to ``pressure and blackmail'' in the region, Defense
Secretary William Cohen offered Saudi Arabia new weapons and
military training Sunday to help shore up its defenses against any
threat from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The offer came on what may be the most important stop in a
nine-nation tour in which Cohen is seeking to solidify anti-Iraq
sentiment among friendly Arab governments. Some Saudi officials are
uncomfortable with the ongoing American air attacks on Iraq, and
Cohen has said an important goal of his trip is to persuade Arab
allies that the United States is ``acting appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement has prompted mockery from Iraq, where
government-controlled newspapers predicted Sunday that Cohen would
fail to win Arab support. But in the country that is the main base
for American warplanes in the region, Saudi officials voiced no
public dissent.
</P>
<P>
   An American official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said that Cohen had held a ``very productive meeting'' with Prince
Sultan bin Abd al-Aziz, the king's brother and Cohen's Saudi
counterpart, who has in the recent past objected to the hard-line
American stand.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's offer to sell Saudi Arabia an undisclosed number of
sophisticated air-to-air missiles making it only the third Arab
country to be granted that opportunity, was a clear sweetener in
the American diplomatic campaign. The missiles have a range of more
than 50 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the United Arab Emirates was the first country in the
region to be promised the missiles, which cost $380,000 each. The
second was Bahrain, which was promised the missiles on Saturday,
during the first stop on Cohen's current tour.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq appeared to have those weapons sales in mind Sunday as it
accused the United States of trying once again to buy favor in
region. ``The tour by Zionist Cohen in the region is part of a
continuous American policy of pressure and blackmail,'' the ruling
Baath party newspaper, Al Thawra, wrote in an editorial Sunday. It
said the two states that ``submit to American blackmail are Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain carried out four days of intensive
air raids against Iraq last December. In the weeks since, the
American-led attacks have continued in response to Iraqi attempts
to target American and British pilots patrolling no-flight zones
over northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has mounted an aggressive campaign to persuade fellow Arabs
that the American-led attacks are unjust and that accounts provided
by Washington are nothing more than a pretext for what amounts to a
low-level war.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to reassure uneasy Arab leaders, Cohen contends that
Iraq is leaving the United States little choice but to shoot back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to make sure that we are acting appropriately,''
Cohen said at the outset of his trip in a reference to friendly
Arab governments. ``And I think that we can demonstrate very
clearly'' that Iraq ``has been consistently violating the no-fly
zones,'' which were imposed by Western powers after the Persian
Gulf war of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very dangerous mission flying over the north and the
south, so we intend to take whatever measures we can to insure the
safety of those pilots,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his offer of air-to-air missiles, Cohen agreed with
the prince on a plan to increase joint American-Saudi army training
exercises in Saudi Arabia, a senior American official said.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia was the second stop on Cohen's Persian Gulf and
Middle East tour, which began on Friday. He flew to Oman on Sunday
night and is scheduled to travel on to the United Arab Emirates,
Qatar, Kuwait, Jordan, Egypt and Israel before flying home next
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
