<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CAMBODIA-KHMERROUGE     03-07 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CAMBODIA-KHMERROUGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA PLANS TRIAL FOR JAILED KHMER ROUGE LEADER
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating to eliminate art advisory. No other changes.)   (ms) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cambodian officials said Sunday they will conduct a trial in
Phnom Penh for Ta Mok, the last fugitive Khmer Rouge leader, who
was captured on Saturday. Their statements raised further doubts
about their commitment to produce other Khmer Rouge leaders for an
international tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Ta Mok, who is believed to be about 72, led the dwindling rebel
force after its former leader, Pol Pot, was purged in 1997. He
remained on the run even after other fugitive leaders surrendered
to the government, along with virtually all their fighting forces.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Ta Mok had few friends, and a number of political
analysts were predicting that the Cambodian government would seek
to make him a scapegoat for the crimes of the Khmer Rouge. The
brutal communist movement was responsible for the deaths of more
than a million people when it held power from 1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure we will try him in Cambodia,'' said Om Yentieng, a
top adviser to Prime Minister Hun Sen. ``We have everything here,
why should we try him abroad?''
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen has been much more ambiguous about the fate of other
former Khmer Rouge leaders _ notably two top officials who defected
last December, Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea. He has warned that a
trial could endanger an ill-defined process that he calls
``national reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Since their surrender, Khieu Samphan and Muon Chea have been
allowed to live freely in a remote enclave populated by former
rebels and guarded by former Khmer Rouge fighters. They have urged
the world to ``let bygones be bygones.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is prosecuted, Ta Mok would be the first Khmer Rouge
leader to appear in court. Immediately after their ouster from
power, Pol Pot and his Foreign Minister, Ieng Sary, were tried and
convicted in absentia by a newly installed Cambodian government in
a proceeding that is not generally recognized as having been valid.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Sunday that Ta Mok was being held in shackles in
a prison in downtown Phnom Penh, almost within sight of Tuol Sleng,
the former prison and torture house where at least 14,000 people
were sent to their deaths by the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   A team of lawyers has recommended to the United Nations that 20
to 30 former leaders of the Khmer Rouge be tried in an
international court. The lawyers said Cambodia's judicial system is
not adequate to handle such a complex and politically volatile
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Jones, the Asia director of the New York-based group
Human Rights Watch, said it would be unlikely that Hun Sen's
government could defuse pressure for an international tribunal by
putting Ta Mok on trial at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that even by having some kind of show trial in
Cambodia, pressure for an international tribunal is going to go
away,'' she said. ``I think things have already gone too far. In
fact, any attempt to try Ta Mok in Cambodia could provide more
momentum for having an international tribunal simply because it
will focus attention on all the problems of holding a trial inside
Cambodia.''
</P>
<P>
   Still in tatters 20 years after the ouster of the Khmer Rouge by
a Vietnamese invasion, Cambodia's legal system is primitive,
unschooled and riven with graft and political influence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cambodian researchers who have been compiling
evidence against leading Khmer Rouge figures say that despite Ta
Mok's widespread reputation for brutality, the documentary evidence
that he participated in the crimes of the Khmer Rouge is slim.
</P>
<P>
   A jungle fighter since his youth, Ta Mok was a resistance
soldier against the French colonial government in the 1940s. There
is some uncertainty about his given name, but historians say he was
born Ek Chhoen. Well before old age, he was using the revolutionary
alias that includes the honorific ``Ta,'' meaning ``grandfather.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a regional commander in the Khmer Rouge's fight for power
in the 1960s and 1970s _ known for his brutality even against
fellow revolutionaries with whom he disagreed. After the movement
came to power, he was a member of the nine-member Standing
Committee that ruled the country under Pol Pot.
</P>
<P>
   He led what amounted to a coup within the Khmer Rouge in June
1997, ousting Pol Pot from leadership of what had again become a
guerrilla movement and engineering a show trial and house arrest
for the former leader.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, he had close relations with military commanders
just across Cambodia's northern border in Thailand and is widely
believed to have become a millionaire through cross-border business
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in prison in Phnom Penh, a Cambodian official said, ``He is
looking very tired, very frail and, of course, he is looking sad
that he has been arrested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
