<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-CHILDBIRTH-ART-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ORDERS END TO CASH DEMAND AT CHILDBIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., N.Y., Conn., Mich., Mass., Vt.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some doctors and hospitals have been forcing poor
women to pay hundreds of dollars in cash for a popular procedure to
relieve pain in childbirth, federal officials say, and the
government has ordered hospitals to stop the practice immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law says that pregnant Medicaid patients may not be
charged for prenatal care, delivery or other medical services that
relate to pregnancy. Medicaid reimburses hospitals and doctors for
such services, but doctors say the payments for pain treatment are
grossly inadequate, sometimes only 10 percent or 20 percent of what
private insurance companies pay.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent recently to state health officials, Sally
Richardson, the national director of the Medicaid program, said she
had received reports that health-care providers were improperly
requiring patients to pay cash for services covered by Medicaid,
which pays the bills for more than one-third of all births in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say they do not know how widespread the
problem is, but doctors and health-policy experts say they have
heard complaints from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, Ms. Richardson said, anesthesiologists have
insisted that Medicaid patients pay in advance, with their own
money, for the widely used form of anesthesia, known as the
epidural block.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one instance,'' Ms. Richardson said, ``the obstetrician
ordered the epidural in advance, but when the woman was in active
labor, she was refused this service for lack of prepayment. Even
though she tried to pay by check, credit card and a Western Union
money telegram, the doctor refused anything but cash.''
</P>
<P>
   With somewhat more passion than midlevel federal officials
usually express, Ms. Richardson said, ``Treatment of a Medicaid
patient in this manner is not just a concern, it is alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   She told state Medicaid directors to make sure that hospitals
understood their obligations to provide all medically necessary
services, including anesthesia, to Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Richardson did not name any of the doctors who demanded
cash, nor did she name any hospital. But Medicaid patients said
last year that they had been asked to pay cash for epidural
injections at a dozen hospitals in the Los Angeles area, and
Florida officials say they have received similar complaints.
Patients who could not pay were, in many cases, offered less
effective and less expensive forms of pain relief.
</P>
<P>
   A recent article in the newsletter of the American Society of
Anesthesiologists quoted doctors who believe they are grossly
underpaid by Medicaid. ``Poor people can't expect to drive a
Rolls-Royce or to eat at a fine French restaurant, so why should
they expect to receive the Cadillac of analgesics for free?'' one
doctor asked.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Birnbach, director of obstetric anesthesiology at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in New York, said such comments
came from ``a vocal minority of anesthesiologists'' and were
contrary to the society's official position, which holds that women
in labor should not be denied pain relief for financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Health Services found that
anesthesiologists at one hospital, Northridge Hospital Medical
Center, had required Medicaid patients to pay $400 in cash for
epidural pain relief in labor and delivery, and it said the
hospital had helped collect the money.
</P>
<P>
   The state demanded that Northridge refund the money to patients,
and Ken August, a spokesman for the California Department of Health
Services, said 114 women had received such refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Women said it was humiliating to dispatch their husbands to
automated teller machines, friends and neighbors to get cash.
</P>
<P>
   One patient, Ozzie Chavez, said she thought the nurse was joking
when she asked for $400 in cash just hours before Mrs. Chavez gave
birth at Northridge in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a wimp when it comes to pain,'' Mrs. Chavez said in an
interview. ``But it was a very painful delivery. The
anesthesiologist wouldn't even come into the room until she got her
money. I offered her a credit card and a check, but she wouldn't
accept it. I was lying there having contractions, and they wouldn't
give me an epidural. I felt like an animal. It was degrading.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Chavez's sister called relatives in England, who wired the
money to Los Angeles. ``By the time the money arrived, I had had
the baby,'' Mrs. Chavez said. Wendell Mobley, a spokesman for
Northridge, said the hospital had apologized to Mrs. Chavez. Mobley
refused to discuss the hospital practices in detail, because of
pending lawsuits, including one by Mrs. Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Neeld Jr., president of the American Society of
Anesthesiologists, said, ``It's unethical to withhold services
because of reimbursement. Anesthesiologists share with all
physicians the responsibility to provide care for patients
irrespective of their ability to pay for their care.''
</P>
<P>
   Birnbach agreed. While Medicaid payments are far too low, he
said, ``we should not practice in a way that will allow us to be
accused of extorting money'' from patients, and ``we should not
fight the battle of unfair reimbursement for epidurals at the
patient's bedside.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The epidural injection blocks pain in the lower part of the
body, but the mother generally remains wide awake.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid is financed jointly by the federal government and the
states, and states set reimbursement levels. Some states have
increased payments for obstetricians in recent years, but
reimbursement for anesthesiologists has lagged behind.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last year by the American Society of Anesthesiologists
found that New York, for example, typically paid $55 to $105 for
the epidural block, and Connecticut paid $64, while insurance
companies often paid more than $800 in those states.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, the society said, Medicaid reimbursement averaged
$60, about one-tenth of the amounts typically paid by insurance
companies. In California, Medicaid payments ranged from $98 to
$170, while private insurers often paid more than $400.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, including New York and California,
anesthesiologists have lobbied state legislators and Medicaid
officials to increase the payments for pain-relief services in
childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bodkin, executive director of the Florida Society of
Anesthesiologists, said, ``The Medicaid reimbursement rates are so
dreadfully low _ the equivalent of $20 an hour for someone with 12
years of professional training _ that they discourage
anesthesiologists from taking Medicaid patients, who deserve the
same quality care as other patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Rosenbaum, a professor of health law and policy at George
Washington University, said doctors, nursing homes and other
health-care providers had often tried to get Medicaid patients to
pay more than the amounts paid by Medicaid. But Medicaid officials
said it was particularly inappropriate to require such payments by
women in labor.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bullen, the Medicaid director in Massachusetts, who is
chairman of the National Association of State Medicaid Directors,
said, ``This shouldn't be happening,'' and he added, ``You cannot
require cost sharing of any kind as a condition of services being
rendered to pregnant Medicaid patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Crayton, the Medicaid director in Florida, said his agency
had received reports similar to those in California.
``Anesthesiologists told Medicaid patients they did not accept
Medicaid payments for epidurals and required payment in advance for
the service at labor and delivery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wallace-Brodeur, the Medicaid director in Vermont, said
that even if anesthesiologists had valid concerns about inadequate
reimbursement, ``they shouldn't take it out on the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   In her letter to state officials, Ms. Richardson said: ``Under
federal Medicaid law, deductions, cost sharing or similar charges
are not permitted for Medicaid services furnished to pregnant
women. Thus, a participating physician's demand for these
additional payments would be in violation of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Anesthesiologists say that Medicaid patients sometimes agree to
pay them directly for their services during labor and delivery,
just as private patients would. But, Ms. Richardson said,
regardless of the preferences of any particular doctor, the
hospital has a duty to ensure that pregnant Medicaid patients can
obtain services ``without the imposition of deductibles, cost
sharing or similar charges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
