<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-MARCH08-COX     03-07 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-MARCH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis, delegation of lawmakers march in Alabama to celebrate
spirit of civil rights movement
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala. _ They crossed their arms across their chests and
held each other's hands, black hand on white, white hand on brown.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen members of Congress from across the country came to
this town along the banks of the Alabama River to understand the
struggle African-Americans endured to gain the right to vote and to
remove the laws segregating blacks from whites.
</P>
<P>
   It was here 34 years ago that Alabama state troopers clobbered
and left for dead one of their fellow congressmen _ Rep. John Lewis
(D-Ga.) _ for leading 600 people across the Edmund Pettus Bridge to
protest the rules that kept blacks from voting.
</P>
<P>
   Returning as a congressman, Lewis is hoping that the
re-enactment of the march will ignite a dialogue on race relations
in America and tear down the social barriers that remain more than
three decades after Congress passed the Voters' Rights Act and the
Civil Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must still move to build bridges, bridges of
understanding,'' Lewis said. ``We have come a great distance, but
we still have a distance to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan congressional delegation retraced Lewis'
footsteps on March 7, 1965, walking from Brown Chapel AME down
Martin Luther King Boulevard and past the low slung brick buildings
lining downtown. As they walked, they began singing, ``God is on
our side today,'' their voices getting louder with each step.
</P>
<P>
   Just ahead, children carried signs that said ``Wake Up America''
and ``Justice for all'' and sang ``no one is going turn us
around,'' as they walked to the bridge where white troopers once
attacked Lewis and his fellow marchers.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of that march was clear to Marquita Harris, 15, and
her friend Joyce Watts, 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who think that the white people are bigger and the
black people are smaller are wrong,'' said Harris, a Selma
resident. ``Everyone should be treated equal. I think all the
blacks and whites should be together.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the march only drew a few whites despite town officials
declaring Selma the ``most integrated city in America.'' Both Watts
and Harris said it made them sad that their white friends did not
show. ``We should all be here together,'' said Watts.
</P>
<P>
   It is these young people who Lewis and the congressional group
want to reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to walk this bridge for the children and the
unsung heros,'' Lewis said. ``We are going to redeem the soul of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   It is time, he said, to lay down the burden of race: ``When we
go back to Washington I hope we can do what we can to create one
home, the American House.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the weekend, sponsored by the Faith &AMP; Politics
Institute, a nonprofit interfaith group based in Washington, D.C.,
the lawmakers toured monuments of the civil rights movement and
heard live testimonials from those who fought for equality.
</P>
<P>
   In Birmingham, they met the Rev. Fred Shuttlesworth, who was a
target of white segregationists. His church and home were bombed
and he was chain-whipped for trying to enroll his daughter in an
all-white school.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Shuttlesworth walked through the Kelly Ingram Park,
where protestors once were sprayed by the Birmingham police with
fire hoses that were so strong they could remove bark from trees 80
feet away. Standing in front of a sculpture of a boy being attacked
by a white police officer, gospel singer Bettie Fikes began to
sing, ``I've been in the storm so long,'' a song that her
grandmother, a slave, had passed on to her.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of the Capitol in Montgomery, the delegation bowed
their heads and prayed in former church of the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power structure of Alabama is up there,'' said Lewis,
pointing to the Capitol. ``The power of the human spirit is here in
this church.''
</P>
<P>
   In Selma, they ate dinner with Mayor Joe Smitherman, the same
mayor who stood against Lewis 34 years ago. Once a segregationist,
Smitherman now says he ``was on the wrong side.''
</P>
<P>
   At the National Voting Rights Museum and Institute in Selma, the
group ate breakfast with Coretta Scott King and Martin Luther King
III, King's widow and son, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have caught the spirit, the sense of family and
community'' said Scott King. ``There is nothing greater than the
power of the spirit. .. we can now begin the transformation in
Congress which is so desperately needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Sawyer (D-Ohio) said he intended take his experience
back to his district in the hopes of improving race relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a country that is still in need of healing,'' Sawyer
said. ``We still struggle over divisions. And the ability to see
people for what they really are is the first step to repair the
divisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's division of the Atlanta-based Southern Christian
Leadership Conference was also in Selma, marking the 13th year they
have honored the the march's anniversary and the death of Viola
Gregg Liuzzo.
</P>
<P>
   Liuzzo had watched the state troopers beat Lewis and the other
marchers on television. It so enraged her that she left her five
children and drove to Selma to help the movement.
</P>
<P>
   After driving carloads of blacks between Selma and Montgomery,
she was shot and killed by Klansmen.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Lowery, founder of the 20-year-old SCLC/WOMEN, said the
group came to Selma to make sure that ``no one ever forgets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must never forget the struggles and the sacrifices made,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the trip was a sad reminder of what they did not do
earlier. Rep. Jay Dickey (R-Ark.) said he grew up in the South, but
was not involved in the civil rights struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt like I was better than my black brothers and
sisters, that was just the way it was,'' Dickey said. ``My purpose
now is to bring about racial harmony and understanding. We have an
opportunity to bring change. That is my duty.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is much change that needs to occur, say the veterans
of the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Fikes, the gospel singer who had marched with Lewis, said she is
saddened that the spirit of the movement has not caught on with the
younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many dreams have been deferred?'' Fikes asked. ``Somewhere
along the line we lost the main ingredient: unity.''
</P>
<P>
   She is dismayed at the black on black violence that terrorizes
inner city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Recently her son said to her, ``I get it now. In the 1960s they
(whites) sicked the dogs on us. Now we sick the dogs on each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, said Fikes, is the reason why the struggle is far from
over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
