<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPIRAL SOLUTION FOR THE PATENT OFFICE'S LIBRARIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Pa., Texas, Ky.)   By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of U.S. patents issued last year reached an all-time
high, jumping 31.5 percent from 1997, according to statistics
recently released by the Patent Office.
</P>
<P>
   This crush of new patents simply intensifies what has long been
a headache for the agency: trying to figure out where to store
paper copies of all those new patents.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Patent Office sprawls across 1.4 million square
feet in 18 buildings in Crystal City, Va. This spring, a government
panel is expected to make a final decision about whether to
renovate the existing quarters or move into a new campus. Although
there has long been talk of making the Patent Office a paperless
agency, paper copies are expected to be around for at least another
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Bromer, a patent agent based in Marietta, Pa., thinks he
has come up with a way to simplify the complicated logistics of
adding millions of pages of patents each year to the Patent Office.
Of course, he has patented the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Bromer has designed a spiral patent office. It is essentially
one long, skinny, curving building that coils loosely around
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people hear the word spiral they think of the Guggenheim
Museum,'' Bromer said. ``But that is really a conical-helical
shape,'' he said, noting that his spiral, rather than curving
upward, radiates outward on a single horizontal plane.
</P>
<P>
   Bromer said that the patent collection could be arranged in line
on a single, curving, continuous track that extends the length of
the building _ thus eliminating the need to reshelve to make space
for new patents, which the agency arranges according to a special
classification system.
</P>
<P>
   Once the track started to become full, the building could be
made bigger by simply adding on to the end of the spiral. ``The new
construction would always be on the outside, so no one would be
disrupted,'' Bromer said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bromer had the Patent Office in mind when he designed
his building, he thinks it would work for any expanding library or
archive. He said the building could be several stories high, with
each floor having its own long, snaking shelf. He said different
parts of the spiral would be connected with walkways, so that one
wouldn't have to travel the entire length of the spiral to get from
the start of the collection to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Bromer received patent number 5,855,098. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Preventing Fires In Auto Crashes
</P>
<P>
   When Sandra Kerns was 13, she watched two men burn to death
after a car accident. ``It's a sound, sight, and smell you never
forget,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kerns, a housewife, and her husband, Joe, a retired
mechanic, who live in Edmonton, Ky, have invented a device intended
to prevent a fire from igniting once a car has crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the gas lines of most vehicles automatically
disconnect upon impact. ``But the main problem isn't the gas tank _
it's the fumes,'' Mrs. Kerns said. ``What you need to do is
eliminate any possibility of an electrical spark igniting the
fumes, That's why the first thing emergency workers do is
disconnect the battery when they get to the scene of an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Housed inside the Kernses' small plastic device is a chamber
filled with mercury or some other liquid that conducts electricity.
The device attaches to the battery cables and under normal
circumstances, the mercury conducts electricity through the cables.
</P>
<P>
   If the car rolls over, however, the mercury flows through a
series of one-way valves into some tubes on the top of the device.
Once the mercury has escaped, the battery cuts off because the
conductive material is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a front impact or a rear impact or a side impact, what
happens is there's a sliding block covering the hole that holds the
mercury,'' Mrs. Kerns said. ``On impact, an air canister triggers
the block to drop so the mercury drops into a bottom chamber'' _
thereby cutting off the battery connection.
</P>
<P>
   In either situation, the mercury also comes into contact with a
metal plate, and this action causes the alternator to shut off,
according to Mrs. Kerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes in contact with a metal-clad wall that also has
screws in it and has wires going to your alternator,'' she said.
``And that kills the alternator. You can start your car and remove
your battery and it will continue to run because your alternator is
running. So you want to kill both of them at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kernses contend that the device would cost about $100 to
manufacture and could be easily installed on existing or new cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Kernses received patent number 5,602,371. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Zinc Toothpicks To Fight Infection
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies have shown that periodontal disease can
foreshadow or worsen other infections in the body. Edward J.
Petrus, a doctor in Austin, Texas, patented two things last week
that he says will keep gums healthier: zinc-coated toothpicks and
zinc-coated dental floss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zinc is antibacterial, antifungal, and antiviral,'' Dr. Petrus
said. ``It also acts as an astringent. It reduces swelling and
bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Petrus said he was looking to license patents patents
5,875,799 and 5,875,798 to a company that would finance clinical
research on the floss and toothpicks. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
