<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cable Deregulation Raises Specter of Higher Rates
</P>
<P>
   Cable television, one of the last industries to have its prices
controlled by the government, is set to become almost completely
deregulated this month. But while the prospect of competition was
supposed to drive prices down, the opposite has happened. Cable
rates continue to rise, with many companies announcing increases
for this year averaging 5 percent, more than twice the projected
inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996 assumed the cable industry
would be facing far more competition from satellite broadcasters
and telephone companies. But that has not happened, raising deep
concerns that cable companies unshackled from price controls and
not threatened by competition will continue to impose big rate
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Online Payment System Developed
</P>
<P>
   A company that has developed an Internet system to allow
advertisers to pay for a computer user's attention plans to begin
permitting consumers to earn money online and use it to buy digital
content, including music files, articles, maps, software and other
information.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine Apologizes for Mailing
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand subscribers to Poz, a magazine for people who
are HIV positive, who had requested that their names not be rented
out to other companies became alarmed when they received a letter
last month from a company with information about a new HIV
treatment. The magazine's parent, Poz Publishing, said the mailing
was a mistake and apologized.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listening for Rumors on the Web
</P>
<P>
   Corporations have long paid clipping services to monitor their
appearances in the conventional news media. But now a company
called Ewatch and its competitors have taken the practice online
and a step further. This new generation of monitors trolls for
rumor and innuendo in the back alleys of the Web, where unchecked
scuttlebutt can damage corporate reputations and stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Red Alerts From Partisan Sites
</P>
<P>
   A year after the gossipy Web site run by Matt Drudge became a
bookmark in Washington computers, other, more partisan Web sites
are becoming early warning systems for the mainstream news media.
</P>
<P>
   Screens Go Dark in TV Dispute
</P>
<P>
   In a setback for DirecTV, the satellite television provider,
750,000 viewers have lost programming from Fox and CBS because of a
legal battle between broadcasters and the satellite television
industry over who can receive network signals.
</P>
<P>
   Turning Browsers Into Buyers
</P>
<P>
   Those who shop on the Internet abandon one-half to two-thirds of
the purchases they begin, industry executives and analysts say.
Some consumers are just trying out the online shopping experience.
Others abandon the process when confronted with big shipping
charges or with registration forms that ask for personal
information. Tired of not closing sales, e-commerce sites have
begun devising ways to convert browsers into buyers.
</P>
<P>
   New Devices for Internet Music
</P>
<P>
   At the New York Music and Internet Expo over the weekend,
Creative Technology, the leading seller of audio circuitry for
personal computers, showed off a line of products that can retrieve
and play music from the Internet using the MP3 software format,
including a portable MP3 player that will cost less than $200,
roughly the same price as an MP3 player offered by Diamond
Multimedia.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
