<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL-HARRINGTON08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harrington's loving spirit still alive, friends and family say
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Precious few tears were shed Sunday for the late Rev.
W. Frank Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   Even the weather, sunny and unseasonably warm, seemed to agree.
</P>
<P>
   A great man had passed and left a legacy hardly worth mourning,
but rather worth celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, 63, died last week after a long illness. In 28 years
he shepherded Peachtree Presbyterian Church from obscure pastorate
to the biggest mainline Presbyterian church in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorial service packed to overflowing _ and cybercast live
on the Internet _ the resonant feeling was that Harrington's spirit
still invests ``every brick and every plank'' of the expanding
church, said Peachtree minister Frank Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always said, `Keep us in your prayers, and remember how
much I love you,''' said Skinner of his old friend. ``What made
that sentence so powerful is that single word `love.' It defines
the ministry and life of Frank Harrington.''
</P>
<P>
   The many who attended _ an estimated 5,000 _ and the names of
many who attended _ former Mayor Maynard Jackson, Mayor Bill
Campbell, Gov. Roy Barnes, businessman Guy Millner _ spoke volumes
about the reach and stature of Harrington's ministry.
</P>
<P>
   He was remembered as iron-willed and soft-hearted, a spinner of
sometimes folksy, highly personal (``I never gave a sermon I didn't
need to hear myself,'' he once said), often elegant sermons.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke his mind, and would occasionally use Sunday morning as
a bully pulpit. Last year he called for the resignation of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But he never lost sight of his evangelical calling to build the
ranks of Presbyterianism, said the Rev. Douglas Oldenberg,
president of Columbia Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally (Frank) disagreed with the decisions of the
(Presbyterian) General Assembly,'' Oldenberg said, evoking
laughter. ``But ne never wavered from his support of what he called
the `Mother of my Faith.'''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner recalled that Harrington ``never made small plans, and
the construction all around is testament to that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his tenure at Peachtree, the congregation grew five fold and
the church's annual budget increased from about $300,000 to $9
million. He baptized 3,000 infants, about 1,000 adults, and
performed nearly 1,000 weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the low country of South Carolina, Harrington rose
through a number of smaller churches before arriving at Peachtree.
Even though he befriended many of his faith's aristocracy _
including evangelist Billy Graham _ he never lost his ambition, or
attention to detail.
</P>
<P>
   New members to Peachtree were told by Harrington they could only
join if they would agree to ride the church's shuttle bus. The
congregation long ago outgrew its parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A visit from Frank was always a memorable experience,'' said
Skinner. ``And, I might add, expensive. He was never above passing
the offering plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The hour-and-a half service ended simply and hauntingly. Two bag
pipe players, leading the gathered from the main chapel. They
played ``Amazing Grace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
