<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOST-PLAYS-865&AMP;ADD-NY     03-07 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-PLAYS-865&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: IN PLAYS OF FLEDGLINGS, INTIMATIONS OF
IMMORTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the late 1930s a hopeful young playwright studying
at a Midwestern university spent many weekends visiting a friend
who was working in a nearby prison. From his observations he wrote
a play about what he called ``the system's malign pressure on human
brains.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was turned down in a competition, he put it aside and
went on to other plays. But he said he was haunted by his memories
of ``those hot, humid cellblocks with tier on tier of humans'' and
``the wild, insane laughter and threatening uproars that
periodically arose.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright was not Tennessee Williams; it was Arthur Miller,
and the play was ``The Great Disobedience.'' Where are you, Vanessa
Redgrave?
</P>
<P>
   It is a remarkable coincidence that at approximately the same
time and at the same point in their careers both playwrights were
writing about prison conditions. In contrast to Miller, Williams
was not writing from firsthand experience. As a student at the
University of Iowa he had read a newspaper article about a
rebellion of inmates, and, inspired by gangster movies of the
period (like ``The Big House''), he wrote ``Not About
Nightingales.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Redgrave discovered this ``lost play'' and brought it to the
attention of the Royal National Theater, which presented its
premiere in London. Trevor Nunn's production, starring Ms.
Redgrave's brother, Corin, recently opened at Circle in the Square
on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   While Miller was a student at the University of Michigan, his
plays won the Avery Hopwood Award two years in a row, but ``The
Great Disobedience'' was rejected and he put it away in a trunk.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of a half-dozen works by Miller that preceded his
first Broadway play, ``The Man Who Had All the Luck,'' in 1944.
Obviously Miller was not discouraged. As he wrote in his
autobiography, ``Timebends,'' ``My play's failure did nothing to
weaken my conviction that art ought to be of use in changing
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Most writers have a long apprenticeship and years of struggle
before they break through, and even the most accomplished have
early plays that have not been produced, sometimes with
justification, sometimes through oversight. In many cases the
authors simply forget their apprentice work.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction to a volume of two early plays by Joe Orton
(recently published in England), the editor says that Orton ``liked
to give the impression that he had sprung, a fully mature
playwright, straight from the head of Dionysius.''
</P>
<P>
   Orton claimed that ``Entertaining Mr. Sloane,'' the play that
established his reputation in 1964, was his first full-length work.
In fact three other unproduced plays had preceded it, along with at
least seven novels that he wrote by himself or in collaboration. So
much for Dionysius.
</P>
<P>
   Currently New Yorkers have an opportunity to see lost plays by
two diverse writers, ``Not About Nightingales'' and ``The
Hothouse'' by Harold Pinter. Each followed a different path to
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not About Nightingales,'' written in 1938, was rejected by the
Group Theater, and it was not staged in Williams' lifetime. Reading
it, one can understand the reasons for the neglect. In the unlikely
event that it had been performed, it undoubtedly would not have had
the kind of rousing production Nunn has given it, or the impressive
cast of British and American actors. Anything less would have been
a disservice to the playwright.
</P>
<P>
   The play reveals Williams' nascent talent, but it is a long way
from ``The Glass Menagerie,'' his first masterwork. If it had been
done first, it might have set him off on a different course,
encouraging him to write other melodramas instead of the intimate,
autobiographical plays that followed.
</P>
<P>
   When lost plays are finally produced, timing is important.
Although ``Nightingales'' is a period piece, it gains new relevance
from current incidents of prison injustice and police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Also it can now be approached in the context of Williams' other
work. There are hints of themes that were to obsess him throughout
his career, especially in the portraits of characters too sensitive
to withstand the battering of malevolent forces in society.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Williams, Pinter put aside ``The Hothouse''
because of the adverse critical reaction to his first full-length
play, ``The Birthday Party.'' Twenty years later he read it ``as a
stranger'' and ``laughed quite a lot,'' and he decided to stage it.
Since then it has become an essential part of his body of work. A
new production is playing off-Broadway at the Atlantic Theater
Company.
</P>
<P>
   A black farce set in a state-subsidized mental institution,
``The Hothouse'' is unlike other early Pinter works. With its
zestful exuberance it is also far from his new play _ the terse,
mysterious ``Ashes to Ashes'' _ which is currently being presented
by the Roundabout Theater Company. It is closer to the spirit of
Orton (who at the time had not yet written his best plays).
</P>
<P>
   Had ``The Hothouse'' been produced when it was written, it might
have given the playwright a different image. ``The Caretaker,'' the
next full-length Pinter play to be staged, was the tone setter,
with its air of comic malice and lingering dread.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As for Orton, ``Fred and Madge'' and ``The Visitors,'' his
earliest unproduced comedies, demonstrate his talent for spoofing
the working class. One can see in them sparks of ``Entertaining Mr.
Sloane'' and ``What the Butler Saw.''
</P>
<P>
   With another early play, Chekhov's ``Wood Demon,'' there is the
added asset of historical significance; this work was the original
version of ``Uncle Vanya.'' Looking at them together illuminates
the growth of the author's genius.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947 Samuel Beckett wrote his first play, ``Eleutheria,''
followed by ``Waiting for Godot,'' and tried to get either or both
produced. Finally Roger Blin, an actor and director in Paris, chose
to do ``Godot,'' at least partly because it had a smaller cast than
the other work. And Beckett was on his way into theatrical history.
He withdrew ``Eleutheria'' from consideration, but he chose not to
discard it.
</P>
<P>
   As James Knowlson points out in his biography of Beckett, if it
had been done in 1948, ``it would certainly be talked of now, in
spite of its limitations and flaws, as one of the plays that
ushered in a new era in avant-garde French theater.''
``Eleutheria'' is closer to Ionesco than to Beckett. One hopes that
if and when ``Eleutheria'' is finally presented, it will be done
with the fidelity and imagination that Nunn has brought to
``Nightingales.''
</P>
<P>
   A final note: ``Nightingales'' was not Williams' first but his
fourth full-length play. His first was ``Beauty Is the Word'' in
1930.
</P>
<P>
   His first play to be staged was ``Cairo! Shanghai! Bombay!,''
produced in 1935 by a community theater in Memphis, Tenn. As Lyle
Leverich recounts in his biography, ``Tom: the Unknown Tennessee
Williams,'' the playwright described it as ``a farcical but rather
touching little comedy about two sailors on a date with a couple of
`light ladies.'''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing it, Williams was impressed by ``the laughter, genuine and
loud'' and the applause. In his ``Memoirs,'' he wrote, ``Then and
there the theater and I found each other for better and for
worse.'' It would be another 10 years before the world discovered
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
