<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCARLEDE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oh, brother: Jeff Burton edges sibling
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The Burton brothers started racing Go-Karts in
Virginia when each was only eight years old. But their age
difference _ Ward is six years older than Jeff _ deterred any
rivalry on the dirt tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no sibling duel will ever match the battle that occurred
in the final laps of Sunday's Las Vegas 400. The Burtons led 170 of
the final 197 laps, and with only 10 remaining, Jeff passed his
brother on the high side of the back straightaway for his sixth
career Winston Cup victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always wanted it to come down to the end like that,'' Jeff
Burton said. ``The next time he'll get me. That's awfully
stressful. To sit there and try to beat him is really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been Ward Burton's first victory since October
1995, a winless streak of 96 races. Two-time defending Winston Cup
champion Jeff Gordon finished third, with Mike Skinner and Bobby
Labonte rounding out the top five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat everybody but one car,'' Ward Burton said. ``I feel
pretty disappointed not beating that one car, but if I have to lose
to somebody, I'd want to lose to my brother. That's still not much
consolation, though.''
</P>
<P>
   A restart with only 32 laps left set up the dramatic finish. A
late caution sent the drivers to pit road after the engine in
Geoffrey Bodine's No. 60 Chevrolet blew up, leaving oil between
turns 1 and 2 of the 1.5-mile oval of Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed Ward Burton to take the lead from his brother after
getting out of the pits first. He owned the lead for 21 of the next
22 laps, holding off a challenge from Gordon, who led only one lap
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   When Gordon tried to pass Ward Burton between turns 1 and 2 with
only 25 laps remaining, Burton blocked him and then his brother
took second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't want to go to the outside of Ward,'' Gordon
said. ``He kind of gave me the inside. I wanted to get to the
outside of him. Had I been able to back off and get back in behind
him and work on him a little bit, I might have been able to do
that. But Jeff was there and got by me and they started battling.
My car got loose and I faded.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton didn't. With only 14 laps remaining, Ward Burton
opened up a sizable advantage. Jeff started closing about two laps
later, though, and the brothers raced side by side for the next
four laps until Jeff finally took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to give him an inch,'' Ward Burton said. ``I
even thought about moving up a little bit higher than I did, but I
knew one of us wouldn't have gotten out of the corner if I did. I
was trying to crowd him as much as I could without wrecking him. I
don't want to wreck my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't forget he's your brother,'' Jeff added. ``No matter
what, he's your brother. But I was doing everything I could to win
the race and he was, too.... I kind of giggled during the race
because Winston Cup racing is such a really big deal, and for two
brothers to be racing for a win is pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burtons had never finished 1-2 in a Winston Cup race, but
they accomplished the feat in a Busch Series race at Myrtle Beach,
S.C., in 1993. Jeff won that race, too, after Ward missed a shift
with only two laps left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was different,'' Jeff said. ``This was a side-by-side
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton was one of only three drivers of Ford cars who
finished in the top 10. Ford teams dominated the inaugural event
here last year with 13 of the top 14 finishers. But General Motors
teams led Sunday's race, placing seven in the top 10, including
four Chevy teams.
</P>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS 400 TOP 5
</P>
<P>
   1. Jeff Burton, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   2. Ward Burton, Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   3. Jeff Gordon, Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   4. Mike Skinner, Ford.
</P>
<P>
   5. Bobby Labonte, Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
