<HEADLINE>
GANSTER COMEDY `ANALYZE THIS' WHACKS BOX OFFICE COMPETITORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO -- &UR;  &LR; Moviegoers mobbed the nation's multiplexes for
gangster-comedy ``Analyze This'' as it dominated offerings with an
estimated $17.7 million at 2,518 theaters during the Friday-Sunday
period, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Warner Bros. release, starring Robert De Niro as a crime
boss seeking the aid of a psychiatrist played by Billy Crystal,
topped Hollywood's expectations and benefited from strong
word-of-mouth among moviegoers. Attendance jumped an impressive 55
percent from Friday's $5.15 million to Saturday's $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised that `Analyze This' did so well because it's
something of a dark comedy, which is not an easy sell,'' said movie
analyst Arthur Rockwell. ``Warner's marketing campaign was clearly
effective, because it obviously broadened the audience beyond
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell also noted that the success of ``Analyze This,'' which
received fairly positive reviews, came despite Crystal's lack of
drawing power in recent years. ``He can do well if he's in the
right kind of role, which is what happened here,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
credited the studio's strategy of showing sneak screenings during
the past two weekends. ``The sneaks really helped get the marketing
to work,'' he said, adding that ``Analyze This'' would probably
wind up grossing $55 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other opening, Sony's prep-school drama ``Cruel
Intentions'' with Sarah Michelle Gellar, finished a respectable
second with $13.2 million at 2,312 theaters although the total was
below projections made earlier this year. Bucksbaum predicted the
``Dangerous Liaisons'' update will take in $38 million overall _ a
solid return on a reported $10.5 million budget _ and noted that
``Intentions'' had to overcome an R rating and a marketplace that
has been saturated with films aimed at teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teen films that have been performing best are light
comedies like `She's All That,' &UR;  &LR; '' Bucksbaum said. `` &UR;  &LR; `Cruel
Intentions' may have been a little too sophisticated and dark for
young teen-age girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum noted that adult-oriented star-driven films, such as
``Analyze This,'' ``Payback,'' ``Message in a Bottle'' and ``8mm,''
have outperformed teen movies in recent weeks. ``There's been a
real resurgence in that part of the market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's second weekend of ``8mm'' lost slightly over half its
audience, finishing third with $7 million at 2,370 sites. ``Movies
of that genre usually lose their legs pretty quickly,'' Rockwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Disney's second weekend of romantic drama ``The
Other Sister'' held up moderately well with $5.6 million at 1,846
theaters as the studio added 503 screens. Paramount's fifth weekend
of ``Payback'' continued to draw respectably in fifth with $4.1
million at 2,855 theaters, going past $72 million overall as it
extended its lead as the top grosser of 1999 movies.
</P>
<P>
   Three films in their fourth weekends took the sixth, seventh and
eighth spots, led by Universal's ``October Sky'' with $3.7 million
at 1,695 theaters. It edged Disney's ``My Favorite Martian'' with
$3.6 million at 2,309 screens and Warner's ``Message in a Bottle''
with $3.4 million at 2,489 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's ``Shakespeare in Love'' finished ninth with $3.2
million at 1,721 theaters to push its 87-day total to nearly $65
million. ``Shakespeare'' continues to benefit from its 13 Academy
Award nominations and may still be in the top 10 when Oscars are
handed out March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's sixth weekend of ``She's All That'' continued to draw
respectably with $2.6 million at 1,865 theaters to top $57 million
overall, followed by its 20th weekend of ``Life Is Beautiful,''
which has seven Oscar nominations, with $2 million at 672
locations. ``Life'' has become the first foreign language movie to
go past $30 million in U.S. ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' ``Saving Private Ryan,'' with 11 Oscar nods, showed
it still has some drawing power with $1.2 million at 945 locations.
``Ryan'' has topped $207 million and holds the 23rd spot on the
all-time domestic chart.
</P>
<P>
   Gramercy racked up solid returns from its opening of ``Lock,
Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' with $144,000 at eight theaters.
The British comedy, made for a minuscule $1.6 million, has grossed
more than $20 million in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Overall grosses hit about $80 million, down about 8 percent from
the same weekend a year ago when the 12th weekend of ``Titanic''
led the box office. Year-to-date grosses have gone past $900
million, trailing the 1998 period by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Five new movies will open Friday, including 20th Century Fox's
action-adventure ``Wing Commander,'' Sony's drama ``Deep End of the
Ocean,'' MGM's horror-sequel ``The Rage: Carrie 2,'' Sony's comedy
``Baby Geniuses'' and New Line's police drama ``The Corruptor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wing Commander'' will be helped if a new trailer for ``Star
Wars Episode One: The Phantom Menace'' plays before it, as was
reported recently, but Fox has not confirmed those plans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
