<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SELMA-ANNIVERSARY-NYT     03-07 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELMA-ANNIVERSARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT SELMA ANNIVERSARY MARCH, A PLEA FOR INTERGRATED POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala. _ Each year on March 7, this tumbledown town comes
alive with the spirit of an instant in time, the beginning of the
end of American apartheid, when an Alabama state trooper cracked
John Lewis' skull.
</P>
<P>
   On March 7, 1965, the troopers and a racist posse attacked 600
black civil rights marchers on the Edmund Pettus Bridge over the
Alabama River, splitting flesh and bone with clubs, bullwhips,
rubber hoses wrapped with barbed wire. The attack shamed Congress
into guaranteeing black people the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The man at the head of that march was Lewis. Now a seven-term
U.S. representative from Georgia, he returned to the bridge Sunday
with 20 fellow members of Congress, Republicans and Democrats, who
joined several hundred Alabama residents to reenact the march.
Selma was the last stop on a two-day pilgrimage by bus to some of
the stations of the cross of civil rights: Birmingham, Montgomery,
Selma.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he was trying to make his colleagues feel the spirit
of the movement that transformed the law, and to start them talking
together about race and reconciliation _ or, for that matter,
talking together about anything.
</P>
<P>
   The House members say they spend less and less time speaking
with one another as they become more and more ideologically
segregated. Not even the chaplains of the Senate and House attract
politically integrated congressional congregants, members say.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, we really don't talk,'' said Lewis, 59.
``You can go days on end in Washington and never speak to another
member. In the House, most Republicans, as a rule, walk in on the
Republican side, and leave the same way,'' as do Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on Martin Luther King Jr. Street in Selma, Ray LaHood,
a Republican from Peoria, Ill., who gaveled Lewis to silence in the
divisive impeachment debate, said much the same about his
colleagues: ``They don't mix because they don't know each other.
They are separate. You don't know the people you're trying to make
laws with.''
</P>
<P>
   In a hotel by the Alabama River, once Selma's slave-trading
post, Rep. Fred Upton, a Republican from southwest Michigan, said:
``We don't know each other. There's not been a lot of dialogue
lately.''
</P>
<P>
   On a bus to Montgomery, Rep. Marion Berry, a Democrat from
northeastern Arkansas, and a farmer, said Congress is ``structured
to keep us apart.''
</P>
<P>
   And outside the 16th Street Baptist Church in Birmingham, where
four girls were murdered by a racist's bomb, Rep. Michael Forbes,
R-N.Y., said: ``It's gotten so bad, so partisan, so polarized.
That's why you have to have shared experiences, to blow away
preconceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the point, Lewis said: to show his colleagues a time
and place that changed Congress, in the hope it might change again.
On the bus from Birmingham to Montgomery, where, in 1961, Lewis,
then a 21-year-old Freedom Rider, was beaten for trying to
integrate interstate bus lines, Rep. Bob Filner of San Diego was
traveling through the past. He was a Freedom Rider, too. He and
Lewis are the only members of Congress to have served time at
Parchman Farm, the legendarily tough Mississippi State
Penitentiary. They were arrested for their civil rights activism by
lawmen commanded by G.V. (Sonny) Montgomery, who went on to serve
30 years in Congress before retiring in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been back here for 33 years,'' Filner said. ``When I
saw that the motorcycle cops escorting us out of Birmingham were
black, I thought: This place has changed. We changed American
history.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement did not transform Selma. ``It remains today what it
was back then, a sleepy, dying little Southern town,'' Lewis wrote
in his autobiography, ``Walking With the Wind'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1998). The races still do not mix much; few white people joined
today's parade. The mayor, Joe Smitherman, stayed away. He has been
mayor since 1964, and he stood with the troopers and the vigilantes
on the bridge as they savaged the marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Smitherman shares power with black people now, not always
easily. ``I was on the wrong side'' of the bridge, he said on
Saturday night in a speech at a dinner commemorating the march.
``I'm often on the wrong side now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, at a breakfast before the march, Rep. David E.
Bonior of Michigan, the House Democratic whip, said he felt ``a
magic, an essence'' emanating from the place. ``It radiates.''
</P>
<P>
   This radiance, said Coretta Scott King, King's widow, was the
light that shined through the civil rights movement. ``It was a
spiritual movement,'' she said at the breakfast. ``That same spirit
is available today. You just have to claim it.'' That reclamation,
she said, ``could bring about a transformation of the Congress that
is desperately needed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
