<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-ADVANCE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `A great day for Auburn,' bad day for the ACC
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was joy at Auburn and the SEC but anger
throughout the ACC Sunday as the 64-team field for the NCAA Men's
basketball tournament was announced in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing to Kentucky in Saturday's semifinals of the SEC
Tournament, Auburn (27-3) received the first No. 1 seed in school
history and is in the field for the first time since 1988. The
Tigers open the tournament Thursday against Winthrop, the Big South
Champ, in the first round of the South Regional in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous story and a great day for Auburn,'' said
coach Cliff Ellis. ``Our kids and our fans deserve this.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC got six teams (Auburn, Kentucky, Tennessee, Florida,
Arkansas, Ole Miss) with a seventh, Mississippi State, getting
passed over with a 20-12 record. The Big Ten led all conferences
with seven bids.
</P>
<P>
   History, the bad kind, was made in the ACC as for the first time
since 1980 it got only three teams in the tournament. Duke,
Maryland, and North Carolina were all top three seeds, but Wake
Forest (16-13) and N.C. State (18-13) were left out. Wake Forest,
which finished fourth in the ACC, lost its chance when it fell to
N.C. State in Friday's second round of the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people in the ACC are upset but once the automatic
entries are put in place, you have play your way in,'' said
Kentucky's C.M. Newton, the chairman of the NCAA selection
committee. ``I think it would have helped Wake Forest to win a game
in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament's other top seeds included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Duke (32-3), which brings a 27-game winning streak into
Friday's first round of the East Regional in Charlotte, where they
beat North Carolina 96-73 on Sunday for the ACC Tournament
championship. The Blue Devils will open against 16th-seeded Florida
A&AMP;M (12-18).
</P>
<P>
   _ UConn (28-2), which is the No. 1 seed in the West after
beating St. John's 82-63 for the Big East Tournament title. The
Huskies open with Texas-San Antonio on Thursday in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michigan State (29-4), which beat Illinois 67-50 win the Big
Ten Tournament final on Sunday. The Spartans, the top seed in the
Midwest, will open the tournament Friday in Milwaukee against Mount
St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland, Miami, Utah and Stanford were the No. 2 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (25-8), the defending national champions, drew a No. 3
seed in the Midwest Regional and will open the tournament Thursday
in New Orleans against New Mexico State, winners of the Big West
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other surprises from selection Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Alabama Birmingham (20-11), as the fourth team picked from
Conference USA. The Blazers had struggled down the stretch and lost
in the semifinals of the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   _ A No. 8 seed for the College of Charleston (28-2), despite a
25-game winning streak which includes a victory over North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   _ An at-large bid for New Mexico (23-7) despite an RPI of 86 and
a strength of schedule of 229.
</P>
<P>
   MEN'S TOURNAMENT
</P>
<P>
   _ TOP SEEDS: East _ Duke; South _ Auburn; Midwest _ Michigan
St.; West _ UConn.
</P>
<P>
   _ SEC: Arkansas (W4); Auburn (S1); Florida (W6); Kentucky (MW3);
Mississippi (MW9); Tennessee (E4).
</P>
<P>
   _ ACC: North Carolina (W3); Maryland (S2).
</P>
<P>
   _ UNLIKELIEST CINDERELLA: Florida A&AMP;M, the Mid-Eastern Athletic
Conference tournament champion, brings a 12-18 record. The Rattlers
would have to win the title to finish .500.
</P>
<P>
   _ KNOWING THE ROPES: North Carolina is making its 25th
consecutive appearance.
</P>
<P>
   _ CONFERENCE CALL: The Big Ten's seven entries are the most of
any conference.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S TOURNAMENT
</P>
<P>
   _ TOP SEEDS: East _ Tennessee Mideast _ Connecticut; Midwest _
Purdue; West _ Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   _ SEC: Alabama (MW5); Auburn (E5); Florida (MW11); Georgia
(ME3); Kentucky (W6); LSU (W4); Mississippi State (MW7).
</P>
<P>
   _ ACC: Clemson (ME2); Duke (E3); North Carolina (MW4); N.C.
State (MW10); Virginia (W9).
</P>
<P>
   _ ONE AND DONE?: Surprising Southern Conference tournament
champion Appalachian State (14-14) run may be short. The 16th seed
plays at three-time champion Tennessee in its opener.
</P>
<P>
   _ SAME OLD, SAME OLD: Should Tennessee and Louisiana Tech win
out, the 1998 finalists would meet in the title game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
