<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-CONFERENCE-720&AMP;     03-07 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-CONFERENCE-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: CARTER'S RETIREMENT IS A LIFE OF LEARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Jimmy Carter's latest book is ``The Virtues of
Aging'' (Ballantine, 1998), and in a speech at the American Society
on Aging's annual conference here, the 75-year-old former president
presented his personal list of those virtues, from time to learn
new things to grandchildren to a closer relationship with his wife,
Rosalynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become mountain climbers,'' said Carter, who was 56 when
he was voted out of the White House and into early retirement. At
64, he climbed to the top of Mount Kilimanjaro, he said. At 70, he
climbed Mount Fuji.
</P>
<P>
   From Orlando he planned to fly to Aspen to join his wife and
grandchildren on the ski slopes. ``I never saw skis till I was
62,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   He has learned how to write books, he said, and recently
embarked on his first novel. He makes furniture. He has mastered
the computer. ``We have tied our family together with e-mail,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the four-day conference, which was attended by
3,000 gerontologists, academics, nurses, social workers and others,
was a celebration of aging. As such, Carter, who looked fit and
younger than his years, was a fitting choice as the keynote
speaker, opening the event on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the conference workshops emphasized the importance of
relationships to the health and well-being of older people, and
Carter told the audience that he had taken particular satisfaction
in his marriage of nearly 53 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our love has deepened in many ways, including in physical
ways,'' Carter said. ``We have made a deliberate decision to do
more things together.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that while he and his wife had had difficult times in
their marriage, and plenty of arguments, they had learned to
forgive each other.
</P>
<P>
   He described one argument, not so long ago, that went on for
days. ``We could hardly speak to each other,'' he said. ``We wrote
ugly notes back and forth on our computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he said, he went to his woodworking shop and fashioned
a check out of a piece of walnut. ``I wrote on it: `This is good
for the rest of our lives for an apology or forgiveness, whichever
we prefer,''' he said. ``I signed it, and I gave it to Rosalynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``She uses it frequently,'' he added, to warm laughter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to exploring the opportunities of life, Carter said,
it is also necessary to think about the end of life. He talked
about his own family history in that regard. ``My father died of
pancreatic cancer,'' he said. ``My mother died of pancreatic
cancer. My older sister died of pancreatic cancer, as did my
youngest sister, as did my only brother. I'm the only one left.''
</P>
<P>
   All of his family members died at home, he said. ``They've not
been strangled by tubes.'' He said that he and his wife have signed
living wills stating that they do not want to be kept alive by
artificial means.
</P>
<P>
   If Carter is the embodiment of what is talked about these days
as successful aging, then what about people who cannot play tennis
and climb mountains? What about the frail elderly? Are they to be
viewed as failures at aging? If independence and autonomy are among
the highest American virtues, then how shall those who have no
choice but to depend on others be regarded?
</P>
<P>
   These were some of the questions posed by Mark H. Waymack, an
associate professor of philosophy and co-director of graduate
programs in health care at Loyola University, in a workshop called
``Dependency and the American Myth of Rugged Individualism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the theses of the new gerontology is that successful
aging is not an aging of dependency,'' Waymack said. ``You climb
mountains, play tennis, go hiking. I'm worried about the elderly
who are in nursing homes, or in home care, and who find it
difficult to get out of their homes because they're frail and
dependent. And they may be dependent in ways we can't change.'' He
also pointed out that money often buys health and independence.
</P>
<P>
   There have to be new models for what is regarded as successful
aging, Waymack said. ``What's wrong with being dependent?'' he
asked. ``We don't think it's shameful for children to be dependent.
Why do we then think it's shameful for adults to be dependent?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his lecture on creativity and aging, Gene Cohen, a
psychiatrist and gerontologist, quoted William Carlos Williams, who
wrote about ``an old age that adds as it takes away.''
</P>
<P>
   The poet was 79 when he published ``Pictures from Brueghel and
Other Poems,'' which won the Pulitzer prize, said Cohen, who is the
director of the Center on Aging, Health and Humanities at George
Washington University in Washington. Through his work at the
center, as well as that of a team of social workers in the
Washington area, Cohen said he had found astonishing painting,
sculpture and collages among elderly people who had never
considered themselves artists.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about a ``liberation phase,'' which can begin in the
mid-60s and 70s, and which can be demonstrated in everything from
social action to evolving family relationships _ both of which can
be creative, he said _ to painting and sculpture. ``Many people
feel free to do the right thing,'' he said.``They feel this
creative push to do what they might have done. If not now, when?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
