<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALVADOR-VOTE-550&AMP;ADD     03-07 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-VOTE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE CONSERVATIVE LEADS SALVADORAN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador _ A moderate candidate from the
governing conservative party led the voting Sunday in El Salvador's
second presidential election since the end of its civil war seven
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An early survey of voters leaving polling stations showed
Francisco Flores, the 39-year-old candidate of the governing
Nationalist Republican Alliance, with a comfortable lead over
Facundo Guardado, 44, his opponent from a coalition led by the
country's former guerrilla movement, the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front.
</P>
<P>
   Among five other candidates, Ruben Zamora, the FMLN presidential
candidate in the last election but now running under his own
Democratic Center Union, drew the third largest block of votes,
about 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout among 3.1 million registered voters appeared low after
an election campaign dominated by the grave problems that have
plagued El Salvador since its 12-year civil war ended, including
rampant crime, inflation and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Voter apathy, political analysts said, demonstrated a loss of
faith in the effectiveness of government since peace arrived in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that despite the end of the war, the fundamental
problems of the country have not been solved like they had
expected,'' said Jose Miguel Cruz, director of the Public Opinion
University Institute at the Central American University. ``They say
we've had war, elections, peace accords and more elections, and we
still have violence and problems of unemployment and poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous elections only half of the eligible voters cast
ballots. Two out of three Salvadorans had little or no interest in
this election, according to a survey last month by the Public
Opinion University Institute. The reasons, it found, ranged from
mistrust of politicians to skepticism that the vote would make a
difference in solving the country's problems or improving living
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But the disillusionment of Salvadorans was not enough to turn
voters away from the Nationalist Republican Alliance, or ARENA,
which suffered serious losses to the party of the former guerrillas
in municipal an legislative elections in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the polls opened Sunday, Flores, a conservative
economist and philosopher with a fresh face and no ties to the
civil war, was favored to win, though it was unclear whether he
would gain enough votes to avoid a run-off.
</P>
<P>
   The FMLN, after much infighting, had rejected broadening its
appeal and settled on Guardadoa, a leftist activist and moderate
ex-guerrilla commander who himself had pushed for the selection of
a centrist candidate from an allied party.
</P>
<P>
   Guardado's war credentials and Flores' resume, which includes
studies in Indian philosophy and a bachelor's degree in political
science from the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, seemed to
leave many voters unable to see an alternative beyond ARENA,
however dissatisfied they might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Francisco Flores seems to me more capable, better educated,''
said Raul Avila, 68, a tailor who said he has been held up twice in
recent years. ``No government is ideal but the hope we all have is
that he can begin solving the most serious problems of the
country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Avila voted at the fairgrounds here where 69,000 Salvadorans
were registered to vote and where throngs of voters filed into
cavernous pavilions Sunday morning to cast their ballots at
cardboard podiums.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the scene was festive, with food and drink vendors
hollering for business as voters came and went, many of them
wearing T-shirts, caps and hair ribbons with party colors and
honking their horns in electoral euphoria as they sat in heavy
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The elections were held on the eve of President Clinton's
four-day visit to Central America to survey the damage inflicted by
Hurricane Mitch late last year. His visit begins in Nicargua and El
Salvador Monday. Flags welcoming the ``Excelentisimo Senor
Presidente,'' the first U.S. president to visit El Salvador since
Lyndon B. Johnson stopped by in 1960s, have been up on major roads
here for days.
</P>
<P>
   At a press teleconference this week from Washington, Peter
Romero, the State Department's subsecretary for Western Hemisphere
affairs, said the president is also coming to celebrate the
region's democratic transformation after the civil wars of the
1980s and, particularly, the results of El Salvador's elections.
</P>
<P>
   That transformation would have been even more remarkable if the
FMLN, which the United States helped the government here fight
after El Salvador became a main Cold War battleground, had built on
previous electoral victories to take over power now.
</P>
<P>
   But after capturing the second largest bloc of legislative seats
and a large number of mayoral posts, including the capital, in
1997, internal divisions within the party reinforced feelings among
many voters that the ex-guerrillas were ill-prepared to govern as
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora, a social democrat and highly regarded intellectual, was
expected to capture much of the disaffected leftist vote.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ARENA, which was founded in the early 1980s by
leaders of El Salvador's right-wing death squads but has since
cultivated a moderate image, united after the losses of 1997 behind
Flores, a candidate known in the national assembly for building
consensus. He seemed to epitomize the party's message of
``renovation and openness.''
</P>
<P>
   He avoided personal attacks and campaigned on a platform of
bringing professionalism to the police force, reforming a corrupt
judicial system and generating jobs through increased foreign
investment and support of small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major change in ARENA is a change toward the common good,
the national good,'' Flores said in an interview Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Many Salvadorans, however, regard Flores as a question mark,
noting it remains to be seen whether he would still mainly respond
to economic sectors, such as banking, that benefit from ARENA
government policies.
</P>
<P>
   For most Salvadorans, the overriding issue in this election was
crime and unemployment and underemployment rates of 30 percent. The
``delinquency problem,'' as it is called here, is blamed on a
variety of factors, including the availability of arms left over
from the war and the loss of moral values.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
