   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, March 8. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Phoenix) - This column was originally suppos ed
to run last week, but since it's about National Procrastinati on
Week, it seems fitting. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the
``L'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ARPAIO (undated) Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio on Sunday
vehemently denied he's ordered deputies to tail his enemies, and
said he's ordered an internal investigation into the roots of the
allegation. The Arizona Republic reported Saturday that federal
investigators are probing whether Arpaio ordered surveillance on a
laundry list of foes, including Maricopa County Attorney Rick
Romley. ``This is ridiculous,'' Arpaio said. ``Its just a product
of vile and bizarre imagination.'' By RICHARD RUELAS. Move in `A'
category.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO (DENVER) When Rex Brown proposed a charter school in
the city's urban center, it wasn't state education officials he had
to win over. Or the community. Or the parents. He had to win over
the competition _ the public school district. Under Colorado law,
charters must petition public school districts for permission to
operate. The districts decide what charter schools can open within
their boundaries, what goals the charters must achieve, even how
the charters are to be funded. In Colorado, charter schools are a
small, controlled experiment. Their performances are analyzed each
year by the state education board, their licenses must be renewed
every three to five years, and only 60 can exist at any time. &UR; By
KELLY PEARCE. Move in `A' category.
</P>
<P>
   W/COLOSIDE (CASTLE ROCK, Colo. &UR; )In 1993, the Douglas County
Schools became the first Colorado district to approve a charter
school, Academy Charter. &UR; . It wasn't easy, said Melinda Windler,
one of the parents who put together the 600-page proposal. ``Most
people starting a school don't have any experience in running
schools,'' she said. ``It's impossible to do it alone.'' Since
then, five other charter schools _ including one that secured
enough money to build its own facility _ have sprouted in this
hilly, picturesque region where homes in the shadow of the Rocky
Mountains are big and filled with professionals who work just up
the interstate in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   SEDONA (SEDONA) For $1, you could have had your name in the
movies. Selling screen time for a buck was one ingenious method
that indie filmmaker Allan Piper used to raise money for Starving
Artists, the comedy he wrote, directed, produced, edited and stars
in. Piper, of Boston, and other independent filmmakers from around
the world gathered in Sedona over the weekend, where they shared
the movies they risked fortune and sanity to make with 1,200 movie
lovers during the fifth annual Sedona Film Festival. &UR; By BOB
FENSTER. Move in 'A' category.
</P>
