<SLUG> BC-BBO-ORIOLES-CUBANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA-BOUND OWNER OF ORIOLES WANTS TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Angelos has spent several years trying to take his
Baltimore Orioles to Cuba, and now that he has succeeded in
arranging a game there, he wants to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' the team's owner said Sunday when asked if the
Orioles would take their regulars. ``They're a pretty formidable
opponent. While we wish them all the best, we don't want to lose.
We want to make our best effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement reached Saturday evening in a meeting that
included representatives of the State Department and the Cuban
government, the Orioles will play the Cuban national team March 28,
although a slight possibility remains that the game could be March
27.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans then will visit Baltimore for a game whose date will
be determined this week when a delegation from Major League
Baseball travels to Cuba to make final arrangements for the game
there. The game at Camden Yards will be played on April 3, the day
before the season opens, if logistics can be worked out, or on
April 26 or May 3, which would make it an in-season exhibition
game.
</P>
<P>
   The second game was critical to the first because without it,
the players association would not have approved the Havana game, a
union official said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Angelos wants to win the games, he said the outcome was
not of paramount importance. ``Ultimately, who wins and loses is
not the important thing,'' the owner said by telephone from
Baltimore. ``The key is the contact and establishing a better
understanding and atmosphere of friendship between the people of
both countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone feels that way. More than 70 Cuban exiles
demonstrated Sunday at Fort Lauderdale Stadium, the Orioles' spring
training base, before and during an exhibition game with the
Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to Cuba under the current conditions there is a sign of
insensitivity and lack of respect for human rights there,'' said
Huber Matos, a native of Cuba who spent 20 years in prison for
opposing Fidel Castro's government. ``It's like taking part in the
abuses that are going on there.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig, in Tampa, Fla., at an exhibition game
between the New York Yankees and the Minnesota Twins, said he was
sensitive to the concerns of people opposed to the Orioles' trip.
He added, ``Given the advice we've gotten from the State
Department, we're very excited about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of all factions needed 12 hours of meetings in
Washington on Friday and Saturday to resolve the remaining
roadblocks to the games. The primary issue, the proceeds of the
games, was settled with the understanding that if there are any
proceeds, they would be used for endeavors related to sports,
chiefly baseball.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the negotiations credited Sandy Berger,
President Clinton's national security adviser, and Wendy Sherman of
the State Department with helping get the matters resolved. Neither
attended the meetings, but they contributed by telephone, Sherman
from Beijing last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government has agreed to several changes at the
stadium where the Havana game will be played. Padding will be added
to the outfield fences, and temporary dressing facilities will be
built because the stadium has no locker rooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2114EST &QL; 
