A1066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GEORGE-ATWATER-NY     03-07 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE-ATWATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATWATER THE SUPER BOWL SAFETY WHO FELL TO EARTH
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is not likely to openly display selfishness or to rant, rave
or pout when things go sour. No, Steve Atwater offered a convincing
performance while the Denver Broncos were winning the last two
Super Bowls. All the while, Atwater was slipping in stature among
his coaches and was toiling in an unusual, personal mix of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The team was winning championships.
</P>
<P>
   But Atwater's role at safety was different, reduced.
</P>
<P>
   His coaches said he was slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was, but from what level? From superior to great? After
all, he was still making game-swinging plays. He had also earned
his eighth Pro Bowl selection last season.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 seasons Atwater had played safety for Denver in a
physical and nasty style, and then last year the Denver coaches
asked him late in the season to sit on third-down plays. They told
him that he looked slower, that his quick bursts had waned.
Atwater's heart sank, but he did not show it. He was bruised, but
hid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' Atwater said, ``they asked me in two or three
games for four or five series to sit down on third-down plays, and
I didn't understand why. I kept asking and they finally told me it
was to increase my efficiency. I really didn't buy into that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the end of the year and throughout the playoffs, it
stopped, but even then, I was not happy in the defense. We've been
running the type of defense in the last two years where I play more
the role of a cornerback and the cornerback plays more the role of
the safety. And then when I roll up to the cornerback slot, teams
would often run the other way. I just wasn't getting to play around
the ball enough. Other guys were making plays and I was happy for
them. But I'm used to being in the game more, getting a chance to
make more plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, how can you complain? It was working. We won two Super
Bowls. So, unselfishly, for the team, it was great and we were
champions. But selfishly, it was a system where I felt I was going
to waste. I was very unhappy. Really, if the Broncos had asked me
back, I'm not sure I would have wanted to come back to that. I
really might have been ready to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Retire at age 32 after so many operations on his knees and
shoulders, even after the shots of morphine for two straight weeks
last season to keep dealing with the pain? Retire because the
Broncos saw younger players as being on the cutting edge and
Atwater as on the edge of a cliff ready to plunge, not at all worth
the $2.6 million he was scheduled to earn in 1999 from the Broncos?
</P>
<P>
   Atwater would not have to retire. Nearly three weeks ago, he was
cut. See you. The Broncos said they were doing him a favor, letting
him go early so he could sign with another team while free-agent
money was still floating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like someone saying, `You're fired and it's a favor,'''
Atwater said, bemused. ``The day I got the word was the night
before my grandmother's funeral in Mississippi. I got six messages
to call my agent. I knew. I called him back and said, `OK, where
are we going?'''
</P>
<P>
   To the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos cut Atwater loose because they believe he is about
to plummet toward his football finish. The Jets wrapped their arms
around all 6 feet 3 inches and 217 pounds of him because they
believe he is a player who will bring them savvy, toughness,
experience and championship mettle along with his reputation as
football's biggest hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos see bone.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets see meat.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Atwater never plays a down for the Jets, he helps them
immensely in two ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, he becomes an important example of the dedication and
desire required to win championships. Atwater is pure pro. The way
he practices, prepares and handles himself on and off the field
will be a joy for Jets players and coaches to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Second, recall that Denver beat the Jets in the American
Football Conference championship game. Denver is the hunted. What
better way to gain insight on the team to topple than by signing
one if its smartest and most mature players? Atwater will help the
Jets understand techniques about how to beat Denver in ways that
few could. He gives them the blueprint, the floor plan, the
combination, the key.
</P>
<P>
   A prime example? An insightful scout? Atwater plans on being
much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have played the last two years hurt, especially with my
shoulders and the knee,'' he said. ``I haven't been able to
practice or play the way that I can. I made the Pro Bowl last year,
but that is not how I gauge myself. I can play better and do more.
I'm sure of it. I'm healthy and I'm ready. And now I'm challenged
to go out there are prove it to myself and earn the respect of my
new coaches and teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   And earn more from the old ones, too.
</P>
<P>
   The new, shiny Bronco is Dale Carter, a free-agent signee at
cornerback from Kansas City. The present and future for the Broncos
also includes the young players Tori Noel at cornerback/safety and
George Coghill at safety.
</P>
<P>
   Atwater said: ``In the back of my mind, after the way things
were going last year, I kind of had the feeling that Denver was
going to let me go. I did not shed a tear. I'm not bitter. In this
era of free agency nowadays, most guys don't get to stay with a
team for 10 years. I was lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   And happy now. Happy to land with the Jets. A new start, a new
chance. He will be appreciated anew. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He will still be appreciated in Denver, too, where the Broncos
say that Atwater will most likely one day be placed in the team's
Ring of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   A shove out the door _ with love.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 10 years in Denver, I will miss my friends, my teammates
and some of my coaches,'' Atwater said. ``But I'm going to a place
where they are going to use me in the role of a traditional safety
and where Coach Bill Parcells and the Jets are known for being
rough and expecting a lot. That kind of stuff fires me up _ as long
as you tell it like it is.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
