<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VAN HORN CAUGHT IN THE NETS' VORTEX
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Out of a useless timeout 27.1 seconds from the end of
a hopeless game, the ball found Keith Van Horn, way out in the
right corner where the baseline and sideline meet, and from where
an offensive player has nowhere to go. Metaphorically, this is also
where the New Jersey Nets happen to be, about as far away from
where they thought they were headed, their hopes for a turnaround
in a season stuck on fast forward suddenly reduced to a wing and a
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   From the corner, his back to the basket, Van Horn rotated on
long, tired legs for a wild 3-point try that Larry Johnson, who is
about 4 inches smaller, pinned back against his hands. A clean
stuff, the final slur in another foul day in an increasingly
obscene season for the Nets' franchise player.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no franchise players on a team that's 3-13,'' Van Horn
said sadly in the Nets' locker room, offering profundity where not
long ago there was so much promise.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, now operating on a whole different plane of
expectation, broke in similarly, 14 years ago. Ewing started with a
bad, injury-wracked New York Knicks team and an overbearing coach
named Hubie Brown. It didn't take long before the practice of
dwelling on what Ewing couldn't do as opposed to what he could do
became something of a pastime in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd come out and there'd be Patrick and guys like Louis Orr
and Trent Tucker,'' said Herb Williams, omitting the likes of Ken
Bannister and Eddie Wilkins from those old Knicks-Indiana Pacers
games. ``We'd swarm Patrick with three, four guys. When you have a
star player who doesn't have the right people around him, it's hard
for him to be the star.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the hardest lesson for a man who carries the weight of a
NBA team that is sinking fast. The 22 points and 16 rebounds
produced by Van Horn in the Ewing-dominated 97-86 Knicks' victory
Sunday at Madison Square Garden would not define his afternoon's
work as much as his 16 missed shots, his inability to rise in the
closing moments and a costly turnover as he passed cross court out
of a double team on the left post with the Nets down a doable five.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not college any more,'' said Van Horn's protector,
Jayson Williams, who needs a legitimate center as a guardian for
himself, now that Rony Seikaly has beamed back to his usual
outpost, the injured list. ``You're not going to win your whole
career. Michael Jordan didn't win his whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan never lost this way, though, not even when his supporting
cast was more nightmare than Jordanaire. Van Horn is no heir to
Jordan, but nor was he supposed to be an Iverson or a Webber, the
young bull in a china shop, the centerpiece of a breakable team.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn and Tim Duncan were hailed as exceptions to the rule,
mature four-year college players lucky enough to land as rookies
last season where there was help. Now Duncan struggles with a
strangely disappointing San Antonio team, while Van Horn strokes
his goatee more than he does his jumper, as he ponders a season
riding, in part, on players named Doug Overton and Damon Jones.
</P>
<P>
   He tries to maintain a semblance of calm amidst the dissension
and chaos that such underachievement begets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's upsetting and frustrating and we get mad at each other,''
said Van Horn, who finds himself the middle man between the jittery
John Calipari and the coach's physically banged-up and emotionally
worn-down troops.
</P>
<P>
   He took it upon himself to sit down with Calipari last week,
after a rock-bottom defeat to Charlotte. Someone asked Sunday if he
had called for management to be patient, and he shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never once talked to Cal about keeping the team together,''
Van Horn said. ``I asked him to keep us together, to make sure our
heads stay in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   This is no job for a player whose professional career has not
yet reached 100 games, whose life has been made tough enough by the
loss of the injured Sam Cassell. The peculiarly sassy point guard
was the Nets' creative eye, the difference for Van Horn and Kerry
Kittles between shots in the flow and those painfully contrived _
like Van Horn's blind, spinning adventure right into the Knicks'
defense with the Nets trailing by 85-80.
</P>
<P>
   He missed, badly, and on the Nets' next possession came the
aforementioned Van Horn turnover out of the double team. Then Allan
Houston scored, and Johnson successfully posted up Van Horn, and
the outcome was guaranteed. As was another night for Van Horn to
dwell on inadequacies, not assets.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't muscle Johnson on defense, couldn't create for
others on offense. Ewing, with 30 points, nine rebounds and four
blocked shots, didn't have to make a game-winning shot to beat the
Nets. For this day, he was the franchise player, the one, true
thing. There is no equivalent on a 3-13 team, and those with the
potential often start to wonder if they could become one someplace
else. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
