<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1078 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     03-07 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEL FREE TO READ THIS . . . SOMETIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The original plan was to write a column about National
Procrastination Week last week, when it was observed. But one thing
and another came up and . . . well, here we are.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shame in procrastination. Serious procrastinators are
actually optimists in lazy clothing. If you continually put things
off until tomorrow, you assume that there is always going to be a
tomorrow. There's a comfort there.
</P>
<P>
   ``With procrastinators, there generally is a tomorrow,'' Les
Waas said. ``They seem to live longer than those people who are
anticrastinators (cool word; he made it up). They are the people
who are literally rushing through life. They rush into their graves
because they're uptight all the time, doing too much, more than
they have time to do, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   He would know. Waas, a semiretired advertising executive who
lives in Bryn Athyn, Pa., is the president of the Procrastinators
Club of America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was elected president in 1956,'' when the club was founded,
he said. ``The nominating committee still hasn't reported back for
1957.''
</P>
<P>
   Ba-da-boom. Waas is one of those people who should have a
drummer on hand for all his conversations. For instance, ask him
how one joins his august group, and he replies, ``Very slowly, of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Or listen to him talk about club membership:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have half a million members in the U.S. alone who haven't
gotten around to joining yet,'' he said. ``We have 14,000
card-carrying members. I don't know what their hurry was.'' &QL; 
The week that
</P>
<P>
   Forget Procrastination Week. To hear Waas talk about
procrastination, it's clear that, for most of us, it's a year-round
activity, even if some of us won't admit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do two things at a time,'' Waas said. ``That means
everybody's a procrastinator because anytime you're doing
something, you're putting off 100 other things.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right, sort of. We all procrastinate on some level. Got a
leaky faucet you've been promising you'd fix? Well? What's stopping
you? I'm sure you're going to get to it right away, just as soon as
you finish your coffee and . . . hey, that ``Today'' show interview
with an expert on aging explaining how to keep dentures in pristine
shape looks good. The leaky faucet will wait.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's bigger than that. We live in a city, after all,
that managed to put off building a manageable freeway system until
so many people lived here that now, as soon as a new road is
finished, it's instantly choked with so much stop-and-go traffic
that a 3-year-old riding backward on a tricycle could get home
faster during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has something else to do. But don't confuse
procrastination with dereliction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Procrastination is simply putting something off,'' Waas said.
``That means you do it. You just don't do it now. What we do is
wait till the last minute to do something. Then we have all that
time up front.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you do with the time?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything you want to,'' Waas said. ``If you want to go to the
movies, take a vacation, smell the flowers, you have time to do it.
That's what's important in life. Life isn't about working 20 hours
a day.'' &QL; 
You can join whenever
</P>
<P>
   Some would say he's right _ there are 24 hours in a day; if
you're working only 20, you're wasting four. Waas happily begs to
differ.
</P>
<P>
   And at 77, he's hoping he's right about all this. He's working
on the Big Procrastinate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to put off demise for as long as I can,'' he said.
``I'd like to be the last one out.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you do want to join the Procrastinators Club,
send $21 to P.O. Box 712, Bryn Athyn, PA 19009. That'll get you a
lifetime membership. (``It wasn't supposed to be that way,'' Waas
said. ``It was supposed to be $5 a year. But we had a
procrastinator who was our treasurer. By the time he got all the
work done, everyone had moved.'')
</P>
<P>
   No hurry, though. It'll wait. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
