<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC gets 6, ACC only 3
 &HT;    (EDS: Updated version _ please use.)
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was joy at Auburn and the SEC but anger in the ACC on
Sunday as the 64-team field for the NCAA Tournament was announced
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing to Kentucky in the semifinals of the SEC
Tournament, Auburn (27-3) received the first No. 1 seed in school
history. The Tigers open Thursday against Winthrop, the Big South
champion, in the South Regional in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Six SEC teams (Auburn, Kentucky, Tennessee, Florida, Arkansas
and Mississippi) made the field, while a seventh, Mississippi
State, was passed over despite a 20-12 record. The Big Ten led all
conferences with seven teams.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC got only three teams in the tournament for the first
time since 1980. Duke, Maryland and North Carolina were top-three
seeds, but Wake Forest (16-13) and N.C. State (18-13) were left
out. Wake, which finished fourth in the ACC, lost its chance when
it fell to N.C. State in the second round of the conference
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people in the ACC are upset, but once the automatic
entries are put in place, you have to play your way in,'' said
Kentucky's C.M. Newton, chairman of the NCAA selection committee.
``I think it would have helped Wake Forest to win a game in the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The other top seeds:
</P>
<P>
   _ Duke (32-3), which brings a 27-game winning streak into
Friday's first round of the East Regional in Charlotte, where it
beat North Carolina 96-73 Sunday in the ACC final. The Blue Devils
will open against 16th-seeded Florida A&AMP;M (12-18).
</P>
<P>
   _ Connecticut (28-2), which is the No. 1 seed in the West after
beating St. John's 82-63 for the Big East title. The Huskies open
with Texas-San Antonio on Thursday in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michigan State (29-4), which beat Illinois 67-50 win the Big
Ten final Sunday. The Spartans, top seed in the Midwest, open
Friday in Milwaukee against Mount St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland, Miami, Utah and Stanford were the No. 2 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (25-8), the defending national champion, drew a No. 3
seed in the Midwest and will open Thursday in New Orleans vs. New
Mexico State.
</P>
<P>
   MEN'S TOURNAMENT
</P>
<P>
   _ TOP SEEDS: East _ Duke; South _ Auburn; Midwest _ Michigan
St.; West _ UConn.
</P>
<P>
   _ SEC: Arkansas (W4), Auburn (S1), Florida (W6), Kentucky (MW3),
Mississippi (MW9), Tennessee (E4).
</P>
<P>
   _ ACC: Duke (E1), North Carolina (W3), Maryland (S2).
</P>
<P>
   _ UNLIKELIEST CINDERELLA: Florida A&AMP;M, the Mid-Eastern Athletic
Conference tournament champion, owns a 12-18 record. The Rattlers
would have to win the title to finish .500.
</P>
<P>
   _ KNOWING THE ROPES: North Carolina is making its 25th
consecutive appearance.
</P>
<P>
   _ CONFERENCE CALL: The Big Ten's seven entries are the most of
any conference.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S TOURNAMENT
</P>
<P>
   _ TOP SEEDS: East _ Tennessee Mideast _ Connecticut; Midwest _
Purdue; West _ Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   _ SEC: Alabama (MW5), Auburn (E5), Florida (MW11), Georgia
(ME3), Kentucky (W6), LSU (W4), Mississippi State (MW7).
</P>
<P>
   _ ACC: Clemson (ME2), Duke (E3), North Carolina (MW4), N.C.
State (MW10), Virginia (W9).
</P>
<P>
   _ ONE AND DONE? Surprising Southern Conference tournament
champion Appalachian State's (14-14) run may be short. The 16th
seed plays at three-time champion Tennessee in its opener.
</P>
<P>
   _ SAME OLD, SAME OLD: Should Tennessee and Louisiana Tech win
out, the 1998 finalists would meet in the title game.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
