<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC makes history with 8 teams in field
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEC coaches have been griping for years that they don't get
enough NCAA Tournament teams, even though every year they get more
than any other conference. On Sunday afternoon, however, they got a
pleasant surprise that broke new ground.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in NCAA women's tournament history, a single
conference, the SEC, will be represented by eight teams. Florida
(19-13), which finished 6-8 in SEC play, also became the first
women's team ever to be selected with a losing conference record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've understood for a long time that it's the best conference
in the country,'' Georgia coach Andy Landers said. ``Getting eight
is a compliment to all the coaches and players in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC also got three teams among the Top 16 seeds, one of them
being Georgia, the No. 3 seed in the Mideast. Second-ranked
Tennessee is the No. 1 seed in the East, while LSU, which toppled
the Lady Volunteers two weeks ago, is No. 4 in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Seven SEC teams finished at .500 or above in conference games,
but the selection of Florida reflects the NCAA women's basketball
committee's objective of choosing what it considered the best
teams. The Lady Gators also had a losing record in February, but
their win total and an RPI of 24 pushed them into the bracket as
the No. 11 seed in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had 19 wins in the No. 1-ranked conference in the
country,'' NCAA women's basketball committee chairwoman Bernadette
McGlade said. ``That's a pretty good season that most teams in the
country would take.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has had seven teams qualify two other times, but getting
eight usually has been viewed as a stretch. Mississippi State, the
only SEC team never to get invited, was made a No. 7 seed in the
Midwest. Auburn and Alabama got No. 5 seeds in the East and
Midwest, respectively, and Kentucky is the No. 6 seed in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time defending NCAA champion Tennessee (28-2) is the No. 1
seed in the East. But the Lady Vols have had several close calls
this year in trying to follow last year's 39-0 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Tennessee team that takes the court in March is expected
to win,'' said senior point guard Kellie Jolly. ``We're probably
not as much of a favorite as we were last year but we're still a
threat. And we know people are going to be out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Purdue is the No. 1 seed in the Midwest, while No. 3
Louisiana Tech got the top seed in the West. Connecticut took the
final No. 1 seed and was assigned to the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   The second seed there is Clemson, which won the ACC Tournament
and drew the highest NCAA seed in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC and Big 12 each got five teams in.Regular-season
champion Duke is No. 3 in the East and North Carolina is No. 4 in
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Other firsts included multiple berths for two minor conferences.
Even though Maine and Santa Clara lost in their conference
tournaments in the American East and West Coast, respectively, they
were included because of high RPI numbers. Conversely, the Big 10
and Pac 10, which usually send five teams each, were held to four
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried not to worry about what everyone would say and tried
to put the best teams in the tournament,'' McGlade said. ``There
were some good teams that didn't get in because there were only
four places. The 64th team this year is much stronger than it was
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   There are seven teams making their first NCAA appearances,
including Cal State-Northridge, winner of the Big Sky Conference.
The Matadors have played this season under an interim coach after
their former coach was charged with drug trafficking in October.
</P>
<P>
   There are no losing teams among the group of 64, but Appalachian
State evened its record at 14-14 by winning the Southern Conference
tournament. For their troubles, the Lady Mountaineers get to play
Tennessee Saturday in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
