<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-CHURCH-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BUILDING IS NEW, THE IDEALS AREN'T, AT KING'S HOME CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With a short walk across Auburn Avenue Sunday, the
faithful members of Ebenezer Baptist Church left the cramped
sanctuary where the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. had preached
his gospel of nonviolence, and consecrated an airy new church that
they dedicated to the legacy of his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   It took more than 11 years of planning, fund raising and
construction to enable the congregants to take their brief journey
from a farewell service in their old church to the ribbon-cutting
of their new one. Many acknowledged that they felt conflicting
emotions as they left behind the bittersweet history of the simple
sanctuary where King, his father, and his maternal grandfather all
preached, where King's funeral was held, and where his mother was
killed by a deranged gunman.
</P>
<P>
   But as the procession crossed the street, led by young girls
dressed in white gowns with angels' wings, any misgivings seemed to
dissolve. The congregants settled into their new pews, with King's
sister, Christine King Farris, taking a seat in the fourth row. The
110 members of the choir, their shoulders draped with scarves of
kinte cloth, tested the acoustics by belting out ``We Have Come
Into This House.'' The Rev. Joseph L. Roberts Jr. used a rousing
sermon to emphasize that his church was making a statement by
staying in a struggling inner-city neighborhood rather than fleeing
with other churches to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we could have moved away,'' Roberts shouted in a resonant
baritone. ``Yes, we could have gone to the suburbs. But this is the
place for which Christ died.''
</P>
<P>
   After trying a particularly athletic riff behind his new
lectern, completed with a gyrating twirl, the 60-year-old Roberts
smiled with satisfaction at his preacher's version of a zero-to-60
test drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to like this place,'' he said, as his parishioners
chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for Ebenezer's move was the need for more
space. Each year, 500,000 tourists visit the church, many for
Sunday services, and members and visitors often struggle to squeeze
into 750 seats. The new $8 million sanctuary seats more than 1,700.
</P>
<P>
   But the move also holds great promise for preservation and the
development of Atlanta's King historic district into a significant
tourist attraction. The original church will be leased by the
National Park Service, which plans to spend $2 million to restore
the building and use it for daily programs about the history of
Ebenezer and the role of the black church in the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the latest effort by the park service to broaden the
appeal of the district, which includes King's birth home, his
crypt, a visitor's center, a firehouse and the Martin Luther King
Jr. Center for Nonviolent Social Change. The park service is
negotiating with the King family to buy the King Center and the
house where King lived as an adult, as well as a large number of
artifacts, including clothing and the funeral wagon that carried
his casket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredible opportunity for us to tell the story,''
said Frank Catroppa, superintendent of the Martin Luther King Jr.
National Historic Site.
</P>
<P>
   For most of King's life, Ebenezer Baptist Church was home. His
grandfather, the Rev. A.D. Williams, Ebenezer's second pastor,
built the modest red-brick church, which was completed in 1922. His
father, the Rev. Martin Luther King Sr., succeeded Williams as
pastor in 1931. After beginning his ministerial career in
Montgomery, Ala., Martin Luther King Jr. joined Ebenezer as
co-pastor in 1960 and remained in that position until his
assassination in April 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Historians who have studied King's preaching at Ebenezer detect
an unusual sense of calm and comfort in his voice. He was more
relaxed and self-revealing there, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whenever Martin Luther King Jr. came back to Ebenezer
it was like returning to the bosom of a community that had nurtured
him and supported him throughout his whole life,'' said Richard A.
Lischer, a professor of homiletics at Duke University and the
author of ``The Preacher King'' (Oxford University Press, 1995).
``I've listened to many tapes of King preaching in Ebenezer, and
there's always this great sense of weariness from all the travel
and struggle, and yet there is this tremendous sense of relief that
is audible in his voice.''
</P>
<P>
   King delivered his first and last sermons at Ebenezer, and
old-timers still recall the Sunday mornings when the young preacher
sought to stir the crowd with sophisticated oratory while his
father, seated behind him, implored him to ``make it plain, M.L.,
make it plain.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-CHURCH-ART-2NDTA     03-07 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-CHURCH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ATLANTA: it plain.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They also recall the unimaginable day in 1974, six years after
King's assassination, when Marcus Wayne Chenault Jr. entered the
church with two pistols and began firing, killing a deacon and
King's mother, Alberta Williams King, as she sat at the organ
playing ``The Lord's Prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The old Ebenezer, which will be called the Heritage Sanctuary,
is not a fancy church, a point of some pride for longtime members
who remember its working-class origins. Its exterior is advertised
with a simple neon cross, and the interior, with its sagging
balcony and peeling paint, is overwhelmed by the brilliant burgundy
of its carpeting, pew cushions and baptismal drapery.
</P>
<P>
   Ebenezer always has been the kind of church where members will
pointedly hand an open hymnal to visitors who dare not join in the
singing. Its leaders boast not just of its history, but of its
continued commitment to social justice through youth mentoring
programs and a food co-operative.
</P>
<P>
   The striking new building, which will be called the Horizon
Sanctuary, is set diagonally to Auburn Avenue so that its axis
travels through King's crypt. The architects, the Atlanta husband
and wife team of William J. Stanley III and Ivenue Love-Stanley,
gave the church a conical shape that resembles a ram's horn. Its
stepped, arched roof, overlaid in copper, is intended to recall an
African hut, and an adjacent bell tower is patterned after an
African obelisk.
</P>
<P>
   Stained glass windows, which have yet to be designed, will trace
the passage of Africans to the United States and their progress
from slavery to civil rights. Roberts is particularly eager for the
installation of a mosaic that will depict ``a Jesus of a darker
hue'' than the white image in stained glass over the altar of the
Heritage Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Ebenezer searched for years for a site for its new building, and
ultimately found an ideal solution through a three-way deal. The
city of Atlanta gave the National Park Service a piece of land
directly across the street from the old church, and the Park
Service then gave part of the parcel to the church in exchange for
a 99-year lease on the Heritage Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Although 96 percent of the church's approximately 1,600 members
now live outside the Sweet Auburn neighborhood, which was a black
commercial center in segregated Atlanta, Roberts stressed that it
was vital for Ebenezer's ministry to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King never ran to the suburbs,'' Roberts
preached. ``Martin Luther King didn't stay in the Peabody Hotel but
in the Lorraine Motel,'' he said referring to a luxury hotel in
Memphis and the motel at which he was staying when he was
assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King didn't stay with the high and mighty, but
in his death he identified with garbage workers. If we're ever
going to make our society better we've got to stop running away
from our problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
