<HEADLINE>
CATCHERS TO SHARE STARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ One of the Angels' most pressing questions this
spring involves the catching situation. It seems the Angels will
not have a designated everyday catcher, instead dividing the duties
among three.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are hoping Todd Greene, depending on the health of
his surgically repaired right shoulder, will be able to catch two
or three times a week. Matt Walbeck, who signed a two-year contract
during the off-season, will get his share of starts behind the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining starts will go either to veteran Charlie O'Brien
or Phil Nevin, who can also play first and third base but only
began catching two years ago. One will make the team, the other
won't.
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck, who hit .257 in 108 games for the Angels last year,
says the foursome doesn't talk about the situation among
themselves, but they get along well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things you don't have control over,'' he
said. ``It's a lot of wasted emotion to talk about it or even think
about it. With Todd's situation, he hasn't caught much and it will
be difficult to jump right in there. So we all have to be able to
step in and do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, 37, is the best at throwing out potential basestealers
and calling a game. In other words, he's a pitcher's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can catch,'' manager Terry Collins said. ``He also has a
plan of what he wants to do. He's one of those guys who knows what
he does best and makes sure that stays sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Scratches: First baseman Mo Vaughn and third baseman Dave
Hollins were scratched from Sunday's game just before game time,
partly because of the weather conditions _ cool and light rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo's legs are real tight,'' Collins said. ``All of a sudden it
got so cold and they tightened up again.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins participated in a strenuous throwing workout with coach
Larry Bowa on Saturday, and his arm was too sore to play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   __ First look at Belcher: Pitcher Tim Belcher made his debut in
an Angels uniform Sunday afternoon in the Angels' 9-8 win over the
Oakland A's at Tempe Diablo Stadium. He went 22/3 innings, allowing
five runs (all earned) and four hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically I felt really good; the ball was jumping out of my
hand a lot better,'' he said. ``You hope the results follow, but if
they don't, you try not to dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels won the game in the 10th inning on Keith Luuloa's
two-out RBI single, scoring Steve Decker from second base. Jim
Edmonds, Chris Pritchett, Tim Salmon and Jeff Huson each had two
hits for the Angels. Salmon also hit his second homer of the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   __ Appier available:A former teammate of Belcher's in Kansas
City, Kevin Appier, is on the trading block. And Belcher said he
believes Appier, 31 and coming back from arm surgery, could help
any team, including the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't hesitate to add him to this club,'' Belcher said of
the former Antelope Valley High and Antelope Valley College star.
``If he's healthy, he could put someone over the top. Having said
that, I'm not saying we NEED someone like him.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels currently have Omar Olivares, Jason Dickson and
Jarrod Washburn competing for the No. 5 spot in the starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   __ Next: The Angels travel to Peoria, Ariz., to play the
Mariners today at 12:05 p.m. Ken Hill will start for the Angels
against the Mariners' Jeff Fassero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
