u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-07 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THAT MARCH RITUAL REACHES 60 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the nation's most compelling sports rituals was set in
motion Sunday: 64 Division I men's college basketball teams set
sail for four regions where they will begin the pursuit of a
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   This year is the 60th anniversary of the annual rite called
March Madness. In 1939 the University of Oregon defeated Ohio State
University in the championship game of the first tournament. That
tournament was sponsored by the National Association of Basketball
Coaches, who turned it over to the National Collegiate Athletic
Association after the tournament lost $2,531. In the intervening
years it has grown from eight teams in two divisions to 64 teams in
four regions. The tournament has introduced a vocabulary of its
own, with terms such as ``ratings percentage index'' and ``on the
bubble'' assuming as much significance as ``pick and roll'' and
``give and go.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the tournaments has had its own character. Some were
characterized by sensational runs of upsets. In 1963 _ in the
pre-robber baron era of college basketball when it was possible for
an underdog to actually win _tiny Loyola upset the two-time
defending champion, Cincinnati, in overtime. In the late '60s and
'70s, on the other hand, the tournament was known as the UCLA
Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   This year the tournament has the traditional plots and subplots.
The tone was set on Saturday when Lamar Odom's long, arduous fight
to play college basketball paid off in dramatic fashion, with his
game-winning shot sending Rhode Island into the tournament for the
second straight season. After first signing with Nevada-Las Vegas,
Odom decided to transfer to Rhode Island after being accused, with
others, of cheating on tests. He finally won his fight to prove he
qualified legitimately, but missed a year of basketball. After the
game Saturday, a tearful Odom said: ``I just know that everything
that I was going through was the past. I just knew my day would
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Tears. The tournament always offers plenty of tears. Last year
Coach Jim Harrick was seconds away from taking Rhode Island to the
first Final Four in school history when his team crumbled before
his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   For all the intriguing plots that will arise, this year's
tournament should come down to three questions.
</P>
<P>
   First, a standard question: Will Kentucky repeat? Last year was
a feel-good year: Tubby Smith, the first African-American head
coach at Kentucky, won a championship in his first season. This
season has been all about basketball, and it has been more
difficult. The Wildcats will have to defend their title as the
third-seeded team in a murderous Midwest region.
</P>
<P>
   Second: Will Connecticut finally reach the Final Four? For eight
years now, the nation has watched Coach Jim Calhoun build a strong
foundation only to fumble with the final brick. In 1990, the
Huskies lost in the East Regional final to Duke on a buzzer-beating
shot by Christian Laettner in overtime. In 1994, Donyell Marshall
missed two free throws with three seconds left and the game tied in
the East Regional semifinal, and the Huskies lost to Florida in
overtime. In 1995, the Huskies were beaten by the eventual
champion, UCLA, in the West Regional final. In 1996, with point
guard Ricky Moore injured, UConn fell to Mississippi State in the
Southeast Regional final. Last year they lost to North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Calhoun, repeating what has become his mantra,
said, ``If we reach the Final Four I will not be a better coach,
and if we don't make it I won't be a worse coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally: Will Duke win the national championship? For some the
question is simpler: By how many points will Duke win?
</P>
<P>
   The experts call No. 1-ranked Duke the most prohibitive favorite
to win the NCAA tournament since the 1992 Duke team repeated as
national champion. The Blue Devils won a school-record 26
consecutive games and became the first Atlantic Coast Conference
team to go 16-0 in league play. Pete Gillen, the Virginia coach,
declared: ``Nobody's going to beat Duke. Who's going to beat them?
It's going to be boring. They're a wrecking machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillen's comments are a bit self-serving: Virginia lost two
regular-season games to the Blue Devils by 46 points each. Then it
lost by 37 in the ACC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   If only Duke could play Virginia for the next three weeks. As
Duke Coach Mike Krzyzewski knows, this tournament is a funny
animal. For many years Krzyzewski was like Calhoun. He took his
team to the brink but could not cross that River Jordan. The lowest
point came in 1990, when his team was routed by UNLV, 103-73, in
the national championship game. Then Grant Hill happened. The next
year Duke finally won the elusive championship _ it beat an even
better UNLV team _ and repeated in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure that Duke fans understood _ or understand _ how
central Hill was to carrying the Blue Devils into the promised
land. Duke has not been to the Final Four in five years. In 1995,
with Krzyzewski missing most of the season because of a back
ailment, Duke dropped to 13-18. Last year Duke was a game away from
the Final Four but blew a 17-point second-half lead in the South
Regional final to the eventual champion, Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Now they carry a 31-1 record into the tournament. It could be a
heavy burden to carry, but only time will tell. It's March. It's
mad, and it's finally here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
