<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-815(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSH LIMBAUGH TAKES HIS SHOW TO THE INTERNET  
 AFTER THE INTERVIEW: THE GOOD AND THE TAWDRY  
 GANNETT WITHDRAWS ADS FROM JOURNALISM REVIEW  
 POZ APOLOGIZES FOR DIRECT MAILING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last few years, Rush Limbaugh, the blustery conservative
radio talk-show host, resisted taking his radio show to the
Internet, even though an increasing number of syndicated radio
programs were being sent online to homes and offices throughout the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until last Monday, when his show began broadcasting _
or ``streaming,'' as a technophile would say _ over the Internet at
Broadcast.com, a Web site that broadcasts audio and video over the
Internet ranging from radio and television programs to full-length
compact discs and audio books.
</P>
<P>
   Limbaugh said that he had waited to begin streaming his show to
protect the more than 600 radio stations that carry his program _
affiliates in the industry lexicon _ from losing listeners to the
Internet, which transmits his show without the local commercials
carried by the affiliates and the advertising dollars that pay for
them.
</P>
<P>
   But Limbaugh said that there had been ``such a public demand''
to hear his show from people who ``cannot get a radio signal in an
office building,'' that he and the producers of his show, which is
owned by the Premiere Radio Networks unit of Jacor Communications,
decided it was the right time to move to the Internet. He noted
that many of his affiliates were now streaming programs on the
Internet anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But as part of his efforts to protect his affiliates, listeners
will not be able to download his show and listen to it at any time,
as they can with many other programs. The ``Rush Limbaugh Show''
will only be available live, from noon to 3 p.m. Eastern standard
time.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harrison, the editor of Talkers, a talk-radio trade
publication, said that while Limbaugh might be one of the last
big-name radio hosts to begin streaming a show _ Dr. Laura
Schlessinger's program, another widely listened-to syndicated radio
show, has been available on the Internet for almost two years _ the
medium is still in its nascent stages and the number of Internet
listeners is minuscule compared with the estimated 20 million
people Limbaugh's radio show draws every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new technology and there was no reason for him to jump
in early,'' Harrison said. ``But it's become apparent that
eventually this is where people are going to be, and he knows
that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG
</P>
<P>
   After the Interview: The Good and the Tawdry
</P>
<P>
   A few final observations before the Monica Lewinsky interview
fades into history:
</P>
<P>
   BEST POSTMODERN MOMENT: MSNBC's ``Hockenberry'' producers,
knowing they couldn't beat 'em, tried to join 'em. MSNBC promotions
urged viewers to tune in to John Hockenberry's 10 p.m. talk show
using the picture-in-a-picture mode, if they had it, or during
commercials on ABC's ``20/20.'' For the latter group,
``Hockenberry'' even put a clock on the screen showing how many
minutes remained in ABC commercials before the interview resumed.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, ABC's ``Good Morning America'' had a blitz of
postinterview reportage that included a segment on the
``Hockenberry'' gambit. That's an ABC station reporting on an NBC
cable network reporting on an ABC News prime-time interview _ a
real media pretzel.
</P>
<P>
   BEST MEDIA SCOLDING: Ted Koppel had Barbara Walters and Joe
Klein of The New Yorker on ABC News' ``Nightline'' after the
interview. Toward the end, Klein held forth about the private lives
of public figures providing ``the stuff of fiction forever'' (both
he and Shakespeare had done it, Klein said, although ``Shakespeare
did it far more profoundly'').
</P>
<P>
   But Klein, the ``anonymous'' author of ``Primary Colors,'' went
on to say that the ``reality'' of the Clinton-Lewinsky saga and the
media's coverage of it was ``just kind of embarrassing and tawdry,
and it diminishes all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Koppel bordered on indignant in response, telling Klein: ``It
was unbecoming in the way, yes, that it was handled by the press,
by politicians, but in large measure unbecoming because of the way
in which the president himself handled it. So before you start
slapping all kinds of blame around left and right, I think we need
to bring it back where it belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   COMMERCE AND REALITY: In some instances, it seemed advertisers
on the interview program were well aware of the surroundings in
which their commercials would be shown. Victoria's Secret, for
example, owned by Intimate Brands Inc., ran a sultry,
black-and-white spot promoting its lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   Of several commercials now running for Diet Dr Pepper, Cadbury
Schweppes PLC chose to run one set at a make-believe congressional
hearing; at one point, a young woman runs up to a can of the soft
drink and shouts dramatically, ``No, no, tell them that you're
diet!''
</P>
<P>
   And a promotion for a program on ABC on May 23 about Cleopatra
began, ``When she was 20, she seduced the most powerful man in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gannett Withdraws Ads From Journalism Review
</P>
<P>
   In journalism, as in so many other endeavors, timing is
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Editors and reporters make statements not just by printing
articles but by deciding when to print them _ or not print them.
Advertisers, too, can make statements, not just by buying
advertisements but by choosing when to buy them _ or withdraw them.
</P>
<P>
   So the staff at American Journalism Review, the monthly magazine
published by the University of Maryland's College of Journalism,
could not help but wonder whether Gannett Co. was making a
statement in January when it pulled all its annual advertising _
about eight pages, according to AJR's editor, Rem Rieder. ``I was
surprised,'' he said, noting that Gannett had advertised in the
magazine for at least eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, a few weeks before Rieder learned about Gannett's
decision, the magazine published an article titled ``Editor Inc.,''
part of a series of wide-ranging, in-depth reports in a project
called the State of the American Newspaper. The article, by Geneva
Overholser, a former Gannett editor, took some not-so-subtle swipes
at her old bosses.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, discussing the cuts she was required to make in
the newsroom budget of The Des Moines Register in her last year as
editor there in 1995, she wrote: ``Having already removed heart,
soul and giblets, we cut some more _ another $63,000 in newsroom
spending. Very shortly thereafter, we learned that during the
months we were engaged in these hope-withering negotiations,
Gannett earnings were up 22 percent over the previous year's fourth
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacted last week, a Gannett spokeswoman, Mimi Feller, said,
``We have realigned some ad spending beginning last fall and going
on forward, by starting to put some dollars into campus newspapers,
because early recruiting is so important for us. So what we've done
is cut some of the dollars for trade'' publications like AJR.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   Poz Apologizes for Direct Mailing
</P>
<P>
   Some magazines tell their subscribers that if they do not want
their names rented out to other companies hawking merchandise, the
readers can check a box on the subscription form, or call a
toll-free number to protect their names and privacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Poz magazine, a monthly publication for
HIV-positive readers, privacy is an especially serious issue. The
magazine gives out free subscriptions to people who will declare on
a subscription form that they are HIV positive. Issues are
delivered to subscribers in a nondescript envelope.
</P>
<P>
   So when several thousand subscribers to Poz who had specifically
requested that their names not be rented out to other companies
found a letter from Community Prescription Services, with
information about a new HIV treatment, in their mailboxes last
month, they were alarmed. Had their wishes not been honored? And
did Community Prescription Services know their HIV status?
</P>
<P>
   The mailing was a mistake, said Sean Strub, an owner and
chairman of Poz Publishing LLC. In a letter of apology mailed to
those subscribers two weeks ago, Strub wrote, ``This was a terrible
mistake that makes it appear that we do not respect readers'
privacy or the option we so clearly gave readers not to have their
names exchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the mistake ``demonstrates that even with the best
intentions, once a name is on a list it is never 100 percent
private'' and that the publishers of Poz ``are extremely aware of
the dangers of involuntary disclosure and believe strongly in our
readers' rights to keep their names private.''
</P>
<P>
   Community Prescription Services, he noted in the letter, is a
sister company to Poz Publishing, but he wrote that the company's
affiliation was no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Strub also owns Metamorphics Media, a direct-marketing company
that controls several mailing lists. Critics have said that Strub,
through Metamorphics, could take unfair advantage of his Poz
subscriber list.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for that reason, we have to be doubly safe with this sort
of thing,'' he said. ``This time, we were not. To the recipient who
checked the box saying `I don't want to receive any other
mailings,' and then they got something from another company, this
was a violation. And we are sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
