<HEADLINE>
MODERATE CONSERVATIVE LEADS SALVADORAN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador _ A moderate candidate from the
governing conservative party led the voting Sunday in El Salvador's
second presidential election since the end of its civil war seven
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An early survey of voters leaving polling stations showed
Francisco Flores, the 39-year-old candidate of the governing
Nationalist Republican Alliance, with a comfortable lead over
Facundo Guardado, 44, his opponent from a coalition led by the
country's former guerrilla movement, the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front.
</P>
<P>
   Among five other candidates, Ruben Zamora, the FMLN presidential
candidate in the last election but now the candidate of his own
Democratic Center Union, drew the third largest block of votes,
about 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout among 3.1 million registered voters appeared low after
an election campaign dominated by the grave problems that have
plagued El Salvador since its 12-year civil war ended _ rampant
crime, high unemployment, inflation and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that despite the end of the war, the fundamental
problems of the country have not been solved like they had
expected,'' said Jose Miguel Cruz, director of the Public Opinion
University Institute at the Central American University.
</P>
<P>
   But the disillusionment of Salvadorans was not enough to turn
voters away from the Nationalist Republican Alliance, or ARENA,
which had suffered serious losses to the party of the former
guerrillas in municipal an legislative elections in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ARENA, which was founded in the early 1980s by leaders of El
Salvador's right-wing death squads but has since cultivated a
moderate image, united after the losses of 1997 behind Flores, a
candidate known in the national assembly for building consensus. He
seemed to epitomize the party's message of ``renovation and
openness.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, FMLN, after much infighting, rejected broadening
its appeal and settled on Guardadoa, a leftist activist and
moderate ex-guerrilla commander who himself had pushed for the
selection of a centrist candidate from an allied party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
