</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-WARNINGS-MEDIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HATH DRUDGE WROUGHT? PARTISAN WEB SITES GAIN SOME MEDIA
CREDIBILITY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rash of telephone calls started coming in to Doug Thompson,
the publisher of Capitol Hill Blue, a four-year-old Web site, about
three weeks ago. Journalists from a broadcast news organization,
from U.S. News &AMP; World Report, and from several British and
American newspapers, wanted his Web publication to help them reach
the sources for an article he had published.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson refused to help them. Reporters, he said in an
interview last week, do not ask for other reporters' sources. In an
editorial on his Web site _ a rant, in Webspeak _ he scoffed at the
idea that he should ``trust the mainstream media that has either
ignored the mounting evidence'' against President Clinton or
``rushed to his defense whenever legitimate stories were published
about his many high crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's telephone calls tell a tale. A year after the gossipy
Web site run by Matt Drudge became a bookmark in Washington
computers, other, more partisan Web sites are becoming early
warning systems for the mainstream press. Like talk radio, they are
filled with free-form invective. Like trailers from a new X-Files
movie, they offer previews of coming attractions from places where
conspiracy is king.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening with Capitol Hill Blue reminds me of the
early days of Drudge,'' said Stephen G. Smith, the editor of U.S.
News &AMP; World Report, who confirmed that his reporters were among
those who called Thompson last month. ``It has caught on as an
early warning sign of stories coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   It became clear last week that journalists in some corners of
the mainstream press check in with Capitol Hill Blue. Last Monday,
for the first time, The Hotline, the capital's most widely used
daily electronic tip sheet, used material from Capitol Hill Blue
and a liberal site called American Politics. Hotline is a summary
of all things political, from newspaper coverage of candidates to
the most recent polling data.
</P>
<P>
   An offshoot of the National Journal, an eminently respectable
magazine, The Hotline, according to Smith of U.S. News, is ``beamed
directly into the consciousness'' of Washington politicians and
journalists every weekday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Crawford, the editor of The Hotline, said he decided to
include chatter from the two partisan Web sites in his daily
round-up in part because some British newspapers, like The Daily
Telegraph, had begun passing on Capitol Hill Blue's reports. ``It's
hard to discern when you see something if it is the next NBC
interview or the next love-child fiasco,'' Crawford said. The
Hotline earlier this year included in its daily summary both the
reports about the then-unbroadcast NBC interview with Juanita
Broaddrick, who accused the president of sexually assaulting her 21
years ago, and unfounded tabloid speculation about an illegitimate
child fathered by the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drudge may have started it,'' Crawford added, ``but there are
many more Drudges out there, and more to come.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Capitol Hill Blue began as a one-man operation four years ago.
Then Thompson, 51, added three unpaid contributors, all older than
55 with backgrounds at newspapers. Thompson began his career as a
journalist before working as an aide to Republicans like Manuel
Lujan, the former representative from New Mexico. He is now a
public relations consultant but said he began the Web site because
``I'm an ex-newspaperman who wanted to get back into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   His site, established in 1994, is emblazoned with a motto
derived from one of Mark Twain's celebrated remarks: ``Because
nobody's life, liberty or property is safe while Congress is in
session.'' It carries the news the four contributors generate and
news from syndicated services like The Washington Post-Los Angeles
Times news service. It also features news photos and political
cartoons from major syndicates.
</P>
<P>
   The revenue needed to pay for such features comes from banner
advertisements from businesses like The Wall Street Journal's
interactive edition and Macy's. Thompson said advertising revenue
covered the $20,000 a month needed to pay for these features and
the three computer servers the site uses.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the news that appears on a site like Free Republic
is the news the stridently conservative readers bring to it. Free
Republic, a Web-based discussion group run by a former software
company executive in Fresno, Calif., posts the full text of
articles from major newspapers and asks for comment. The site is
being sued for copyright violation by The Los Angeles Times and The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe his readers, the site's owner, Jim Robinson,
said: ``We're basically just a group of individuals, conservatives,
who are debating what we can do to roll back some of the liberal
laws and agencies. The government has overstepped its limits, in
our opinion.'' Robinson, who works on the site 18 hours a day, and
says it is supported by reader donations.
</P>
<P>
   For Mark Hosenball, an investigative reporter in Newsweek's
Washington bureau, Free Republic is ``more entertainment and a
study in abnormal psychology than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   For Smith of U.S. News and World Report, checking in on the
conservative sites is a necessary part of the routine. ``It's
defensive editing,'' he said. ``If there's going to be a freight
train moving down the tracks, better to hear the vibrations
early.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
