<SLUG> BC-BKCR-STJOHNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S GETS ITS WISH: NO HOOPLA AND NO DUKE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nothing against Boston, but you could not miss the
relief when the East Regional of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament was announced Sunday and St.John's was not
in that bracket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to Boston,'' exulted Dermon Player, a St.
John's assistant coach, as his boss, Mike Jarvis, applauded.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's is going to Disney World, or, more specifically,
Orlando, Fla., where the Red Storm (25-8) will be seeded third and
will face 14th-seeded Samford (24-5), the Trans America Athletic
Conference champion, in the first round of the South Regional on
Thursday. In going South, St. John's avoids what would have been an
overwhelming amount of attention for the return of Jarvis, a
Cambridge, Mass., native, but also top-seeded Duke.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck for Miami, though. The Hurricanes, who lost to St.
John's in the semifinals of the Big East tournament, but who beat
the Red Storm twice in the regular season, were rewarded with a No.
2 seeding in the East, which means that they could play Duke in the
regional final at the Meadowlands to advance to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy we're not in the East,'' said Jarvis, whose team
lost to Duke in overtime in January. ``If I had gone back to
Boston, the media would have been so uncontrollable. There would
have been far too much emphasis on me. And if we're going to play
Duke again, let it be in the Final Four. Right now, there isn't
another team today that can beat Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most intriguing aspect of St. John's draw is that it
holds the potential for what would be a dramatic second-round game.
If St. John's gets by Samford _ forward Ron Artest said he
accidentally watched Samford highlights on television a few weeks
ago because he thought the announcer said Stanford _ it would play
the winner of the game between the 6th- and 11th-seeded teams. Pick
your poison: Bobby Knight and Indiana (No. 6) or George Washington,
the team Jarvis coached for eight years before leaving for St.
John's last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Colonials, who are now coached by Tom Penders, got an
at-large bid out of the Atlantic 10 and Indiana comes from one of
the nation's toughest conference, the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis wears a huge ring on his right hand commemorating 1993,
the year he took the Colonials on a wild run to the Sweet 16. But
Jarvis is ambivalent about seeing his former team in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I chose the field, I would not have George Washington in my
bracket,'' he said. ``Only because I'd much rather be rooting for
them rather than playing against them. I'll wish them well. And if
we play them, I'll have to forget about the fact I recruited
them.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, St. John's appears to have been placed in
one of the more manageable brackets. Not one of the region's top
four seeded teams _ Auburn, Maryland, St. John's and Ohio State _
is a conference champion. If St. John's gets out of the first
weekend, though, it would have a tough meeting in the Sweet 16 in
Knoxville, Tenn., likely with Maryland, which lost to North
Carolina in the Atlantic Coast Conference semifinals but has spent
much of the season in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse is the No. 8-seeded team in the South and, if it beats
ninth-seeded Oklahoma State, would likely face top-seeded Auburn in
the second round. Villanova, which beat St. John's in the last game
of the regular season, is seeded eighth in the Midwest, and faces
Mississippi in the first round. Rutgers, which has been on the
bubble for the last few weeks, did not make it and will be in the
National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, St. John's assistants were tucking into their
offices, preparing for an all-nighter of scouting Samford, since
nobody knew much about it. Jarvis didn't even know what city it was
in (Birmingham, Ala.). Since St. John's tapes every game on
television anywhere, Jarvis was sure there had to be a tape of the
Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a primer on Samford: Its big victory of the season was
over Tulane on Dec. 1. its second-year coach is Jim Tillette and he
was the conference coach of the year. Its star player is the junior
forward Reed Rawlings (6 feet 7 inches, 225 pounds), the
conference's player of the year, who is averaging 16.6 points per
game in the team's motion offense that features pick-and-rolls and
backdoor plays.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last season, St. John's was in a similar
predicament, knowing little more about its first-round opponent,
Detroit, than that the television analyst Dick Vitale had once
coached there. It apparently didn't learn fast enough because
Detroit beat the Red Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what we're getting into,'' point guard Erick
Barkley said of Samford. ``But I guarantee you, what happened last
year with Detroit will not happen again. We're not coming home so
fast.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
