u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-BRUINS-NY     03-07 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-BRUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WIN BATTLE BUT LOSE SAMUELSSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With two regular defensemen already out of the lineup
with injuries, the New York Rangers could not afford to lose any
more, especially in a game with serious implications for the
playoff race. But one went down, early, against the Boston Bruins
on Sunday in the Fleet Center. He was Ulf Samuelsson, knocked
unconscious and bleeding from the face, by Ken Belanger's vicious
board check.
</P>
<P>
   So with five defensemen left to fill six roles, the Rangers
could not afford to lose any more. But they did, for about a
minute, when Brian Leetch limped to the locker room after blocking
a shot with his right leg while killing a penalty near the end of
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Without Leetch, their captain and leader in minutes played, the
Rangers would have had a hard time preserving their two-goal lead,
winning the game and extending their unbeaten streak.
</P>
<P>
   But Leetch came back for the third period, the streak grew to
five games, and the Rangers beat the Bruins by 3-1 to move within 2
points of the Bruins in the Eastern Conference standing. The
Rangers (27-28-8, 62 points) are in ninth place in the conference.
The Bruins (27-26-10, 64 points) hold the eighth and final playoff
berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sitting on the bench going, `Please, not Leetchie!'''
said Marc Savard, who helped set up the clinching goal by Kevin
Stevens. He said some players stopped by the trainer's room during
the second intermission to make sure Leetch would be able to return
for the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Samuelsson, who probably sustained a concussion, will be
re-examined Monday and is unlikely to play against the Toronto
Maple Leafs at Madison Square Garden in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first game of a busy stretch, with the Rangers playing
five games in the next eight days. It is very likely they will use
defenseman Stan Neckar, who has not suited up for the last five
games. Defenseman Peter Popovic, out since Feb. 14 with an eye
injury, is expected to resume practice this week. Defenseman Jeff
Beukeboom's return from his second concussion of the season is
still uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's was the second consecutive victory for the Rangers, who
are 4-0-1 in their last five games. The Rangers were outshot by
38-18, and their best performer was goalie Mike Richter. They lost
all but 17 of 42 face-offs. But they got a slap-shot goal by John
MacLean and a short-handed goal by Niklas Sundstrom in the second
period for a 2-0 lead. After Boston's Landon Wilson cut the lead to
2-1 at 12 minutes 25 seconds of the third period, Stevens scored
1:26 later to clinch the victory.
</P>
<P>
   He fired a one-timer after Rumun Ndur banked a pass off the
boards for Savard, who gambles by leaving the defensive zone early
but rarely gets burned. ``I didn't see him, but I heard him,'' Ndur
said. Savard said, ``I saw an opening.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who scored his 16th goal of the season, said MacLean
helped by going to the net, taking the coverage with him and
leaving goalie Byron Dafoe exposed for a one-timer.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger's hit against Samuelsson came at 15:04 of the first
period, after Belanger exited the penalty box after serving his
roughing minor. He charged across the ice and crunched Samuelsson
from behind, earning a major penalty for boarding and an ejection.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston fans cheered the sight of an obviously injured
Samuelsson. They dislike him because of altercations years ago with
Cam Neely, the former Bruin, when Samuelsson played for Pittsburgh.
Samuelsson stayed on the ice for more than a minute and needed help
to stay upright after he was revived.
</P>
<P>
   John Muckler, the Ranger coach, said the hit was ``about as bad
as you can get.'' In a lighthearted remark, he said: ``Sammy says
he's back on the planet.'' But the coach did not specify which
planet, and Samuelsson was not able to speak with reporters. Leetch
said: ``Ulfie never saw him coming. It was a bad hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Leetch played 35:12 and seemed weary at the end, missing an open
Savard with a pass and getting beaten by Wilson on the Boston goal.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the unbeaten streak and the final 19 games of the
regular season, Leetch said: ``You see the end of the season. You
see the playoffs. You want to be in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter, referring to the result and the developing team
personality, said: ``That was an important win for us. It kept our
momentum going. We'll look back on this one, I think. There's a
feeling on this team this year that we are a more competitive
squad. We feel capable of beating anyone on a given night.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Wednesday, they face the Maple Leafs and the
Ottawa Senators, the top two teams in the conference, and possible
playoff opponents for whoever finishes eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
