<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DRAW-MEN-ART-NYT &LR;      03-07 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DRAW-MEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIELD OF DREAMERS AND DUKE GOING THE NCAA FINAL 64
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Duke Blue Devils officially became prohibitive favorites.
Their most formidable potential opponent, Connecticut, will have to
win out West to get to them. And the balance of power in college
basketball appears to have shifted to the East and Midwest. Or at
least that appeared to be the meaning of the invitations and
seedings announced Sunday for the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1-ranked Blue Devils (32-1) will begin their national
title campaign as the top-seeded team in the East Region on Friday,
in their home state of North Carolina. They topped off a dominating
year by thumping North Carolina, 96-73, in the Atlantic Coast
Conference tournament final Sunday in Charlotte, and they will
return there Friday against the team with the worst record in the
field of 64: Florida A&AMP;M, the champion of the Mid-Eastern Athletic
Conference tournament despite a 12-18 record.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Coach Mike Krzyzewski said that even if the Blue Devils did
not win the tournament, after being selected as the nation's
toughest team, ``we'll know that we did everything we could to try
to win it and we didn't let pressure stop us.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut (28-1) was made the top-seeded team in the West
Regional and will try once again to get to its first Final Four
beginning Thursday against Texas-San Antonio (18-10) in Denver.
Like Duke, Connecticut captured its regular season and conference
tournament championships in impressive fashion, whipping St. John's
by 82-63 to win the Big East on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``UConn came out second, but had to go out of the region because
Duke was the top seed,'' said C.M. Newton, chairman of the NCAA
selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun anticipated his team would be
moved, but was more concerned that it remain healthy _ especially
after its dominating run through the Big East tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just care about looking at going someplace and finding out
who is there, who we have to play against to get where we want to
be,'' Calhoun said. ``I've always been a bracket guy much more than
geography.''
</P>
<P>
   He should like the West _ the No. 2-seeded team is Stanford
(25-6), a team Connecticut beat in February. No. 3 is North
Carolina and No. 4 is Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   The Auburn Tigers (27-3) and Michigan State (29-4) earned top
seedings in their home regions of the South and the Midwest, and
will join the tussle to bring down Duke. Over all, the tournament
bids provoked little controversy and provided hope for one Big East
team and heartache for another.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's will travel to Orlando, Fla., as the No. 3-seeded in
perhaps the softest regional of all, the South. They will meet
Samford on Thursday. Both the No. 1- and No. 2-seeded teams, Auburn
and Maryland, exited their conference tournaments early this past
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Hurricanes, however, could not win for losing. They
were knocked out in the semifinals of the Big East tournament by
St. John's, but still earned a No. 2 seeding in the East. If they
hope for a trip to the Final Four in St. Petersburg, Fla., the
Hurricanes will probably have to beat No. 3-seeded Cincinnati, the
only team to vanquish Duke this season, in the regional semifinals
next week at the Meadowlands. And then, of course, the Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten, led by Michigan State, put the most teams in the
tournament with seven _ tying the record set by the Big East in
1991 and the Big Ten in 1994. If Illinois had upset the Spartans in
Sunday's Big Ten conference tournament final, the selection
committee was prepared to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   The traditionally powerful Atlantic Coast Conference did not
fare as well. Only Maryland (26-5) and North Carolina (24-9)
advanced to the tournament along with Duke _ the three teams being
the lowest total since two were chosen for the field of 48 in 1980.
Newton said the committee considered Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wake Forest really needed to win a game in the ACC tournament
and they didn't do that,'' Newton said. ``They had a chance to play
their way in and didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
