</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NETS-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDS COMES OFF BENCH TO HELP KNICKS BURY NETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For two years, Chris Childs was a misfit. He would
step onto the court as if dressed in a plaid jacket for a black-tie
affair and force his racy, loud style on the conservative New York
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Not the least bit shy, Childs would disrupt the team's flow with
his flashy notions and elicit scowls from his teammates upon his
rash decisions. After being plopped down on the bench a year ago,
after hearing his name echo in trade speculation, Childs has
discovered that playing with a calmer head does not have to dull
his energy.
</P>
<P>
   A more mature, grown-up Childs revealed how he has learned to
mesh his talents with those of his teammates Sunday afternoon at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd that has occasionally booed his petulance in the past
watched with approval as Childs worked in concert with Latrell
Sprewell off the bench to pick up the Knicks for a 97-86 victory
over a crestfallen and confused New Jersey Nets team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie and say I wouldn't want to start,'' said
Childs, who scored 15 points and grabbed six rebounds in 31 minutes
of play. ``Everyone's dream is to start. For this particular team,
I'm a better fit this way, especially with Latrell coming off, too.
That gives us a lot of intensity and energy and firepower off the
bench. We're high-energy guys.''
</P>
<P>
   In different ways, the electricity generated by Sprewell and
Childs provided a finger snap to jar a daydreaming Knicks team that
was losing interest and its 11-point halftime lead as the game wore
on.
</P>
<P>
   With his touch as flat as an anvil, Sprewell ditched his own
shot and made a nifty inside pass to Larry Johnson for a layup
after the Nets had closed within three points with four minutes
left to play. A few moments later, Childs patiently worked the ball
around, and then, when it circled back to him, he unabashedly hit
his third 3-pointer of the game to turn a six-point Knick lead into
a crushing nine-point edge with 1 minute 27 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Childs and Sprewell were co-hosts to Patrick Ewing's
30-point effort as the Knicks (10-7) sent the Nets to their ninth
loss in 10 games as New Jersey's record dropped to 3-12.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Childs and Sprewell took the burden off Ewing. For the
first time in three games, Ewing was not forced to take a shot at
the buzzer only to miss and lose and draw criticism. This time, the
Knicks were playing at home, where their margin for error is
greater and the victories come more easily. Despite their
rebounding flaws and offensive limitations, the Knicks are 8-1 at
the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing a fabulous job at home,'' said Ewing, who scored
18 points in the third quarter. ``We just have to turn it around on
the road. I think it's mental.''
</P>
<P>
   It's physical, too. For a week, coach Jeff Van Gundy has
criticized the Knicks' inability to rebound and pleaded for his
team to put a body on someone. The Knicks allowed the Nets an edge
in rebounding, 51-40.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about that, and it's done absolutely no good,''
said Van Gundy, whose team ranks 28th in rebounding. ``We may just
run around in football pads at practice, but we're going to do
something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs did his part. He dodged bigger bodies for six rebounds.
Only Ewing, with nine rebounds, had more for the Knicks. Flaunting
his diversity, Childs also hit three of four 3-pointers (including
a 40-footer at the end of the third quarter) to maintain his
league-best 3-point-shooting average (59.3 percent), while his
bench partner, Sprewell, managed to deliver five assists to play a
part in his first victory with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Before his heel injury, the Knicks were 0-2 with Sprewell in
uniform as a starter. In his first game back on Friday, the Knicks
lost in Milwaukee despite Sprewell's pop off the bench. He was
almost too pushy, too shot-happy against the Bucks. A game later,
Sprewell was almost too tentative against the Nets. But when he
passed up shots, he moved the ball. And it worked against the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, winning is the important thing,'' said Sprewell, who
shot 2 for 6 and had five points in 21 minutes on the floor. ``I'm
happy playing this role right now. I'm satisfied with it at this
point.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There may come a point when Sprewell balks at his bench status.
There may come a time when Van Gundy returns him to the starting
lineup. But for a day, the combination of Sprewell and Childs
provided enough edge to pull the Knicks out of their two-game
slide.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets merely continued their unfathomable free fall. As well
as point guard Doug Overton (18 points) played, the Nets are lost
without the injured Sam Cassell. About a month ago, they were the
league darlings and even had the audacity to proclaim themselves
the top dogs of this metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bragged a little bit, but I'm not even going to come back
and say what kind of dog they are now,'' Childs said with a smile.
``I mean, I think if they are at full strength and they're
confident, they're a dangerous team. Right now, they're driving a
car with only two wheels. And that won't get you very far.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs should know. He used to be the Nets' guide. In some ways,
he was a lot like Cassell. He was the frenetic playmaker and shot
taker. Once he left New Jersey, he tried to take his stylish act
through the Lincoln Tunnel. It did not travel well at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've finally come to grips with the way I have to play for the
Knicks to be successful,'' Childs said. ``I think the first couple
of years, I was in a position where I tried to make a lot of things
happen at once instead of letting the game come to me. Now, I don't
want to take over the game. I'm not the first option anymore. We
have other guys on this team that are capable scorers.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
