<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-NC-NYT &LR;      03-07 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-NC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE RUNS THE TABLE, LEAVING ACC IN AWE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BARRY JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ The details differed from game to game, but
when the Duke basketball team played in the Atlantic Coast
Conference this season the result was always the same.
</P>
<P>
   The top-ranked Blue Devils finished a 19-0 run through the
conference regular season and post-season Sunday and staked a claim
as the most dominant squad in league history. They did it with a
commanding 96-73 victory over No. 15 North Carolina to capture the
ACC tournament championship.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (32-1) won its 27th consecutive game and earned the league
title for the first time since 1992, when it went on to win its
second consecutive national championship. The Blue Devils, who
Sunday were awarded the top seeding in the East Regional of the
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament, will play
Florida A&AMP;M (12-18), the only team in the N.C.A.A. tournament with
a losing record, at the Charlotte Coliseum on Friday in the opening
round.
</P>
<P>
   Duke set a record for winning margin in the ACC tournament,
beating North Carolina, North Carolina State and Virginia by an
average of 25 points. The Blue Devils also set a league record for
margin of victory during the regular season (25.5 points).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they have any weaknesses,'' said Bill Guthridge,
who is in his second season as North Carolina's coach after 30
years as Dean Smith's assistant. ``It's hard to compare teams from
year to year, but I don't remember a team dominating a league the
way they have, the way they just took everybody apart. They're so
efficient, so effective.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, the third-seeded team in the conference
tournament, fell to 24-9. The Tar Heels are seeded third in the
West Regional of the NCAA tournament, and will face Weber State
(24-7) on Thursday in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils were paced by their big man, Elton Brand, the
tournament's most valuable player, who had 24 points and 13
rebounds, and guard William Avery, who led both teams with 29
points and had 4 steals and 5 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing without Trajan Langdon, their second-leading
scorer, the Blue Devils did not trail North Carolina after the
game's first two and a half minutes. Langdon, a senior guard who,
his teammate Shane Battier said, is the team's emotional leader,
has a sprained foot but is expected to play this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils became only the fifth team to finish the ACC
regular season without a loss and then go on to win the league
tournament, along with North Carolina's undefeated national
champions of 1957, Duke's Final Four squad of 1963 and North
Carolina State's teams of 1973 and 1974. The '74 Wolfpack team was
an NCAA champion; the '73 team was on probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineteen and 0, even if they're all 1-point games, would be
pretty impressive,'' said Duke Coach Mike Krzyzewski, acknowledging
that his team ``really wanted to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team needs to take the lead and keep the lead,
not just necessarily in a game,'' added Krzyzewski, who won his
fourth ACC title. ``We're playing so well, to let up would be
tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Tar Heels, the ACC's two-time defending champions,
Duke took the lead for good at 9-6 on a 3-pointer by Battier two
minutes and 42 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Against North Carolina's mix of zone and sagging man-to-man
defense, Duke made seven of 13 three-pointers in the first half and
10 of 22 in the game. The Blue Devils average 19 three-point
attempts a game.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Blue Devils forced 13 turnovers, which they
converted into 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   Duke took a 49-35 lead at the half on 60 percent shooting. For
the game, the Blue Devils shot 57.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Duke opened the second half with 10 consecutive points, building
its largest lead of the game, 59-35, on an Avery 3-pointer with
18:13 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, which reached the final by defeating Georgia
Tech and second-seeded Maryland, was in danger of being embarrassed
after playing its best basketball in three months. The Tar Heels
responded with 14 straight points, then pulled within 65-56 on a
free throw by center Brendon Haywood with 10:28 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, the North Carolina inside game was
neutralized as Duke controlled the boards, 35-30. The Heels got a
team-high 22 points from wing Max Owens and 11 assists from guard
Ed Cota, who set a tournament record with 29 for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Battier recalled squandering a 17-point lead midway
through the second half when similarly challenged in the 1998 NCAA
Southeast Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, in the Kentucky game, when they made that run, our
eyes were wide open,'' said Battier, a sophomore forward. ``We were
all looking at each other, not knowing what to think. When Carolina
made the run today, we just huddled up and said, `Hey, let's just
play ball,' and responded with a run of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke quickly pushed the lead back to 18 points and coasted the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good, but we have six games to prove we're a great
team,'' said Duke wing Chris Carrawell, who contributed 12 points
and 7 assists. ``We're not there yet.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
