<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA VOWS TO PUNISH CHECHNYA FOR ABDUCTION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia vowed Sunday night to punish the separatist
Chechnya region unless Chechen kidnappers quickly released a
high-ranking Russian officer. The threat that represented the most
serious deterioration in Russian-Chechen relations since a peace
settlement was concluded more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials declined to specify how they would respond to
the kidnapping of Maj. Gen. Gennadi Shpigun, a senior Interior
Ministry official. Sergei Stepashin, the interior minister, said
Sunday night that Russia was planning a series of economic,
political and ``operational'' measures.
</P>
<P>
   The aim was not just to free the kidnapped officer but also to
punish the Chechens, said Stepashin, who was a hawk during the
fierce Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be tanks or 18-year-old boys,'' he told Russian
television. ``It will be appropriate measures.''
</P>
<P>
   As Moscow brandished its threats, representatives of the Russian
government were evacuated by convoy from the breakaway Caucasus
republic. Chechnya has been racked by kidnappings since it won its
freedom, making it one of the most lawless regions of the former
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Russia insists that Chechnya is still part of
Russia. But the region enjoys a kind of de facto independence,
underscored by the withdrawal of the Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The latest drama began on Friday when Shpigun was seized by
masked gunmen after he boarded a plane in Grozny bound for Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers had hidden in the luggage compartment of the
plane. Armed with assault rifles, they barged into the passenger
compartment as the plane was taxiing on the tarmac, seized the
officer, stopped the plane and then fled with their captive.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear why the officer had been seized.
One view, reflected in the Russian news media, was that the
kidnappers reported to Salman Raduyev, the Chechen commander, who
wants to exchange the officer for two Chechen women jailed for
bombing a railway station in Pyatigorsk, in southern Russia. The
bombing killed two people and the Chechen women were sentenced,
respectively, to 16 and 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   But kidnappings have also been carried out for ransom, Chechen
officials noted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was not the first time that Russian officials have been
kidnapped. Valentin Vlasov, President Boris Yeltsin's personal
representative to Chechnya, was kidnapped but released six months
later. Another Russian government representative, Akmal Saidov, was
killed by the gunman who seized him.
</P>
<P>
   The latest kidnapping, however, was portrayed in Moscow as the
last straw: an intolerable humiliation aided by Chechen
authorities. Vlasov said Chechnya had been given until Monday to
secure the release of the officer.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen security officials, for their part, insisted they had
not orchestrated the kidnapping and were investigating the case.
They also expressed concern that the evacuation of Russian
officials was a prelude to an airstrike or other military action.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, who talked to Yeltsin several times over the weekend,
said his plan to punish Chechnya would be considered by the
government's Security Council on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that thousands of Russians still live in Chechnya,
Stepashin opposed an all-out economic blockade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk should be less about sanctions that affect the population
than measures that would bar anyone from earning money from
carrying on like the band that seized Gennady Shpigun,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
