<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIMATE-STUDENT-ART-N     03-07 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMATE-STUDENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 19-YEAR-OLD WITH HER SCHOLARLY HEAD IN THE CLOUDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo of Meredith Croke is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STONY BROOK, N.Y. _ Two years ago, Dr. Robert D. Cess, a
climatologist at the State University of New York here, grumbled
when another professor urged him to supervise a local high school
student in a summer program for bright teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Cess said, was that in nearly four decades as a
professor, he had never found any use for an undergraduate research
assistant, let alone a junior from Miller Place High School, even
one with a passion for weather.
</P>
<P>
   He grudgingly agreed, and sent the student, Meredith Croke, then
17, down the hall to a computer in an empty office. He told her to
familiarize herself with its sophisticated package of
number-crunching software. ``I figured that would take at least
half the summer,'' Cess said.
</P>
<P>
   He went to lunch. ``When I got back,'' he said, ``she asked me,
`Professor Cess, what shall I do next?'''
</P>
<P>
   Cess began to think that Ms. Croke might have some potential
after all, he said, and now he is sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Croke's research at Stony Brook on links between clouds and
temperature has been accepted for publication in The Journal of
Climate, a prominent research periodical that is usually the
province of gray-haired doctorate, not peach-faced 19-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The same work was rejected by judges last year for the finals of
the Westinghouse Science Talent Search, a high school competition
that is now sponsored by the Intel Corp.. That was a blow, Ms.
Croke said. ``But I'll take this any day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely unusual to have someone this young who's out
there doing research in an important area,'' said Dr. James J.
Hack, a climate scientist at the National Center for Atmospheric
Research in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Hack reviewed an early version of the paper. ``It's original and
provocative and raises interesting questions about one of the
central mysteries of the climate system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Croke's research led to a full scholarship to Stony Brook,
where she is a freshman with plans for graduate work in applied
physics and meteorology. ``There is just something about weather,''
she said, ``how it's always changing, with so many things involved
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents, Robert, a Suffolk County police inspector, and
Susan, a secretary, said they have no idea where their daughter's
fascination with weather came from, but that it was there at a
young age.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 5, during trips in the car she would chat idly in
the back seat _ until the forecast came on the radio, Croke said.
``She'd stop dead and listen to the weather,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 10, for Christmas she wanted a weather station with
an anemometer to check wind speed. ``We thought that was a somewhat
unusual request,'' Croke said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of becoming addicted to Nickelodeon or MTV, she sat
mesmerized by satellite images on the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   She applied for the summer program at Stony Brook in 1997,
writing in her application about her love of weather.
</P>
<P>
   Her aim was to find relationships between long-term patterns of
cloudiness, precipitation and temperature across Long Island, she
said. Dr. Cess gave her a weighty tome with 87 years of global
weather data, and she began sifting for clues using the computer.
</P>
<P>
   The study expanded to the East Coast, then the West Coast near
San Diego and the southern Great Plains. Slowly, a pattern emerged
linking years with unusual cloudiness to changes in high pressure
zones near Hawaii and in the North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Cess said Ms. Croke's work significantly advances the
understanding of the relationship between changes in global
temperature and changes in cloudiness.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds can cool and warm the planet, reflecting some of the
sun's heat back into space but also acting like an insulating
blanket, trapping some heat near the surface. Warmer weather tends
to spawn more clouds, but the details remain _ well _ cloudy, Dr.
Cess said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like trying to unscramble an egg,'' he said to illustrate
how difficult it is to find patterns in the turbulence of global
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Croke's research appears to reveal at least one small link,
he said. It may help scientists refine computer models of the
atmosphere that are being used to assess the potential impact of
global warming but are hampered by a lack of understanding of the
physics of clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The paper is dense with technical terms and statistical
formulas. But there is at least one hint of adolescence in the
acknowledgments: ``One of us (MC) would like to thank her dad for
letting her use the car to get to Stony Brook during this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Croke said that for now, her climate research will take a
back seat to introductory calculus and literature courses and track
meets. She runs 60 or 70 miles a week to stay in shape for a
cross-country event, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer, she will be back at her research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
