<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-INDOOR-CHAMPIONSH     03-07 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-INDOOR-CHAMPIONSHIPS-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEBRSELASSIE, SZABO WIN THEIR SECOND GOLDS AT WORLD INDOOR TRACK
CHAMPIONSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PAUL GAINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAEBASHI, Japan _ Haile Gebrselassie's amazing string of
performances continued Sunday with a victory in the 1,500 meters at
the World Indoor Track Championships. Coupled with his 3,000-meter
victory on Friday, it gave the 25-year-old Ethiopian an
unprecedented double, one duplicated Sunday by Gabriela Szabo of
Romania. It was not easy for Gebrselassie, though.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing his lethal finishing kick, the two Kenyan runners in the
field, Laban Rotich and William Tanui, plotted a fast early pace
that stretched out the field and, up until the final straightaway,
appeared to have done the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Rotich, holder of the Kenyan 1,500-meter record, had a
commanding lead with 40 meters remaining. But Gebrselassie found an
extra gear and squeezed past the struggling Kenyan to win in 3
minutes 33.77 seconds, the fastest time ever at the indoor
championships. Rotich held on for the silver medal in 3:33.98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not expecting that, because I thought everybody would be
running for the win,'' Gebrselassie said of the quick pace. ``But
Tanui pushed at the beginning, and I was happy because everybody
was tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Szabo, 23, finished her double by winning the 3,000 in 8:36.42,
passing Zahra Ouaziz of Morocco on the last lap. She won the 1,500
in a championships record time of 4:03.23 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could things be better?'' Szabo said. ``One gold is great;
two in a championships, now that is remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Two world records were set in the 4x400-meter relay Sunday, by
the U.S. men's team and by the Russian women's team. Milt Campbell
anchored the American men to victory in 3:02.83, overtaking Robert
Mackowiak of Poland in the final straightaway. The Russian women
won in 3:24.25.
</P>
<P>
   There were upsets in both 800-meter races. Maria Mutola of
Mozambique lost for the first time indoors since June 1993,
finishing second to Ludmila Formanova of the Czech Republic, whose
1:56.90 was the second-fastest time in history and a meet record.
And Johan Botha of South Africa beat the world record-holder,
Wilson Kipketer of Denmark, by .02 seconds in 1:45.47.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene of the United States won the men's 60 meters in
6.42 seconds, a championships record.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of his two gold medals, Gebrselassie said he was most satisfied
with the 1,500 meters. ``Because the real competition was today,''
he said. ``The 3,000 meters was just a jog at 10,000-meter pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Gebrselassie has not lost a world championships or Olympic final
on the track since 1993. He holds the 5,000- and 10,000-meter world
records outdoors and the 5,000-meter record indoors, which he set
last month in Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the 3,000 on Friday, Gebrselassie had tried to
play down his ability in the 1,500 _ even though he ran the
second-fastest indoor time in history, 3:31.76 last year at
Stuttgart, Germany. According to his agent, Jos Hermens, who took
Gebrselassie to Europe as a teen-ager in 1992 and has nurtured his
career since, Gebrselassie was relaxed in the days leading up to
Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an incredible talent,'' Hermens said. ``He's so relaxed
_ that's his strength. He is always relaxed. The smile at the start
is genuine. He amazes me all the time how relaxed he is. He doesn't
worry, doesn't think a lot about tactics. He just runs and does his
best and if someone is better, then they are better. No problem.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
