<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1113 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEDONA-AZR &LR;      03-07 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEDONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT FILMMAKERS FROM AROUND WORLD GATHER FOR SEDONA FILM
FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ For $1, you could have had your name in the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Selling screen time for a buck was one ingenious method that
indie filmmaker Allan Piper used to raise money for ``Starving
Artists,'' the comedy he wrote, directed, produced, edited and
stars in.
</P>
<P>
   Piper, of Boston, and other independent filmmakers from around
the world gathered in Sedona over the weekend, where they shared
the movies they risked fortune and sanity to make with 1,200 movie
lovers during the fifth annual Sedona Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   When Piper was raising money to make ``Starving Artists,'' an
energetic farce whose plot is encapsulated in its title, he
promised that anyone who gave him even $1 would find their name on
screen in the movie _ as graffiti on walls, in newspaper headlines,
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That inspired some people to give more than a dollar so their
names would be more prominent,'' Piper told an amused audience of
movie lovers at the filmmakers' panel Sunday morning. ``I have to
describe it as divine intervention that we finished the movie at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   While the moviemakers struggled to get their films to Sedona,
movie fans faced a dizzying array of films and events, including a
workshop staffed with Oscar-winning sound editors; a wide range of
American indies; films from Italy, China, Japan, Greece, Iceland
and Mali; documentaries; and four collections of short films.
</P>
<P>
   From Friday morning through Sunday night, festivalgoers chose
from four different programs every two hours. Movie die-hards could
have spent the weekend watching 16 different films, not to mention
attending the parties and Q&AMP;A sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Sean Young, who lives in Sedona, showed up at the
opening night party with small white wings on the shoulders of her
glittery gown. An angel is a central character in Young's film,
``Special Delivery,'' a comedy about a woman who thinks she is
bearing the next Christ child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special Delivery'' is not your typical film festival picture,
although it might become your typical megaplex release or
made-for-TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   Why did director Ken Carlson choose Sedona for the world
premiere? ``I had a chance to make this movie through a studio, but
I didn't think they'd let me keep in some of the spiritual
material,'' the Arizona filmmaker explained.
</P>
<P>
   Young felt that ``Special Delivery'' had found a home at the
Sedona Festival. ``We all know in Sedona that it's OK to be
spiritual,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Schay, who directs the festival and heads the Sedona
Cultural Park, includes films like ``Special Delivery'' because
``there are more mainstream movies here than you'd see at
Sundance,'' he said. ``We like movies that are about something more
than saying, `Look how clever I am.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other big star in attendance was Sean Astin, best
known for starring in such movies as ``Rudy'' and ``Encino Man.''
</P>
<P>
   After the U.S. premiere of his sweet romance, ``Boy Meets
Girl,'' Astin talked with the audience _ one of the intimate
thrills that you'll only find at this kind of boutique film
festival.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a Hollywood star like Astin make a small-budget movie
like ``Boy'' ``Meets Girl?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom to take risks,'' the actor explained. ``It's a great
change of pace because studios wouldn't make a movie like this.
There aren't marketing strategies that impose themselves on the
making of a movie like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Astin also likes the rapid, intense pacing of a small-budget
production, where producers don't have enough money to waste time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get there, you start working and you're out of there,''
Astin said. ``I love the speed of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rhapsody in Bloom,'' a romantic comedy starring Penelope Ann
Miller and Ron Silver, was Sedona's other mainstream movie, one
that could easily find its way to a multiplex near you.
</P>
<P>
   ````Rhapsody in Bloom'' fits an interesting niche,''
director/producer Craig Saavedra admitted. ``The independents felt
it was too studiolike, and the studios thought it was too
independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Saavedra's project was attractive to an accomplished screen
actress like Miller because it gave her ``the chance to headline a
cast and not just play the girlfriend, like she did in
``Kindergarten Cop'','' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   But stars bring other problems to new directors. ``I told them
in the beginning, I know you guys have been on films where you have
your egos stroked,'' Saavedra recalled. ``But I'm not going to do
that. You're going to have to be adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge for a new filmmaker with his cast is to
make sure you're all making the same movie, telling the same
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Piper had no stars available to him when he made ``Starving
Artists'' on a budget that would keep actors starving, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Piper didn't want stars. ``You see the same stars in every
movie,'' he said. ``There's something wonderful about looking at
unknown actors and really believing that they are the characters in
the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Saavedra agreed. ``I'm looking forward to becoming successful
enough that I can cast unknown actors because often the stars come
with baggage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All indie filmmakers face the essential problem: Name actors can
help get distribution deals, especially overseas and in video
stores.
</P>
<P>
   With the market flooded with indie films, Saavedra recouped his
investment in ``Rhapsody in Bloom'' by selling the overseas, cable
and video rights so that he won't lose money even if the film never
reaches movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some indies will premiere first on cable, then get picked up
because distributors see it as a proven commodity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarian director Momchil Karamitev, whose dark drama, ``The
Insurance,'' was one of the more complex films at the festival,
described trying to get his movie made in a non-movie-producing
country as ``painful for a long period.''
</P>
<P>
   Karamitev's producer had lined up funding from the Bulgarian
cultural department, but then died and they lost the connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up putting my own savings in to finish the film,'' he
said. ``That was the main support we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the scores of film festivals around the country can be
a pricey proposition for the indie filmmaker, with each festival
requiring an entry fee, with no guarantee of acceptance and no
payoff even if the film is shown. Sedona's $50 is among the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   But filmmakers like Harish Saluja of India, who directed and
produced ``The'' ``Journey,'' built the price of entering film
festivals into his production budget. ``The Journey'' has now
played in 18 festivals around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The festival circuit is a process that for films like mine
need to happen,'' Saluja said. ``It's like a song. You sing it for
people and let it be heard. That interaction is very important to
the harmony of the work. You get the film in front of people and
see whether they love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Native American filmmaker Robby Romero ``(Hidden Medicine)''
sees indie movies in a different light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all filmmaking is mainstream, whether it's independent
or not,'' he said, ``because you want as many people to see it as
possible.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
