cast and not just play the girlfriend, like she did in
``Kindergarten Cop'','' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   But stars bring other problems to new directors. ``I told them
in the beginning, I know you guys have been on films where you have
your egos stroked,'' Saavedra recalled. ``But I'm not going to do
that. You're going to have to be adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge for a new filmmaker with his cast is to
make sure you're all making the same movie, telling the same
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Piper had no stars available to him when he made ``Starving
Artists'' on a budget that would keep actors starving, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Piper didn't want stars. ``You see the same stars in every
movie,'' he said. ``There's something wonderful about looking at
unknown actors and really believing that they are the characters in
the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Saavedra agreed. ``I'm looking forward to becoming successful
enough that I can cast unknown actors because often the stars come
with baggage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All indie filmmakers face the essential problem: Name actors can
help get distribution deals, especially overseas and in video
stores.
</P>
<P>
   With the market flooded with indie films, Saavedra recouped his
investment in ``Rhapsody in Bloom'' by selling the overseas, cable
and video rights so that he won't lose money even if the film never
reaches movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some indies will premiere first on cable, then get picked up
because distributors see it as a proven commodity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarian director Momchil Karamitev, whose dark drama, ``The
Insurance,'' was one of the more complex films at the festival,
described trying to get his movie made in a non-movie-producing
country as ``painful for a long period.''
</P>
<P>
   Karamitev's producer had lined up funding from the Bulgarian
cultural department, but then died and they lost the connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up putting my own savings in to finish the film,'' he
said. ``That was the main support we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the scores of film festivals around the country can be
a pricey proposition for the indie filmmaker, with each festival
requiring an entry fee, with no guarantee of acceptance and no
payoff even if the film is shown. Sedona's $50 is among the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   But filmmakers like Harish Saluja of India, who directed and
produced ``The'' ``Journey,'' built the price of entering film
festivals into his production budget. ``The Journey'' has now
played in 18 festivals around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The festival circuit is a process that for films like mine
need to happen,'' Saluja said. ``It's like a song. You sing it for
people and let it be heard. That interaction is very important to
the harmony of the work. You get the film in front of people and
see whether they love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Native American filmmaker Robby Romero ``(Hidden Medicine)''
sees indie movies in a different light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all filmmaking is mainstream, whether it's independent
or not,'' he said, ``because you want as many people to see it as
possible.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
