<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT &LR;      03-07 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   One morning recently, I boarded the 79th Street crosstown bus
and sat down next to a little girl of 5 or 6 and her nanny. I soon
felt a small hand on my wrist and looked down to see the smiling
face of the child, who admired my bracelet. I thanked her for the
compliment, and she asked if she could have the bracelet when I
die.
</P>
<P>
   Her nanny admonished her, but the little girl defended her
question by saying that she was going to get jewelry when her
grandmother dies. She then asked me if I had grandchildren. When I
told her that I didn't, she smiled brightly and once again asked if
she could have the bracelet when I die.
</P>
<P>
   Before I could respond, her nanny escorted her off the bus, and
off to school they went.
</P>
<P>
   _ LYNDA FOX-FRAZER
</P>
<P>
   Margie Goldsmith was walking in midtown with Sara Smith, her
12-year-old visitor from Davenport, Iowa. They stopped to look at
an FAO Schwarz window in which Barbie was featured wearing various
costumes. ``She's been a teacher, a vet, a dentist, an Olympic
skater, and now all these people,'' Sara said. ``Why can't Barbie
hold a job?''
</P>
<P>
   Kate Brokaw, after a screening of ``Rushmore'' at the Sony
Lincoln Square theater, heard a father say to his teen-age son, ``I
didn't understand it at all, but I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Constance Bullard was in front of the Grand Hyatt Hotel at
Lexington Avenue and 42nd Street when a young businessman came
flying out. He hailed a taxi, opened the door, flung his coat and
briefcase in the back seat and, as he got in, yelled at the driver:
``Take me to Grand Central Station.'' The terminal is precisely one
building away from the hotel. Ms. Bullard's observation: ``Possibly
from out of town?''
</P>
<P>
   George and Didi Gold were having dinner at a new restaurant on
the East Side. Gold ordered a reasonably priced wine, finished the
bottle and, having found it pleasant and worth remembering, asked
the waitress to take off the label. She returned with the bottle,
without the label. ``It's a lovely bottle, isn't it?'' she said
cheerily. But where was the label? he asked. ``In the garbage,''
she replied.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   When I recently tried to visit the Veterans Administration
building in downtown Manhattan, I was refused admittance because I
was carrying a pocket knife. I offered to leave it with the guard
and pick it up when I left, but was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   So I went across the street to a hot-dog vendor. ``Hold this for
me,'' I said, ``and when I come out, I'll take care of you.'' He
agreed. When I completed my business and returned, he waved off my
tip, saying, ``That's all right _ I do this for people every day.''
_ SAM WEINBERG
</P>
<P>
   RITE OF SPRING
</P>
<P>
   A springtime procedure
</P>
<P>
   Consistent and rigid:
</P>
<P>
   Coats to the cleaners _
</P>
<P>
   Then weather turns frigid.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROSEMARIE WILLIAMSON
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Kirschen parked his car at an indoor garage in midtown.
The attendant went over to his wife, who was standing several feet
away, and asked her at what time they would be returning. Curious,
Kirschen asked why his wife had been queried. ``I like to go right
to the top,'' the attendant replied.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I had just missed two crosstown buses at Park Avenue and 86th
Street and, waiting impatiently, walked into the street to see if I
could spot the next one.
</P>
<P>
   A nicely dressed woman asked if there was anything in sight. I
told her there wasn't, and she asked if I wanted to share a ride to
the West Side _ she was getting out about a half-mile before my
destination. We hailed a cab and arrived at her stop so quickly
that I decided to get out and walk the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   As we paid, the driver said to me, ``Don't get out, I'll take
you the rest of the way, no problem.'' I was incredulous. ``Free,
you mean?'' I asked. He nodded and sped along. I fished in my
wallet for an additional tip but when we pulled up, he refused it.
``Well,'' I said, ``I hope you have a wonderful day, you deserve
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled and said, ``That's all the tip I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JUDY WARREN
</P>
<P>
   Nice taxi story No. 2: Before dawn, Catherine Ursillo caught a
cab to La Guardia Airport and was dropped off at Continental Air
Lines. Twenty minutes later, as she was waiting in the check-in
line, the driver appeared. He pulled out his wallet and gave her
change for the $100 bill she had mistakenly given him, thinking it
was a $20. She thanked him, of course, and offered a reward. No, he
said, and off he went. She still can scarcely believe it.
</P>
<P>
   A shopper who prefers to remain anonymous was at the Fairway
market at 74th Street and Broadway. She figured that she would have
just enough time to make her purchases and get to her appointment
with her therapist. However, with one customer asking for samples
of different meats before making a decision and more people than
usual at the prepared-food counter, she was still waiting in a long
line at the cashier when her session was scheduled to begin.
</P>
<P>
   She whipped out her new cellular phone and dialed her
therapist's office. The therapist, a regular Fairway shopper
herself, immediately grasped the reasons for the delay and the two
continued talking as the woman paid for her food and walked the two
blocks to the therapist's office.
</P>
<P>
   As the woman rang the bell, the therapist ended the call,
saying, ``I'm sorry, I have to stop now; there's someone at my
door.'' They were both laughing as the session started.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   In this day and age it is refreshing to witness restraint in the
use of uncouth expletives, no matter how apt. Recently I saw a man,
whose large dog had just soiled the sidewalk along Madison Avenue,
trying to pick up the offending pile with an amount of paper
toweling that was decidedly unequal to the task. As he struggled
unsuccessfully to hold on to the mess, he muttered to himself,
``Oh, sugar!''
</P>
<P>
   _ JUDITH WOLMAN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
