<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EBENEZER-CHURCH-MOVES     03-07 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBENEZER-CHURCH-MOVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving with the Spirit
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lord knows how many marches originated from Ebenezer
Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the members were marching for justice or civil
rights, perhaps no march was sweeter than the one they took Sunday
from their 77-year-old home to their new one 75 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from a church that held 750 to one that can hold nearly
2,000, Ebenezer entered a new era with a rousing service full of
joy and promise for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the cornerstone (of the original church) being placed,''
said Jethro English, a member of Ebenezer for 74 years. ``Now the
Lord has blessed me to walk across the street to our new home and I
am very grateful. I'm going from one degree of grace to another.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people packed Ebenezer's sparkling new Horizon
Sanctuary for the inaugural 10:45 a.m. service. Earlier, less than
half of them squeezed into the old building, the Heritage Sanctuary
_ where the likes of A.D. Williams, Martin Luther King Sr., Martin
Luther King Jr. and A.D. King preached _ to listen to current
pastor Rev. Joseph L. Roberts' final service there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful experience,'' said Terry Woods, who has
been a member of the church all of her life. ``It's kind of sad to
leave the old church, but it will still be there _ right across the
street. The new church is everything I dreamed it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   At the morning service in the Heritage Sanctuary, it was obvious
that the congregation had outgrown its home. People stood in the
aisles or sat on stairs in the balcony, while the area around the
alter was clogged with people trying to come to the microphone to
deliver prayers or testimonials.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said that because the old church, located at 407 Auburn
Ave., only held about 750 people, they often had to turn people
away. With the new 1,800-seat church, at 400 Auburn Ave., that will
no longer be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a miracle to have a new home,'' said church member Steve
Harris, busy snapping pictures of both churches. ``Especially for
the older members of the church. Their parents built (the Heritage
Sanctuary). Now they built this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking across the street after the morning service, Christine
King Farris, the sister of former Ebenezer co-pastor Martin Luther
King Jr. and the only living child of ``Daddy King'' and Albertina
King, reflected on what the old church meant to her and her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed feelings, because the Heritage Sanctuary is my
home. A lot of things are going through my head right now,'' said
Farris, whose grandfather, A.D. Williams, was succeeded as the
church's pastor by her father. ``I was born there. Baptized there.
Married there. My dear mother was taken from me there. All those
things were on my mind, when I was walking across that street.''
</P>
<P>
   Few can deny the beauty of the new facility. With a ceiling
skylight that runs along the spine of the church and high windows
along the sides, the church is bathed with light. The choir stand
and pew are huge, and African carvings adorn most of the wood in
the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am going to like this place,'' Roberts said with a
smile from the pulpit after hearing the applause cascade off the
church's fan-shaped ceiling. But he warned the congregation that
just because they have a nice, new church doesn't mean their work
is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us not get so caught up in the beauty of this house that
we forget where we came from,'' said Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said the new church has to serve as a wall of protection
around the neighborhood and its people and that they can't afford
to run away from the problems of the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do something about our streets,'' said Roberts,
refering to earlier expectations that Ebenezer would relocate away
from Sweet Auburn and the inner city. ``Yes, we could have moved.
We could have moved to the suburbs. But King never ran to the
suburbs. He didn't stay at the Peabody Hotel. He stayed at the
Lorraine. King didn't mingle with the high and mighty. He died for
garbage men. Stop running away from your problems. We have got to
make sure we keep our resources here for those who need them the
most''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the congregation has moved out of the old building, the
Heritage Sanctuary has been turned over to the National Parks
Services for daily tours starting today at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Suggs writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
