<SLUG> BC-ARPAIO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF ARPAIO ORDERS INTERNAL PROBE OF `TAILING' ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio on Sunday
vehemently denied he's ordered deputies to tail his enemies, and
said he's ordered an internal investigation into the roots of the
allegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' reported Saturday that federal
investigators are probing whether Arpaio ordered surveillance on a
laundry list of foes, including Maricopa County Attorney Rick
Romley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ridiculous,'' Arpaio said. ``Its just a product of
vile and bizarre imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the enemies Arpaio's deputies allegedly shadowed were
key figures in a lawsuit stemming from the 1996 death of inmate
Scott Norberg.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Romley, the list of alleged surveilance targets include
the dead man's father Jaron Norberg; Michael Manning, the family's
attorney; and U.S. District Judge Paul Rosenblatt, who heard the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Barnes, president of a fledgling deputy union, told the
``Republic'' he gave the FBI names of deputies who complained they
were assigned to investigate and watch Arpaio enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tailing judges and the Norbergs?'' Arpaio said, incredulously.
``This is so bizarre. This is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaron Norberg said Sunday he never felt that he was being
tailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would never have crossed my mind that would have been
done,'' said Norberg, whose son died strapped in a jailhouse
restraint chair. ``But its getting to the point where nothing would
surprise me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio revealed that deputies in his enforcement support unit do
investigate some of the sheriff's enemies, but only those who
threaten his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're following political enemies around, but
they have been concerning tracking all of these death threats
against me,'' Arpaio said. ``It has nothing to do with this other
stuff. . .about political enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said several people have threatened to kill him, one
recently broadcasting it by pirating onto the MCSO radio frequency.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff theorized that the death threat investigations are
being mistakingly perceived as Arpaio using his office to gather
dirt on enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have detectives working threats on me _ threats to kill _
and people may get confused as to what is going on,'' Arpaio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they're mixed up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said he ordered an internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know where this information is coming from,''
Arpaio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know who is making these statements and if they have
any facts,'' he said. ``We're going to find out if there's any
substance to these ridiculous allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   The internal probe will assume Arpaio did not order the
surveilance, said Chief Deputy Dave Hendershott. Investigators will
not interview the sheriff to ask him if he ordered any enemies
tailed, Hendershott said.
</P>
<P>
   The internal investigation will look into whether any deputies
did in fact tail Romley or the figures in the Norberg case, acting
on their own or under orders from someone other than Arpaio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should a deputy have done that, or course it would come out,''
Hendershott said. ``But I can tell you it didn't happen.'' &QL; 
Richard Ruelas can be reached at 444-8473 or at
richard.ruelas(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
