u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DRAW-WOMEN-650&AMP;AD     03-07 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DRAW-WOMEN-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A SEASON OF STRUGGLE, UCONN GETS A TOP SEEDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the Connecticut women's basketball team, which struggled
through a season laden with injuries, a reward arrived Sunday. The
Huskies (27-4) joined Purdue (28-1), Tennessee (28-2) and Louisiana
Tech (26-2) as top-seeded teams for the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament that begins on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 64 teams in the tournament, 30 qualified automatically as
conference champions. The other 34 were named Sunday, when the
matchups were announced by the NCAA women's basketball committee.
</P>
<P>
   The top four seeded teams in each region will play host to the
first two rounds, half of those games on Friday and Sunday and the
other half on Saturday and next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, the Big East champion for the last six years, was
seeded first in the Mideast and will open against 16th-seeded St.
Francis of Pennsylvania (18-11), the Northeast Conference champion.
Rutgers (26-5), which shared the Big East regular-season title with
Connecticut, was seeded third in the Midwest (behind Purdue and
Texas Tech) and will face Dartmouth (19-8), the Ivy League
champion.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 second-round winners will advance to the regionals on
March 20 and 22 in Greensboro, N.C. (East), Cincinnati (Mideast),
Normal, Ill. (Midwest), and Los Angeles (West). The regional
winners will move into the Final Four March 26 and 28 in San Jose,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Connecticut, the highest seedings followed
expectations. In the latest Associated Press media poll, the top
five teams are Purdue, Tennessee, Louisiana Tech, Colorado State
and Connecticut. Rutgers is ranked eighth and Notre Dame is ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has won the national championship three consecutive
seasons, but that was not a factor in the seedings. The selectors
used a formula that incorporated a team's record, the strength of
its schedule and the strength of its opponents' schedules. A team's
performance in its last 10 games was also a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette McGlade, assistant commissioner of the Atlantic Coast
Conference, heads the NCAA's women's basketball committee, which
makes the at-large selections and assigns the seedings. She said it
was safe to assume that Purdue, Tennessee and Louisiana Tech were
chosen as No. 1 seeded teams ahead of UConn. She said Colorado
State was another candidate. Connecticut was helped by a strong
nonconference schedule and an impressive end to its season after
the return of injured players.
</P>
<P>
   One of those players is the fiery Shea Ralph, now UConn's
leading scorer, who had a sprained knee. The knee is fine now, but
Sunday Ralph got a mild concussion during practice. Coach Geno
Auriemma said she would be back Monday.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth time in six years that Connecticut has
received a No. 1 seeding. Last year it did not because of an
Achilles' tendon injury that ended the season of Nykesha Sales,
Uconn's best player. The Huskies eventually lost to North Carolina
State in the regional final. This time, Auriemma did not know what
to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as us getting a No. 1 seed,'' he said after the Big
East tournament, ``I don't know. But where we go, we go. We'll pack
our bags and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Rutgers not been eliminated by Notre Dame in a semifinal
game of the Big East tournament, it would probably have received a
No. 2 seeding. Coach C. Vivian Stringer is still upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love our chances in this tournament,'' said Stringer, whose
team lost to Tennessee in the Round of 16 last season. ``I think we
are capable of going to the Final Four. We expect to get beyond the
Sweet 16. This team is one that when you say `tournament,' they
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Connecticut's seeding was hurt last year by the injury
to Sales, Notre Dame's seeding was dropped for a similar reason
this season. The Irish, who might have been seeded third or even
second, fell to fifth because of a season-ending knee injury to
Niele Ivey, the team's starting point guard, in the Big East
semifinal game against Notre Dame. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Southeastern Conference, traditionally the strongest in the
nation, landed eight teams in the tournament. The Big 12 and the
Atlantic Coast Conference placed five each and the Big East and the
Big Ten have four each.
</P>
<P>
   One of those SEC teams is Florida (19-13) despite a 6-8
conference record. This was the first time the tournament had given
an at-large berth to a team with a losing record in conference
games.
</P>
<P>
   Teams on the bubble that got in included North Carolina State
(16-11), which won seven of its last 10 games and played a strong
nonconference schedule; Maine, (23-6), which finished 9-1 and lost
to Northeastern by only two points in the American East final and
Santa Clara (22-6), which played a strong game against Colorado
State.
</P>
<P>
   McGlade said eight to 10 teams were in contention for the last
four berths. Among those not chosen, she said, were George
Washington, Western Kentucky, Kent, New Mexico and Northwestern
Louisiana. Georgetown of the Big East missed out, too. Those and
other winning but unselected teams became prime candidates for the
Women's National Invitation Tournament, a 32-team competition that
starts Thursday and will be played at campus sites.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Summitt, the Tennessee coach, spoke highly of her team,
which lost only to Purdue and Louisiana State this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern,'' she said, ``is that we don't get anxious
and quick-shoot the basketball. We have to go inside. Whether we
play against a zone or man defense doesn't matter. We're better
prepared to play against a zone than any time in 25 years because
that's all we see.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamique Holdsclaw, Tennessee's all-American, also dismissed the
theory that a zone defense would present a problem for the Lady
Vols.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything will present a problem for us,'' she
said. ``I don't think any team in America can stop us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
