<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DORAL'S MERCILESS 18TH HAS MERCY ON ELKINGTON
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was a dramatic victory for Steve Elkington, a
disgusting loss for Ernie Els and a cruel turn of events for Greg
Kraft. And when Sunday's final round of the Doral-Ryder Open was
history, the 18th hole, one of the toughest in the world, had added
to its victims. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a double-bogey by Els and a bogey by Kraft on the
final hole, Elkington claimed a suspense-filled one-stroke victory,
despite making bogey at No. 18 as well. Shooting an eight-under-par
64, including a streak of six consecutive birdies, Elkington
overcame a six-stroke deficit and won at Doral Golf Resort and Spa
for the second time in three years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elkington finished at 13-under-par 275, a stroke ahead of Kraft,
the third-round leader, who hit his second shot at No. 18 into the
water, leading to the bogey that sank his dreams. Five players tied
for third at 11 under: Els, Tommy Armour 3d, Scott Dunlap, Jay Haas
and David Toms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it was Elkington who walked away with the $540,000
first-place check, playing tremendous golf to overtake the field,
then watching as his main competitors stumbled on the final hole of
the course nicknamed the Blue Monster. It was the 10th PGA Tour
victory of Elkington's career, but he realized that in addition to
being good, he was fortunate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty lucky, wasn't it?,'' asked Elkington, the 1995 P.G.A.
Championship winner, who was so angry after missing his five-foot
putt for par at No. 18 that he kicked the scorer's trailer. ``But I
will take it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The climax was wild. Completing his round more than an hour
before Kraft and Els finished, Elkington watched on television from
the driving range, preparing for a possible playoff, only to see
Els and Kraft make miscues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Els was the first to fall, arriving at No. 18 at 13 under par,
tied for the lead. But No. 18 is a par-4, 443-yard potential
nightmare that features a narrow driving area and a large pond on
the left side that can swallow both tee shots and approach shots.
After a good drive, Els pulled an 8-iron shot from 154 yards into
the left rough near the water, about 20 feet from the hole. Faced
with a terrible lie, Els needed to hit a delicate chip shot that
would land near the pin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Els made another mistake. He flubbed his chip shot, which
landed only a few feet in front of him, and the ball rolled back
down the bank and almost went into the water. Now Els needed a
miracle _ a chip from about 20 feet, out of a another terrible lie,
to save par and to tie Elkington. It didn't happen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Els blasted his chip shot past the pin, then missed the putt
coming back for a double-bogey. For a two-time United States Open
champion, it was a humbling ending. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play good enough to win,'' said Els, who shot a 70.
``I wanted to hit the first chip on the green, but it was a really
tough lie, almost unplayable. I couldn't get myself to hit it hard
enough. I can't believe I hit that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft soon felt the same way. Looking for his first victory on
tour, Kraft birdied No. 17 to tie Elkington heading to the 18th
hole.
</P>
<P>
   But after a strong drive, Kraft made his blunder, badly
mis-hitting a 5-iron from 190 yards that never had a chance to stay
dry. Many in the crowd gasped as the ball landed in the water,
forcing Kraft to take a penalty stroke and a drop from about 90
yards. Kraft then hit a wedge shot that stopped about 10 feet short
of the pin. He made the putt for bogey and a 71 and settled for the
toughest second-place finish of the three he now has in his
career. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kraft decided to play aggressively on the final hole, and it
cost him dearly. ``I was trying to hit a 5-iron against the wind,
tilted on it and hit it heavy,'' Kraft said. ``I knew it was in the
water as soon as I hit it. I played an aggressive shot, and hit a
very poor one. I was thinking birdie.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the $324,000 second-place check was any consolation,
Kraft said: ``No. It's very disappointing, but it's not going to
stop me. I'm going to work harder. Sooner or later, I'm going to do
it right.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elkington did almost everything right early, shooting a 30 on
the front nine and making six consecutive birdies starting at No.
6, the tour's longest birdie streak this year. But he left the door
open by missing his five-foot putt for par at No. 18. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elkington angrily left the green and spent the next hour
watching from the driving range and hoping for the best. ``I was
upset,'' he said. ``I felt like I let everybody back in, and I was
pretty disgusted with myself.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he emerged a winner. With one of the game's most fluid
swings, Elkington is a premier player, but he has been plagued by
health problems the past two years, including a nasty bout with
viral meningitis last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize how sick he was,'' said Joe (Gypsy)
Grillo, Elkington's caddie. ``I was scared. I've known him for a
long time and I had never seen him like that. He could hardly move,
and he had a 105 fever. But he's O.K. now.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elkington proved that and hoped it signaled the start of good
things to come. ``I'm 36, and when you start to get older, you
focus on the big tournaments,'' he said. ``Doral kind of represents
the start of golf on the East Coast. I'm very happy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
