<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-LEE-NOODGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VOICE ON CAPITOL HILL FILLS THE SILENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House subcommittee hearing was chugging along
unremarkably enough when suddenly, out of nowhere, she piped up.
The panel's Republican chairman, George W. Gekas of Pennsylvania,
all but cringed.
</P>
<P>
   Why, he practically moaned, was Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, a Texas
Democrat, bearing down on a microphone at a meeting of a panel to
which she did not belong? Gekas' expression posed another question,
which went unspoken: Would she please just go away?
</P>
<P>
   The irrepressible Ms. Jackson-Lee lingered, lobbying Democrats
on the subcommittee to yield her a few of the minutes they were
allotted for statements. When one did, Ms. Jackson-Lee got her
moment.
</P>
<P>
   She almost always does.
</P>
<P>
   This scene last week at an inquiry into the future of the
independent counsel law, when Ms. Jackson-Lee argued against the
statute's renewal, confirmed what her four years on Capitol Hill
and her voluble role in the impeachment debate already had made
fairly clear.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson-Lee has become Congress' resident noodge, an
endlessly loquacious presence here, there and everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson-Lee, 49, says that she simply is dedicated to her
job and to her constituents in the section of Houston that she
represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have an obligation to make sure that their concerns are
heard, are answered,'' she said in an interview in her Capitol Hill
office on Thursday. The shade and cut of her purple jacket were
regal, as was the emphatic tone of her voice. ``I need to make a
difference. I don't have wealth to write a check. But maybe I can
be a voice arguing consistently for change.''
</P>
<P>
   It is her opinion that the time and money available to
independent counsels have been unchecked and that the same work
could be done in a less reckless fashion by a strengthened Justice
Department. Ms. Jackson-Lee remains astounded by the treatment of
President Clinton, and while a handful of other House members
dropped by Clinton's Senate trial once or twice, Ms. Jackson-Lee
went daily.
</P>
<P>
   She said that as a member of the House Judiciary Committee,
which had held hearings into the articles of impeachment, she
wanted to bear witness to the completion of a prosecution she
opposed. ``I know oppression when I see it,'' she said. ``I know
unfairness when I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her trial vigil surprised few colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find her an incredibly conscientious, serious, committed,
passionate public servant,'' said Rep. Tom Lantos, D- Calif.. ``I
don't watch C-Span that much, but friends of mine who do tell me
that Sheila is on whenever they turn on the set.''
</P>
<P>
   Her ambitions, she said, were not always grand. When she and her
brother were growing up in Queens, where their mother worked as a
nurse and their father as a hospital orderly, she set her sights on
becoming an executive secretary.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s assassination when she
was in high school altered her future. It triggered the creation of
scholarships for black students at New York University, one of
which she got. And it filled her with a new fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a benefactor of the hills and valleys, the broken bodies
and broken hearts, the loss of life of many who have gone on before
me,'' Ms. Jackson-Lee observed.
</P>
<P>
   She transferred to Yale University, from which she graduated in
1972, then earned a law degree from the University of Virginia.
Marriage led her to Houston, where her husband, Elwyn C. Lee, is an
administrator at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   They have a daughter, 19, in college in North Carolina and a
son, 13, in private school in Houston. Ms. Jackson-Lee never moved
her family to Washington and flies home on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   She said that her political ambitions sprang in part from her
desire to help women and black and Hispanic people get a fair shot
at success. Her seat in Congress, which once belonged to Barbara
Jordan, came after four years on Houston's City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the notice Ms. Jackson-Lee has drawn since arriving here
in 1995 has not been flattering. News reports have pegged her as an
imperious taskmaster who forces staff members to drive her just a
few blocks and who has a high turnover among employees. A former
executive assistant, Rhiannon Burruss, said in an interview that
Ms. Jackson-Lee was so rude to flight attendants that an official
with one airline offered to send the congresswoman's office a
competing carrier's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson-Lee called such accusations ``absolutely
ridiculous,'' out of date and sexist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a point when, just like any other human being,
a politician has the right to say, `That was age-old, and you leave
it be.' And then you have to prove to me you do the same kind of
thing with congressman Somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson-Lee would prefer to talk about issues like better
mental health care for needy children, one of her current concerns.
But colleagues said that her style sometimes undercut her
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat sitting near her at last week's hearing said that
when Ms. Jackson-Lee persuaded Rep. Anthony Weiner, D-New York, to
give some of his time to her, the reaction among a few other
Democrats was audible.
</P>
<P>
   ``They groaned,'' the lawmaker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
