<HEADLINE>
BEING 1ST CHARTER SCHOOL MEANS HARD WORK, DISCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTLE ROCK, Colo. _ In 1993, the Douglas County Schools became
the first Colorado district to approve a charter school, Academy
Charter.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy, said Melinda Windler, one of the parents who put
together the 600-page proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people starting a school don't have any experience in
running schools,'' she said. ``It's impossible to do it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, five other charter schools _ including one that
secured enough money to build its own facility _ have sprouted in
this hilly, picturesque region where homes in the shadow of the
Rocky Mountains are big and filled with professionals who work just
up the interstate in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 percent of the district's students occupy desks inside
these charters, higher than the 2.6 percent state charter
enrollment average.
</P>
<P>
   Each weekday morning, cars stream into the strip-mall parking
lot just south of McDonald's in Castle Rock. Doors open.
Uniform-clad elementary and middle school students pile out and
into Academy Charter School, housed in a former Super Value grocery
store.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Hart used to shop at the store. Now her children study
there.
</P>
<P>
   She also serves as the charter's office manager and deals with
Douglas County Schools, whose central office is just across the
highway from Academy Charter. Sometimes she sees the district as a
tight-fisted employer, requiring the charter to use its liability
insurance and other services and failing to mail monthly checks
promptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the big picture, we're just a little piece for them,'' Hart
said. ``But to us, it's everything.''
</P>
<P>
   She gravitated toward the 300-student Academy Charter School
because of its primary focus on reading, writing and arithmetic.
The curriculum is based on core knowledge guidelines outlined in
the 1987 bestseller ``Cultural Literacy: ``What Every American
Needs to Know''.
</P>
<P>
   Like many back-to-basics schools in Arizona, discipline is
strict. Classes are small. Learning is based on individual-learning
plans, or yearly goals.
</P>
<P>
   That appeals to many students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it better than my old school,'' announced Kaitlyn
Lincoln, a 10-year-old fifth-grader. ``I had a C, now I have an
A.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents, who must volunteer at least 20 hours each school year
to ensure their child has a spot, created this school and work for
it _ literally. They hung drywall and grabbed paintbrushes to get
it ready for students the first year.
</P>
<P>
   They could be put back to work in the near future. Plans are
being made to construct a building nearby that could be used by the
charter school and other community groups.
</P>
<P>
   There is a waiting list. You might even find a newborn's mother
adding her child's name.
</P>
<P>
   The school has had its share of growing pains, however.
</P>
<P>
   It is noisy. Like cubicle partitions, the walls in the center of
the building don't reach the ceiling. So teachers don headsets and
equip rooms with speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Three principals have either quit in frustration or been fired.
One of them was barred from the campus by a court order.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, three-quarters of the 32-member &UR; teaching staff left
because of overzealous parents. Carmen McElhinney, the art teacher,
might be the next to go. She recently recalled confrontations with
parents upset that she was teaching art from different cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're held back by politics,'' said the educator as she
watched fifth-graders sketch Mayan designs.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Smith, the school's latest principal, is trying to change
that. This fall, he began requiring parents to make appointments
with teachers instead of barging into classrooms on a whim.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Goodwin, president of the parent governing board, is most
concerned with whether the school is working for her children _ and
improving the district. For instance, the district has adopted
academic tracks for different types of students, similar to an
honors program already in place at her charter school.
</P>
<P>
   And that's important.
</P>
<P>
   After all, most Academy grads will have to return to the
district to attend high school since there isn't a charter high
school in the area. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
