<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-DEVIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLIED ISLANDERS FAIL TO COME TO THE DEFENSE OF THEIR GOALIE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ A second-period shouting match between the
Islanders' Tommy Salo and the Devils' Scott Stevens was probably
not a factor in the Devils' 4-2 victory Sunday, but it spoke
volumes about the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   First the Islanders stood and watched as Stevens bullied Ted
Donato, their finesse forward, whom Stevens outweighs by 35 pounds.
Then the Islanders allowed Stevens to taunt Salo, their starting
goalie, before 12,045 fans at their home rink.
</P>
<P>
   The victory improved the Devils' record to 3-0 at Nassau
Coliseum this season, giving them their first season sweep here.
The Devils (35-21-8) also moved within 2 points of the Eastern
Conference leader, Ottawa. The Islanders fell to 19-38-8.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils played much of the game without Bobby Holik, their
leading scorer, who was hit by an errant puck while on the bench in
the first period and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' troubles this season can be summed up by the
trash-talking between Salo and Stevens, the Devils' hardened
captain.
</P>
<P>
   They exchanged words late in the second period with the Devils
ahead, 4-2. Stevens was skating toward the exit after he and Donato
had picked up matching roughing penalties. Donato had taken a whack
at Devils goalie Martin Brodeur and Stevens cross-checked Donato
from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Salo began jawing at Stevens, who is known for not backing down.
The two wound up face to face, with Stevens motioning Salo to drop
his gloves and fight. Salo backed down as his teammates watched
from the other end of the ice. No Islander came to Salo's side.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time this season that the Islanders did not
stand up for a teammate, as hockey protocol demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actions speak louder than words,'' Islanders Coach Bill
Stewart said when asked what his team should have done. ``I guess
we'll have to do some actions _ or transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you one thing, Scott Stevens wasn't too scared.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were playing without Rich Pilon, their tough
defenseman, who missed the game after straining his back in
Saturday's 3-3 tie at Philadelphia. Eric Cairns, another tough
Islander, was summoned from the minors Sunday but did not arrive
until the second period. Gino Odjick, the Islanders' only
legitimate tough guy, is out for the season after abdominal
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stevens was pretty tough with Donato,'' said Salo, who refused
to repeat what Stevens said to him. ``We needed to get something
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said that Salo initiated the incident but that it was
not a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was yelling at me,'' Stevens said. ``I asked him what he
said, but I still couldn't understand him. But he came out of the
crease, so he was making an effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Salo and Stevens have a history. On Oct. 29 at Nassau Coliseum,
fans threw foam pucks onto the ice in disgust as the Islanders were
headed toward another loss. Stevens and other Devils began firing
the pucks at Salo, who exchanged words with them, fired the pucks
back and was not laughing after that game.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were running on fumes Sunday after their bruising
game on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, the Devils took a 2-0 lead on goals by
Brendan Morrison and Patrik Elias. Morrison scored on a breakaway
at 2 minutes 56 seconds, and Elias finished off a two-on-one
opportunity with Petr Sykora at 14:32.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders cut the lead to 2-1 on a goal by Sergei Nemchinov
at 9:39 of the second period, but the Devils answered with two
goals, by Petr Sykora and Denis Pederson, in the span of 1 minute
42 seconds. Sykora got his 22d goal of the season by beating Salo
with a wicked wrist shot at 12:59. On the power play, Pederson
backhanded the puck under the Islanders' goalie at 14:41.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders scored once more in the second period on a
power-play goal by Robert Reichel to make it 4-2 at 17:48. But they
failed to make a game of it in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Holik was hit on the forehead by an errant puck midway through
the first period. He left the bench immediately to get six stitches
from the Devils' medical staff. He was not expected to miss any
games.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Carpenter was trying to clear the puck from the Devils'
zone, but it went directly over the boards and hit an unsuspecting
Holik.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not as alert as I should be,'' Holik said. ``I didn't
want to take any chances. I feel better than when it happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
