</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERGOLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET CONCERN PLANS SYSTEM FOR SMALL ONLINE TRANSACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cybergold Inc., a company that pays consumers to
pay attention to World Wide Web sites, now plans to let consumers
make online purchases for as little as 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach, which Cybergold intends to announce on Monday,
is the industry's latest attempt at a so-called micropayment system
for the Internet _ a way to pay for information or services whose
price may be too low to warrant the expense of a credit card
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Cybergold already operates the online Earn and Spend Community,
which has 1.5 million members and enables consumers to earn money
by responding to advertisements or commercial offers. The amounts,
which are credited to a subscriber's account and can be converted
to cash or used as cybercurrency, range from 25 cents for filling
out a form for the online car buying service 1StopAuto to $3 for
purchasing a subscription to Rolling Stone magazine. Currently the
highest fee that a Cybergold member can earn is $25 for signing up
for a Visa card.
</P>
<P>
   The new system would employ electronic accounts from which
members could make online purchases of as little as 25 cents. The
approach is supposed to be simple enough that an individual author,
for example, could offer a document for sale on the Cybergold Web
site. Each time someone decided to purchase and download that
document, the price would be transferred from the reader's account
to the author's account. Other possibilities might be downloading
digital audio files in the popular MP3 format, which would enable
musicians to sell their own recordings directly. Cybergold would
take a fee of 10 to 15 percent for each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is publishing for the rest of us,'' said Nat Goldhaber, a
Silicon Valley entrepreneur, who founded Cybergold in 1996. ``I
believe that there is an audience for content that has a smaller
constituency.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Microsoft Corp. announced an ``electronic
wallet'' system last week, to be known as Microsoft Passport and
intended to let computer users pay for purchases made via the
company's MSN Web portal. Microsoft is trying to attract small
businesses to set up electronic storefronts on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Micropayment systems, which are intended to supplant traditional
currency systems on the Internet, are expected to be the means for
completing 8 of every 10 online transactions _ though only about 25
percent of the total revenue _ by the year 2002, according to
Jupiter Communications, a New York-based market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   There have been various attempts to create micropayment systems
on the Internet, including efforts by Cybercash Inc., Digicash Inc.
and the First Virtual Corp. But so far, none of these efforts have
yet been widely adopted.
</P>
<P>
   They have failed, Goldhaber said, at least in part because their
systems required users to download large software files, which then
limited the consumer to using the PC on which the software was
installed. In contrast, the Cybergold system is based on standard
Web software and can be used from virtually any computer with an
Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Goldhaber said the Cybergold system was still growing rapidly,
with 175,000 new members signed up in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
