A1136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES08-CO     03-07 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elliott, 6 others mix it up accident
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ A seven-car pileup took out a pair of contenders in
Sunday's Las Vegas 400, including Bill Elliott of Dawsonville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin, last year's NASCAR Winston Cup rookie of the year,
appeared to spark a massive pileup for the second time this season.
Irwin, who was running in the top 10 before the wreck, lost control
of his No. 28 Ford and spun in the back straightaway during the
132nd lap.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin's car knocked Kenny Wallace's Chevrolet into the wall,
knocking him out of the race. Elliott, who started 14th and climbed
as high as fifth, was t-boned between Wallace and Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Derrike Cope, Buckshot Jones of Tucker, Joe Nemecheck and Jimmy
Spencer were also involved in the wreck, but they all returned to
the track, although none finished higher than 26th.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wallace) was racing (Irwin) so hard and they came up off the
corner and Kenny just got a little bit loose,'' Elliott said.
``When they hit I thought they were gonna go up so I turned left.
But (Irwin) went up and came back down and I hit him. I tried
everything to miss him, but I just couldn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who was knocked out of the race and finished 41st, caused
a pileup in the season-opening Daytona 500 when he hit the rear of
Roush Racing teammate Dale Jarrett's Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got loose on new tires,'' Irwin said. ``It took about
10 laps to get going and with the lapped car on the outside, I
tried to go to the inside and got a little loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's crew repaired his No. 94 Ford and he later returned to
the track, where he completed 172 of 267 laps to finish 37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really encouraged a lot by how good we were running,''
Elliott said, ``but it sure is disappointing in a lot of ways. It's
definitely the best we've been in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving up
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan struggled in the first two events this season,
finishing 14th and 29th at Daytona and Rockingham, respectively.
Things didn't look much more promising at Las Vegas, where Irvan
started 40th on Sunday after needing a provisional to make the
field.
</P>
<P>
   But Irvan quickly stormed through the field. He made an
unscheduled pit stop during the 10th lap to tighten up the car and
led five laps, 64-68. He finished sixth, matching his best
performance of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good day coming off our struggle at Rockingham,''
Irvan said. ``Anytime you come from the back and go all the way to
the front and lead the race, that's what it's all about. There were
times when it was probably the best car on the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   Falling down
</P>
<P>
   Besides three drivers who didn't qualify for the race -- Robert
Pressley, Kyle Petty and Dave Marcis, Irwin took the biggest hit in
the standings points, falling 12 spots to No. 18. Stewart and
Elliott both fell nine spots to Nos. 27 and 28, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Four drivers who started the race in the first five rows, Tom
Hubert (4th), Jerry Nadeau (8th), Nemecheck (3rd) and Ricky Craven
(6th), all finished outside the top 25.
</P>
<P>
   In the pits
</P>
<P>
   It's rare that Jeff Gordon's Rainbow Warriors are out-performed
on pit stops, but that was the case in the first green-flag stop in
Sunday's race. During the 56th lap, Ward Burton's crew teams got
him out first with a 17-second pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   That equaled Mark Martin's time in the pits, and beat Gordon's
time of 18.2 seconds. Burton got out of the pits first, even though
he spun out on the infield driving onto pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pit crew has been working all winter and that's the first
time in Winston Cup that I've gone in leading and gone out
leading,'' Burton said. ``They just did a fabulous in the pits all
day long. Even when I went through the grass like a clown out
there, we still came out leading the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's second pit stop wasn't as good as his first. He took
only two tires on the stop, but then decided to come back a second
time for two more tires.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin's fortunes weren't as bad as that of Jones and
Jarrett, who both ran out of gas before making it to the pits.
</P>
<P>
   In the garage
</P>
<P>
   Craven, looking to revive his career after suffering from
post-concussion syndrome last year, took the hardest break on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Craven, who had the sixth-fastest qualifying time on Friday, was
forced to pull into the garage area after the power steering pump
in his No. 58 Ford broke. He later returned, but finished 39th
after completing only 136 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just froze up,'' Craven said. ``It started pretty early and
it got worse and worse. It got to the point where I couldn't even
steer it. It's a shame that it happened so early on, but we worked
awfully hard this week and it's getting better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd, who won the pole at Rockingham on Feb. 21, was the
first driver to retire after 115 laps on Sunday and finished 43rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We broke a valve or something,'' Rudd said. ``I guess we made
a big mistake on the first caution. I came in and we were gonna
work on the car because we started in the back, but we started off
racing about three-quarters of a lap down and got a lap down
early.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie watch
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart caught a tough break in only the eighth lap when
Johnny Benson lost it on the front straightaway. Benson's No. 26
Ford caught the right front of Stewart's Pontiac, sending Stewart
into the wall and Benson onto the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just some guy out there in a hurry, I guess,''
Stewart said. ``It must have been a 30-lap race today. They must
have changed the length of it. I thought it was 267 laps.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Elliott Sadler was involved in a wreck for the third race
in a row. During the 188th lap, Michael Waltrip's car went sideways
and hit Steve Grissom's Chevy. Sadler tried to pass in the infield,
but he couldn't avoid the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler returned during the 111th lap and finished 33rd. Stanton
Barrett, making his first start in owner Junie Donlavey's Ford,
finished 30th. Stewart holds a one-point advantage over Sadler in
the rookie of the year standings.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who made his first Cup start of the season, finished 29th
and trails Stewart by 18 points. Jones, the most popular driver on
the Busch Series last year, missed qualifying for the first two Cup
events this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't any good (in practice on Saturday) so we just
guessed with the setup,'' Jones said. ``We missed. It was way too
soft up front on the springs. But we learned a lot and changed a
lot of things on the car. I'm not getting down about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
