u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-KHMERROUGE-B     03-07 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-KHMERROUGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA SAYS IT WILL TRY REBEL LEADER IN DOMESTIC COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY _ Facing mounting calls to try Khmer Rouge leaders blamed
for the deaths of 1.7 million Cambodians, the Cambodian government
said Sunday it would prosecute the last hard-line Khmer Rouge
commander in a domestic military court.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is expected Monday to release recommendations
by a panel of jurists calling for an international tribunal to
judge as many as 30 Khmer Rouge leaders for crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The group ruled Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, imposing a brutal
vision of agrarian Marxism that led to the death of one in six
Cambodians by execution, starvation, overwork or disease.
</P>
<P>
   Observers worry that Prime Minister Hun Sen might use Saturday's
capture of Ta Mok _ the notorious ``one-legged butcher'' who had
evaded authorities for two decades _ as a chance to heap all blame
on one hated figure and absolve others now allied with Hun Sen. A
high-profile prosecution at home _ where courts are widely seen as
vulnerable to corruption and government intimidation _ might also
silence demands for an international trial, which Hun Sen could not
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``A domestic trial ... wouldn't be fair,'' Pin Sisovann,
associate editor of The Cambodia Daily, said in a telephone
interview Sunday. ``The Cambodian government should know that the
international community would never support a tribunal that would
only hold Ta Mok responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not clear whether a broader-based international trial
would be good for the nation or would reopen old wounds. That
debate rages daily in Cambodian homes and newspapers, and whichever
side prevails will shape the moral code and the political culture
of that country.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say an unbiased, international trial would heal a
broken nation, proving that crimes have consequences and squelching
a culture of impunity. Skeptics say assigning blame now could upset
a delicate peace and distract an impoverished country from
rebuilding its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen _ himself a Khmer Rouge battalion commander before he
broke with the rebels and fled for Vietnam in 1977 _ asked the UN
to consider a tribunal in 1997, but lately has spoken against the
idea, saying it could scare defectors into reigniting civil war. In
December, when two top rebels abandoned jungle hideouts where they
were waging a losing battle, Hun Sen welcomed them as VIPs, hosting
them in a five-star hotel and urging the nation to ``dig a hole to
bury the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The government feels differently about Ta Mok, 72, who never
surrendered to authorities. Still, government spokesman Khieu
Kanharith said Sunday that Ta Mok would not be sent to an
international tribunal after being prosecuted at home. ``One
tribunal for one crime and it's over,'' he told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodian Foreign Minister Hor Nam Hong leaves for New York
Monday, and is expected to meet UN Secretary General Kofi Annan
this week to discuss a tribunal. Hun Sen has said he would only
support proceedings that also hold responsible those who aided the
Khmer Rouge, such as China, the United States, and Thailand. That,
all sides agree, is hardly likely.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as Hun Sen throws up obstacles, demands for a trial are
stronger than ever. With last year's death of Khmer Rouge supremo
Pol Pot, the arrest and defections of others, and the UN report, a
growing number of people think there will finally be an accounting
for one of the century's most brutal regimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly everything is coming into place and I feel it's going
to happen. People were frightened to see the welcome given to two
Khmer Rouge leaders last December. . . . Now there is a feeling, a
momentum, an atmosphere _ this is the time,'' said Youk Chhang,
director of the Documentation Center of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   Youk Chhang lost his sister, aunts, and uncles, and was himself
tortured by the Khmer Rouge, and has devoted his life to
documenting their atrocities. He and his staff have visited 410
killing sites _ each with 100 to 2,000 bodies _ and have amassed
350,000 pages of evidence, plus photographs, tapes, and films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell the Khmer Rouge that they can torture me, kill
my sister, torture my mother, but I came back strong. The Khmer
Rouge have done so much psychological damage to us, but now we have
to face them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We collect things that are part of the puzzle, and now the
puzzle is ready to be seen,'' he said, waving at cabinets full of
numerous items such as Khmer Rouge diaries, job applications, death
orders, and crop reports.
</P>
<P>
   One human rights worker who spoke on condition of anonymity
recounted a recent dream in which Khmer Rouge leaders came seeking
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put half in my mother's house, half in my house,'' the
worker said. ``I think it's a reflection of the fear that if they
are put on trial here, it'll be a Mickey Mouse trial. If it's a
serious international trial . . . someone might kill them'' so they
don't reveal the involvement of others.
</P>
<P>
   Yet tribunal supporters say despite the risks, such a
prosecution is necessary for healing. ``This is a broken society.
Think of the population of Europe in 1945, but imagine the entire
population was survivors of Auschwitz,'' said Raoul Marc Jennar,
author of the forthcoming ``Cambodian Chronicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennar said that trying perpetrators in an independent court is
essential for a society that has come to believe people can
literally get away with murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to put a kid in jail for five years for
stealing a motorcycle if (Khmer Rouge leader) Khieu Samphan can get
VIP treatment after what he did,'' Jennar said, referring to a
rebel who was welcomed by Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in his Phnom Penh home, opposition legislator Sam
Rainsy agreed ``impunity is at the root of a never-ending cycle of
violence. Because no one has ever been prosecuted, criminals don't
hesitate to commit more crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has been tried for a grenade attack on a Sam Rainsy rally
that killed at least 16 people in March 1997 _ an attack widely
suspected to have been launched by Hun Sen's supporters. Sam Rainsy
says there have been at least four more attempts on his life since
then.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rainsy said Hun Sen doesn't want a tribunal, because it
would raise questions about his own Khmer Rouge past. ``The worst
type and most dangerous criminals are those still in power: Hun
Sen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hun Sen says if you want peace, we can't have justice, and if
you want justice, we'll have war. We should not be obliged to
choose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys indicate that three-quarters of Cambodians
support a tribunal, and conversations with ordinary people back
that up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want justice, even if it's a choice,'' said Chroy, 29, a
chauffeur. ``If there's justice, there will be peace. If we don't
bring them to trial, the next generation will walk the same way as
the Khmer Rouge.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hammarberg, the UN's special representative for human
rights in Cambodia, said it is critical ``that justice is not only
made, but is seen to be made. . . . There should be a public
apology from the state authority to the people for what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not seeking to put those old men behind bars
necessarily,'' he added. ``One could imagine they could be
pardoned.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of any trial, Youk Chhang said it is
impossible to truly punish the Khmer Rouge. ``How would they pay
back 2 million lives? Should they die 2 million times? Live in hell
2 million years? Be forced to work day and night for 2 million
years? The crimes they committed are so grave that I don't know
what punishment would be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``I think a guilty verdict would be a
start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
