<SLUG> BC-CUOMO-SUPREMECOURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TELLS OF COURTSHIP TO GET CUOMO ON HIGH COURT
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Behind-the-scenes efforts to get Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York to
change his mind and accept a Supreme Court nomination came within
15 minutes of success in 1993, but just before President Clinton
was to make the offer Cuomo called the White House to forestall it,
George Stephanopoulos, the former presidential adviser, says in a
new book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the president to think that I might say yes _ the
president shouldn't call me,'' Cuomo was quoted as telling
Stephanopoulos in a 5:45 p.m. call, pre-empting an offer brokered
by Stephanopoulos and Andrew Cuomo, the governor's son and
political adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was listening to Cuomo in disbelief,'' Stephanopoulos
writes, ``Andrew called. `This is a 180-degree turn from
yesterday,' he said. `I'm sorry.' I was, too. The game was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos relates the Clinton-Cuomo pas de deux over the
nomination that never was (for a seat to be vacated by Justice
Byron White) in a 456-page memoir, ``All Too Human: A Political
Education,'' published this week by Little, Brown. Excerpts appear
in the March 15 issue of Newsweek, out on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Sunday about the account, Cuomo referred to his own
diaries and said he had received only one call from Clinton about
the nomination _ from Air Force One about a week earlier, on April
1, 1993. After several days of intense speculation, Cuomo made
public a letter to Clinton removing himself from consideration and
saying he could better serve as governor and in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the withdrawal, Stephanopoulos said, he and Andrew Cuomo
began quietly trying to change the governor's mind and to get
Clinton to make an offer. ``Andrew and I were caught up in the
world's oldest courtship ritual,'' he wrote. ``He was telling Cuomo
that Clinton really wanted him; I was assuring Clinton that Cuomo
really wanted him.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort came close, Stephanopoulos said, with Cuomo ``on
board'' and Clinton saying that ``Cuomo should expect a call around
6 p.m.'' But, Stephanopoulos said, Cuomo's 5:45 call put an end to
the episode.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said on Sunday that he had no recollection of that call,
but added, ``If George says I called him, I'm sure I called him.''
Cuomo lost the governorship to George Pataki in 1994 and is now a
lawyer who speaks often on public affairs. He said he had no
regrets over his decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
