r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-CSUNWOM-LADN-(SLA     03-07 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CSUNWOM-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN, UCLA NCAA-BOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First the euphoria, then the business.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the excitement of seeing their school's name on television
_ on the NCAA selection show, no less _ some Cal State Northridge
women's basketball players had to ask, ``WHO are we playing?''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, it's Colorado State. Northridge (21-7) received the
15th seed in the West and will play the second-seeded Rams (31-2)
Friday at 9 p.m. PST in a sub-regional at Fort Collins, Colo. The
game will be televised live on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State and UC Santa Barbara are also in CSUN's
half of the bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Also as expected, UCLA will host a sub-regional at Pauley
Pavilion on Saturday at 9 p.m. The Bruins (23-7) earned the West's
third seed and will take on No. 14 Wisconsin-Green Bay (19-9), with
the winner getting either Kentucky or Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second straight tournament appearance for the
Bruins, but it's the first for Northridge. Players, coaches and
fans congregated in the Presidential Suite at the Warner Center
Marriott to watch the selection show.
</P>
<P>
   No one cared where the team was going and few were surprised
Colorado State is the destination. Northridge officials had talked
with Big Sky Conference officials (there was one Big Sky member on
the seeding committee), who told them to expect a trip to the
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's official, what do the Matadors know about their
opponents?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely nothing,'' guard Edniesha Curry said. ``They're
ranked No. 4 and they got beat by (Southern Methodist). I don't
know anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing to expect: The Rams will key on Curry, who was second
in the conference with an 18.3-point scoring average. In the
conference tournament, she scored 24 and 23 points in the two
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to focus on me, then fine,'' she said. ``It's
been like that for all my years at Cal State Northridge. With a
great team like this, and with the chemistry we have, and with the
depth we have, it creates problems. You can't focus on just Eddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State is led by All-American point guard Becky Hammon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll watch tapes and get to know them, and devise a plan,''
Northridge coach Frozena Jerro said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had lost three of its last eight games to fall out of first
place in the Pac-10. But the Bruins rebounded with victories over
Arizona State and Arizona. Coupled with Stanford beating Oregon on
Thursday, UCLA reclaimed a share of the conference title, its first
in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a lull,'' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said. ``We
played such a strong nonconference schedule. Everyone we played,
they're in the tournament (actually, eight of 12 are). It took a
toll on us down the stretch. We lost focus and almost got relaxed.
We always said we needed to finish strong to stay at home and the
players rose to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the victories over the Arizonas and the Bruins found
themselves in as unfamiliar territory as Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   After beating Arizona on Saturday, the team ran off the court as
it always does, only to have athletic directors and sports
information people bring them back to take a bow and cut down the
nets.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will the host Midwestern Collegiate Conference
champion Wisconsin-Green Bay Phoenix, led by senior Chari
Nordgaard, who averaged 22.4 points a game and shot 64 percent from
the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
