u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SPEAKER-NYT &LR;      03-07 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SPEAKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEW SPEAKER ERRS ON REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, March 8:
</P>
<P>
   After two months in office, House Speaker Dennis Hastert is on
his way to making the very mistake that helped destroy Newt
Gingrich. Despite overwhelming bipartisan support in the House for
campaign finance reform, which could lead easily to its swift
passage, Hastert has bottled up the legislation in committee until
later in the year or next year. This is Gingrich-style
obstructionism with a more genial face. Supporters of reform need
to get ready for a renewed battle, including a petition drive to
force the bill to the floor by spring.
</P>
<P>
   The fight started late last month, when Rep. Christopher Shays
of Connecticut and Martin Meehan of Massachusetts reintroduced
their ``soft money'' ban. House rules prevent the start of
collecting signatures for a petition until next month. But
conservative pro-reform House Democrats, led by two Texans, Jim
Turner and Charles Stenholm, have already informed Hastert that
they will take the petition route if he does not yield. Some
Republicans are already prepared to join them. Last year, Gingrich
was humiliated by the success of a similar petition effort. The
same fate awaits Hastert if he does not rise to this first test of
his sincerity in wanting to change the atmosphere in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill would outlaw unrestricted soft-money
donations to parties from corporations, unions and rich
individuals. It passed the House last year by a vote of 252 to 179
and has even more support this year. Hastert says he is
concentrating right now on avoiding another legislative debacle
like last year's, which occurred when Republican squabbling over
taxes and spending blocked passage of a budget resolution. His
aides say he also wants to allow consideration of two other
Democratic favorites, the minimum wage and a patient's bill of
rights, before campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   These tactics are a smokescreen. There is no reason for the
minimum wage or health care to preclude early consideration of the
Shays-Meehan bill, which was debated endlessly last year before it
was passed. Even with the difficult budget schedule, there is a
window of opportunity to do campaign finance reform in April and
May, after the scheduled passage of a joint House-Senate budget
resolution and before appropriations bills are considered toward
the fall. That window should be the target date of all supporters
of reform.
</P>
<P>
   Fast action is needed because, although a majority of senators
favor reform, there are not yet 60 votes to block an expected
filibuster led by Trent Lott and Mitch McConnell. Reformers need
time to wage a campaign of pressure on senators before the campaign
season starts next year. The Senate logjam is not a foregone
conclusion. Recently, McConnell, the leading opponent of reform,
said that some form of compromise on the issue was ``worth
discussing.'' His words clearly reflect the anxiety of senators,
who know that voters are demanding an overhaul of a corrupt system.
Once the presidential campaign heats up, hundreds of millions of
dollars in soft money from special interests will pollute the
system. Hastert must not be allowed to thwart the demands of the
public, and his own members, to clean it up. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2246EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
