<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITIANS-BOATS-COX     03-07 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITIANS-BOATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    40 refugees feared dead off Florida coast
 &HT;    By John Holland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Estinvie Celius is waiting for his family
to wash ashore.
</P>
<P>
   They crammed onto a 17-foot boat in the Bahamas last week, his
son, three nephews and about a dozen other Haitians paying big
money for a seat on a rickety boat and a better life in South
Florida. Now they are among 40 presumed dead at sea, victims of
perhaps the most deadly smuggling mission in Florida history.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Coast Guard called off its search for survivors Sunday
morning, a day after two boats carrying 43 Haitians foundered and
sank 26 miles east of West Palm Beach. Three men were rescued, but
their conflicting stories and the slim chance of recovering the
boats dampen hopes of finding out exactly what happened, Coast
Guard officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol agents say the gas-powered boats _ one a
17-footer, the other 20-feet long _ carried no life preservers and
were part of an organized smuggling operation out of the West End,
Grand Bahama Island. Bahamian authorities found two trucks and
trailers Saturday at a public boat ram used to launch the vessels,
said Art Bullock, head of the Border Patrol office in West Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Celius said he talked to his 21-year-old son and three nephews
last Monday night, just before they left St. Mark in Haiti for the
Bahamas. He expected them to arrive Friday night, but then heard
about the sinking through news reports over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he and more than a dozen men and women gathered at
the Haitian American Community Council in Delray Beach awaiting
word on whether any bodies had been found and praying that their
relatives would have a proper burial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they didn't get on the boat; I'm calling (Haiti) but I
think they are gone,'' Celius said quietly through an interpreter,
wiping his eyes and nose with a white handkerchief. ``I want to
find the bodies so I'll know for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Four men's bodies have been recovered, leaving 29 men and seven
women missing. Agents believe the smugglers died with their
passengers, although officials are still searching Grand Bahama
Island to make sure they aren't hiding out.
</P>
<P>
   The three survivors were not involved in the smuggling
operation, Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pure speculation as to what happened out there (at sea),
and the Border Patrol is still gathering information,'' Coast Guard
Lt. Commander Mark Woodring said. ``I don't expect to see any
bodies or wreckage. Traditionally, that far out, people get caught
up in the Gulf Stream and just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   The search began about 2 a.m. Saturday after crewmembers of the
Tomis Faith, a freighter from Malta, heard screams in the water and
saw flashing lights 30 miles east of West Palm Beach. Two Coast
Guard cutters and 12 helicopters and planes looked for survivors
over a 2,600 square mile area, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter found the first survivor, weakly trying to stay
afloat as he grasped a propane tank, at about at about 5 a.m., and
two others were found clinging to a barrel at about 8 a.m. All
three survivors, one man in his late 30s, one in his early 40s and
another in his 20s, were treated for hypothermia, and questioned by
the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors were taken to West Palm Beach hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Pierre, who was on the boat carrying 25 people, remains
hospitalized in stable condition at Good Samaritan Medical Center,
while the other survivors are being held at the Krome Detention
Center near Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Two boats, one carring 16 men and two women, the other 20 men
and five women, left Grand Bahama Island during the night late last
week, according to relatives, Coast Guard officers and Border
Patrol agents. About 30 miles off shore, the small boat began
taking on water and the second boat attempted to help, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, both vessels were under water, taking most of
the passengers with them, according to agents' interviews with
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The drownings are the latest in a deadly 12 month which has seen
nearly 60 Haitians and Cubans die trying to reach American shores.
On Dec. 17, a 29-foot boat capsized in 6-foot high seas off Elliott
Key, some 22 miles south of Miami. Nine Cubans drowned and another
five were lost at sea and presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard and Border Patrol officials said Saturday's
smuggling disaster was the deadliest in Florida's history.
</P>
<P>
   Oppressive conditions at home and the promise of a better life
in Florida entice many Haitians to pay smugglers up to $3,000 per
trip, members of the Haitian community in Palm Beach County said
Sunday. Unless the Haitian and American governments can restore
economic and political stability in Haiti, more smuggling and
drownings are certain, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have peace, real safety in our homes and on our streets,
we won't come to the U.S.,'' said Jean Detreffe, who left Haiti two
decades ago and now owns a transmission shop in West Palm Beach.
``People never know when they'll be shot or attacked in their home.
If (street gangs) know you have money, even a little money, they
are going to come and take it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no control, no police in Haiti right now,'' added
Derrilus Jean, another Haitian immigrant. ``As long as it's out of
control, dangerous, more people are going to die trying to get
here.''
</P>
<P>
   John Holland writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Palm Beach Post wire services contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
