<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS CELEBRATE PASTOR'S RELEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a worship service that felt at turns like a rock
concert and a religious revival, more than 2,000 people gathered
Sunday in an old movie house in Queens to celebrate the freedom of
the Rev. Frank Almonte, proclaiming it a clear sign that in times
of crisis, God works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus is our man in battle,'' shouted Carlos Jimenez, an
assistant to Almonte. ``He led our pastor to victory. He can defeat
any enemy. He will lift us through any hardships. Glory, glory to
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Almonte walked slowly to the stage. And as he turned to look out
at the cheering crowd, even he, a man who believes in miracles,
seemed awestruck.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is so wonderful,'' he said. ``Blessed is the name of the
Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   It was from the airwaves of Radio Vision Cristiana, heard from
New York to Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic at 1330 AM, that
Almonte built his growing congregation of more than 1,600 people,
most of them immigrants, in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his most rousing sermon, however, was delivered last
month in a five-minute telephone conversation from jail. It was a
call that galvanized immigrants from across the city to demand
freedom for the minister and to protest recent immigration reforms.
And it set Almonte, a 40-year-old father of three sons, on a new
mission to make sure that no other immigrant ever has to endure
what happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   The minister had been arrested on drug charges when he arrived
at Kennedy International Airport from his native Dominican Republic
and customs officials discovered 300 steroid tablets in his
suitcase. The pastor explained that the pills were available
legally and over the counter in the Dominican Republic, that he
bought them at the suggestion of a Dominican doctor to help improve
his son's appetite, and that he had no idea they were illegal in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, customs agents shackled the pastor, who had no previous
criminal record, and took him to jail. And because of the felony
arrest, the Immigration and Naturalization Service moved to deport
Almonte, who has lived legally in this country for 23 years and
whose sons are American citizens.
</P>
<P>
   On the Sunday after his arrest, Almonte called his church, the
Adonai Christian Center, from jail. His voice cracking over a
loudspeaker, the minister told his flock that they must practice
the faith he had taught them, and he urged them to pray.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the church decided the time had come to do more than
pray. They called people on prayer lists to raise support for their
pastor, and circulated petitions. Radio evangelists made Almonte's
arrest the focus of their talk shows. And immigrants' rights
advocates criticized America's laws in interviews with Hispanic
newspapers and television programs.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Almonte appeared for arraignment at the Queens
County courthouse, more than 1,000 people were there. And last
week, when Almonte appeared in court again, the size of the crowd
outside had doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the drug charges against him were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are on the radio with just a microphone, you feel
like you are alone,'' he said. ``But this has made me realize that
I am not alone. From that microphone, I was able to reach the
hearts of many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Almonte said that in his 23 years in America, he had never
participated in demonstrations, nor used his church to push
political agendas. But since the rallies on his behalf, Almonte
said he had warmed to the idea of participating in political
causes, adding that he would work to change America's immigration
laws.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, he has one more legal battle of his own: he is
still under threat of deportation.
</P>
</TEXT>
