<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUBRICK-OBITUARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY KUBRICK, MASTER FILMMAKER, IS DEAD AT 70 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick, the last of the great cinema artists of the
20th century, died Sunday at age 70 in his home outside London. No
cause of death was given by his family.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from one genre to the next in a 45-year career _ jabbing
and weaving from the epic story of ``Spartacus'' (1960) to the
intimate adaptation of ``Lolita'' two years later _ the Bronx-born
filmmaker mixed form and function with unmatched wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicholson, a longtime friend who delivered one of his
finest performances as the deranged writer-husband-father in Mr.
Kubrick's ``The Shining,'' was devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy was just so great,'' Nicholson said Sunday from his
home in Beverly Hills. ``This is a loss for everyone. We've never
had anyone like him, both as a man and a filmmaker. He's in a class
by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In an industry that relies on passing fads and hopeless cliches
to feed the appetite of the nation's box office, Mr. Kubrick took
his time. He had the last open-ended deal with a studio _ in his
case, Warner Bros. Mr. Kubrick selected his material, created his
production schedule, and oversaw everything from the script to the
finished film with no pressure or interference from the studio. He
was, in the truest sense of the word, an independent. And he wasn't
in it for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York, Mr. Kubrick showed very early promise as an
artist with a camera. When he was 14, he earned $100 from Look
magazine for the first of a number of assignments and was hired
there as a staff photographer when he was 17.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, he sold his first film, ``Day of the Fight,'' a
16-minute-long documentary, to the RKO film studio.
</P>
<P>
   In a time when the words ``artist'' and ``genius'' are used to
describe everything from hairdressers to baseball players, perhaps
we should create new words to describe Mr. Kubrick. He was so far
ahead of everyone else, they may never catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Even his films of the '50s, particularly ``The Killing'' (1956),
a magnificent film noir starring Sterling Hayden as the brains
behind a race track robbery, and the ironically titled ``Paths of
Glory'' (1957), could have been made Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kubrick made 13 feature films. ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' starring
Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, his final movie, is slated to be in
theaters this July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him why he didn't make more movies,'' said Nicholson,
while recalling the many hours the two men spent talking on the
phone about boxing, movies, and life in general over the years. ``
`Well, Jack,' he said. `You really wouldn't want me to get bored
making movies, would you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He was never bored. And he certainly never bored us.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kubrick never went for cheap thrills. Even in his most
controversial work, ``A Clockwork Orange'' (1971), which was
criticized for the ultra-violence it decried, Mr. Kubrick never
took the easy way out. He appreciated complexity, embraced
ambiguity, and danced with enigmas. His plans were never simple,
and his vision never failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' (1968) remains the most personal
science fiction movie ever made _ and Mr. Kubrick shot it in
widescreen Cinerama. Watching it Monday is like seeing a brand new
film. While more than 30 years old, there's nothing dated about it.
There were sequences in the film, particularly the stargate montage
toward the end, where Mr. Kubrick had to reinvent the technology in
order to find the cinematic equivalent of his imagination. He had
to put his planned next film ``A.I.'' (for Artificial Intelligence)
on hold because cinema couldn't technically accommodate his
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were making our picture,'' said Nicholson, referring
to ``The Shining'' (1980), ``he had already started thinking about
`Eyes Wide Shut.' He just hadn't come up with an ending. I remember
when he called and told me he came up with an ending but he
wouldn't say what it was. Stanley didn't go into battle without
being fully prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks ``Saving Private Ryan'' is the definitive war
film should take a good, hard look at ``Full Metal Jacket'' (1987).
Mr. Kubrick understood that the Vietnam War was not an aberration
but a brutal, uncomfortable outgrowth of American culture. It
wasn't a matter of hawks and doves, it was the inevitability of
violence as the logical extension of manifest destiny that drew Mr.
Kubrick to the material.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same theme he brought to the equally brilliant ``Dr.
Strangelove, or, How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb''
23 years earlier. While Peter Sellers was remarkable in his many
roles, it was Slim Pickens, riding the bomb as if it were a bucking
bronco, that gave the film its crowning image.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Shining,'' Mr. Kubrick wasn't content to simply make a
terrifying horror film. He wanted the terror to be personal, to get
under our skins, to hit us where we live. He took a rather
one-dimensional story of a family ``getting away from it all'' and
transformed it into a tale of abuse that went back generations.
When Nicholson, the deranged writer, stalks his only son in the
snowbound maze at the film's conclusion, it's not an act of madness
but a logical extension of the psychic pressures that had built up
over time. In many ways, it's more Old Testament than New Wave.
</P>
<P>
   Some myopic viewers only saw Mr. Kubrick as a technocrat, more
concerned with the special lenses he had ground for particular
shots than in developing dramatic themes. Nothing could be farther
from the truth. Mr. Kubrick developed the technology only to
actualize the humanity of his films.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Christiane, and three daughters from a
previous marriage. Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2249EST &QL; 
