<HEADER>
A1149 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLORADO-AZR &LR;      03-07 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORADO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARTER SCHOOLS SLOWLY NURTURED IN DENVER AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ When Rex Brown proposed a charter school in the city's
urban center, it wasn't state education officials he had to win
over. Or the community. Or the parents.
</P>
<P>
   He had to win over the competition _ the public school district.
</P>
<P>
   Under Colorado law, charters must petition public school
districts for permission to operate. The districts decide what
charter schools can open within their boundaries, what goals the
charters must achieve, even how the charters are to be funded.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, charter schools are a small, controlled experiment.
Their performances are analyzed each year by the state education
board, their licenses must be renewed every three to five years,
and only 60 can exist at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado is something of a national model for how to nurture
charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Miles away in neighboring Arizona, a younger charter school
movement is bounding ahead, growing furiously and with few
restrictions. The explosion includes 270 charter schools to date,
accounting for almost a quarter of all charter schools in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   This is often cited as a criticism: That the charter law passed
in 1994 is too loose because it allows the movement to be too
large.
</P>
<P>
   While only the school districts in Colorado have authority to
sponsor a charter school, there are three ways charters can come
into being in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   School districts, the Arizona Board of Education, and the state
Board for Charter Schools each can sponsor charter schools. The two
boards are limited to 25 new charters a year, but a district can
sponsor any number, inside or outside its boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Charter leases can run 15 years, and the law doesn't force the
sponsors to evaluate the schools' quality.
</P>
<P>
   All of which has captivated national observers of charter
schools, and most are more skeptical than impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wild West is what we call Arizona. It's too loose,'' said
Brown, executive director of P.S. 1, an ethnically and economically
diverse charter school in inner-city Denver where students build
homes, stroll through the nearby art museum and work in tattoo
parlors as part of their education.
</P>
<P>
   Brown had to wage a two-year campaign to win sponsorship for his
school. By having to plead his case to the public school board, he
said he had to scrutinize his proposal from all financial,
administrative and educational angles.
</P>
<P>
   That depth of scrutiny doesn't exist in Arizona, a state that
national educators say seems more concerned with quantity than
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Jim Griffin, executive director of the
Colorado League of Charter Schools, say the Grand Canyon State
should have a better system for evaluating charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``By having district-level sponsorship only, accountability (in
Colorado) is clear,'' said Eric Hirsch, an education specialist at
the National Conference of State Legislatures, a nonpartisan
research group based in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 34 states with charter-school laws have a similar
system, wherein districts are the sole sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The concept sounds contradictory _ the apparent equivalent of
Burger King asking McDonald's for permission to open a franchise _
and at times those seeking to create charter schools certainly feel
the system is stacked against them.
</P>
<P>
   When the first wave of charter applications hit Denver Public
Schools in 1993, district school board members balked at approving
them. Student population growth had been stagnant, and allowing new
schools meant the loss of tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And board members were far from impressed with the proposals for
new schools. Said district spokesman Mark Stevens, ``the board
wasn't going to allow city students to go to these schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Into this climate walked Rex Brown with his proposal for P.S. 1,
a school with an untraditional bent: lax classrooms, few exams,
heavy emphasis on out-of-class projects.
</P>
<P>
   The first year Brown pitched P.S. 1, the board instructed him to
fine-tune the idea before it would even consider it. The next year,
it took the unprecedented step of approving the school without
giving it any funding.
</P>
<P>
   Brown appealed to the state board of education and, in the third
year, won. In 1995, P.S. 1 opened in the city library. Today, the
school is housed in an overhauled warehouse that had once been a
bank. Community members also use the building for gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. 1 has no grades, no credits and little structure. The
campus is in effect all of Denver: students are given bus passes to
ride city buses to and from school, to the city library, and to
field trips to places like Colorado rivers to study water
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   The diverse mix of students learns about urban life and how to
become part of it. Standardized test scores are some of the highest
in the Denver district.
</P>
<P>
   Brown credits the success, in part, to the rigorous approval
process P.S. 1 had to go through.
</P>
<P>
   As in Arizona but on a lesser scale, Colorado districts have
responded to the charter school phenomenon by offering new
programs. One Colorado district, faced with an application for a
charter school for gifted students, opened its own gifted school.
Another started a back-to-basics district school because of parent
demand. But these are exceptions to the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Colorado education officials say charter schools' impact
on traditional schools here has been minimal compared to the
situation in Arizona, where districts have responded by offering an
array of innovative programs.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, charters tend to offer programs that public
district schools already offer, some educators say.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the Denver Public Schools spokesman, said that the
district's 120 schools already were providing many alternatives to
traditional learning when charters came on the scene. Within the
district, there are Montessori schools, art-based and gifted magnet
schools, vocational and pre-professional schools.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he and other Colorado officials say that charters
have a legitimate place alongside traditional schools, even if they
must undergo an arduous process to prove they could thrive on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Rick O'Connell, for one, believes he is proof that an open mind
can make the coexistence of charter and traditional schools work.
The Douglas County Schools superintendent embraced the untested
charter-school concept while many of his peers felt threatened by
it.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said it wasn't easy when parents told him he wasn't
adequately serving their children and that charter schools could
better meet their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he knew charters had great potential.
</P>
<P>
   Charters can take the pressure off overburdened district schools
by reducing student numbers. Pupils are flocking to O'Connell's
district, located in one of the fastest-growing counties in the
country. In one year, 10 schools had to be constructed, and school
calendars were extended year-round to make room for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charter schools are one of the best things to happen to
Douglas County,'' said O'Connell, who came to the district two
decades ago when there were 3,000 students. Now, the district hosts
30,000 pupils with 3,000 more coming aboard each year.
</P>
<P>
   Both Colorado and Arizona are bursting with children. Maricopa
County also is one of the nation's fastest growing counties.
</P>
<P>
   Critics fear that Arizona's lax charter school law sets up many
schools for failure, for reasons ranging from the possibility of
fly-by-night operators to well-intentioned educators who have no
financial acumen to keep the business afloat.
</P>
<P>
   They fear more cases like Citizen 2000, a charter school whose
founder was accused of using $100,000 state money to buy a home and
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it should be easy,'' said Brown of the P.S. 1
school, ``to start a public school.'' &QL; 
Kelly Pearce can be reached at 444-7981 or at
kelly.pearce(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
