<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1150 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN     03-07 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS INDY THE FAST TRACK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The hot topic is where they are: Indianapolis,
site of the 1996 Princeton debacle. The relevant issue is where
they are not.
</P>
<P>
   They are not in the East.
</P>
<P>
   They are not with Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we weren't in the East,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said,
``a lot of kids were excited.''
</P>
<P>
   For good reason. With the dominating Blue Devils as its No. 1
seed, the East Region is ground zero for early exits in the 1999
NCAA Tournament. The Bruins had a 1-in-3 chance of landing there,
and they'd rather face a hundred Princetons than wander into Duke's
path early in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you want to avoid the No. 1 team in the country,''
UCLA forward Sean Farnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Bruins are seeded No. 5 in the South Region and
will play Midwestern Collegiate Conference champ Detroit, the No.
12 seed, on Thursday in the RCA Dome in Indianapolis. (Tipoff time
will be announced today, but expect no earlier than 7:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   If they win, the Bruins will face either Ohio State or Murray
State in Saturday's second round. (Keep in mind: Murray State is no
longer coached by former UCLA assistant Mark Gottfried; he's at
Alabama.)
</P>
<P>
   Auburn is the South's No. 1 seed and UCLA's potential Sweet 16
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the seed we deserved,'' Bruins guard Baron Davis said.
``It's a nice environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they got the best No. 5 seed possible. They avoided
Duke, Connecticut and Michigan State _ the obvious No. 1s _ and
were packaged with an Auburn team that has no substantive
nonconference victories and lost to Kentucky in the Southeastern
Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the South appears to be the weakest region: None of the
top seeds (Auburn, No. 2 Maryland, No. 3 St. John's and No. 4 Ohio
State) won their conference tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the Bruins' 17-point loss at Arizona on Saturday
was a blessing. As expected, the winning Wildcats became a No. 4
seed and were shipped to the Midwest Region, the tournament's
toughest, while the Bruins became a No. 5 and were sent to the
weakest.
</P>
<P>
   Had UCLA won in Tucson, the teams probably would have switched
positions _ their records and power ratings are almost identical _
placing the Bruins in the Midwest alongside Michigan State, Utah
and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a spot in the Midwest could have created a
second-round collision with Jim Harrick and 12th-seeded Rhode
Island, and no one in Westwood wanted any part of that circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we have to do is focus on ourselves and Detroit,''
Farnham said. ``The tournament is a one-game process. If you
overlook one team, you'll get bounced out so quick you won't know
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (22-8) know enough about Detroit to know another
Princeton-esque fate awaits if they're poorly prepared mentally and
strategically.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans (24-5) defeated St. John's in the tournament last
year and probably would have received an at-large berth Sunday if
they hadn't won the MCC title.
</P>
<P>
   They defeated Gonzaga on a neutral court in December and lost at
Iowa by one point. They have a tough, defensive-minded coach, Perry
Watson, who was an assistant at Michigan during Lavin's tenure at
Purdue in the early '90s. They have a sparkling guard tandem in
Rashad Phillips and Jermaine Jackson, an NBA prospect. And they'll
be playing as close to home as L.A. is to Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're one of the top defensive teams and they're similar to
Miami in that way,'' Lavin said, referring to UCLA's smothering
first-round opponent last year. ``It'll be an unbelievably
competitive game.''
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, they almost always are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
