u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NY     03-07 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS SAY INVESTIGATORS SOUGHT DAMAGING INFORMATION ON DIALLO
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers for the family of Amadou Diallo said Sunday
that police investigators searched for damaging evidence and
questioned Diallo's roommates in an effort to taint his character
in the hours immediately after the fatal shooting of the West
African immigrant by four police officers last month.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, who accused the police of trying to ``dirty up''
Diallo's background, said they were calling on local and federal
law enforcement officials to broaden their investigations into the
death of Diallo, who died in a barrage of 41 bullets fired by the
four officers on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawyers, Peter J. Neufeld, said Sunday that Diallo's
Bronx apartment was thoroughly searched by investigators, and that
Diallo's roommates were taken to the local police station house in
the Soundview section and questioned for hours about his habits
without being told that the police had killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld said that police investigators emptied two wardrobes in
Diallo's bedroom, removing all of his clothes and leaving them in
piles on the floor, and then took the curtains and curtain rods off
the windows. While the four police officers who shot Diallo were
not questioned because Bronx prosecutors feared it could jeopardize
their criminal investigation into the shooting, the victim's
roommates said they were asked about Diallo's character and whether
he had any enemies, Neufeld said. The allegations were first
reported Sunday in The Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutionally, you have a situation where police officers
become the only class of suspect who are not promptly questioned
about their conduct when a crime may have occurred,'' Neufeld said
Sunday. ``They are also able to abuse their authority to dirty up
the victim and cover up for their fellow officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Watters, another lawyer for the Diallo family, said Sunday,
``This is a further indication that the New York Police
Department's common or ordinary course of business when the police
are involved in possible criminal activity is that they try to find
out something bad about the victim and protect their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani referred questions about the allegations
to the police department. Inspector Michael Collins, a police
department spokesman, said he could not comment because the Diallo
case is still the subject of a grand jury investigation in the
Bronx. Steven Reed, a spokesman for the Bronx district attorney,
Robert Johnson, said he could not say whether the grand jury would
look into the police department's handling of its inquiry into the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   One of Diallo's roommates, Abdou Rahman Diallo, said that when
he was questioned extensively at the 43d Precinct station house
immediately after the shooting, he had no idea that it was police
officers who had killed Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were asking if he had enemies,'' Abdou Rahman Diallo, who
is a cousin by marriage, said Sunday. When the six-hour interview
ended, he said, the detectives asked him whether they could do
anything for him, and he replied, ``All I want is for you to help
me find out who killed Amadou and why Amadou was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not until he returned to his apartment at 1157 Wheeler
Ave. around 7 the next morning, he said, that he got a telephone
call from a reporter informing him that it was police officers who
had shot his roommate.
</P>
<P>
   A senior police official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said: ``It would not be uncommon for investigators to
talk to the roommates or search his room. They couldn't talk to the
officers, and they were still trying to find out what he was doing
on the street that night.''
</P>
<P>
   The police official said it was possible that detectives might
not have immediately told the two roommates who were questioned
that Diallo had been shot by the police, for fear they would not
cooperate, but he could not imagine why they would not tell them at
the end of the interview.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, when police officers have shot people, police
officials have revealed the criminal records, if any, of the
shooting victims.
</P>
<P>
   Amadou Diallo was unarmed when he was shot and had no criminal
record, officials said after he was killed. His friends and family
described him as a hard-working and pious man who neither drank nor
smoked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
