<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-FUND-RAISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR HIRES A FUND-RAISER WITH NATIONAL EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In what aides are describing as the most concrete
sign yet that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is planning to run for the
U.S. Senate next year, his main political action committee has
hired a finance director with broad experience in national
Republican fund raising and a strong background in Senate
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The finance director, Laura Van Hove, who started last week, has
limited New York experience but a strong command of federal
campaign finance regulations, former colleagues said. Since 1990,
she has worked on three Senate campaigns, on Bob Dole's 1996
presidential campaign and for the Republican Senatorial Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Her addition to the political action committee, Solutions
America, suggests that the mayor is concentrating his efforts on
running for the Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick
Moynihan. Giuliani's advisers said they were moving quickly to
capitalize on intense national interest in a possible contest
between the mayor and the first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani, in public, has repeatedly said he has made no
definite decision about his plans, some of his associates have said
that a clear signal, if not a formal declaration of his candidacy,
could come within the next three weeks. Hiring a finance director
is a crucial step in preparing for any such announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's highly public consideration of running for the
New York seat has energized campaign contributors in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last several weeks, the interest that I have seen in
the race has increased dramatically,'' said Bruce Teitelbaum,
executive director of Solutions America, ``specifically with
respect to those who want to lend support to the mayor's
campaign.'' Teitelbaum, the mayor's former chief of staff, has been
laying the groundwork for Giuliani's political future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was important to hire someone with the expertise in
a federal campaign,'' Teitelbaum said. ``Laura has extensive
experience in fund raising on the presidential, Senate and
congressional levels,'' he added. Ms. Van Hove was recommended to
him by Republicans in Washington, Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Van Hove's national skills could just as easily prove
useful in a presidential or vice presidential run, the mayor's
aides have said it is unlikely that Giuliani will seek the
Republican nomination for president. The mayor has also suggested
he would show particular deference to two likely Republican
presidential contenders: Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John
McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues of Ms. Hove's and aides to the mayor say she has
experience in raising both ``hard'' money, contributions given
directly to candidates, and ``soft'' money, unregulated
contributions to political parties and committees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
