<SLUG> BC-ALLIED-WASTE-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIED WASTE SEEN IN DEAL TO ACQUIRE BROWNING-FERRIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ariz.) (lb) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what is believed to be one of the largest leveraged buyouts
since Kohlberg, Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.'s hostile takeover of RJR
Nabisco in 1988 for $25 billion, Allied Waste Industries and two
investment firms, Blackstone Group and Apollo Advisors, are
expected to announce as early as Monday that they are acquiring
Browning-Ferris Industries, another waste-services company, for
about $7.1 billion in cash, executives close to the talks said
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of Allied Waste and Browning-Ferris met Sunday and
are believed to have approved the deal late Sunday night. Allied
and the investment firms are offering $45 a share in cash for
Browning-Ferris, a premium of $10.25, or 29.5 percent, over the
company's closing stock price on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They would also assume Browning-Ferris' long-term debt of about
$2.5 billion, bringing the total value of the deal close to $10
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But as with any deal, the agreement could fall apart if all
parties do not sign the deal documents.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Allied Waste and Browning-Ferris
have been reported to be in talks or in some kind of joint
operation. Last May, Allied Waste was reportedly interested in
buying Browning-Ferris for about $7 billion. More recently, in
February, the companies announced a definitive agreement to
exchange certain service assets, including customer contracts,
equipment and facilities representing $120 million in acquired
revenues to each party.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Browning-Ferris' stock price rose $1 to close at
$34.75 in heavier than normal volume. Traders attributed that stock
rise in part to a Bear Stearns research note that speculated that
Browning-Ferris could be a takeover target of the French waste
company Sita. Stock-options trading in Browning-Ferris at the end
of last week was heavier than usual too.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Waste, for its part, plunged $5 on Friday _ or 25 percent
_ to close at $15. As a result of the stock dive, the New York
Stock Exchange asked the company to issue a statement outlining any
corporate developments that might have affected the stock price.
The company did not issue a statement then.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have long considered Browning-Ferris a turnaround play.
Allied is likely to merge overlapping operations _ including
collection, truck routes and landfill properties _ to increase
revenues and profits. Operating through a network of 109 collection
companies, Allied runs 69 landfills and provides solid-waste
management and handling for 2.2 million customers in 28 states.
Browning-Ferris collects refuse in 46 states, Puerto Rico and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Browning-Ferris, which is based in Houston, is the United
States' second-largest waste-services company, after Waste
Management Inc. Allied Waste, which is based in Scottsdale, Ariz.,
is No. 3, although it has a much smaller market capitalization, of
$2.7 billion, than Browning-Ferris.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Allied, the two other partners involved in the buyout
are Blackstone, which was started in 1985, and Apollo Advisors,
which is led by the financier Leon Black. The two companies invest
in ailing companies _ either outright or with a minority stake _
with the expectation they will sell them in the future for a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a stock swap where companies exchange shares, investors
in a leveraged buyout borrow debt to pay for a company. The three
parties are expected to borrow a total of about $11 billion to
complete the deal, one executive said. But that loan will be
reduced by the end of the year after the sale of some of the
combined operations assets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
