<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STRANGE-330&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC IS BEHIND THIS ANNOYING CONSPIRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC enters the lively sweepstakes Monday for most
incomprehensible TV show.
</P>
<P>
   The entry is ``Strange World,'' a midseason ``X-Files'' wannabe
that makes practically no sense at all.
</P>
<P>
   It's also dreary, if that's any consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange World,'' which moves to its regular time slot Tuesday,
is about a deadly virus, a Desert Storm veteran and USAMRIID.
</P>
<P>
   Confused already? OK, Desert Storm was the Gulf War back in '91.
Seems that Paul Turner (series star Tim Guinee) was exposed to
toxic chemicals during the war and now perspires all the time.
</P>
<P>
   He's kept alive by some mysterious serum that is secreted to
him, one dose at a time, by a character known only as Asian Woman
(Vivian Wu).
</P>
<P>
   And he is recruited, against his will, to join USAMRIID (U.S.
Army Medical Research Institute, and, no, I don't know what the
``ID'' means.)
</P>
<P>
   So he's supposed to be a government agent fighting abuses of
science and medicine _ Monday's pilot apparently involves cloning
children _ but he seems to have landed smack dab in a sinister
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   USAMRIID, or the FBI, or both, or neither, are responsible for
the conspiracy, the aim of which seems to be to confound and
irritate the American television viewing audience, and to force it
never again to watch sci-fi shows on the American Broadcasting Co.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I know that brighter bulbs than I will make sense of
``Strange World.'' If I had any brains, would I be a TV critic?
</P>
<P>
   The show is created by Howard Gordon, an ``X-Files'' import who
wrote Monday's program with Tim Kring. ``Strange World'' has that
damp, dim Vancouver look, and the production team has successfully
wrung all traces of levity from the program.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy buffs are never giddy with laughter, I've noticed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ ``RedHanded'' is a UPN thing with a Fox veneer, only tackier.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Erik Nelson of ``Busted on the Job'' fame has created
another hidden-camera show to catch people in the act of being
dishonest, venal or just plain obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   In the first installment, airing Monday, the show puts the sting
on a guy who steals everything that isn't nailed down in his hotel
room. Entrapped and confronted by ``RedHanded,'' he tries to blame
his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say that there are no future Nobel laureates on
this program. The tone, the attitude and even the off-camera voice
of the commentator, comedian Adam Carolla, are reminiscent of the
``You Don't Know Jack'' computer games.
</P>
<P>
   Looking on the bright side, it's better than ``The Secret Diary
of Desmond Pfeiffer,'' a show UPN will never be allowed to live
down.
</P>
<P>
   The allotted time is seven weeks. If ``RedHanded'' catches on,
it's a candidate for fall. Stop it now, before it kills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
