<SLUG> BC-SILICONALLEY-CASH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK'S NEW MEDIA COMING TO SAN FRANCISCO  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Start spreading the news: When it comes to new
media and money, New York concedes San Francisco's superiority.
</P>
<P>
   What else explains today's Alley to the Valley conference? For
the second year in a row, a lineup of companies from New York
City's ``Silicon Alley'' new-media district are coming to the
Sheraton Palace Hotel in San Francisco to look for some of those
Silicon Valley venture dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, New York can learn a lot from California investors
and can offer a lot to California investors. There's a tradition of
technology-related venture capital in California, and we want to
learn the way that they think,'' said Charles Millard, president of
the New York City Economic Development Corp., a city agency that's
co-hosting the conference with AlleyCat News, a monthly magazine
for investors in New York's new-media industry.
</P>
<P>
   Companies presenting this week include Bikini.com, cha!, The
Duck Corp., and Absolute Reality.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Alley also has produced numerous public companies well
known in the Internet world, including Theglobe.com, N2K, EarthWeb,
24/7 Media and DoubleClick,
</P>
<P>
   ``More companies have had IPOs in New York than anywhere else in
the country,'' Millard said. ``We want California venture
capitalists to be aware of the tremendous strength and diversity of
New York companies.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the New Yorkers hope that West Coast exposure could
lead to other deals, such as mergers, acquisitions and joint
ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's silly to think you'd only merge two companies on the East
Coast,'' said Janet Stites, editor of AlleyCat News. ``You're
talking about the Internet, this global technology.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's technology industry was born out of the advertising
and publishing trades, Stites said. At first, big companies'
new-media divisions were ``the unwanted stepchild,'' she said, but
eventually the people doing that work left to start their own
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now technology has expanded beyond new media _ companies
presenting this week include Renal Tech, a biotech firm _ and it
has grown increasingly important to the New York economy.
Conference literature says high tech in New York has doubled in the
past two years, with 2,600 companies employing more than 55,000
workers and generating about $3billion per year.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has become a key part of the city's redevelopment
efforts, Millard said. New York is developing small Internet-ready
offices and has inked 160 leases on such spaces in the past three
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everywhere you go. You hear people on the subway talking
about Web sites,'' Stites said. ``I wonder where traditional media
companies are getting their talent because everyone wants to be
involved in the cutting edge.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference runs today and tomorrow. Information is at
www.alleyvalley.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
