<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-AINGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS LABELED SLACKERS  
 BUT AINGE THINKS TEAM WILL RECOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Blunt as usual, Suns Coach Danny Ainge said Sunday
that his team has lacked discipline, toughness and smarts on too
many occasions this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a second home court loss to the Sacramento Kings,
Ainge said the Suns just aren't as good as they assume.
</P>
<P>
   It's a stinging assessment, but plenty of evidence supports all
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's what I feel,'' Ainge said Sunday as the Suns
began to pick up the pieces before traveling to Dallas for a game
Tuesday night. ``We just come out to play the game and play to the
level of the competition, whatever that might be. We think we can
turn the switch and it's going to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it's going to take for them to realize
that's not the case. It's hard enough for great teams to do it, let
alone a team that has to scratch for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he doesn't want to overemphasize what happened
against the Kings, and he believes the Suns will recover. But he
said the club's struggles now go beyond the NBA lockout and its
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that stuff,'' he said. ``I think it's a lack of
discipline. I'm trying to instill discipline, but if you have
people who won't listen to what you're trying to teach, you have a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge didn't single out players, but he said he's perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need discipline at both ends of the court because we don't
have superior talent,'' he said. ``We have to be able to execute
and be willing to play at a high intensity level. It seems like we
either have to play a great opponent or be down by 15 in order to
reach that high level.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the Suns have sunk to the bottom of the NBA, but
they don't have the depth of talent to coast through games and flip
on the afterburners to win at the wire.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what they have attempted to do. Their pattern through
the first 13 games was to fall behind early, make a big run to get
back into the game and hope for the best at the end. They appeared
to have broken that cycle, despite two losses to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But as forward George McCloud put it, the Suns ``took a step
backward'' against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked a lot about being physically, mentally and
emotionally tough,'' Ainge said. ``I thought we failed in all three
categories.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing consistent in this lockout-shortened season has
been inconsistency, but a few things have become apparent:
</P>
<P>
   The Suns don't have much of an inside game. The additions of Tom
Gugliotta and Luc Longley give the club some firepower, but they're
not strong on the post. In fact, point guard Jason Kidd has been
the team's most efficient player on the block.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns are weak on the boards. They've been outrebounded in
six consecutive games. They rank 20th in the league in rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   When they play hard defensively, the Suns are very effective.
But they usually play soft on defense until they're in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   When Rex Chapman's is shooting well, the Suns are at their best.
But he hasn't been effective often enough. He's shooting 32
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta, who was playing at an All-Star level at the start of
the season, hasn't played that well of late. A sore back, which
Gugliotta can be seen stretching out during timeouts, probably has
contributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a better player than he's showing,'' Ainge said of
Gugliotta. ``He needs to take responsibility and play better. I
need to take responsibility for finding ways of using him, and
putting combinations (of players) on the floor that better utilize
his skills.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns are 9-8 and have won only four of nine games at America
West Arena. If the playoffs had begun Sunday, the Suns would have
been tied with San Antonio for seventh in the Western Conference
and only one game ahead of Sacramento, which has the head-to-head
tiebreaker against Phoenix already.
</P>
<P>
   The top eight teams in the conference will go to the playoffs,
and with the easiest stretch of their schedule gone in February,
the Suns can't take their 10-year playoff streak for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of good players who have experience, they're
smart, they can pass,'' Ainge said. ``But we always have to match
the intensity and play smarter than the opponent. We have not done
that consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what this team is capable of achieving yet, but I
know it's capable of more than we're getting. I've seen the best
side of us and the worst side. The worst side is like the worst
team in the NBA. The best side can compete with the best teams in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my job and my responsibility, to have this team achieve
what it's capable of achieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team will respond, I believe.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
