<HEADER>
A1280 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-INTERNET-SF     03-07 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INSURANCE PLAYING INTERNET CATCH-UP  &HT;     By JAMIE BECKETT 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Kaye knew he was paying way too much for his car
insurance: $1,400 a year just for liability coverage on his Dodge
Dart.
</P>
<P>
   So when his policy was ready to expire, the 24-year-old shopped
around _ on the Web. With a few clicks of a mouse, he was able to
get full coverage, including collision and comprehensive, for just
$800 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, a Web-savvy consumer who owns a San Jose business
designing microprocessors for small appliances, is still a pioneer.
Not many consumers are shopping for insurance online because not
many insurers are offering it. Unlike the banking and brokerage
industries, insurance has been slow to embrace the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Online sales of auto, homeowners and term life insurance totaled
just $155 million last year _ less than 1 percent of all premiums,
according to Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cambridge, Mass., firm expects online insurance sales to
balloon to $4.1 billion by 2003 as a growing number of insurers
overcome regulatory and technical hurdles to offer quotes,
information and sales on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, most insurance sites let you comparison shop and
complete an application online. But some still require an agent to
actually sell you the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe insurance is a huge market because of the inherent
convenience of being able to shop for your product without any
pressure and complete a transaction in a fraction of the time it
now takes,'' said Steven Aldrich, president of financial
software-maker Intuit's insurance unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain View company's Web site, www.insuremarket.com, went
up in 1996 and now offers term life, auto (but not yet in
California) health and other types of insurance from several
different insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some insurers have their own Web sites _ State Farm
(www.statefarm.com) provides quotes for auto and life insurance.
Progressive sells auto insurance at www.progressive.com. But much
of the growth in online insurance is coming from ``malls'' that
represent multiple carriers, such as InsWeb, Intuit's InsureMarket,
InsureRate (life only), QuickQuote (life), Quotesmith and others.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, independent insurance agents have offered one-stop
shopping for decades. But the online malls think that they can do
it for less.
</P>
<P>
   InsWeb _ founded in 1995 in Redwood City by Hussein Enan, a
former insurance executive, and software entrepreneur Darrell
Ticehurt _ pioneered the mall concept. Enan got the idea when he
saw how easily his son bought a CD on the Internet. Enan figured he
could do the same for insurance. His site, www.insweb.com, offers
quotes for home, auto, life and health insurance. InsWeb lets
customers do everything but pay for a policy online.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Shopping for insurance has been a pretty tedious business,''
said Ticehurt, InsWeb president. Consumers typically must telephone
several carriers, provide information or fill out forms, collect
rates and then make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   By gathering quotes and information from several carriers in one
place, www.insweb.com is designed to let consumers comparison shop
and save time, too, Ticehurt said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The company provides quotes from 32 carriers, though not all
carriers sell all types of insurance in all states. In California,
for instance, drivers can get quotes from nine or 10 carriers. Like
all of the insurance malls, InsWeb is busy adding carriers and
expanding service.
</P>
<P>
   The site does not yet allow customers to purchase online _
instead, they get a quote and are contacted by the insurer.
However, that quote is guaranteed as long as the buyer provided
accurate information.
</P>
<P>
   A few companies concentrate on just one type of insurance.
</P>
<P>
   HealthAxis (www.healthaxis.com) offers health coverage for
individuals (a $20 billion market) and small companies (a $50
billion market).
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of INSURANC () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; ``This is probably the largest untapped area of the Internet,''
said Andrew Felder, chief operating officer of the Norristown, Pa.,
company.
</P>
<P>
   Launched at the end of last year, the fledgling site has just
five carriers so far, but it is up and running in most states,
including California. Unlike most insurance sites, it lets
consumers buy online.
</P>
<P>
   HealthAxis is working to add dental, vision, disability and life
insurance, Felder said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers have been slow to migrate to the Web, Gazala said, in
part because of technical and regulatory complexities. Each state
has its own rules for insurance, and each insurer has its own set
of insurability standards. &UR;  &LR; What's more, insurance is an inherently
risk-adverse business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry that's all about protecting (against) the
downside. A lot of the managers are very cautious people,'' Gazala
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he expects that to change because consumers are eager to
shop the Web. ``The online insurance market will be up for grabs,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
