<HEADER>
A1282 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-KUBRICK-COMMENT &LR;      03-07 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KUBRICK-COMMENT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUBRICK: A MOVIE MAVERICK TO THE END 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD GUTHMANN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word ``maverick'' gets tossed around awfully carelessly in
the movie world. Express an opinion, show a rebellious streak and
suddenly you're a maverick, a woolly ``independent'' who can't be
corraled.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that talk is self-serving hoo-hah, but in Stanley
Kubrick, the brilliant filmmaker who died Sunday at 70, the
qualities of independence, perfectionism and pureness of vision
were uniquely crystallized.
</P>
<P>
   In 45 years as a filmmaker, spent largely in isolation in his
adopted country of England, Kubrick never drank at the trough of
safe, audience-friendly formulas. His films drew from genres as
diverse as horror (``The Shining''), film noir (``The Killing''),
sexual satire (``Lolita''), space exploration (``2001: A Space
Odyssey''), dystopia (``Clockwork Orange'') and period costume
drama (``Barry Lyndon''), and yet the world they captured was
largely constant: a place where dread is real, disorder is rampant
and our efforts to master the world's moral void are inevitably
useless.
</P>
<P>
   A Kubrick film was alive with ideas, artistic rigor and a formal
technique that some found cold: the slow, ominous zooms, the
austere sets that seemed to swallow or diminish the actors, the
meticulous composition and camera placement. His most popular work,
``Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the
Bomb,'' is a savagely funny black comedy from 1964 that dared to
mock U.S. defense policy, right-wing paranoia and the arrogance of
the American military at the height of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   His films puzzled and confounded, encouraged debate and inspired
reverence among his fans. The opening of a new Kubrick film, so
infrequent because of his painstaking work habits, was occasion for
celebration. Only Terrence Malick (``The Thin Red Line''), who
shares Kubrick's reclusiveness, isolation from Hollywood and
intellectual adroitness, could claim that same allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, that loyalty grew despite the fact that Kubrick revealed
little of himself, avoided the press and shunned the American cult
of celebrity. A native New Yorker and graduate of Taft High School
in the Bronx, Kubrick became a staff photographer for Look magazine
at 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a skinny, unkempt kid who carried his cameras in a paper
bag,'' he once remembered, ``so he wouldn't be mistaken for a
tourist.'' When photography proved ``too passive,'' he turned to
filmmaking, educating himself by watching movies at the Museum of
Modern Art in New York. By 29, when he made the anti-war classic
``Paths of Glory'' (1957), Kubrick was being compared to Orson
Welles.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times piece from 1958 described him as a ``slightly
elusive, seemingly diffident young man who talks little ... and
makes astonishing movies.''
</P>
<P>
   When Premiere magazine ran its annual list of Hollywood's 100
most powerful people a couple of years back, a reader wrote in to
chide the magazine for omitting Kubrick. Who else but Kubrick, the
reader demanded, had the power to make films at a safe geographical
distance from Hollywood, without interference, and with absolute
control over every detail of his films?
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick shot one scene for ``Paths of Glory'' 58 times. When
``Dr. Strangelove'' was rereleased to celebrate its 30th
anniversary, Kubrick personally restored the film, photographing
his own print, frame by frame, to create a new negative master.
</P>
<P>
   On his last film, the still-unreleased ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
Kubrick reportedly shot and reshot endlessly _ obsessing over
details, changing his mind, tying up the schedules of stars Tom
Cruise and Nicole Kidman. I say ``reportedly'' because the film was
shrouded in secrecy, as so much of Kubrick's life and work were.
Warner Bros. plans to release the film in July.
</P>
<P>
   The greatness of Kubrick's legacy can't be judged by his films
alone but by the inspiration he gives to young filmmakers. We've
all heard horror stories of studio interference and films altered
beyond recognition, but a budding director can always look to
Kubrick's example _ to his fearlessness, obstinateness and refusal
to walk in lockstep with the pack _ to fortify the creative spirit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
