<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANEX-MOVIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SPECIAL-EFFECTS FIRM CREATING ILLUSIONS AT NAVAL BASE  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMEDA, Calif. -- It's a cinematic illusion that defies gravity
and time: Keanu Reeves and an opponent _ both suspended in midair _
engage in a climactic gun battle. While the camera swoops around
and through the action at full speed, bullets pass by in slow
motion.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is from ``The Matrix,'' a Warner Bros. sci-fi movie
opening April 2. It represents a breakthrough in special effects _
the first time a moviemaker could take the viewer anywhere in a
full-motion, live action scene.
</P>
<P>
   An Alameda company, Manex Entertainment Ltd., made the
impossible a reality with new equipment and digital wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a first step toward virtual cinema,'' said Manex general
manager Robert Bobo. ``Any camera move you can dream of, you can
do; the director can dial in from any point of view.``
</P>
<P>
   Manex is making a major name for itself in special effects. Its
creative director is a top contender for a special effects Oscar
for ``What Dreams May Come,'' the Robin Williams movie lauded for
its awesome depictions of heaven and hell.
</P>
<P>
   But special effects is just one arm of the company's business.
Manex is attempting to turn &UR;  &LR; most of the old Alameda Naval Air
Station into Hollywood's newest outpost with a trio of ventures:
special effects, soundstage rentals and its own movie studio.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this summer, Manex Filmed Entertainment will produce
two to four &UR;  &LR; feature films a year, drawing on Bay Area talent,
locales and crew.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to start with moderate-budget films for which it will
provide effects at cost. Manex executives point to Miramax and New
Line Cinemas as role models.
</P>
<P>
   Encamped in the Alameda base's vintage 1940s Navy funk, Manex
currently looks more like a shoestring startup than a Hollywood
power player. Bobo, its 28-year-old leader, seems more scoutmaster
than movie mogul.
</P>
<P>
   But Bobo says the firm, which is 90 percent owned by a private
Ohio financial management company, the Manex Group, can raise the
tens of millions of dollars it will need to launch its own studio
and produce films that cost $15 million to $40 million each.
</P>
<P>
   The company grew out of a Massachusetts visual effects firm
called Mass Illusions. It moved to Alameda a year ago, mushroomed
from 10 people to 100 and grossed $12 million in 1998, largely from
the effects business. Bobo declined to discuss profits.
</P>
<P>
   For now, creating special effects is Manex's bread and butter,
though it has plenty of competition from effects houses ranging
from George Lucas's gargantuan Industrial Light &AMP; Magic in Marin to
hundreds of Silicon Valley and Hollywood firms.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Hynek, Manex's visual effects supervisor, is an Oscar
candidate for ``What Dreams May Come.'' He spent two years working
on the film's lush depiction of heaven as an Impressionist
masterpiece. Hynek previously was nominated for effects for
``Predator'' and won a special technical achievement Academy Award
for an optical printer he designed.
</P>
<P>
   Low-key and personable, he ducks the inevitable questions about
the Oscars, just saying it was a delight to work on a movie that
married ``technology and fine arts.''
</P>
<P>
   But film mavens aren't so restrained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday in the future, we'll look back at `Dreams' as a
benchmark that expanded the visionary palette of directors,'' said
Tom Atkin, executive director of the Visual Effects Society in
Sherman Oaks (Los Angeles County).
</P>
<P>
   Manex just expanded its staff and its Hollywood presence by
buying special-effects house Computer Film Co. of Culver City (Los
Angeles County). With 30 people and credits on this year's other
two special-effects Oscar nominees (``Mighty Joe Young'' and
``Armageddon''), CFC ``is a perfect alter-ego for us,'' said Bobo.
``It's an award-winning company with a beautiful Hollywood
screening room,'' perfect for sealing power deals.
</P>
<P>
   Manex is continuing to blaze new trails in special effects. For
``Matrix,'' it honed a technique called Flo-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   For the gun-battle scene, the effects pros first created a
digital, photo-realistic, 3-D image of the subway station based on
photographs of a real subway station.
</P>
<P>
   Then they videotaped the battle with Reeves and his co-star from
multiple camera angles and transferred it to a computer to create a
``body track'' that would control the final filming.
</P>
<P>
   Then they positioned an array of still cameras in front of a
green screen.
</P>
<P>
   The actors then recreated the battle as the still cameras fired
sequentially in a precisely timed sequence.
</P>
<P>
   The still photos were scanned into a computer, where a
programmer melded them together into a continuous action sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the action footage was integrated into the digital 3-D
background, and the computer-generated slow-motion bullets were
added.
</P>
<P>
   Manex plans to use this technique to create ``virtual back
lots'' _ digital stock footage of famous locales that can be used
to create spectacular effects without the expense of shooting on
location.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it could make a 360-degree, navigable film of the
Eiffel Tower, shoot an actor on a green screen and insert him in
the famous landmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a yawn if he just walked around,'' said Manex's
John Gaeta, visual effects supervisor on ``Matrix.'' ``But we can
fill the tower with marshmallows and have them dripping down onto
him, or have him _ and the camera _ fly around and through it, or
make it the year 2050 with a red sky.''
</P>
<P>
   When it's not cooking up effects, Manex takes advantage of the
cavernous buildings sprawled over the base. It has long-term leases
on five huge airplane hangers, totaling 260,000 square feet, which
it rents out as sound stages to the likes of Warner Bros., Walt
Disney and PolyGram.
</P>
<P>
   Disney plans to shoot its big-budget Christmas feature,
``Bicentennial Man,'' on two of Manex's stages and at one on
Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   Power tools whine and sawdust dances in the air as two dozen
carpenters pound plywood into sets for ``Bicentennial Man.'' Right
now, they look like nothing more than an unfinished deck and a
backyard pool enclosure, but by the time the movie starts filming
in April, they will be transformed into the futuristic world where
android Robin Williams fights for his civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The two largest stages, 80,000 square feet each, lease for
$45,000 a month or $2,900 a day. The smallest, at 19,000 square
feet, goes for $22,500 a month or $1,600 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Drab tan on the outside, inside the hangars are well suited for
filming. There are no supporting beams to obstruct camera views.
Several come outfitted with cranes that can lift up to five tons.
Others have movable gantries attached to the ceiling, perfect for
camera operators and lights. A filtering system, installed to
dispel fumes from airplane paint, can be used to quickly clear
smoke or other atmospheric effects.
</P>
<P>
   Traces of the military remain: Chest-tall letters on the walls
still shout out Navy messages such as ``Committed to quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, although movies from ``True Crime'' to ``Flubber'' have
already been filmed in these hangars, the buildings aren't yet up
to most filmmakers' standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see them made into real soundstages, not just
warehouses where you can shoot,'' said Rory Enke, a location scout
for Disney. ``Right now, when the foghorns go off on the Bay, you
hear it. If the Blue Angels come, you lose a day of shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   During the next two years, Manex plans to bring the hangars up
to building code and to rig them for moviemakers with sound
abatement, blackout control and more electrical installations _ to
the tune of $5 million, said Dale Skaggs, vice president of
operations and studios. The company will get part of that back in
rent rebates from the base.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the soundstages, Manex provides other on-site services
to filmmakers: It rents out lighting and grip equipment, has a
35,000-square-foot warehouse for storing sets and props, and
provides stage managers who are familiar with the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``It's smoother because it's managed by people who understand
all of our quirks,'' Enke said. ``Manex makes it very simple for a
motion picture company to find a home in the Bay Area.''
</P>
<P>
   The base offers another amenity: real-life sets. The Navy left
behind an array of buildings that evoke small-town America: a post
office, a chapel, a bowling alley, a movie theater, a tree-lined
street with '60s-style ranch houses, another with colonial-style
houses _ both unobstructed by power and telephone lines. Of course,
there also are props for a military movie, including a fleet of a
dozen ships, an aircraft carrier, an airplane control tower and
barracks. And the island boasts breathtaking views of San Francisco
and the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Manex competes with two other former Navy bases _ Treasure
Island and Mare Island _ for movie shoots, and with a handful of
privately run soundstages in San Francisco for small-scale shoots,
such as commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Filming on Treasure and Mare islands is arranged through San
Francisco and Vallejo, respectively. Both cities welcome filmmakers
and offer some of the same amenities as Manex.
</P>
<P>
   Manex is helping make the East Bay more of a nexus for movie
shoots, said Ami Zins, Oakland's film coordinator. ``They're a big
part of my pitch'' to filmmakers, she said. ``They're 10 minutes
from downtown Oakland, with total ease of parking and
transportation. They have vast spaces, incredible ceiling clearance
and they have the capability and willingness to accommodate a great
variety of sizes of production,'' from big-budget feature films to
one-day commercial shoots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
