<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRANKLIN-FINAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBILL WINS TUNEUP TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Sunday's singles final in the Franklin
Templeton Tennis Classic had a little bit of everything.
</P>
<P>
   There was a rain delay, fierce competition, a controversial call
and a first-time ATP Tour champion.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, 21-year-old Jan-Michael Gambill of Colbert, Wash.,
outlasted 18-year-old Australian Lleyton Hewitt, 7-6 (7-2), 4-6,
6-4, at at the Canadian Pacific Princess Resort.
</P>
<P>
   The match, filled with long volleys, took 2 hours and 21 minutes
to complete. That's not counting a 46-minute rain delay between the
second and third sets.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial call went against Hewitt, who was at break
point in the third set that would have given him a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill's second serve hit near the line and was called out by
the linesman. But chair umpire Steve Ullrich overruled the call.
Gambill ended up winning the game to make it 4-4. Gambill won the
next two games and the match.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual for an umpire to overrule a linesman unless the
umpire absolutely believes the call was incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt displayed his displeasure. He said he was sure it had
been out. Gambill said he believed it had been in.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it changed the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my momentum, and his was going down,'' Hewitt said.
``That call lifted his confidence. It got the crowd behind him
again. And he got some great serves.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the rain delay hurt Hewitt's game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so, a little bit,'' he said. ``He came out and did a
little better than I did right after the delay. I had the momentum
at the end of the second set, but he got off to a quick start after
the delay, and it helped build his momentum.``
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt said he'd be helped if he got stronger and a few more
cheap points with his serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did have a little better serve,'' Hewitt said, ``My serve
was stronger than it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there was quite a bit of difference in the serves.
Gambill had 11 aces, Hewitt two. But Gambill had four double
faults, Hewett only one.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt is known as a counter-puncher who keeps the ball in play.
Gambill is more of a power player. It showed Sunday. Gambill had 46
unforced turnovers, Hewitt 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of good wins,'' Hewitt said, ``and it increased my
confidence. What I have to do is forget this loss and play well the
next two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time the two players have met.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about us meeting again,'' Hewitt said. ``He
has a great game. I expected him to serve well and hit some
winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he surprised to be playing Gambill?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was anticipating playing (Andre) Agassi,'' he said. ``I
think everyone was.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, the second-seeded player, injured a hamstring during his
semifinal match with Gambill and was forced to retire in the first
set.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill was exhuberant follow ing his match. He not only won his
first singles title but also beat the top player in the world, Pete
Sampras, in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels great,'' Gambill said. ``It feels even better
because it was such a tough match. There were a lot of long rallies
today. It was a war out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my game is really coming along. My volleys were a
lot more solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill welcomed the rain delay. He said he thought it had
helped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had time to think about it, figure things out,'' he said.
``I'd quit attacking. I stepped it up, and serve and return were
better in the third set.''
</P>
<P>
   In the doubles finals, Justin Gimelstob of Miami and Richey
Reneberg of Atlanta beat second-seeded Mark Knowles of the Bahamas
and Sandon Stolle of Australia, 6-4, 6-7 (4-7), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   The doubles winners split $22,600; the losers $13,290. The
singles champ received $46,000; the loser $27,000. The tournament
drew 55,863 in attendance, compared with 45,166 a year ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
