<SLUG> BC-MANEXSIDE-MILITARYBASES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CLOSED MILITARY BASES ARE OPENING DOORS FOR FILMMAKERS  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bay Area, with its stunning views and cultural amenities,
has long been a favorite of filmmakers for on-location shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But the shuttering of three former local military bases _
Treasure Island, Alameda Naval Air Station and Mare Island _ has
created opportunities for moviemakers to do far more work in the
Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   All three facilities have colossal _ and now empty _ airplane
hangars, warehouses and other buildings that can be set up as
soundstages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be the only reason you came to San Francisco was to
shoot the Golden Gate Bridge, Coit Tower and other landmarks; then
you'd go back to L.A.,'' said Rory Enke, a location scout for
Disney. ``Now, you can shoot the entire picture here.''
</P>
<P>
   Treasure Island, run by the city of San Francisco, was first to
get in on the act. It started renting space to moviemakers a couple
of years before the Navy finished moving out in October 1997. The
TV show ``Nash Bridges'' has a permanent home in Building 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage the use of the island for filming,'' said
Annemarie Conroy, executive director of the Treasure Island
Development Authority. ``It's a great PR thing for Treasure Island
and the city. It's very lucrative to attract films to the city _
the spending power of these large productions is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities tend to greet moviemakers, known for their lavish
spending, with unreserved glee. A major motion picture might employ
several hundred people _ both imports from Hollywood and local
hires _ and they all need housing, transportation and food. During
location shoots, residents sometimes gripe about hassles with
parking and noise, but those aren't problems on the nearly
deserted &UR;  &LR; former bases.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's ``Bicentennial Man'' will start shooting in April on
the Treasure Island and Alameda sites. ``What Dreams May Come,''
``Flubber'' and ``Jack'' were shot mostly on the former bases.
</P>
<P>
   Those movies all have something in common: They star San
Francisco resident Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin Williams is a mini-industry all by himself; he prefers
to work up here for family reasons, and with his clout, he can get
what he wants,'' said independent location scout Lance Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Besides scenery and soundstages, the Bay Area has another draw
for filmmakers: Dozens of special effects, sound editing and
animation shops give the region an edge for post-production work,
and it also can draw on the technical expertise of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having stage space is very important to the development of the
film business in San Francisco and the Bay Area. It's like an arm
or a leg; it makes it possible for major feature films to stay here
in the Bay Area,'' said Carole Isaacs, acting director of the San
Francisco Film &AMP; Video Arts Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
