<SLUG> BC-NY-OFFICE-SURGERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS PERILS IN SURGERY IN DOCTORS' OFFICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patients who undergo surgery in a doctor's office
instead of in a hospital are protected by few regulations and face
dangers like outdated anesthesia equipment, according to a report
by a New York Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by the Senate Committee on Investigations, Taxation
and Government Operations, called office surgery ``an entirely
unregulated area of medicine in New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem, it said, was that some doctors performed surgery in
their offices that was outside their specialty. Hospitals, on the
other hand, verify that a doctor is qualified to perform a given
type of surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dermatologist could perform brain surgery in his garage if
he could get a patient to agree to that,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's chairman, Sen. Roy Goodman, R-Manhattan, said he
would push for further regulation. ``I think very few people are
aware of this,'' he said by telephone on Sunday. ``There should be
the same precautions in the office that there are in the
hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's largest doctors' group, the Medical Society of the
State of New York, said Sunday that it was aware of the concerns
about office surgeries and had been working on a solution for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Aswad, the society's chief executive, said his
organization had been working with the state Health Department to
create an educational program on office surgeries for doctors and
patients, which is to be announced shortly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cases in which there are adverse effects are rare,'' Aswad
said. ``While they're rare, we have zero tolerance for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the abuses cited in the report involved elective
procedures like liposuction and plastic surgery. But medical
officials said an increasing number of operations of many types
were being done in doctors' offices because of rising hospital-care
costs and growing restrictions by insurers.
</P>
<P>
   According to estimates cited in the report, elective surgeries
in doctors' offices are expected to rise to 20 percent by 2001,
from 6 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said some procedures, including laser eye surgery and
examinations to diagnose colon cancer, can very properly be
performed in a doctor's office. But he said that in many other
cases, his investigators found health hazards, lax procedures and
doctors practicing outside their specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Aswad said adding new regulations was not the answer, because
state agencies have complained that they did not have the resources
to enforce rules already on the books. He said doctors were in a
bind because managed-care companies were urging them to do more
procedures outside hospitals, to keep costs down.
</P>
<P>
   The report gave another reason for doctors' willingness to do
surgery in their offices these days. ``A large proportion of office
surgery is now done for cosmetic purposes,'' the study said.
``Cosmetic surgery creates a considerable cash business, and it is
attractive to many doctors who feel restricted by the financial
limits of, and the delays in, health-insurance reimbursements.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the committee said it found one doctor in
Manhattan who was trained in ophthalmology but now specialized in
breast enlargements. ``The conditions in his office and the result
of his work were shocking,'' the report said. The doctor was not
named.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said that during nine months of research, staff
members found that anesthesia equipment used in office surgeries
was often outdated or poorly maintained. ``Some physicians purchase
old anesthesia machines for their offices which have been discarded
by hospitals because they are not up to date,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   When doing office surgery, a doctor is more likely to administer
anesthesia without the help of a specialist, the committee said.
This poses a special risk for patients who are obese or are elderly
with underlying medical problems, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee advised patients considering, for example, plastic
surgery at a doctor's office to check whether the doctor was
board-certified in that specialty. The report said every office
surgical unit should have an emergency cart that included oxygen, a
defibrillator and other equipment to resuscitate a patient in case
the surgery goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving nothing to chance, the report added, ``In addition, the
staff should know how to use these devices and medications.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
