<HEADLINE>
FASTBALL WHACKS WOMACK; X-RAY SHOWS MARK ON BONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Just when Tony Womack was starting to feel comfortable
with the Diamondbacks . . .
</P>
<P>
   A fastball from Chicago White Sox left-hander Jim Parque ruined
his Sunday _ and perhaps several days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed-hitting Womack, who was acquired in a trade from
Pittsburgh on Feb. 26 for the primary purpose of being Arizona's
leadoff man, was hit on the outside edge of his right wrist (ulna
bone) in the second inning of Arizona's 11-5 victory at Tucson
Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   He remained in the game and went on to score the team's fourth
run, and he played defense in left field in the bottom of the
second inning. Then he departed and went next door to Kino
Community Hospital for X-rays, which revealed a mark of some sort.
</P>
<P>
   It was uncertain whether the mark was a fracture, so Womack will
travel to Phoenix today to be examined more thoroughly by Dr. Don
Sheridan, a hand specialist, and Dr. David Zeman, the team
physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something there. We're hoping for the best. We'll
see,'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Womack said, ``It was a fastball that ran in on the hands and
actually did (hit the hand).''
</P>
<P>
   Parque also hit second baseman Jay Bell with a pitch in the
first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Womack was initially upset because he never has had a serious
injury before, but he was feeling more upbeat later in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to get dressed with both hands, and I was flexing
it a little,'' he said, tugging on the tape that secured a padded
wrap.
</P>
<P>
   There was little or no swelling, Womack said, ``because they
(team trainers Paul Lessard and Dave Edwards) got ice on it real
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessard said it was difficult to tell how long Womack will be
sidelined, break or no break.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he doesn't appear to have any pain is a good
sign. We are hopeful,'' Lessard said.
</P>
<P>
   Womack said he hopes he won't be out more than three or four
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something like this is going to happen, it's better that it
happens now,'' he said. ``We don't punch the clock until April 5
(the season opener in Los Angeles).''
</P>
<P>
   While Womack is sidelined, the Diamondbacks likely will move
veteran Luis Gonzalez from right field back to left field.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days following Womack's arrival, Showalter's plan
was to have Womack in right and Gonzalez in left, but he felt
Womack was a better fit in left with Gonzalez in right. Gonzalez
also is likely to assume the leadoff role, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility in left is David Dellucci, who started 80
games there for the Diamondbacks in their inaugural season.
Dellucci is off to a hot start this spring with four hits in nine
at-bats (.444). Three have been for extra bases, including a home
run Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Womack wasn't the only Arizona outfielder to suffer an injury.
Bernard Gilkey left the game because of tightness in his left calf
muscle. His playing status is uncertain, and he will be evaluated
daily. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
