<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SHAMAN PHARMACEUTICALS' CEO PITCHING ITS REINCARNATION  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shaman Pharmaceuticals Inc. will hold what promises to be a
lively conference call with shareholders this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Shaman is the former media darling whose high-profile chief
executive, Lisa Conte, once wowed investors with her groovy plans
to scour the rain forests for potential cures.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, however, Conte all but shut down Shaman after the
Food and Drug Administration balked at licensing its most promising
drug candidate. The company's stock is now trading at 28 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Conte, who has led this company throughout its 10-year
history, is trying to sell Shaman's skeptical shareholders on her
latest plan. It calls for transferring much of the company's
intellectual property _ all carefully collected leaves, twigs and
barks _ to a private spin-off called Shaman Botanicals.
</P>
<P>
   Conte has said the Botanicals spin-off would end-run the FDA by
turning these rain forest products into over-the-counter herbal
potions _ that can be sold without government permission.
</P>
<P>
   But the small _ and some not-so-small investors _ who got stuck
with Shaman's 32 million near-worthless shares, have been burning
up the online chat rooms, trying to figure out what they get out of
this transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The details are spelled out in the proxy statement Shaman filed
February 24.
</P>
<P>
   Conte apparently is seeking to transfer the plant library from
publicly held Shaman Pharmaceuticals to the private Shaman
Botanicals in exchange for 720,000 shares of Shaman Botanicals
stock valued at $1 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Those shares would not be distributed to current shareholders,
but would be held as an asset of the pharmaceuticals firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to transfer a plant library that took them 10 years
and $100 million to collect for shares valued at $720,000,'' said
Joel Hungerford of Kennebunk, Maine, who owns 56,000 shares of
Shaman that he bought at an average price of $1.84.
</P>
<P>
   I read the proxy myself and got much the same understanding. I
called Shaman to make sure I wasn't misreading, but my calls went
unreturned.
</P>
<P>
   Shaman officials are scheduled to answer questions today in a
conference call open to all shareholders _ (800) 260-0719. A replay
of the call will be available for seven days by dialing (800)
475-6701.
</P>
<P>
   This unusual call-in is a prelude to a March 24 shareholder
meeting at the Embassy Suites hotel in South San Francisco, where
Conte needs a majority of those 32 million shares to vote approval
of her plans.
</P>
<P>
   I'll keep following the Shaman saga, but meanwhile, the lesson
is clear: Investing in biotech shares is like sailing the Titanic
through an ice field at high speed. A bad scientific trial or a
negative review by an FDA panel can sink a company pronto _ and the
risks are below the waterline.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran biotech watcher Karen Bernstein has standard advice for
individual investors _ before you buy, ask yourself: Is this money
I could afford to lose?
</P>
<P>
   CAT'S PAW: In November, I wrote about Neurobiological
Technologies Inc., a Richmond firm that was trying to scrounge up
the cash to finish clinical trials on a drug that could help people
with Alzheimer's disease and a related condition called AIDS
dementia.
</P>
<P>
   NTI chief executive Paul Freiman called last week with the good
news that NTI's drug candidate, Memantine, did well in Phase III
clinical trial in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The trial involved 166 Alzheimer's patients, some of whom
received Memantine, others of whom got a placebo. The results,
published in the Wednesday edition of the International Journal of
Geriatric Psychiatry, showed that the Memantine patients showed
considerable improvement in ordinary tasks like dressing themselves
or recognizing visitors.
</P>
<P>
   A similar Phase III trial already is under way in the United
States. If it also turns out positive results, then later this year
or early next year, Freiman hopes to ask European and U.S. drug
regulators to approve Memantine to relive Alzheimer's symptoms.
(The AIDS dementia trials are at an early stage of testing.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with two weeks cash on hand, Freiman said he's
confident that he'll close another $750,000 private placement to
keep the publicly held company afloat for a few more months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're scratching and clawing,'' he said. ``This is the 10th
life of the cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmmnn. Is there a theme here?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
