<SLUG> BC-Y-JAIL-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABUSE ACCUSATIONS OVERBLOWN, GUARDS FEEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST MEADOW, N.Y. _ ``Look,'' said Bruce Kusky, a burly
51-year-old, who has put in 20 years as a correction officer at the
Nassau County jail, ``We don't come to work looking for somebody to
beat up. We want it nice and easy, nice and safe. I want to pick up
my paycheck and go home and kiss my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been hard recently to be the one in uniform at the jail,
said Kusky. He and two other officers were speaking as they sat at
a corner table on Thursday at Runyon's Roadside Tavern, a bar
wrapped in neon across the street from the jail.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,200-bed Nassau County Correctional Center has become the
focus of a federal investigation of reports that officers
systematically beat inmates. The inquiry began after the Jan. 13
death of Thomas Pizzuto, 38, an inmate whose family contends that
he was beaten and then left unattended for days. The Medical
Examiner has ruled Pizzuto's death a homicide.
</P>
<P>
   And last Monday, a federal jury found Salvatore Gemelli, a
15-year jail officer, liable for the 1993 beating of a mentally
retarded man with a frying pan. Later in the day, Gemelli was fired
by Sheriff Joseph P. Jablonsky.
</P>
<P>
   Until that verdict, the men at Runyon's Tavern said, they were
instructed by union officials to say nothing, for fear of
prejudicing Gemelli's trial. Now that he has been dismissed, they
said, they have plenty to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the media attention, he was never going to receive a
fair trial,'' said Corporal Mike Selover, 42, a vice president of
the unit of the Civil Service Employees Union that represents 1,000
Nassau County correction officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public negativity you can take,'' he said. ``But the
outright dismissal? Jablonsky is a tool, a political tool, and he's
got no idea what it means to be in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jablonsky worked as a correction officer for six years before
serving as the deputy director of the county's work-release program
from 1979 to 1985. He became an under sheriff and was appointed
sheriff in 1986. The sheriff is a Republican leader in Hicksville
and three of his top four administrators at the jail are Republican
committeemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are politicians, not officers,'' Selover said. Then,
recounting the official version of the beating, he said: ``You
telling me a guy went to a pantry, walked across a room full of
inmates and beat a guy with a frying pan, and nobody saw it? It
never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The third officer, Chris McShane, 37, who has a business degree
from C.W. Post, said officers have had a much harder time of it at
the jail since Pizzuto's death. Television and newspaper reports
have kept the inmates well informed about the allegations, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stand there and tell you junk about your mother, grab
their genitals and tell you, `Go ahead and beat me, I can use the
money,''' McShane said. ``It's made it real tough to work in there,
but you battle it out with your mind, not your fists.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be some bad apples among the officers, the three
conceded, but incidents of abuse are rare. The district attorney's
office said that of more than 14,000 people who were in the jail
last year, 15 filed complaints against officers. Six of those
complaints were dismissed after investigations, and the other nine
cases are still open, according to the district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that sound systematic to you?'' Selover said.
</P>
<P>
   The jail holds convicts who have been sentenced to terms of a
year or less and defendants awaiting trial. Colin Ferguson, who was
convicted of murdering six Long Island Rail road passengers, and
Joel Rifkin, who was sentenced to life after admitting killing 17
prostitutes, were held there during their trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the nicest people,'' Kusky said. ``This is not a
job many people want to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
