<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-VEGAS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, BROTHER, BURTONS RUN 1-2 AT LAS VEGAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Only three races into the season and NASCAR already
has its first monumental upset.
</P>
<P>
   Someone other than Jeff Gordon and Mark Martin motored into
victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton survived a bravely fought battle against the only
NASCAR Winston Cup driver he dearly loves, his older brother, Ward,
and won a Las Vegas 400 on Sunday at Las Vegas Motor Speedway that
included four of the most spine-tingling laps in series history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's awfully stressful,'' said Jeff, the 31-year-old,
out-of-breath victor. ``I'm a big fan of Ward Burton's. I want Ward
to do well and to sit there and try to have to beat him is really
hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were door to door and all but rubbed a couple times. The
first couple of laps we were side by side, I didn't drive hard
enough and I said to myself, `You've got to drive harder.' And I
started to drive it a little bit harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always want it to come down to the end like that, (but) the
next time he'll get me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burtons, one of six sets of brothers to reach the 43-car
starting grid, were nearly flawless throughout the 267-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff led six times in the Exide Batteries Ford Taurus for 111
laps and Ward, 37, who finished runner-up by 1.074 seconds, led
seven times in the Caterpillar Pontiac Grand Prix for 71 laps.
</P>
<P>
   No one else led more than 25 laps, and Gordon and Martin
combined to lead only 18.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon (13) and Martin (seven), who combined for 20 wins in 33
Winston Cup races last season, had dominated the season's first two
races, splitting wins at Daytona (Gordon) and Rockingham (Martin).
</P>
<P>
   But here in Sin City, there were few heavenly moments for the
sport's dynamic duo.
</P>
<P>
   Although Martin appeared that he might have the late-race
ammunition to spoil the Burtons' day, he settled for 10th after
dropping a cylinder late in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon finished third ahead of Mike Skinner and pole-sitter
Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Until about the final 100 laps, the race, watched by a crowd of
125,000, lacked much drama or suspense.
</P>
<P>
   To put it bluntly, it was dull.
</P>
<P>
   But the stirring duel involving the Burtons, plus some other
dicey moments involving other drivers, helped rocket the
thrill-o-meter.
</P>
<P>
   The Burton battle began with Jeff entering pit road with the
lead following the fifth and final caution flag on Lap 232. He
re-emerged onto the 1.5-mile oval in third behind his brother and
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   On Lap 244, Jeff managed to ease by Gordon. Then on Lap 254,
Jeff was door to door with Ward.
</P>
<P>
   And for four nail-biting laps, they waged a battle for the lead,
the fans craning their necks for a better view of the unfolding
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Lap 257, Ward squeezed by Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   A lap later, it was Jeff back in front. This time, he was in
front to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to crowd (Jeff) as much as I could without
wrecking him,'' Ward said. ``I don't want to wreck my brother. I
wasn't giving him an inch. I even thought about moving him up a
little higher to be honest with you. I knew if I did, one of us
wasn't going to make it out of the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want your brother to beat you. But at the same time,
I love my brother and I want the best for my brother. I do know
Jeff can't do anything in a race car that I can't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, he was just a little bit better when he needed to be
better to beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end, Gordon thought he might be better than one of
the Burtons, but not two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of took off there at the end and I started to run down
Ward, and I said, `All right, we've got a shot a this,' '' said
Gordon, whose only lead was on Lap 242. ``(Dale) Jarrett was
holding up Jeff Burton and I was hoping he'd keep holding him up
because I knew we were all in trouble if he got free of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure enough, that's the way it turned out. I tried to make a
run at Ward (again), but I got too loose. I knew nobody could touch
Jeff.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
