<HEADLINE>
YOUTH CLIMBS TO TOP  
 COMBINED AGE OF FINALISTS IS 39 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - The title contenders Sunday were the
youngest on the ATP Tour this season.
</P>
<P>
   The winner,  &UR; Jan-Michael Gambill, is only 21. His opponent,
 &UR; Lleyton
 &UR; Hewitt, turned 18 less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill became the fourth first-time winner on the Association
of Tennis Professionals Tour this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill earned $46,000 for the win. Hewitt won $27,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt became the fourth Australian to make the Franklin
Templeton Classic finals in as many years. Only one, Jerome
Golmard, has won.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt had to go through qualifying rounds to make the
tournament. Had he won, he would have been only the fourth
qualifier to win an ATP tournament in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   His current ranking is No. 91 in the world, but making the
finals here will put him in the top 65.
</P>
<P>
   That means he won't have to qualify at Indians Wells, Calif., in
this week's ATP tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill, ranked 45th, will rise to about 30th.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the highest ranking either has held.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt also is the fifth-lowest ranked player to make the finals
on the ATP Tour this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill led the tournament in aces with 42. &QL; 
Unorthodox serve &QL; 
 &UR; Andre Agassi may be Gambill's hero, but he didn't pattern his game
after Agassi's.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill calls his two-handed forehand unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would watch tapes of his (Agassi's) games over and over,''
Gambill said. ``I loved to see his intensity and focus. But I
didn't pattern myself after him because my stroke is a little
unorthodox.''
</P>
<P>
   It has to do with Gambill's tennis background.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started (playing tennis) early. I was a tall, skinny kid and
didn't have any strength. I just started using the two-handed
forehand to get more power. I've just stayed with it.'' &QL; 
Agassi on road &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who was forced to retire in the first game of Saturday's
semifinals because of what his physician called a mild hamstring
strain, had a treatment Sunday morning and headed for Indian Wells.
He hopes to heal sufficiently to play a first-round match Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; Doug Spreen, the ATP trainer who gave the treatment, said
it is questionable whether Agassi can compete.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Wells' $2.4 million purse is among the ATP's largest,
other than Grand Slam events. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
