<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-COLUMN-SFCHR     03-07 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 `NET-ESCAPEES' SPAWNING STARTUPS IN SILICON VALLEY  &HT;     By JON SWARTZ 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Netscape Communications may disappear as an independent company
when America Online finishes its $4.2 billion acquisition this
month. But it has begat a new wave of companies dotting Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   At least half a dozen startups are either headed or heavily
staffed by ``Net-escapees,'' former executives of the Internet
pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're entrepreneurs at heart. We all want to create something
new _ maybe the next Netscape,'' said Todd Rulon-Miller, lead
partner at Apogee Venture Group, a new venture capital company in
Burlingame. When he was senior vice president of sales at Netscape,
Rulon-Miller hired 800 people in less than three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our years there trained us how to spot hot technologies and
build a company fast,'' said Rulon-Miller, who left Netscape in
August 1997. He now works at Apogee with two other Net-escapees,
Bill Foss and Jim Sha. ``There are a lot of opportunities out
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atri Chatterjee, who used to run marketing for Netscape's
profitable server business, last fall joined Responsys.com, a Santa
Clara company &LR;   &LR; that provides specialized software services to
e-commerce companies. About eight Net-escapees work for the Santa
Clara startup.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape has created ``an incredible alumni society,'' said
Daniel Shader, a former vice president of developer relations at
Netscape who is now CEO of Accept.com, a mysterious e-commerce firm
in Redwood Shores. ``It's like Go, which spawned a number of
startups. Who knows? We may end up working with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The most intriguing post-Netscape venture may be TellMe.com, a
top-secret endeavor run by Mike McCue, Netscape's former vice
president of technology, and whiz kid Angus Davis. Jim Clark,
co-founder of Netscape, Silicon Graphics and Healtheon, is rumored
to be involved with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Other new companies headed by former Netscapers include
PassPoints, an e-commerce company in San Francisco, and
AllBusiness.com., another Internet company in the city.
</P>
<P>
   If you think all of these departures will result in brain drain
at Netscape, think again. Marc Andreessen, company co-founder and
resident visionary, will remain as chief technology officer at AOL.
</P>
<P>
   YOU SAY PORTAL. I SAY VORTAL: As if the Internet really needed
another buzzword ... here comes vortal _ an amalgamation of
``vertical'' and ``portal.''
</P>
<P>
   A portal is a welcome mat to the Internet. These sites try to
pack in so many lures _ news, search engines, free e-mail, online
shopping, instant messaging, chat rooms, etc. _ that many people
won't want to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, the Internet can only support four or five major
portals, and America Online, Yahoo, Microsoft and Excite already
have been declared winners.
</P>
<P>
   That left a bunch of portal-wannabes looking for a buzzword of
their own. They leafed through the hype dictionary and came up with
vortal.
</P>
<P>
   A vortal is a Web site that combines specific, ``vertical''
content such as sports, technology or health care, with some portal
features such as e-mail and shopping
</P>
<P>
   Cnet (www.cnet.com), the online technology news services that
claims to have coined the term ``portal,'' now calls itself a
vortal or _ get ready for this _ a portical.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the San Francisco company announced a new home page
with specialized portal features. For example, its search engine
covers 10 specific categories, such as hardware, software, games
and gadgets. And it sponsors chats on topics such as Y2K, MP3,
pagers and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Monster.com also claims to be a vortal. ``Consumers are going
directly to the source and not through a main gateway,'' said Jeff
Taylor, CEO of Monster.com, the world's largest online recruitment
service. ``We're entering the age of specialization.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a new name for an old (in Internet years) concept,
scoff industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventing a new name (for portals) is carrying it a bit too
far,'' said David Thomas, CEO of BroadQuest Inc. a San Jose company
that could call itself a vortal but won't. ``Let's not abuse the
portal name.''
</P>
<P>
   ALL FOR ONE, AND ONE FOR ALL?: Much has been made of Open
Service Gateway, the 13-company global consortium created last week
to design software &UR;  &LR; linking a variety of appliances _ personal
computers, telephones, TVs, VCRs and even toasters _ to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The powerhouse combine includes IBM, Oracle, Sun Microsystems
and Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   But before we pronounce OSG the Internet's next great
advancement, remember what happened to Open Software Foundation,
Taligent, Kaleida Labs and Advanced Computing Environment.
</P>
<P>
   They were all hyped alliances that didn't amount to a hill of
beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``For-profit business alliances don't mix well when their
members are competing companies,'' said Internet co-founder Vint
Cerf. ``Trying to get fierce rivals to share intellectual property
is pretty tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassroots organizations tend to get more accomplished, Cerf
said. He said the Linux movement is a good example. It's a loosely
organized group of computer users working toward a common goal: a
free alternative to Microsoft's operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   The OSG alliance does not include Microsoft _ the dominant force
in consumer computing. What that leaves is a group with plenty of
swagger but not much bite.
</P>
<P>
   DEPARTMENT OF CORRECTIONS: Whoops! I must have been in fantasy
land when I listed the wrong Web address for AtomFilms, an online
resource for short films and animated features in last week's
column. The correct URL is www.atomfilms.com.
</P>
<P>
   SITES OF THE WEEK: Dance the day away with a whimsical tribute
to burrowing rodents at www.hamsterdance.com. Movie choreographer
Busby Berkeley would be proud.
</P>
<P>
   For a slice of Italia, www.virtualitalia.com is an antipasto of
culinary delights, culture and contacts in San Francisco. Bello.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
