A1301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESBYTERIANS-GAYS-AR     03-07 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESBYTERIANS-GAYS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY MAN IS ALLOWED TO BE A CHURCH LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add art note))  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ An openly gay man may sit on the governing
board of his Presbyterian church here despite his refusal to
divulge whether he engages in sexual activities that would bar him
from serving, ecclesiastical judges have ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-1 decision, handed down on Saturday by the Permanent
Judiciary Commission of the Presbytery of Southern New England and
announced Sunday, is the first test of a 1997 amendment to the
constitution of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) that requires
deacons, elders and ministers ``to live in fidelity within the
marriage of a man and woman or in chastity in singleness.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has been monitored around the United States in churches
struggling with the issue of gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendment, known as Amendment B, also
requires candidates for church leadership to state that they have
repented of any self-acknowledged sin. The church considers
homosexual activity _ though not homosexuality itself _ sinful.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the Stamford case is Wayne Osborne, a
38-year-old financial adviser and a graduate of the Princeton
Theological Seminary who was elected to serve on the session, or
governing body, of the 700-member First Presbyterian Church of
Stamford in May. He has been a member of the church for more than
five years.
</P>
<P>
   It was not his first elevation to the session. He had already
served for three years starting in 1994. But this time, the
circumstances were different, and the session itself was pitted
against congregants who claimed that it was violating the church
constitution by installing Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   After he finished his first term as a member of the session, he
divulged to the congregation that he was in a long-term
relationship with another man, Greg Price, a fellow congregant who
worked with developmentally disabled adults.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Osborne was nominated for a second term on the
30-member session because he was deemed by the nominating committee
to have been called on by God to serve. Like the other 10
candidates, he was examined by the session, whose members asked a
prescribed set of questions. Among them: ``Are you a
self-acknowledged sinner unrepentant of that sin?''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne denied having committed any sins requiring repentance,
but was then asked whether his relationship with Price involved
sexual activity. He declined to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Standing quietly in the church on Sunday after the service at
which the verdict was announced, Osborne explained his refusal to
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not an appropriate question,'' he said. ``Even my best
friends don't ask me, and for me to have answered would be to go
against who I am as a person and who God made me to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Two church members _ Mairi Hair and James MacCallum _ filed
charges against the session, alleging irregularities in its
examination and approval of Osborne as a session member. In the
Presbyterian Church, ordination to elder is a lifetime appointment,
although not all elders serve on sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The ecclesiastical trial was held on Feb. 26 at the Quinnipiac
School of Law in Hamden.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the constitution, the elders examining the person
are required to ask certain necessary questions, including ones
about sin, but the constitution does not require that they get a
clear answer,'' Dan Sassi, a church deacon, explained in a
telephone interview. ``It says that sessions are to respect the
right of the individual to decline to answer and not discuss the
issue. The other side in this case believes that living with a
person is enough proof of sex outside marriage; we say that it is
not.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reached by telephone after the news conference, William Prey, a
representative of the church members who challenged Osborne's
appointment, said: ``We are understandably disappointed with the
decision. Be assured that we remain committed to praying for and
working for Amendment B. We are leaning to filing an appeal but
have made no decision yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, emphasizing that the complainants were not motivated by
prejudice against homosexuals, he said: ``There are provisions in
the constitution that apply equally to heterosexuals and
homosexuals that spell out sinful behavior inappropriate for
elected leaders. What one church does locally is really on behalf
of the whole denomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the service on Sunday, Mary Morrison, executive director
of the Darien Chamber of Commerce, remarked: ``I am so pleased. I
know Wayne well and he is a man of exceptional standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amendment B is labeled a gay amendment but that is a
misnomer,'' she went on. ``It could impact all of us who are
single, including me. I am a divorced mother of two grown children.
And Wayne was being truthful to himself and to God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
