<HEADLINE>
UA WOMEN HEADING TO JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN J. PEDERSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ There was a moment of hesitation, sprinkled with fear
and trepidation, before the ensuing celebration began for Arizona's
third consecutive NCAA Tournament selection.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Wildcats had finished the regular season on an
impressive 8-2 stretch, there was still a lingering doubt Sunday,
right up until Arizona saw its name flashed across the television
screen during the selection show on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw Arizona up on the screen, but it took us three or four
seconds to realize we were Arizona,'' guard Felecity Willis said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (17-10) earned a No. 6 seed and will play No. 11 Florida
(19-13) on Friday at 4 p.m. in Piscataway, N.J., on the Rutgers
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players and Coach Joan Bonvicini were confident that
the Wildcats' strong second half of the season had assured them of
being the fourth team from the Pac-10 to make the tournament, but
the memories of Arizona's snub three years ago kept everyone on
edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more than satisfied,'' said guard Lisa Griffith, the
only active player from the 1995-96 team that went 22-8 but had to
settle for a National Invitation Tournament invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Bonvicini said Arizona's win over Stanford last weekend and the
Wildcats' come-from-behind win at Southern California on Thursday
combined with a non-conference schedule that included seven
tournament teams put them over the edge. Still, she expects her
team to improve by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we played our best this past weekend (in the win
over USC and a season-ending loss to UCLA),'' Bonvicini said. ``We
really had a great second half of the conference season. We're just
going to go one game at a time, and I know that's a cliche.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats have a potential second round match-up with No. 3
Rutgers (26-5) or No. 14 Dartmouth (19-8), but first the Wildcats
will have to tangle with an athletic Florida team that includes
talented freshman guard Brandi McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's going to be tough,'' Griffith said. ``In the
tournament when you're not hosting, it's hard. But we're not
expected to do a lot, so that should work to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Willis and Bonvicini have a lot of family in the New Jersey
and New York area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been praying for some opportunity to go back East and
play,'' Willis said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has played Florida once, losing, 94-76, to open the
1994-95 season in a tournament in Hawaii. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
