<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON UNFAZED BY WIND  
 ALLOWS HIT, 2 WALKS IN HIS 2-INNING STINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ At first glance, the weather conditions for Sunday's
game between the Diamondbacks and Chicago White Sox did not seem to
be conducive to pitching productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The wind gusted from behind the plate at Tucson Electric Park
toward center field at 20 mph. Thick clouds moved in to create a
contrast to what has been a sun-baked spring.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't faze Arizona left-hander  &UR; Randy Johnson as he made his
first official Cactus League start.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who struck out four of the six batters he faced against
the University of Arizona on Wednesday, pitched two innings Sunday
(27 pitches), giving up an infield hit while striking out one and
walking two. Arizona coasted to an 11-5 victory, its fourth in a
row after dropping the opener on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson didn't have the location he desired with his fastball,
but he was pleased with his breaking pitches. His strikeout of the
first man he faced, White Sox outfielder  &UR; McKay Christensen, came
on a slider. Johnson threw only a few off-speed pitches against UA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a noticeable improvement,'' Johnson said. ``I have a
ways to go as far as my mechanics are concerned, but I'm getting
there. I also got to throw from the stretch, which was good
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also benefited from two double plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good because it cuts down the number of pitches you
throw early, so you'll have more (energy) left later in the game,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   His next start is scheduled at TEP on Thursday against the
Chicago Cubs. His pitch count likely will be around 55. &QL; 
Stinnett's first start &QL; 
After being limited to one pinch-hitting role in the first four
games because of tightness in the back of his throwing shoulder,
catcher &UR; Kelly Stinnett got his first start and responded with two
doubles and a home run. He also scored three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to be out there,'' he said. ``There are a lot of
new faces on the team and you want to see what you can do. It was
good to be able to catch Randy. And it was good to swing the bat.
The one (homer to left in the fourth inning) was helped by the
wind, but I got a couple of decent hacks on the others.'' &QL; 
Short stops &QL; 
Infielder-outfielder  &UR; Andy Fox was sent home Sunday morning with
flulike symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre is the scheduled starter today as
Arizona plays for the first time this spring in Phoenix against the
Milwaukee Brewers at Maryvale Baseball Park. Right-hander  &UR; Steve
Woodard will be on the mound for the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   The club sent three players to its minor league camp Sunday.
Catchers  &UR; Rod Barajas and  &UR; Ramsey Koeyers, both non-roster players,
were reassigned, and right-hander  &UR; Jason Boyd, a member of the
40-man roster, was optioned. With 52 players in the big league
camp, three more are scheduled to be reassigned today.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately one-fourth of the grass at Tucson Electric Park
and the 15 practice fields for the Diamondbacks and White Sox has
been replaced at a cost of $200,000 to Pima County, about $25,000
more than the original estimate, according to the ``Arizona Daily
Star.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
