<SLUG> BC-XXX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOIS WANN, 87, AN OBOIST AND TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lois Wann, an oboist who played in several American orchestras
and taught at the Juilliard School and the Mannes College of Music,
died on Feb. 23 at her home in Bronxville, N.Y. She was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wann who was born in Monticello, Minn., in 1912, studied the
oboe and piano as a child in San Diego and later at the Juilliard
School in New York, from which she graduated in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   When she began her career in the 1930s, there were few women in
American orchestras, and her first jobs were with the New York
Women's Symphony and the all-women Orchestrette. Hired by the San
Diego Symphony in the mid-1930s, she became one of the first women
to hold a principal chair in a professional orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to perform with the Pittsburgh Symphony and the St.
Louis Symphony, and was for many years the principal oboist of the
New York City Ballet Orchestra and in the orchestras of the summer
festivals at Aspen, Colo., and Marlboro, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   She also played in chamber music concerts with the Juilliard and
Budapest string quartets. As a recitalist, she gave the premiere of
Darius Milhaud's Sonatine for Oboe and Piano in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wann taught at Juilliard from 1936 to 1992 and at Mannes
College from 1946 to 1976.
</P>
<P>
   She also taught at Vassar and Manhattanville Colleges, the Henry
Street Settlement and the United Nations International School.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by two daughters, Barbara Bodenhorn of
Cambridge, England, and Karynn Hatch of Bronxville, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
