<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1314 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TOURNEY-BICKLEY-A     03-07 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TOURNEY-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY TO FALL IN LOVE, ALL OVER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Once, my brother stormed away from the television. Off
into another room. His favorite team _ the undefeated Indiana
Hoosiers of 1974-75 _ was going down in flames.
</P>
<P>
   I monitored the end with curiosity: A quick rally. A burst of
the unexpected. A timeout.
</P>
<P>
   My brother came flying back into the room, discovering a
two-point game with a few seconds left. He frantically asked who
had the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indiana,'' I said, as he melted into the couch, thrilled by
the reprieve, believing his prayers had been answered.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, I was wrong. Indiana didn't have the ball. And when
the commercials ended and my brother endured such a tragic twist of
emotion . . .
</P>
<P>
   Well, I was 11 when I first understood the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this passion is universal. Everyone has fallen along
with a Goliath. Risen with an underdog. Drawn in by a tournament
that never plays favorites and never lets you down.
</P>
<P>
   A tournament where every school has a story, every team has a
dream _ and some of them actually come true.
</P>
<P>
   So it is the last Big Dance of the century, and no one can play
like Duke. A team with stars coming off the bench and answers for
every nuance of the game. Once, Mike Krzyzewski was the subject of
jokes, like how he quit playing golf after 14 holes because he
didn't like the final four.
</P>
<P>
   Now, less than five years after lying in a hospital bed,
recovering from back surgery and exhaustion, Krzyzewski has roared
back to the top of the coaching profession.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no team has been so heavily favored since UNLV in 1992,
the team that beat Duke by 30 in the previous championship game. A
team so traumatizing that Bobby Hurley spent that off-season
dreaming about sharks. A team that came back and tore through the
country on its way to a repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they lost. Which is what normally happens to the
preordained.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, since 1974, 16 teams have entered the tournament with
one loss. Only two have reached the Final Four, and neither won the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that as you gaze at your bracket. And remember, this
tournament is always about the little guys. One-shot wonders.
One-time moments, like Bryce Drew shooting Valparaiso past a
horrified Rob Evans. Like Christian Laettner's catch-and-kill
against Kentucky. Like Lorenzo Charles dunking an airball.
</P>
<P>
   And remember that while favorites do prevail, it rarely goes as
planned. In 1995, UCLA entered with a No. 1 ranking and left with
the nets. Of course, if Tyus Edney hadn't gone coast-to-coast
against Missouri on the final play of the game, the Bruins would've
been casualties of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, you've been there. On one side or the other.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I remember skipping high school on a day I hated the
world. I ended up at DePaul University, walking around the campus,
mourning the first-round choke of Mark Aguirre and the Blue Demons.
</P>
<P>
   So you wonder: Does the College of Charleston have a chance? A
team that has beaten North Carolina and won 25 in a row?
</P>
<P>
   Can Cincinnati catch fire and beat Duke for the second time this
season? Can Auburn regroup? Can UCLA survive a game without Baron
Davis? Is Kentucky the smart choice, a team that has won 28 of its
past 30 tournament games? Can Connecticut finally break through and
lose the postseason collar?
</P>
<P>
   Of all the outsiders, none may be more intriguing than Arizona.
In their shredding of UCLA on Saturday, the Wildcats looked every
bit like a contender, Jason Terry very much like the player of the
year. Question is, do they have the swagger to win six games on
neutral courts?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they're a year away. Just like they were in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Still, can anyone beat Duke?
</P>
<P>
   Not sure, but I remember sitting in a bar in 1985, next to a
strange girl with a Wildcat painted on her face. It was the night
Villanova played a perfect game, shot nearly 80 percent from the
field, dethroning the Evil Empire from Georgetown . . . by two
points.
</P>
<P>
   The night I fell in love. With the NCAA Tournament. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
