<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1321 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALVADOR-VOTE-1STLD-W     03-07 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-VOTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALVADORAN RULING PARTY GAINS EARLY EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update and reorganize; changes throughout.)  (lh) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR _ The candidate of the conservative governing
party, a philosopher with a reputation for consensus building, led
Sunday in presidential elections that Salvadorans hoped would solve
problems of crime and unemployment that afflict the country seven
years after the end of its civil war.
</P>
<P>
   An early survey of voters leaving polling stations showed that
Francisco Flores, the 39-year-old candidate of the governing
Nationalist Republican Alliance, known as ARENA, with about 52
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   That provided him with a comfortable lead over his chief
opponent, Facundo Guardado, 44, the candidate of a coalition led by
the country's former guerrilla movement, the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front, who was given 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at the Camino Real Hotel here less than
three hours after polls closed, Flores claimed an early victory and
said said ARENA's own polls showed that he had garnered 53 percent
of the vote, which would preclude a runoff election. But he said he
would await the first official results by the Supreme Electoral
Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the coalition party said they rejected ARENA's
numbers and would also wait for the first official numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Among five other candidates, Ruben Zamora, the coalition's
presidential candidate in the last election who this year ran under
his own Democratic Center Union, was third with about 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout among 3.1 million registered voters appeared low after a
campaign dominated by the grave problems that Salvadorans have
inherited since their 12-year civil war ended, including rampant
crime, unemployment and poverty. The presidential vote was only
their second since the war's end.
</P>
<P>
   Such apathy, political analysts said, demonstrates a loss of
faith in the effectiveness of government since peace arrived in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that despite the end of the war, the fundamental
problems of the country have not been solved like they had
expected,'' said Jose Miguel Cruz, the director of the Public
Opinion Institute at the Central American University. ``They say
we've had war, elections, peace accords and more elections, and we
still have violence and problems of unemployment and poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous elections only half of the eligible voters cast
ballots. Two out of three Salvadorans had little or no interest in
this election, according to a survey last month by the public
opinion institute. The reasons, it found, ranged from mistrust of
politicians to skepticism that the vote could make a difference in
solving the country's problems or improving living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But the disillusionment of Salvadorans was not enough to turn
many voters away from ARENA, which suffered serious losses to the
party of the former guerrillas in municipal and legislative
elections in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the polls opened Sunday, Flores, a philosopher with
a fresh face and no ties to the civil war, was favored to win,
though it was unclear whether he would gain enough votes to avoid a
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition party led by the former rebels, after much
infighting, had rejected broadening its appeal and settled on
Guardado, a moderate ex-guerrilla commander who had pushed for the
selection of a centrist candidate from an allied party.
</P>
<P>
   Guardado's war credentials and Flores' resume, which includes
studies in Indian philosophy and a bachelor's degree in political
science from the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, seemed to
leave many voters unable to see an alternative beyond ARENA,
however dissatisfied they might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Francisco Flores seems to me more capable, better educated,''
said Raul Avila, 68, a tailor who said he had been held up twice in
recent years during the day. ``No Government is ideal but the hope
we all have is that he can begin solving the most serious problems
of the country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Avila voted at the fairgrounds here where 69,000 Salvadorans
were registered to vote. If the overall turnout was low, spirits
were high Sunday, as throngs filed into cavernous pavilions to cast
their ballots at cardboard podiums.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the scene was festive, with food and drink vendors
hollering for business as voters came and went, many of them
wearing T-shirts, caps and hair ribbons with party colors and
honking their horns in electoral euphoria as they sat in heavy
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The elections were held on the eve of President Clinton's
four-day visit to Central America to survey the damage inflicted by
Hurricane Mitch late last year. He will start with Nicaragua and El
Salvador on Monday. Flags welcoming Clinton as the ``Excelentisimo
Senor Presidente'' have been up on major roads here for days.
Clinton will be the first American president to visit El Salvador
since Lyndon B. Johnson stopped by in 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   At a news teleconference this week from Washington, Peter F.
Romero, the State Department's sub-secretary for western hemisphere
affairs, said the president was also coming to celebrate the
region's democratic transformation after the civil wars of the
1980s and, particularly, the results of El Salvador's elections.
</P>
<P>
   That transformation would have been even more remarkable if the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, which the United States
helped the government here fight after El Salvador became a main
Cold War battleground, had built on previous electoral victories to
take over power now.
</P>
<P>
   But after capturing the second largest bloc of legislative seats
and a large number of mayoral posts, including the capital, in
1997, its own inner divisions reinforced feelings among many voters
that the ex-guerrillas were ill-prepared to govern.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora, a social democrat and highly regarded intellectual, was
expected to capture much of the disaffected leftist vote.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Arena, which was founded in the early 1980s by
leaders associated with El Salvador's right-wing death squads but
has since cultivated a moderate image, united after the losses of
1997 behind Flores, a candidate known in the National Assembly for
building consensus and who epitomized the party's message of
``renovation and openness.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores avoided personal attacks and campaigned on a platform of
bringing professionalism to the police, reforming a corrupt
judicial system and generating jobs through increased foreign
investment and support of small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major change in Arena is a change toward the common good,
the national good,'' Flores said in an interview Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
