<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-JOHNSON-NYT &LR;      03-07 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEANE JOHNSON, 80, LAWYER FOR ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., Iowa, Pa., Idaho)  (lb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deane F. Johnson, an entertainment-industry lawyer and corporate
executive prominent in nonprofit institutions, died on Feb. 28 at
his home in Beverly Hills, Calif. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   He had a long illness, according to an announcement of his death
by the Los Angeles-based law firm O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, of which he
had been the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his second wife, the former Anne McDonnell Ford,
were familiar figures for years in Los Angeles' social and arts
scene. They were married in 1968, four years after she and Henry
Ford II divorced. She soon became the most prestigious hostess in
Los Angeles and was also active in social and charitable events in
New York. She died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was with O'Melveny &AMP; Myers from 1942 to 1981. His
clients in those years included William Holden, William S. Paley,
James Stewart, Bing Crosby, Shirley Temple, Dinah Shore, Gary
Cooper, CBS and Paramount.
</P>
<P>
   For a dozen years beginning in 1981, he was in New York as an
executive and director of Warner Communications, and then of Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson received a bachelor's degree in 1939 and a law degree in
1942, both from Stanford University. Later he became chairman of
the Stanford law school's board of visitors and donated his
Colorado ranch to the law school, where he had been first in his
class. That is the largest gift the law school has ever received.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Des Moines, Iowa, grew up in Ione, Calif., became
one of his law firm's partners in 1950 and was chairman of its
management committee from 1977 to 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was president of the Pittsburgh Pirates baseball team
for a time. He was a trustee of the American Film Institute and the
California Institute of Technology, a member of boards at the
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York and a director
of the Los Angeles Lakers basketball team, the Boy Scouts of
America, the Actors Fund and the American Museum of the Moving
Image, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, to Jane Pendergast, ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is survived by his wife, Kate Edelman Johnson, whom he
married in 1996; a son, Deane Jr. of Ketchum, Idaho, and a twin
sister, Doris Winters Johnson of Redwood City, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
