<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/07/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) STAMFORD, Ct. -- March 07, 1999 -- PRESBYTERIANS-GAYS,
03-07 -- Wayne Osborne, a 38-year-old financial adviser and a
graduate of the Princeton Theological Seminary, gets a hug Sunday
at the First Presbyterian Church of Stamford. Church judges have
ruled that he can serve as a church leader despite his refusal to
say whether he engages in homosexual activity. The case has been
monitored around the United States in churches struggling with the
issue of gay rights. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 07, 1999 -- BUSH-POLITICS, 03-07
-- Gov. George W. Bush of Texas waiting to introduce his
Presidential exploratory committee in Austin Sunday. The carefully
choreographed juggernaut was intended to convey a sense of
inevitability about Bush's presidential quest, a move that could
help him lock up crucial financial and political support in the
next few months. (Bryce Harper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) STONY BROOK, N.Y. -- March 07, 1999 -- CLIMATE-STUDENT,
03-07 -- Meredith Croke, 19, whose research at the State University
of New York at Stony Brook on links between clouds and temperature
has been accepted for publication in The Journal of Climate, a
prominent research periodical, usually the province of gray-haired
doctorate. Ms. Croke's research led to a full scholarship to Stony
Brook, where she is a freshman with plans for graduate work in
applied physics and meteorology. ``There is just something about
weather,'' she says. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- March 07, 1999 -- SENATE-REPUBS, 03-07 --
Post-impeachment, Senate Republicans, with Trent Lott their leader,
have come out of the House's shadow. After four years in which
House Republicans dominated Congress, bringing their party its
legislative energy as well as its public-relations disasters and
the impeachment drive, power has shifted on Capitol Hill. In the
106th Congress, Trent Lott and his Senate majority have become the
ascendant Republican presence. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ATLANTA -- March 07, 1999 -- KING-CHURCH-2, 03-07 --
Members of the Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta, where the Rev.
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his first and last sermons,
waiting to enter their new church for the dedication ceremonies
Sunday morning. Each year, 500,000 tourists visit the church, many
for Sunday services, and members and visitors often struggle to
squeeze into 750 seats. The new $8 million sanctuary seats more
than 1,700. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ATLANTA -- March 07, 1999 -- KING-CHURCH-1, 03-07 --
After being led by young girls dressed in white gowns with angels'
wings, members of the Ebenezer Baptist Church left the sanctuary
where the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. had preached his gospel
of nonviolence, and consecrated an airy new church that they
dedicated to the legacy of his ministry. The original church will
be leased by the National Park Service, which plans to use it for a
variety of programs, including the role of the black church in the
civil rights movement. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- March 07, 1999 -- SUB-JACKSON-LEE-NOODGE,
03-07 -- Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, 49, D-Texas, usually gets her
moment to speak. She has become Congress' resident noodge, an
endlessly loquacious presence here, there and everywhere. Ms.
Jackson-Lee says that she simply is simply dedicated to her job and
to her constituents in the section of Houston that she represents.
``You have an obligation to make sure that their concerns are
heard, are answered,'' she says. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo) *SUB* for Photo, not caption material.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WEST HILLS, Calif. -- March 07, 1999 --
MEDICAID-CHILDBIRTH, 03-07 -- Ozzie Chavez says she was denied
anesthesia at Northridge Hospital Medical Center in California,
when her daughter, Amy, now 3, was born. On Medicaid at the time,
Ms. Chavez was told she would have to pay $400 in cash just hours
before she gave birth. ``I'm not a wimp when it comes to pain, but
it was a very painful delivery. The anesthesiologist wouldn't even
come into the room until she got her money,'' says Ms. Chavez.
(Jill Connelly/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) VAIL, Colorado -- March 07, 1999 -- SAT-TV-MEDIA, 03-07
-- A satellite dish outside a house in Vail, Colo. Most satellite
subscribers in Colorado are in urban areas. A ruling last year by a
federal judge who said that Prime Time 24, a contractor of DirecTV,
the nation's largest satellite television provider, had violated
federal law by illegally delivering network signals to homes in
areas where coverage maps indicate that customers can receive
programming from local stations, may soon cut off many more
satellite subscribers nationwide. (Peter M. Fredin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ZHANLONG, China -- March 07, 1999 -- CHINA-POLICE, 03-07
-- Residents of the village of Zhanlong, China, washing their
laundry near local fields. Seven policemen are to go on trial on
murder charges this month in the killing of four farmers from the
village, a case that illustrates problems of police abuse in China.
(Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
