<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-DAUBE-NYT &LR;      03-07 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAUBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID DAUBE, 90, AN AUTHORITY ON TALMUDIC AND ROMAN LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prof. David Daube, an eminent authority on legal history who was
best known for his writings on Talmudic law, other biblical law and
Roman law, died on Feb. 24 in Oak Park Convalescent Hospital in
Pleasant Hill, Calif. He was 90 and had lived in San Francisco for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   Daube (pronounced DOW-beh) retired in 1981 after 11 years as
professor-in-residence at the law school of the University of
California at Berkeley. In those years he also served as the
director of the Robbins Hebraic and Roman Law Collections in the
law school's library.
</P>
<P>
   In later years he continued to teach courses at the law school
in Talmudic, Roman and ancient law. He had been Regius Professor of
civil law at Oxford University from 1955 to 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Daube's collected works are being edited by Calum Carmichael,
professor of comparative literature and adjunct professor of law at
Cornell University. Carmichael said that over five decades, Daube,
who came from a strict Orthodox Jewish home, had produced ``work on
the New Testament that was revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mining Talmudic literature with a sharpness of focus and an
extraordinary degree of sophistication,'' Carmichael went on, ``he
showed that the ideas and institutions of the New Testament
belonged to a thoroughly Jewish setting and could not be understood
without the perspective provided by the Talmud. He saw what others
saw, but could produce thoughts that no one had ever thought
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Daube was born in Freiburg im Breisgau, Germany, and went on to
receive a doctorate in law in 1932 from Gottingen University after
writing a dissertation on an aspect of biblical law. He left
Germany in 1933 to escape Hitler's rule and to pursue his study of
Roman law at Gonville and Caius College at Cambridge University.
</P>
<P>
   He received a second doctorate, on Roman law, in 1936, then went
on to be a lecturer in law at Cambridge and then a professor of
jurisprudence at Aberdeen University before becoming a Regius
Professor at Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   His 1936 marriage to Hertha Aufseesser ended in divorce in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 13 years, Helen Smelser Daube of
San Francisco; three sons, Jonathan, of Manchester, Conn.,
Benjamin, of Toronto, and Michael, of Perth, Australia; two
stepchildren, Eric and Tina Smelser, both of San Francisco, and six
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-99 2353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990307.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-07 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1333 &Cx1f; tdy-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TOURNEY-ARIZONA-A     03-07 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TOURNEY-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATURING FRESHMEN MAKE ARIZONA THE `X-FACTOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Jason Terry carried Arizona into the Top 10 and to its
12th straight 20-win season.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's tournament time, six consecutive do-or-die games,
beginning Friday in Milwaukee against Oklahoma in the first round
of the Midwest Regional. If the fourth-seeded Wildcats are to go
deep into March Madness, Terry can't do it alone. Ultimately, it's
the Wildcats' deep, talented but inconsistent pool of freshmen who
likely will determine how far they go in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Five freshmen are among the Wildcats' first nine players. Three
start. Two were named to the Pac-10 All-Freshman team. One is the
conference Freshman of the Year. A sixth freshman, Luke Walton, was
redshirted after he suffered a stress fracture in his foot in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence is mounting that this is Coach Lute Olson's best rookie
class. But is it ready for the next step?
</P>
<P>
   Power forward Michael Wright, the Freshman of the Year and most
dominating among the group, recognizes that this is a new season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was a good learning year for all of our
freshmen,'' Wright said. ``Now we're into a situation in the
tournament where it's one loss and you're out. We've got to fight
like dogs. All of us have to step up and show our stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wright has been the leader of the freshmen, Olson said
it's shooting guard Ruben Douglas, who found a home in the closing
four games, and small forward Richard Jefferson, a Phoenix Moon
Valley High School product who joined Wright on the All-Freshman
team, who will most influence Arizona's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on whether those two wings have developed far
enough to hurt people,'' Olson said. ``When people spread their
defense, they've got to attack and make them pay. It gets down to
the play of those two wings offensively and defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the midpoint of the Pac-10 race, the indicators
were not encouraging. But they're looking up. ``They understand now
the kind of commitment, the kind of effort that it takes,'' Olson
said. ``I think they see that we have some idea of what we are
trying to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure early they didn't think we were messing with
their games. They think sometimes we're striving for perfection too
much. The day you stop striving for perfection is the day you stop
getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said that inconsistency is to be expected in freshmen, but
that Wright and Jefferson are atypical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual for a freshman to be consistent, and we've
got two who are in Wright and Jefferson,'' Olson said. ``Richard is
shooting shooting 50 percent and 82 percent at the line (in Pac-10
play). Those are not freshman numbers there. The thing I like about
Richard is that when there is a big shot, he's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright was the Pac-10's leading rookie scorer and rebounder. In
two of the final three regular-season games, though, even he showed
telltale freshman traits. He got into foul trouble at Stanford,
playing only six minutes, and against UCLA, playing 20.
</P>
<P>
   But when the 6-foot-7, 252-pound Wright catches the ball in the
low post, he either scores, gets fouled, or both. Wright changed
the face of the Wildcats from the perimeter-oriented club that won
the national title two years ago and the Pac-10 title last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to say over last four weeks what was the biggest
change in our team, it was the ability of our inside guys to get
open and the ability of our perimeter guys to get the ball to
them,'' Olson said. ``We have much better balance now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright is making opponents pay if they foul him, too. He made 12
in a row at the line in the next-to-last game against Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take it to the basket aggressively, you'll get calls,''
Wright said. ``I've noticed that a lot of big men aren't good
free-throw shooters. I shoot at least 100 a day in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wright teaming with seniors Terry, the Pac-10 Player of the
Year, and all-conference center A.J. Bramlett, the Wildcats have
been solid at three positions since the start. Jefferson grew into
a dependable fourth option.
</P>
<P>
   The final piece was shooting guard. Because Arizona had not
established a consistent threat, opponents could double-team Terry
off that position. Douglas started there early. So did classmates
Traves Wilson and Rick Anderson. They were 30 percent shooters. And
except for the long arms of the 6-8 Anderson, they were no threat
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Douglas was reinserted. In the Wildcats' closing
four games, he averaged 28.3 minutes, shot 52 percent overall and a
sizzling 47.6 from three-point range while averaging 16.5 points.
His outside shooting limited opponents' ability to double Terry. He
also had two five-assist games and made six steals in his closing
run.
</P>
<P>
   The latter statistic was the most convincing evidence to Olson
that Douglas is maturing into a reliable player. ``It's frustrating
in terms of getting the young guys to understand that the game is
about defense,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said he and Wilson didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden I was in there against Kris Weems (of
Stanford) and Geno Carlisle (of California), guys who have been
playing college ball for four or five years, and I'm trying to stop
them,'' Douglas said. ``Those are physical, experienced guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to define our role at two-guard. The focus
has been defense primarily. Offense is kind of last. Me and Richard
and Traves and Ricky have all had a tough adjustment. In high
school, we were the stars of the team. We didn't have to get back
on defense. We didn't pass too much, either. This year has been a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Olson, Terry is probably the most appreciative of
Douglas' emergence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until lately if our two-guard was open, the defense would
still double me and take its chances with him,'' Terry said. ``Now
Ruben is looking for his shot and making his shot. He can take it
to the hole, too. He's causing problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, like Douglas, can put the ball on the floor and
create opportunities. Jefferson is second on the team in assists
and third in rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just rely on J.T. in the tournament,'' Jefferson
said. ``He has gotten a lot of publicity with all of his awards,
and teams will be focused to stop him. We've got to get it from all
of the others. You could tell a couple of games ago that J.T. was
getting tired. Everybody helped out, and that helped him get his
energy back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to peak.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``With about three or four minutes to go (in the season-ending
87-70 rout of No. 12 UCLA), I told the young guys on the bench,
`Let's ride this. Let's go into the tournament with a lot of
confidence,' '' Terry said. ``The biggest thing is the way Ruben is
playing. There's no question about our two-guard anymore. That
means we're solid at all five postions. That's going to make us
pretty hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   With continued consistency from Douglas and Jefferson, the
Wildcats can be a formidable NCAA Tournament team, Olson said.
Terry takes it a step further. He says they can make their fourth
trip to the Final Four since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be the X-factors in the tournament, without a
doubt,'' Douglas said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
