A1342 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ANALYSIS-LADN     03-07 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMITTEE'S DECISIONS PROVE BAFFLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last week, the Pacific-10 coaches selected three
Arizona State players to the 10-man all-conference team, an
embarrassingly high number for a team that finished ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the NCAA Tournament selection committee has been
doodling at the same greaseboard.
</P>
<P>
   One word describes the 64-team field announced Sunday: huh?
</P>
<P>
   The committee is good for a few surprises each March; that's
part of the allure. But this year's pairings make less sense than
an all-star team of Sun Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with Auburn, No. 1 in the South, and Kentucky, No. 2
in the Midwest. Each year, the committee stresses the importance of
nonconference schedules: You can't control your family, it says,
but you can control your friends.
</P>
<P>
   So the Wildcats played what might be the toughest nonconference
schedule in history (UCLA, Kansas, Miami, Indiana, Maryland, Duke
and Louisville) while Auburn did not play a ranked team and stocked
its schedule with directional schools. The Wildcats also beat
Auburn twice, including in the Southeastern Conference tournament,
and somehow they're seeded behind the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kentucky isn't a No. 1, but based on stated criteria,
neither is Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford lost its No. 1 seed when it lost at Oregon State on
Saturday night, but Maryland has the strongest complaint. The Terps
are 26-5 with losses to Duke (twice), North Carolina and Kentucky
(road). They beat Stanford, UCLA and North Carolina (twice). And
they aren't a No. 1?
</P>
<P>
   Give the committee credit for recognizing Utah's dominating
performance and awarding the Utes a No. 2 seed, even though it
necessitated moving them out of the West.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the decision backfired: As the No. 2 seed in
the Midwest, the Utes are scheduled to face Kentucky in the Sweet
16. The teams have played four times in recent tournaments,
including the 1998 title game, and Kentucky has won all four.
They're two of the hottest and best-coached teams in the draw;
unfortunately, one will be out a round too soon.
</P>
<P>
   There are other sensitive seeding issues. The Big Ten got seven
bids _ and would have received an eighth had Illinois won the
conference tournament _ while the Pac-10 got four and the ACC
three, a record low. Explained committee chairman C.M. Newton:
``Other than the automatic qualifiers, we don't worry about the
leagues'' when picking at-large teams.
</P>
<P>
   As the only at-large 13th seed, Oklahoma was the last team in.
Xavier, Mississippi State, Fresno State and Wake Forest were
justifiably excluded. The Missouri Valley Conference received three
berths, the Mid-American Conference two: Call it the rise of the
mid-majors.
</P>
<P>
   But the selection committee made its most serious blunder in
selecting New Mexico over California. The Lobos had a Sagarin
rating in the 80s, a nonconference schedule so pathetic that state
politicians complained publicly, no quality road wins and only one
decent home win, Arizona, at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cal beat Rhode Island, North Carolina, UCLA and
Arizona, lost at DePaul and played Stanford close. On a neutral
court, Cal beats New Mexico by double figures, easy, with or
without Kenny Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the end, the Bears never had a chance: Lobos athletic
director Rudy Davalos is on the selection committee.
</P>
